<PB N="[3]"><HEAD>The Form of Living</HEAD>
<NOTE ID="n1">At this point the text of MS Arundel 507 includes the following "little scraps" printed by Horstman:
<Q><MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="folio"><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nota.</FOREIGN>  For als mykil as mannes saule es made euer to life: for-&thorn;i es man halden
to serue god &amp; lufe god / euer with-outen ende.  And for &thorn;is bande &thorn;at byndes man to serue god / es endeles: to do &thorn;er-agayn with deadly synne / es trespas
endeles; &amp; sen &thorn;e trespas es endeles: &thorn;e payne &thorn;at &thorn;erto falles / es endeles.</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Item</FOREIGN>.  Oure euil dedes are oure awne as oure propre catell; bot &thorn;e gode when we
it do: es oddes.  &THORN;en, thorugh &thorn;e rightwisenes of god / we are more worthi til
haue payne for oure euil dedes: &thorn;en any mede of god / for any gode &thorn;at we doo.</P></Q></NOTE>                                           <NOTE TARGET="n2">The next few lines also comprise the first half of the short text "On the Name of Iesus," given in the companion volume with other pieces from Rawl. C 285.</NOTE>
<DIV3 N="Cambridge Dd V.64" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Cambr. Dd V. 64</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="101" UNIT="folio">

<OPENER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Incipit forma uiuendi scripta a beato
Ricardo heremita ad Margaretam
anachoritam, suam dilectam
discipulam.</FOREIGN>
</OPENER>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap. 1<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(I)N ilk a synful man or woman,
&thorn;at es bunden in dedly syn, er thre
wrechednes: &thorn;e wylk brynges &thorn;am&dot; to
&thorn;e dede of hell. // &THORN;e first es: defaute
of gastly strenght: &THORN;at &thorn;ai er sa wayke&dot;


<PB N="4">

with-in &thorn;air hert, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may nouther
stand&dot; agaynes &thorn;e fandynges of &thorn;e fende,
ne &thorn;ai may lyft &thorn;air will&dot; to &yogh;erne &thorn;e
lofe of god, and folow &thorn;ar-till. // &THORN;e
secund es: use of fleschly desyres:&mdash;for
&thorn;ai haue na will ne myght to stand, &thorn;ai
fall in lustes&dot; &amp; likynges of &thorn;is worlde;
and for &thorn;ai thynk &thorn;am swete, &thorn;ai
dwell in &thorn;am still, many tyll &thorn;aire
lyues ende: &amp; sa &thorn;ai com&macr; to &thorn;e thrid
wrechednes. // &THORN;e thred wrechednes
es: chaungyng of lastand gode&dot; for a
passande delite.  Als swa say, &thorn;ai gif
ioy endles&dot; for a litell ioy of &thorn;is
lyfe.  If &thorn;ai will torn &thorn;am, &amp; ryse till
penance, god will ordeyne &thorn;air wonyng&dot;
with awngels&dot; &amp; with haly men.  Bot
for &thorn;ai chese &thorn;e vile syn of &thorn;is world,
&amp; hase mare delite&dot; in &thorn;e fylth of
&thorn;aire flesch, &thorn;an in &thorn;e fairhede of
heuen, &thorn;ai lose bath &thorn;e worlde &amp; heuen.  For he &thorn;at hase noght Ihesu
Criste, he tynes all &thorn;at he has, &amp; all
&thorn;at he es, &amp; all &thorn;at he myght
gete.  He ne es worthy &thorn;e lyfe, ne to be
fedde&dot; with swynes mete.  All creaturs
sal be styrde in his vengaunce&dot; at &thorn;e
day of dome. // &THORN;iere wrechednes &thorn;at
I haue of talde, er noght anely in
worldly men or women, &thorn;at vses gluttry
or litcheri, &amp; o&thorn;er apert synnes: bot
&thorn;ai er alswa&dot; in other &thorn;at semes in
penance&dot; &amp; in gode lyfe.  For &thorn;e deuyll,


<PB N="5">

&thorn;at es enmy till all man kynde, when
he sees a man or a woman, ymang a
thousand, turne haly to god, and
forsake all &thorn;e vanytees &amp; ryches &thorn;at men
&thorn;at lufes &thorn;is worlde couaytise, &amp; sekes
&thorn;e Ioy lastand: a thousand wiles he
has&dot; on what maner he may desayue
&thorn;am.  And when he may noght bryng
&thorn;am in till swylk synnes&dot; &thorn;e whylk
myght gar all men wonder on &thorn;am&dot; &thorn;at
knew &thorn;am, he begyles many swa
priuely, &thorn;at &thorn;ai kan noght oft-syth fele
&thorn;e trap &thorn;at has taken &thorn;aime.
</P>
<P>Somme he takes with errour, &thorn;at
he puttes &thorn;am yn. // Som wyth singulere
witt: when he gars &thorn;aime wene&dot; &thorn;at
&thorn;e thyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai sai or do es best;
and for-&thorn;i &thorn;ai wyll na counsell haue&dot;
of o&thorn;er &thorn;at es better &amp; conander &thorn;en
&thorn;ai: &amp; &thorn;is es a foule stynkand pryde,
for he wolde sett his witt&dot; before all
o&thorn;er. // Some &thorn;e deuell deceyues thurgh
vayne glory, &thorn;at es ydil ioy: When
any has pryde&dot; &amp; delyte in &thorn;am-self, of
&thorn;e penance &thorn;at &thorn;ai suffer, of gode
dedes &thorn;at &thorn;ai do, of any vertu &thorn;at
&thorn;ai haue; es glad when men loues
&thorn;am, sari when men lackes &thorn;am;
haues envy to &thorn;am &thorn;at es spokyn mare
gode of&dot; &thorn;an of &thorn;am.  &THORN;ai halde &thorn;air
self so gloriouse, &amp; swa fer passand &thorn;e
lyf&dot; &thorn;at o&thorn;er men ledes, &thorn;at &thorn;ai thynk
&thorn;at nane suld reprehend &thorn;am, in any


<PB N="6">

thyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai do or say; an dispises
synfull men &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;e whilk will not
do als &thorn;ai byd &thorn;am.  How may &thorn;ow
fynd a synfuller wretche &thorn;an swilk ane?
And sa mykell es he &thorn;e wer, &thorn;at he
wate noght &thorn;at he es yll, &amp; es halden
&amp; honord of men als wyse &amp; hali. //
Some er deceyued with ouer-mykell lust
&amp; likyng in mete &amp; drynk: When &thorn;ai
passe mesure &amp; com in till outrage, &amp; has delyte &thorn;arein; and wenes &thorn;at &thorn;ai
syn&macr; noght, and for&thorn;i &thorn;ai amend &thorn;am
noght; and swa &thorn;ai destruye vertues
of saule. // Some er begylde with
oure-mikell abstinens of mete &amp; drynk &amp; slepe.  &THORN;at es of &thorn;e temptacion of &thorn;e
deuell, for to gar &thorn;am fall in myddes
&thorn;air werk, swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai bryng it till
nane endyng, als &thorn;ai suld haue done
if &thorn;ai had knawne skyll &amp; halden
discrecion: &amp; swa &thorn;ai tyne &thorn;aire merit
for &thorn;aire frawerdnes. // &THORN;is gylder layes
oure enmy to take vs with, when we
begyn to hate wyckednes, &amp; turne vs
till god.  &THORN;en many begynnes &thorn;e thyng
&thorn;at &thorn;ai may neuer-mare bryng till
ende; &thorn;en &thorn;ai wene &thorn;at &thorn;ai may do
what so &thorn;air hert es sett on.  Bot oft
&thorn;ai fall or &thorn;ai come ymyd gate; and
&thorn;at thyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai wend war for &thorn;am,
es lettyng till &thorn;am.  For we haue a
lange way till heuen, and als many


<PB N="7">

gode dedys [als] we do, als many prayers
als we make, &amp; als many gode thoghtes
als we thynk, in trouth &amp; hope &amp; charite: als many paces ga we till
heuen-ward.  &THORN;an if we make vs sa
wayke &amp; so febyll, &thorn;at we may nouther
wyrk ne pray als we suld do, ne thynk:
Er we noght gretly at blame, &thorn;at fayles
when we had maste nede to be
stal-worth?  And wele I wate, it es noght
goddys will &thorn;at we sa do.  For &thorn;e
prophete says: &laquo;Lorde, I sall kepe my
strengh to &thorn;e&raquo;: so &thorn;at he myght susten
goddys seruys till his dede-day, and
noght in a litill &amp; in a schort tyme
waste it &amp; &thorn;an lygge wanand &amp; granand
be &thorn;e wall.  And it es mykel mare
peryll &thorn;an men wenes.  For saynt
Ierome says, &thorn;at he makys of rauyn
offerand &thorn;at outragely tourmentis his
body in oure-lytel mete or slepe.  And
saynt Bernarde sais: &laquo;Fastyng &amp; wakyng
lettes noght gastly godes, bot helpes, if
&thorn;ai be done with discrecion; with-outen
&thorn;at, &thorn;ai er vices&raquo;.  For-&thorn;i, it es noght
gode to pyne vs so mykell, &amp; sithen
haue vnthank for oure dede. // &THORN;are
hase bene many, &amp; er, &thorn;at wenes &thorn;at
it es noght all &thorn;at &thorn;ai do, bot if &thorn;ai
be in sa mikell abstinence &amp; fastyng
&thorn;at all men speke of &thorn;am &thorn;at knawes
&thorn;am.  Bot oft-sythes it befalles &thorn;at ay


<PB N="8">

&thorn;e mare ioy &amp; wonduryng &thorn;ai haue
with-outen of &thorn;e louyng of men, ay
&thorn;e les ioy &thorn;ai haue with-in, of &thorn;e luf
of god.  At my dome, &thorn;ai sulde pay
Ihesu Criste mikell mare if &thorn;ai toke for
his loue, in thankyng &amp; louyng of
hym, forto sustan &thorn;ar body in his
seruyse, and to halde &thorn;am fra mikell speche
of men, what so god send for &thorn;e tyme
and &thorn;e stede, &amp; gaf &thorn;am sithen enterely
&amp; perfitely to &thorn;e luf &amp; &thorn;e louyng of
&thorn;at lorde Ihesu Criste, &thorn;at will
stalworthly be lufed, &amp; lastandly be serued;
so &thorn;at &thorn;aire halynes war mare sene in
goddes egh, &thorn;en in mans.  For ay &thorn;e
better &thorn;ou ert &amp; &thorn;e les speche &thorn;ou has
of men, &thorn;e mare es &thorn;i ioy before
god. // Ha, what it es mykell, to be
worthi louyng, and be noght loued!
And what wrechednes it es, to haue
&thorn;e name &amp; &thorn;e habet of halynes, &amp; be
noght so, bot couer pride, Ire, or enuy,
vnder &thorn;e clathes of Criste barnhede!
A foule thyng it es to hafe lykyng &amp; delite in mens wordes, &thorn;at can na
mare deme what we er in oure saule,
&thorn;en &thorn;ai wate what we thynk.  For
oft-sithe &thorn;ai say &thorn;at he or scho es in &thorn;e
hegher degre, &thorn;at es in &thorn;e lawer; and
&thorn;at &thorn;ai say es in &thorn;e lawer, es in &thorn;e
hegher.  For-&thorn;i, I halde it bot wodnes
to be gladder or sarier, whe&thorn;ir &thorn;ai say
gude or ill.  If we be aboutewarde to


<PB N="9">

hyde vs fra speche and louyng of &thorn;is
worlde, god wyll schew vs till hys
louyng, &amp; oure Ioy.  For &thorn;at es his
ioy when we er strenghfull to stande
agaynes &thorn;e pryue &amp; &thorn;e aperte fandyng
of &thorn;e deuell, &amp; sekes na thyng bot &thorn;e
honoure &amp; &thorn;e louyng of hym, and &thorn;at
we myght enterely loue hym.  And &thorn;at
aght to be oure desyre, oure prayer &amp; oure entent, nyght &amp; day, &thorn;at &thorn;e fyre
of hys lufe kyndell oure hert, &amp; &thorn;e
swetnes of hys grace be oure comforth
&amp; oure solace, in wele and wo. // &THORN;ow
hase now herd a party, how &thorn;e fende
deceyues, wyth hys sotell craftes &amp; whaynt, men &amp; women.  And if &thorn;ou
will do be gode cownsel, &amp; folow haly
lare, als I hope &thorn;at &thorn;ou will: &thorn;ou sall
destroy his trappes, &amp; bryn in &thorn;e fyre
of luf all &thorn;e bandes &thorn;at he walde
bynd &thorn;e with, &amp; all his malys sall
turne &thorn;e til ioy, &amp; hym till mare sorow. /
God suffers hym to tempe gode men
for &thorn;aire profete, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may be &thorn;e
hegher crownde, when &thorn;ai thurgh his
helpe hase ouercomne sa cruell an
enmy, &thorn;at oft-sythes both in body &amp; in saule confowndes many men. // In
thre maners &thorn;e deuell has power to be
in a man.  On a maner: hurtande &thorn;e
godes &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue of kynde, als in
dom&macr; men, &amp; in other, blemysand &thorn;air
thoght.  On a nother maner: revande


<PB N="10">

&thorn;e godes whilk &thorn;ai haue of grace; and
so he es in synfull men &thorn;e whilk he
hase deceyued thurgh delyte of &thorn;e
worlde &amp; of &thorn;air flesche, and ledes
&thorn;am with hym till hell.  On &thorn;e third
maner, he tourmentes a mans body, als
we rede &thorn;at he has done Iob.  Bot
wytt &thorn;ou wele: if he begyle &thorn;e noght
with-in, &thorn;e thar noght drede what he
may do &thorn;e with-outen; for he may do
na mare, &thorn;an god gyfs hym leue for
to do.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. 2<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(F)Or &thorn;at &thorn;ou has forsakyn &thorn;e
solace &amp; &thorn;e ioy of &thorn;is world, &amp; taken
&thorn;e to solitary lyf, for gods luf to suffer
tribulacion &amp; anguys here, &amp; sithen
com to &thorn;at blys &thorn;at neuer-mare blynnes:
I trowe treuly &thorn;at &thorn;e comforth of
Ihesu Criste, &amp; &thorn;e swetnes of his loue,
with &thorn;e fire of &thorn;e haly gast, &thorn;at purges
all syn, sall be in &thorn;e, &amp; with &thorn;e, ledand
&thorn;e, &amp; lerand &thorn;e / how &thorn;ou sall thynk,
how &thorn;ou sall pray, what &thorn;ou sall wyrk;
so &thorn;at in a few &yogh;ers &thorn;ou sall haue
mare delyte, to be by &thorn;i nane, &amp; speke
till &thorn;i luf &amp; to &thorn;i spows Ihesu Crist,
&thorn;at hegh es in heuen, &thorn;an if &thorn;ou war
lady here of a thowsand worldes.  Men
wenes &thorn;at we er in pyne, &amp; in penance
grete: bot we haue mare ioy &amp; mare


<PB N="11">

verray delyte in a day,| &thorn;an &thorn;ai haue
in &thorn;e worlde all &thorn;ar lyue. / &THORN;ai se
oure body, bot &thorn;ai se noght oure hert,
whare oure solace es.  If &thorn;ai saw &thorn;at,
many of &thorn;am wold forsake all &thorn;at &thorn;ai
haue, forto folow vs.  For-&thorn;i be
comford, &amp; stalworth, and drede na noye
ne angwysch: bot fest all thyne entent
in Ihesu, &thorn;at &thorn;i lyf be gode &amp; wheme;
and loke &thorn;at &thorn;ere be na thyng in &thorn;e
&thorn;at suld be mys-payand till hym, &thorn;at
&thorn;ou ne sone amend itt. / &THORN;e state &thorn;at
&thorn;ou ert in, &thorn;at es solitude, es maste
abyll of all othyr til reuelacion of &thorn;e
haly gaste.  For when saynt Ione was
in &thorn;e yle of Pathmos, &thorn;an god schewed
hym his pryuytees.  / &THORN;e godenes of god
it es, &thorn;at he comfortes &thorn;am wondyrfully
&thorn;at has na comforth of &thorn;e worlde, if
&thorn;ai gyf &thorn;air hert enterly till hym, and
couayts noght ne sekes bot hym: &thorn;en
he gyues hym-self till &thorn;aime, in swetnes
&amp; delyte, in byrnyng of luf, &amp; in ioy
&amp; melody, &amp; dwelles ay with &thorn;am, in
thaire saule, sa &thorn;at &thorn;e comforth of
hym departes neuer fra &thorn;am.  / And if
&thorn;ai any tym begyn till erre, thurgh
ignorance or freelte: sone he wysses
&thorn;am &thorn;e right way; &amp; all &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue
nede of, he leres &thorn;am.  // Naman till
swylk reuelacion &amp; grace on &thorn;e first
day may kom: bot thurgh lang trauell
&amp; bysines to loue Ihesu Criste, als &thorn;ou


<PB N="12">

sall here afterward.  / Noght-for-&thorn;i, &thorn;an
he suffers &thorn;am to be temped on sere
maners, both wakand &amp; slepand.  For
ay &thorn;e ma temptacions, &amp; &thorn;e greuoser,
&thorn;ai stande agayne, &amp; ouer-comes: &thorn;e
mare sall &thorn;ai ioy in his luf, when &thorn;ai
er passed.  // Wakand &thorn;ai er vmwhile
tempyd wyth foule thoghtys, vile lustes,
wicked delites; with pryde, Ire, enuy,
despaire, presumpcion, &amp; o&thorn;er many.
Bot &thorn;aire remedy sall be: Prayer,
Gretyng, Fastyng, Wakyng. // &THORN;ire
thynges, if &thorn;ai be done with discrecion,
&thorn;ai put a-way syn &amp; filth fra &thorn;e saule,
&amp; makes it clene, to receyue &thorn;e luf of
Ihesu Criste, &thorn;at may noght be loued,
bot in clennes. // Also, vmwhile &thorn;e
fende tempes men &amp; women, &thorn;at er
solitary by &thorn;am ane, on a qwaynt
maner &amp; a sotell: He transfigurs hym
in &thorn;e lyknes of an awngel of lyght,
&amp; apers till &thorn;am, and sayes &thorn;at he
es ane of goddes awngels, comen to
comforth &thorn;am; &amp; swa he deceyues
foles.  Bot &thorn;ai &thorn;at er wys, &amp; wil not
tyte trow till all spirites, bot askes
cownsel of conand men: he may not
begyle &thorn;am.  Als I fynd writen of a
reclues, &thorn;at was a gude woman; til &thorn;e
whilk &thorn;e ill awngell oft-sythes aperde
in &thorn;e forme of a gode awngel, and
sayd &thorn;at he was comen to bryng hir


<PB N="13">

to heuen.  Wharfore scho was right
glad &amp; ioyful.  Bot neuer-&thorn;e-latter,
scho talde it til hir schryft-fader; and
he, als wyse man and war, gaf hir &thorn;is
counsell: / &laquo;When he comes, he sayde,
byd hym &thorn;at he schew &thorn;e oure lady
saynt Mary.  When he has done swa:
say <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aue maria</FOREIGN>&raquo;.  Scho dyd sa.  &THORN;e
fende sayde: / &laquo;&THORN;ou has na nede to se
hyr; my presence suffyse to &thorn;e&raquo;.  And
scho sayde, on all maner scho suld se
hyr.  He saw &thorn;at hym behoued outher
do hir wyll, or scho walde despyse
hym: Als tyte he broght forth &thorn;e
fayrest woman &thorn;at myght be, als to hyr
syght, &amp; schewed til hyr.  And scho
sett hir on hir knees &amp; sayde: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aue
maria</FOREIGN>.  And als tyte all vanyst away;
&amp; for scham neuer sithen come he at
hir. / &THORN;is I say not, for I hope &thorn;at he
sal haue leue to tempe &thorn;e on &thorn;is maner;
bot for I will &thorn;at &thorn;ou be war, if any
wyk temptacions befall &thorn;e, slepand or
wakand, &thorn;at &thorn;ou trow not oure-tyte,
til &thorn;ou knaw &thorn;e soth.  // Mare priuilyer
he transfigurs hym in &thorn;e forme of an
awngel of lyght&mdash;&thorn;at comonli al men
ar temped with: when he hydes ill
vnder &thorn;e liknes of gode.  And &thorn;at es
in twa maneres: / Ane es, when he
egges vs til oure-mykel ees &amp; rest of
body, and softnes til oure flesche, vndir


<PB N="14">

ne[d]e to susteyne oure kynde.  For
swilk thoghtes he puttes in vs: bot if
we ete wele, &amp; drynk wele, &amp; slepe
wele, &amp; lygge soft &amp; sytt warme: we
may not serue god, ne last in &thorn;e
trauell &thorn;at we haue begonn.  Bot he
thynkes to bryng vs till ouer-mykel
lust. // Another es, when vnder &thorn;e
lyknes of gastly gode he entices vs til
scharp &amp; oure-mikel penance, forto
destroye oure self; and says &thorn;us:
&laquo;&THORN;ou wate wele &thorn;at he &thorn;at suffers
mast penance for goddes lufe, he sall
haue maste mede.  For&thorn;i ete litell,
and febyl mete, &amp; drynk lesse, &thorn;e
thynnest drynk es gode ynogh till &thorn;e.
Recke noght of slepe; were &thorn;e hayre,
&amp; &thorn;e habirion.  All thyng &thorn;at es
affliccion for &thorn;i flesche, do it: so &thorn;at
&thorn;are be nane, &thorn;at may passe &thorn;e in
penance&raquo;. / He &thorn;at says &thorn;e &thorn;us, es
aboute to sla &thorn;e with oure-mykel
abstinence, als he &thorn;at sayde &thorn;e to&thorn;er, to
sla &thorn;e with oure-lytell.  For&thorn;i, if we
will be right disposed, vs behoues sett
vs in a gude mene, &amp; &thorn;at we may
destroy oure vices, &amp; halde oure flesche
vnder, / and neuer-&thorn;e-latter &thorn;at it be
stalworth in &thorn;e seruyse of Ihesu Criste. //
Als-swa, oure enmy will noght suffer
vs to be in rest when we slepe: bot
&thorn;an he es aboute to begyle vs in many


<PB N="15">

maners. // Vmwhile, with vggly ymages:
forto make vs radde, &amp; make vs lathe
with oure state; Vmwhile, with faire
ymages, fayre syghtes &amp; &thorn;at semes
confortabell: forto make vs glad in
vayne, and gar vs wene &thorn;at we er better
&thorn;an we er.  Vmwhile, tels vs &thorn;at we
er haly &amp; gode: forto bryng vs in till
pryde; [Vmwhile, sais &thorn;at we er wicked
&amp; synful: for to ger vs falle in to
dispaire].  Bot he &thorn;at es ordiner of all
thyng, suffers noght &thorn;at oure slepe be
with-owten mede til vs, if we dresse
oure lyfe till his will.  And wyt &thorn;ow
wele, &thorn;ou syns noght slepand: if
&thorn;ou be euermare wakande with-outen
outrage of mete &amp; drynk, &amp; with-outen
ill thoghtes. // Bot many ane &thorn;e deuel
hase deceyued thurgh dremes, when he
haues gart &thorn;am sett &thorn;air hert on &thorn;am. /
For he hase schewed &thorn;am som&macr; sothe,
&amp; sethyn begylt &thorn;am with ane &thorn;at was
fals.  For-&thorn;i says &thorn;e wyse man &thorn;at
many besynes folowes dremes; an &thorn;ai
fell &thorn;at hoped in &thorn;am. // Whar-fore,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou be not begylde with &thorn;am, I
will &thorn;at &thorn;ou witt &thorn;at &thorn;er er sex maners
of dremes.  Twa er &thorn;at na man, haly
ne o&thorn;er, may eschape; &thorn;ai er: // If
&thorn;air wambe be oure-tome, or oure-full;


<PB N="16">

&thorn;an many vanitees in seer maners
befalles &thorn;am slepande. // &THORN;e thryd es, of
illusyons of oure enmy. // &THORN;e ferth es,
of thoght before, and illusion folouand. /
And &thorn;e fyft, thorow &thorn;e reuelacion of
&thorn;e hali gast, &thorn;at es done on many a
maner. / &THORN;e sext es, of thoghtes
before &thorn;at falles to Criste or hali kyrk,
reuelacion comand after. / In &thorn;us many
maners touches &thorn;e ymage of dremes men
when &thorn;ai slepe.  Bot sa mykell we sall
latlyer gyf fayth till any dreme, &thorn;at we
may not sone wyt whilk es soth, whilk
es fals; whilk es of oure enmy, whilk
es of &thorn;e hali gaste. / For whare many
dremes er, &thorn;are er many vanitees.  And
many &thorn;ai may make to erre: for &thorn;ai hegh
vnwhaynt men, &amp; swa deceyues &thorn;am.
</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. 3<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(I) Knawe &thorn;at &thorn;i lyfe es gyuen to
&thorn;e seruyce of god.  &THORN;an es it schame
til &thorn;e, bot if &thorn;ou be als gode, or better,
with-in in &thorn;i sawle, als &thorn;ou ert semand
at &thorn;e syght of men.  Turne for-&thorn;i &thorn;i
thoghtes perfitely till god, als it semes
&thorn;at &thorn;ou hase done &thorn;i body.  For I
will not &thorn;at &thorn;ou wene &thorn;at all er hali
&thorn;at hase &thorn;e abet of halynes, &amp; er noght
ocupyed with &thorn;e worlde; / Ne &thorn;at all
er ill &thorn;at melles &thorn;am with erthly
bysines. // Bot &thorn;ai er anly hali, what
state or degre &thorn;ai be in, &thorn;e whilk
despises all erthly thyng, &thorn;at es at say,
lufs it noght, &amp; byrnes in &thorn;e luf of


<PB N="17">

Ihesu Criste, &amp; al &thorn;air desires er sett
til &thorn;e ioy of heuen, &amp; hates al synn,
&amp; ceses noght of gode werkys, and
feles a swetnes in &thorn;aire hert of &thorn;e
lufe with-outen ende: / and
neuer-&thorn;e-latter &thorn;ai thynk &thorn;am-self vylest of
all, &amp; haldes &thorn;am wretchedest, leste,
&amp; lawest. / &THORN;is es hali mens lyf: folow
it, &amp; be haly. / And if &thorn;ou will be in
mede with apostels, thynk noght what
&thorn;ou for-soke, bot what &thorn;ou despyses. /
For als mykell &thorn;ai forsake &thorn;at foloues
Ihesu Criste, in wilfull pouert, &amp; in
mekenes, &amp; in charite, &amp; in paciens,
als &thorn;ai may couayte &thorn;at folows hym
noght.  And thynk with how mykel, &amp; how gude will &thorn;ou presentes &thorn;i vowes
be-fore hym: for till &thorn;at he hase hys
egh; / and if &thorn;ou with gret desyre
offer &thorn;i praiers, with grete feruoure
couayte to se hym, and seke na erthly
comforth, bot &thorn;e sauoure of heuen, &amp; in
contemplacion &thorn;erof haue &thorn;i delyte. //
Wondurfulli Ihesu wirkes in hys louers:
&thorn;e whilk he reues fra &thorn;e lust of flesch
&amp; of blode, thorow tender lufe.  He
makes &thorn;am to will na erthly thyng, &amp; dose &thorn;am ryse in to &thorn;e solace of hym,
&amp; to forgete vanytees &amp; fleschely lufe
of &thorn;e worlde, &amp; to drede na sorow
&thorn;at may fall; / To lathe with ouer-


<PB N="18">

mykel bodili ees.  To suffer for his luf,
&thorn;am thynk it ioy; and to be solitary
&thorn;ai haue grete comforth: &thorn;at &thorn;ai be
noght lettyd of &thorn;at deuocyon.  // Now
may &thorn;ou se &thorn;at many er war &thorn;an &thorn;ai
seme, &amp; many er better &thorn;an &thorn;ai seme,
&amp; namely amang &thorn;ase &thorn;at hase &thorn;e
habett of halynes.  / For-&thorn;i afforce &thorn;e,
in all &thorn;at &thorn;ow may, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be noght
wer &thorn;an &thorn;ou semes.  / And if &thorn;ou will
do als I lere &thorn;e in &thorn;is schort forme of
lyuyng, I hope, thorou &thorn;e grace of
god, &thorn;at if men halde &thorn;e gude, &thorn;ou
sall be wele better.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. IIII<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(A)T &thorn;e begynnyng, turne &thorn;e
enterely to &thorn;i lorde Ihesu Criste.  / &THORN;at
turnyng till Ihesu es noght els, bot
turnyng fra all &thorn;e couaytyse &amp; &thorn;e
likyng &amp; &thorn;e occupacions &amp; bisynes of
worldly thynges &amp; of fleschly lust and
vayne luf: swa &thorn;at &thorn;i thoght, &thorn;at was
ay donward, modeland in &thorn;e erth,
whils &thorn;ou was in &thorn;e worlde, now be
ay vpwarde als fire, sekand &thorn;e heghest
place in heuen, right til &thorn;i spows, &thorn;are
he syttes in hys blys.  Til hym &thorn;ou
ert turned, when his grace illumyns &thorn;i
hert; &amp; forsakes all vices, &amp; conformes
il til vertues &amp; gude thewes, &amp; til all
maner of debonerte &amp; mekenes.  / And
&thorn;at &thorn;ou may last &amp; wax in gudenes
&thorn;at &thorn;ou hase begon, with-owten slawnes


<PB N="19">

&amp; sarynes &amp; irkyng of &thorn;i lyf: / Fowre
thyngs sall &thorn;ou haue in &thorn;i thoght, til
&thorn;ou be in perfyte lufe&mdash;For when &thorn;ou
ert commen &thorn;ar-till, &thorn;i ioy &amp; desyre
will ay be byrnand in Criste.  Ane es:
&thorn;e mesur of &thorn;i lyf here, &thorn;at sa schort
es &thorn;at vnnethis es it oght.  / For we
lyue bot in a poynt&mdash;&thorn;at es &thorn;e leste
thyng &thorn;at may be.  / And, sothely,
oure lyfe es les &thorn;an a poynt, if we
liken it to &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at lastes ay.  //
Another es: vncertente of owre endyng.
For we wate neuer when we sal dye,
ne whare we sal dye, ne how we sal
dye, ne whider we sal ga when we er
dede.  &amp; &thorn;at god wil &thorn;at &thorn;is be
vncertayn til vs: for he will &thorn;at we be
ay redy to dye.  // &THORN;e thyrd es: &thorn;at we
sall answer before &thorn;e ryghtwys Iuge of
all &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at we haue bene here,
how we haue lyued, what oure
occupacioun hase bene and why, &amp; what
gude we myght haue done when we
haue bene ydel.  For-&thorn;i sayde &thorn;e
prophete: &laquo;He hase calde &thorn;e tyme agayn
me&raquo;, &thorn;at ilk day he hase lent vs
here forto despende in gude vse, and in
penance, &amp; in gods seruys.  / If we
waste it in erthly lufe &amp; in vanitees,
ful greuosly mon we be demed &amp; punyst&mdash;ffor &thorn;at es ane of &thorn;e maste
sorow &thorn;at may be: bot we afforce vs
manly in &thorn;e lufe of god, &amp; do gude til
all &thorn;at we may, whil oure schort tyme
lastes.  And ilk tyme &thorn;at we thynk
not on god, we may cownt it als &thorn;e
thyng &thorn;at we haue tynt.  The ferth es:


<PB N="20">

&thorn;at we thynk how mykell &thorn;e ioy es &thorn;at
&thorn;ai haue &thorn;e whilk lastes in goddes lufe
til &thorn;air endyng.  For &thorn;ai sal be brether
&amp; felaws with awngels &amp; haly men,
lufand &amp; thankand, louand &amp; seand, &thorn;e
kyng of ioy, in &thorn;e fayrhede &amp; in &thorn;e
schynyng of his maieste.  &THORN;e whilk
syght sall be mede &amp; mete, &amp; al delytes
&thorn;at any creature may thynk, &amp; mare
&thorn;an any may tell, till all hys louers,
with-outen ende. / It es mikel lightar
to com&macr; to &thorn;at blys, &thorn;an for to tell it. /
Als-swa thynk what pyne &amp; what
sorow and tormentyng &thorn;ai sall haue
&thorn;e whilk lufs noght god ouer all other
thynges &thorn;at man sees in &thorn;is world,
bot files &thorn;are bodi &amp; &thorn;air sawle in lust
&amp; letchery of &thorn;is lyfe, In pryde &amp; couayties, &amp; o&thorn;er synnes: &thorn;ai sall
byrne in &thorn;e fyre of hell, with &thorn;e
deuell wham &thorn;ai serued, als lang as
god es in heuen with his seruandes:
&thorn;at es euer-mare.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. V<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(I) Wyll &thorn;at &thorn;ou be ay clymbande
till Ihesu-warde, &amp; ekand &thorn;i luf &amp; &thorn;i
seruys in hym: noght als foles doos:
&thorn;ai begyn in &thorn;e heyest degre, &amp; coms
downe till &thorn;e lawest.  I say noght, for
I will &thorn;at if &thorn;ou haue begune
vnskylfull abstinence, &thorn;at &thorn;ou halde it: bot
for many &thorn;at was byrnand at &thorn;e
begynnyng &amp; abyll til &thorn;e luf of Ihesu
Criste, for owre-mykel penans &thorn;ai haue
lettyd &thorn;am-self, &amp; made &thorn;am sa febel
&thorn;at &thorn;ai may noght lufe god as &thorn;ai
sulde.  In &thorn;e whilk luf &thorn;at &thorn;ow wax
ay mare &amp; mare, es my couaytyng &amp;


<PB N="21">

amonestyng.  I halde &thorn;e neuer of &thorn;e
lesse meryt yf &thorn;ou be noght in swa
mykel abstinence; bot if &thorn;ou sett al
&thorn;i thoght how &thorn;ou may luf &thorn;i spouse
Ihesu Criste, mare &thorn;an &thorn;ou has done,
&thorn;an dar I say &thorn;at &thorn;i mede es waxand,
&amp; noght wanande.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum sextum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(W)Harfore, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be ryght
disposed, bath for &thorn;i saule &amp; &thorn;i body,
&thorn;ou sall vnderstande fowre thynges: /
&THORN;e fyrst thyng es: what thyng fyles a
man. / &THORN;e to&thorn;er thyng: what makys
hym clene. / &THORN;e thyrd: what haldes hym
in clennes. / &THORN;e ferth: what thyng
drawes hym for to ordayne his will all
at goddes will. // For &thorn;e fyrst: wyt &thorn;ou
&thorn;at we synne in thre thynges, &thorn;at
makes vs folowe: &thorn;at es wyth hert, and
mouth, &amp; dede.  // &THORN;e synnes of &thorn;e hert,
er &thorn;ir: Ill thoght.  ill delyte.  assent
till synne.  desyre of ill.  wikked will.
Ill suspecion.  vndeuocion.  If &thorn;ou lat
&thorn;i hert any tyme be ydell, with-outen
occupacion of &thorn;e lufe, of &thorn;e louyng
of god.  Ill drede.  ill lufe.  errour.
fleschely affeccioun till &thorn;i frendes or
till other &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes.  Ioy in any
mens ill-fare, whethir &thorn;ai be enmy or
nane.  despyte of pure / or of synfull
men.  to honor ryche men for &thorn;aire
rytches. / vnconabyll ioy of any worldes
vanite. / sorow of &thorn;e worlde. /
vntholmodnes.  perplexite, / &thorn;at es dowt what
es to do / &amp; what noght&mdash; / for ilk a
man aght for to be syker what he sall
do &amp; what he sall leue. / obstinacion in


<PB N="22">

ill. / noy to do gude. / anger to serue
god. / sorow &thorn;at he dyd na mare ill, /
or &thorn;at he dyd noght &thorn;at luste / or &thorn;at
will of his flesche / &thorn;e whilk he myght
haue done. / vnstabylnes of thoght. /
pyne of penance. / ypocrisy. / lufe to
plees to men, / drede to dysplees &thorn;am. /
schame of gude dede, / ioy of ill dede. /
Synguler witt.  couaytyse of honoure,
or of dignite, or to be halden better
&thorn;an other, or rycher, or fayrer, or to
be mare dred.  vayne glory of any godes
of kynde, or of happe, or of grace.
Schame with pore frendes, pryde of &thorn;i
riche kynne, or of gentyl&mdash;for all we
er ilike fre be-for gods face, bot if
owre dedes make any better or wers
&thorn;an other.  despyte of gude counsell,
&amp; of gude techynge. // &THORN;e synnes of &thorn;e
mowthe, er thir: To swere oft-syth. /
forsweryng.  sclaunder of Criste / or
of any of his halows. / To neven his
name with-outen reuerence.
agayn-saiyng, and strife, agayne sothfastnes. /
grotchyng agayns god, / for any angwys,
or noy, or tribulacioun / &thorn;at may
befall in erth. / to say goddes seruys
vndeuowtly / &amp; with-outen reuerence. /
Bakbityng. / flateryng. / lesyng. /
missaiyng. / wariyng. / defamyng. /
flytyng. / manasyng. / sawyng of discorde. /
treson. / fals wytnes. / ill cownsell. /
hethyng. / vnboxumnes with worde. /
to turne gude dedes to ill, / for to gar
&thorn;am be halden ill &thorn;at dose &thorn;am&mdash; /
We aght to lappe oure neghboure dedes
in &thorn;e beste, noght in &thorn;e warst. /
excityng of any man till ire. / to reprehende
in a nother / &thorn;at he dose hym-self. /


<PB N="23">

vayne speche. / mykel speche. / fowle
speche. / to speke ydell wordes / or
wordes &thorn;at er na nede. / rusyng. /
polysyng of wordes. / defendyng of
synne. / criyng of laghter. / mowe
makyng on any man. / to syng seculere
sanges &amp; lufe &thorn;am. / to prayse ill dedes. /
to syng mare for louyng of men &thorn;an of
god. //<PTR TARGET="n1"> &THORN;e synnes of dede, er &thorn;ir:
Glotony. / letchery. / drunkynhede. / symony. /
wytchecraft. / brekyn[g] of &thorn;e haly dayes. /
sacrileghe. / to receyue goddes body in
dedely synn. / brekyng of vowes. /
apostasy. / dissolucioun in goddes
seruys. / to gyf ensawmpyl of il dede.  to
hurt any man in his body / or in his
godes / or in hys fame. / theft. / rauyn. /
vsur. / desayte. / sellyng of ryghtwysnes. /
to herken ill. / to gyf to herlotes. / to
withhalde necessaries fra &thorn;i body, / or
to gyf it to owtrage. / to begyn a thyng
&thorn;at es abowen oure myght. / custom to
syn. / fallyng oft to syn. / fenyng of
mare gude &thorn;an we haue, / for to seme
halyer / or conander / or wiser / &thorn;an
we er. / to halde &thorn;e office &thorn;at we suffice
noght till, or &thorn;at &thorn;at may noght be
halden with-outen syn. / to lede karols. /
to bryng vp new gyse. / to be rebell
agayne hys souerayns. / to defoule &thorn;am
&thorn;at er lesse. / To syn in syght, / in
heryng, / in smellyng, / in towchyng, /
in handelyng, / In swellyng; / In gyftes, /
In wayes, / sygnes, / bydynges,
writynges. / To receyue &thorn;e circumstance,
&thorn;at er: Tyme, / stede, / maner, /
nowmber, / person, / dwellyng, / conyng, /


<PB N="24">

elde: / &thorn;ir makes &thorn;e syn mare or lesse.
to couayte to syn or he be temped.  to
constreyne hym till syn. // Other many
syns &thorn;ar er of omission, &thorn;at es, of leuyng
of gude vndone: when men leues &thorn;e
gude &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld do: Noght thynkand
on god, / ne dredand, / ne louand hym, /
ne thankand hym of his benefices. / to
do noght all &thorn;at he doos for goddes
lufe. / to sorow noght for hys syn as
he sulde do. / to dispoos hym noght to
receyue grace. / And if he haue taken
grace, to vse it noght als hym aght, /
ne to kepe it noght. / to turne noght at
&thorn;e inspiracion of god. / to conforme
noght his will to gods will.  to gyf
noght entent till his prayers, / bot rabill
on, / &amp; rek neuer bot &thorn;ai be sayde. /
to do necligently &thorn;at he es bownden
till, thorow a vowe, / or comawnded, /
or es enioynde in penance. / to draw
on lengh &thorn;at es at do sone. / hauand
na ioy of his neghbur prophet als of
his awne; noght sorowand for his ill
fare. / standand noght agayne
temptacions. / forgifand noght &thorn;am &thorn;at hase
done hym harme. / kepand noght
trouth to his neghbur, als he walde
&thorn;at he dyd till hym; / and yheldand
hym noght a gude dede for a nother,
if he may. / Amendand noght &thorn;am &thorn;at
synnes be-fore his ene. / peesand noght
stryues. / lerand noght &thorn;am &thorn;at er noght
conand. / comfortand noght &thorn;am &thorn;at er
in sorow / or in sekenes / or in pouert /
or in penance / or in pryson.  / &THORN;ir
synnes, &amp; many other, makes men


<PB N="25">

foule.&mdash; // &THORN;e thynges &thorn;at clenses vs of
&thorn;at filth, er thre, agaynes &thorn;ase thre
maners of synnes. // &THORN;e fyrst es: sorow
of hert: agayne &thorn;e syn of thoght.  Ant
it behoues be perfite: &thorn;at &thorn;ou will
neuer syn mare.  And &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue
sorow of all &thorn;i synnes.  And &thorn;at all
ioy &amp; solace, bot of god &amp; in god, be
put out of &thorn;i hert. / &THORN;e to&thorn;er es:
schryft of mouth: agayn &thorn;e syn of
mouth.  And &thorn;at salle be hasty,
with-outen delaying.  Naked, with-outen
excusyng.  Hale, with-owten partyng:
Als forto tell a syn till a preste, &amp; a nother
till a nother.  Say all &thorn;at &thorn;ow wate till
ane: or els &thorn;i schryft es noght worth. //
&THORN;e third es: satisfaccion: &THORN;at has thre
partyes: Fastyng, Prayer, &amp; Almos-dede.
Noght anly to gif pore men mete &amp; drynk: bot for to forgyf &thorn;am &thorn;at dose
&thorn;e wrange, &amp; prai for &thorn;am; / and
enforme &thorn;am how &thorn;ai sall do &thorn;at er in
poynt to perisch.&mdash; // For &thorn;e thyrd
thyng, &thorn;ou sall wyt &thorn;at clennes behoues
be keped in hert, &amp; in mouth, &amp; in
werk. / Clennes of hert, thre thynges
kepes: Ane es, waker thoght &amp; stabel
of god.  A nother es, bisynes to kepe
&thorn;i fyue wittes; sa &thorn;at all &thorn;e wyked
styryngs of &thorn;am be closed out of &thorn;e
flesche. / &THORN;e third, honest occupacion
and prophetabyll. // Alswa, clennes of
mouth, kepes thre thynges: Ane es, &thorn;at
&thorn;ow vmthynk &thorn;e before, or &thorn;ou speke.
A nother es, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not of mikel
speche, but of litel; &amp; namly ay til &thorn;i
hert be stabeld in &thorn;e luf of Ihesu Cryst:


<PB N="26">

swa &thorn;at &thorn;e thynk &thorn;at &thorn;ou lokes ay on
hym, whether &thorn;ou speke or noght.  Bot
swilk a grace may &thorn;ou noght haue in &thorn;e
fyrst day; bot with lang trauell, &amp; grete
bysines to lof hym with custom, so
&thorn;at &thorn;e egh of &thorn;i hert be ay vpwarde,
sall &thorn;ou |com &thorn;ar-till.  / &THORN;e thyrd:&thorn;at
&thorn;ou for nathyng, ne for na mekenes,
lye on any man.  For ilk a lee es syn,
&amp; il, &amp; noght goddes will.  The thar
noght tell all &thorn;e soth ay, bot if &thorn;ow
will.  Bot al lees hate.  Yf &thorn;ou say a
thyng of &thorn;i self &thorn;at semes &thorn;i louyng:
&amp; &thorn;ou say it to &thorn;e louyng of god and
help of other, &thorn;ou dos noght vnwisely,
for &thorn;ou spekes sothfastnes.  Bot if &thorn;ou
will haue oght pryue: tel it til nane
bot swylk ane, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be syker &thorn;at it
sulde noght be schewed bot anly til &thorn;e
louyng of god, of wham es all gudenes,
&amp; &thorn;at makes som&macr; better &thorn;an o&thorn;er, and
gifes &thorn;am special grace, noght anely
for &thorn;am-self, bot alswa for &thorn;am &thorn;at
wil do wele after &thorn;aire ensawmpell.  //
Clennes of werk, thre thynges keps:
Ane es, a bysi thoght of dede&mdash;For &thorn;e
wyse man says: &laquo;Vmbethynk &thorn;e of &thorn;i
last endyng: and &thorn;ou sall noght syn.&raquo;
Another: fle fra ill felyschypp, &thorn;at gyfs
mare ensawmpel to luf &thorn;e worlde &thorn;an
god, erth &thorn;an heuen, filth of body &thorn;an
clennes of saule.  // &THORN;e third es:
temperance &amp; discrecion in mete &amp; drynk:
&thorn;at it be nowther til owtrage, ne beneth
skilwys sustinance for &thorn;i body.  For
both comes til an ende: owtrage, &amp; ouer-mykel fastyng: for nowther es gods
will&mdash;&amp; &thorn;at many wil noght wene, for


<PB N="27">

noght &thorn;at man may say.  / Yf &thorn;ou take
sustenance of swilk gude als god sendys
for &thorn;e tyme &amp; &thorn;e day, what it be, I
owt-take na maner of mete &thorn;at cristen
men vses, with discrecion &amp; mesur:
&thorn;ou dose wele, for sa dyd Criste
hymself, &amp; hys apostels.  / Yf &thorn;ou leue many
metes &thorn;at men has; noght dispysand
&thorn;e mete &thorn;at god has made til mannes
helpe, bot for &thorn;e thynk &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase
na nede &thorn;arof; &thorn;ou dose wele, If &thorn;ou
se &thorn;at &thorn;ow ert stalworth to serue god,
&amp; &thorn;at it brekes noght &thorn;i stomake.  For
if &thorn;ou haue broken it with oure-mikel
abstynence, the es reft appetyte of mete;
and oft sal &thorn;ou be in qwathes, als &thorn;ou
war redy to gyf &thorn;e gast.  And wit
&thorn;ou wele, &thorn;ou synned in &thorn;at dede.  //
And &thorn;ou may not witt some whethir &thorn;i
abstinence be agayne &thorn;e, or with
&thorn;e.  For &thorn;e tyme &thorn;ou ert &yogh;ong, I rede &thorn;at
&thorn;ou ete &amp; drynk, better &amp; war, als it
comes, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be noght be-gylt.  And
after-warde, when &thorn;ou has proued
many thynges, &amp; ouer-commen many
temptacions, &amp; knawes better &thorn;i-self &amp; god &thorn;an &thorn;ou dyd: &thorn;an, if &thorn;ou se &thorn;at it be at do, &thorn;ou mai take til mare
abstinence.  And whils &thorn;ou may do pryue
penance, &thorn;at al men thar noght
wyt.  Ryghtwysnes es noght al in fastyng, ne
in etyng: Bot &thorn;ou ert ryghtwys, if all
ilyke be to &thorn;e despyte &amp; louyng, pouert
&amp; rytches, hunger &amp; nede, als delytes
&amp; dayntes.  If &thorn;ou take &thorn;ir with a
lowyng of god: I halde &thorn;e blyssed, &amp; hee before Ihesu.  Men &thorn;at comes til
&thorn;e, &thorn;ai luf &thorn;e for &thorn;ai se &thorn;i grete
abstinens, &amp; for &thorn;ai se &thorn;e enclosed: Bot


<PB N="28">

I may not loue &thorn;e so lyghtly, for oght
&thorn;at I se &thorn;e do withowten: bot if &thorn;i
wil be conformed enterely to goddes
will.  And sett noght by &thorn;ar louyng
ne &thorn;ar lackyng, and gyf &thorn;ou neuer tale
if &thorn;ai speke lesse gode of &thorn;e &thorn;an &thorn;ai
dyd: bot &thorn;at &thorn;ou be byrnander in
goddes luf &thorn;an &thorn;ou was.  For a thyng
warne I &thorn;e: I hope &thorn;at god has na
perfyte seruand in erth with-outen
ennemyes of som men&mdash;For anely
wretchednes has na enmy.  // Forto draw vs
&thorn;at we conforme oure will till goddes
will: er thre thynges.  Ane es,
ensawmpel of haly men &amp; haly wymen,
&thorn;e whilk war ententife, nyght &amp; day,
to serue god &amp; drede hym, and luf
hym.  And we folow &thorn;am in erth, we mon&macr; be with
&thorn;am in heuen.  Another es, &thorn;e godenes
of oure lorde, &thorn;at despises nane, bot
gladly receyues all &thorn;at comes till hys
mercy; &amp; he es hamlyer to &thorn;am &thorn;an
brother or syster, or any frende &thorn;at
&thorn;ai maste luf, or maste treystes
on.  /&THORN;e thyrd es: &thorn;e wonderfull ioy of &thorn;e
kyngdom of heuen, &thorn;at es mare &thorn;an
tong may tell, or hert mai thynk, or
egh may se, or ere may here.  It es
swa mykel, &thorn;at, als in hel myght na
thyng lyue for mykel pyne, bot at &thorn;e
myght of god suffers &thorn;am noght to
dye: swa &thorn;e ioy in &thorn;e syght of Ihesu
in his godhede es swa mykel, &thorn;at &thorn;ai
mond dye for ioy, if it ne war his
godenes, &thorn;at will &thorn;at his louers be
lyuand ay in blys: als his ryghtwysnes
wil &thorn;at al &thorn;at lufed hym noght, be ay
lyuand in fyre, &thorn;at es horribel till any
man at thynk, loke &thorn;en what it es to


<PB N="29">

fele.  Bot &thorn;ai &thorn;at will not thynk it &amp; drede it now, &thorn;ai sal suffer it
euermare.  Now hase &thorn;ow herd how &thorn;ou
may dispose &thorn;i lyfe, and rewle it to
goddes will.  Bot I vate wele &thorn;at &thorn;ou
desyres to here some special poynt
of &thorn;e luf of Ihesu Criste, &amp; of
contemplatyf lyfe, &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ou hase taken
&thorn;e till at mens syght.  Als I haue grace
&amp; konnyng, I will lere &thorn;e.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. VII<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">(A)More langueo.</FOREIGN>  / &THORN;ir twa wordes
er wryten in &thorn;e boke of lufe, &thorn;at es
kalled &thorn;e sang of lufe, or &thorn;e sang of
sanges.  / For he &thorn;at mykel lufes, hym
lyst oft syng of his luf, for Ioy &thorn;at he
or scho hase when &thorn;ai thynk on &thorn;at
&thorn;at &thorn;ai lufe, namely if &thorn;air louer be
trew &amp; lufand.  / And &thorn;is es &thorn;e Inglisch
of thies twa wordes: &laquo;I languysch for
lufe&raquo;.  // Sere men in erth has sere gyftes
&amp; graces of god: bot &thorn;e special gift of
&thorn;as &thorn;at ledes solitary lyf, es for to lufe
Ihesu Criste.  / &THORN;ow says me: &laquo;all men
lufes hym &thorn;at haldes his
comawndementes.&raquo;  Soth it es.  Bot all men &thorn;at
kepes hys byddyngs, kepes noght also
hys cownsayle.  And all &thorn;at dos his
cownsell, er noght also fulfyld of &thorn;e
swetnes of his lufe, ne feles noght &thorn;e
fyre of byrnand luf of hert.  / For&thorn;i, &thorn;e
diuersite of lufe, makes &thorn;e diuersite of
halynes &amp; of mede.  / In heuen, &thorn;e
awngels &thorn;at er byrnandest in lufe, er
nerrest god.  / Also men &amp; women &thorn;at
maste has of goddes lufe, whether &thorn;ai
do penance or nane: &thorn;ai sall be in &thorn;e
heghest degre in heuen; &thorn;ai &thorn;at lufes


<PB N="30">

hym lesse, in &thorn;e lawer order.  If &thorn;ou
lufe hym mykel: mykel ioy &amp; swetnes
&amp; byrnyng &thorn;ou feles in his lufe, &thorn;at es
&thorn;i comforth &amp; strengh, nyght &amp; day. /
If &thorn;i lufe be not byrnand in hym:
litel es &thorn;i delyte.  For hym may naman
fele in ioy &amp; swetnes, bot if &thorn;ai be
clene, &amp; fylled with his lufe: and
&thorn;artill sal &thorn;ou com with grete trauayle in
praier &amp; thynkyng: hauand swilk
meditacions &thorn;at er al in &thorn;e lufe &amp; in &thorn;e
louyng of god. // And when &thorn;ou ert at
&thorn;i mete: loue ay god in &thorn;i thoght, at
ilk a morsel, &amp; say &thorn;us in &thorn;i hert:
Loued be &thorn;ou keyng, &amp; thanked be &thorn;ou
keyng, &amp; blyssed be &thorn;ou keyng, Ihesu
all my ioyng, of all &thorn;i giftes gude: &thorn;at
for me spylt &thorn;i blude, &amp; died on &thorn;e
rude; &thorn;ou gyf me grace to syng, &thorn;e
sang of &thorn;i louyng. / And thynk it noght
anely whils &thorn;ou etes: bot bath before
&amp; after, ay bot when &thorn;ou prayes or
spekes.  Or if &thorn;ou haue other thoghtes
&thorn;at &thorn;ou has mare swetnes in &amp; deuocion,
&thorn;an in &thorn;ase &thorn;at I lere &thorn;e: &thorn;ou may
thynk [&thorn;am].  For I hope &thorn;at god will do
swilk thoghtes in &thorn;i hert, als he es
payde of, &amp; als &thorn;ou ert ordaynde for. /
When &thorn;ou prayes, loke noght how mykel
&thorn;ou says, bot how wele: &thorn;at &thorn;e lofe
of &thorn;i hert be ay vpwarde, &amp; thy thoght
on &thorn;at &thorn;ou sayes, als mykel als &thorn;ow
may. / If &thorn;ou be in prayers &amp; meditacions al &thorn;e day: I wate wele &thorn;at &thorn;ou
mon wax gretely in &thorn;e lufe of Ihesu


<PB N="31">

Cryste, &amp; mikel fele of delyte, and
within schort tyme.
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum VIII<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(T)Hre degrees of lufe I sal tell
&thorn;e: for I walde &thorn;at &thorn;ou moght wyn
to &thorn;e heest.  The fyrst degre es called
insuperabel. / &THORN;e secund, Inseparabel. /
&THORN;e thyrd es, syngulere.  &THORN;i luf es
Insuperabel: when na thyng &thorn;at es
contrary til gods lufe, ouer-comes it: bot
es stalworth, agayns al fandyngs; and
stabel, whether &thorn;ou be in ese or in
angwys, or in hele or in sekenes; swa
&thorn;at &thorn;e thynk &thorn;at &thorn;ow walde noght,
for all &thorn;e worlde to haue it with-owten
ende, wreth god any tyme; / and &thorn;e
war leuer, if outher sulde be, to suffer
al &thorn;e pyne &amp; waa &thorn;at myght com til
any creature, or &thorn;ou wald do &thorn;e thyng
&thorn;at suld mys- pay hym. / On &thorn;is maner
sal &thorn;i lufe be Insuperabel, &thorn;at na thyng
may downe bryng bot spryngand on
heght. / Blyssed es he or scho &thorn;at es
in &thorn;is degre: bot &yogh;itt er &thorn;ai blyssedar
&thorn;at myght halde &thorn;is degre, &amp; wyn in
til &thorn;e to&thorn;er, &thorn;at es Inseparabel. //
Inseparabel es &thorn;i lufe: when al &thorn;i hert,
&amp; &thorn;i thoght, &amp; &thorn;i myght, es swa haly,
swa enterely, and swa perfytely festend,
sett, &amp; stabeld in Ihesu Cryste: &thorn;at &thorn;i
thoght comes neuer of hym, neuer
departyd fra hym, outaken slepyng; / and
als sone als &thorn;ou wackens, &thorn;i hert es on
hym, sayand: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aue maria</FOREIGN>, or <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gloria
tibi domine</FOREIGN>, or <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN>, or <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mise-


<PB N="32">

rere mei deus</FOREIGN> if &thorn;ou haue bene temped
in &thorn;i slepe; or thynkand on his lufe, &amp; his louyng, als &thorn;ou dyd wakand.  When
&thorn;ou may na tyme forgete hym, what sa
&thorn;ou dose or says: &thorn;an es &thorn;i lufe
Inseparabel. / Ful mykel grace haue &thorn;ai &thorn;at
es in &thorn;is degre of lufe. / And me thynk,
&thorn;ou &thorn;at hase noght els at do bot forto lufe
god, may com &thorn;artill if any may gete it.
</P>
<P>// &THORN;e thyrd degre es heest, &amp; maste
ferly to wyn: &THORN;at es calde Synguler,
for it hase na pere. / Singuler lufe
es: when all comforth &amp; solace es
closed owt of &thorn;i hert, bot of Ihesu
Cryste al-ane.  Other ioy lyst it noght.
/ For &thorn;e swetnes of hym in &thorn;is degre
es swa comfortand, &amp; lastand in his
lufe, sa byrnand &amp; gladand, &thorn;at he
or scho &thorn;at es in &thorn;is degre, mai als
wele fele &thorn;e fyre of lufe byrnand in
&thorn;aire saule, als &thorn;ou may fele &thorn;i fynger
byrn, if &thorn;ou putt it in &thorn;e fyre.  Bot
&thorn;at fire, if it be hate, es swa delitabell
&amp; wondyrful, &thorn;at I kan noght tell it.
&THORN;an &thorn;i sawle es Ihesu lufand, / Ihesu
thynkand, / Ihesu desirand, anly in &thorn;e
couayties of hym anedande, / til hym
syngand, / of hym byrnand, / in hym
restand.  &THORN;an &thorn;e sange of louyng &amp; of
lufe es commen. / &THORN;an &thorn;i thoght turnes
in til sang &amp; in til melody. // &THORN;an &thorn;e
behoues syng &thorn;e psalmes, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
before sayde.  &THORN;an &thorn;ou mon be lang
abowte few psalmes. / &THORN;an &thorn;e wil thynk
&thorn;e deed swettar &thorn;an hony, for &thorn;an &thorn;ou
ert ful syker, to se hym &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes.
[&THORN;an may &thorn;ou hardyly say: &laquo;I languysch
for lufe.&raquo;]  &THORN;an may &thorn;ou say: &laquo;I slepe: &amp;


<PB N="33">

my hert wakes.&raquo; // In &thorn;e first degre men
may say &laquo;I languysch for lufe&raquo; or &laquo;me
langes in lufe,&raquo; &amp; in &thorn;e to&thorn;er degre
alswa, / ffor languysyng es, when men
fayles for sekenes, and &thorn;ai &thorn;at er in
&thorn;ire twa degrees, fayles fra al &thorn;e
couayties of &thorn;is worlde &amp; fra lust &amp; lykyng of synful lyfe, &amp; settes &thorn;air entent
&amp; &thorn;air hert to &thorn;e lufe of god &mdash;
for-&thorn;i &thorn;ai may say: &laquo;I languysch for lufe;&raquo;
and mykel mare &thorn;at er in &thorn;e secund
degre, &thorn;an in &thorn;e fyrst.  Bot &thorn;e sawle
&thorn;at es in &thorn;e thyrd degre, es als
byrnand fyre, and as &thorn;e nyghttyngale,
&thorn;at lufes sang &amp; melody, &amp; fayles for
mykel lufe; swa &thorn;at &thorn;e saule es [anely]
comforted in louyng &amp; lufyng of god,
and til &thorn;e dede com, es syngand
gastly til Ihesu, and in Ihesu, and
Ihesu, noght (bodyly) cryand wyth mouth
&mdash;of &thorn;at maner of syn(gyng sp)eke
I noght, for &thorn;at sang hase bath g(ude
&) ill; and &thorn;is maner of sang hase
nane bot if &thorn;ai be in &thorn;is thyrd degre
of lufe: til &thorn;e whilk degre is es
impossibel to com bot in a grete
multitude of lufe. / For-&thorn;i, if &thorn;ou will wytt
whatkyn ioy &thorn;at sang has, I say &thorn;e,
&thorn;at naman wate bot he or scho &thorn;at
feles it, &thorn;at has it, &amp; &thorn;at loues god,
syngand &thorn;arwyth.  A thyng tel I &thorn;e:
it es of heuen, &amp; god gyfes it til wham
he wil: bot noght with-outen grete
grace comand be-fore.  Wha hase it,
hym thynk al &thorn;e sang &amp; al &thorn;e
mynstralcy of erth noght bot sorow &amp; wa,
&thorn;artil. / In souerayne rest sal &thorn;ai be
&thorn;at may gete it.  Gangrels, and
Iangelers, &amp; Kepers of comers and gangars


<PB N="34">

arely &amp; late, nyght &amp; day, or any
&thorn;at es takked with any syn wilfully &amp; wittandly, or &thorn;at has delyte in any
erthly thyng: &thorn;ai er als far &thorn;ar-fra als
es fra heuen to erth. / In &thorn;e fyrst
degre er many; in &thorn;e to&thorn;er degre er ful
faa: bot in &thorn;e thyrde degre vnnethes
er any: for ay &thorn;e mare &thorn;at &thorn;e
perfeccion es, &thorn;e faer folowers it has.  In &thorn;e
fyrst degre, er men lickend to &thorn;e
sternes; In &thorn;e to&thorn;er: till &thorn;e mone; In
&thorn;e thyrd: til &thorn;e sonne.  For-&thorn;i says
saynt Paule: &laquo;Other of &thorn;e sonne, other
of &thorn;e mone, other of &thorn;e sternes;&raquo; / swa
it es of &thorn;e lufers of god. / In &thorn;is third
degre, if &thorn;ou may wyn &thorn;ar-till, &thorn;ou
sall witt of mare ioy &thorn;an I haue talde
&thorn;e (&yogh;i)tt. // And ymang other affeccions
&amp; sanges, &thorn;ou (may in &thorn;i) langyng syng
&thorn;is in &thorn;i hert / til &thorn;i lorde Ihesu, (when)
&thorn;ou couaytes hys comyng, &amp; &thorn;i gangyng:
When will &thorn;ow com to comforth me,
and bryng me owt of care, / &amp; gyf me
&thorn;e &thorn;at I may se, hauand euer-mare?
/ &THORN;i lufe es ay swettest, of al &thorn;at euer
war: / My hert when sal it brest? for
lufe &thorn;an languyst I namare. / For
lufe my thoght has fest, &amp; I am fayne
to fare. // I stand in still mowrnyng of al
lufelyest of lare;..  es lufe langyng, //
It drawes me til my day: &THORN;e band of
swete byrnyng, for it haldes me ay Fra
place &amp; fra plaiyng, til &thorn;at I get may
&THORN;e syght of my swetyng, &thorn;at wendes
neuer away, In welth bees oure wakyng,
wyth-owten noy or nyght: My lufe es
in lastyng, &amp; langes to &thorn;at syght.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<PB N="35"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum nonum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P><PTR TARGET="n2">(I)F &thorn;ou wil be wele with god, &amp; haue grace to rewle &thorn;i lyf, &amp; com til
&thorn;e ioy of luf: &thorn;is name IHESU fest it
swa fast in &thorn;i hert, &thorn;at it com neuer owt
of &thorn;i thoght.  And when &thorn;ou spekes til hym
&amp; says Ihesu thurgh custom, it sal be in
&thorn;i ere ioy, in &thorn;i mouth hony, &amp; in &thorn;i hert
melody: For &thorn;e sall thynk ioy to here &thorn;at
name be neuend, swetnes to speke it, myrth
&amp; sang to thynk it. / If &thorn;ou thynk Ihesu
contynuly, &amp; halde it stabely, it purges
&thorn;i syn, / &amp; kyndels &thorn;i hert; / it
clarifies &thorn;i sawle; / it remoues anger, / &amp; dose away slawnes. / It woundes in
lufe, / &amp; fulfilles of charite. / It chaces
&thorn;e deuel, / &amp; puttes oute drede. / It
opens heuen / &amp; makes a contemplatif
man. / Haue in mynde Ihesu: for al
vices &amp; fantomes it puttes owte fra &thorn;e
louer.  And haylce oft Mary, bath day
and nyght.  Mikel lufe &amp; ioy sal &thorn;ou
fele, if &thorn;ou wil do aftyr &thorn;is lare. / &THORN;e
thare noght couayte gretely many bokes:
halde lufe in hert, &amp; in werke, and &thorn;ou
hase al &thorn;at we may say or wryte: for fulnes
of &thorn;e law es charite; in &thorn;at hynges all.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. X<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(B)Ot now may &thorn;ou ask me &amp; say: &laquo;&THORN;ou spekes sa mykel of lufe: tel
me / What es lufe, An [d] whar es lufe,
/ And how I sal lufe god verrayly,
/ And how &thorn;at I may knaw &thorn;at I lufe
hym, / And in what state I may maste
lufe hym.&raquo; / &THORN;ir er hard questyons to
lere, til a febyll man &amp; a fleschly als I
am.  Bot neuer-&thorn;e-latter &thorn;ar-fore I sal


<PB N="36">

noght lette &thorn;at I ne sall schew my
wytt, &amp; als me thynk &thorn;at it may be.
For I hope in &thorn;e helpe of Ihesu, &thorn;at
es wel of lufe, &amp; pees, and swetnes. /
&THORN;e Fyrst askyng es: What es lufe?
And I answer: Luf es a byrnand
&yogh;ernyng in god, with a wonderfull delyte
&amp; sykernes.  God es lyght, &amp; byrnyng.
Lyght clarifies oure skyll, byrnyng
kyndels oure couayties, &thorn;at we desyre
noght bot hym.  Lufe es a lyf,
copuland to-gedyr &thorn;e lufand &amp; &thorn;e lufed: /
For mekenes makes vs swete to god,
Purete ioynes vs tyll god, Lufe mase
vs ane with god; luf es fayrhede
of al vertues.  Luf es thyng thurgh
&thorn;e whilk god lufes vs, &amp; we god,
&amp; ilk ane of vs other.  Lufe es
desyre of &thorn;e hert, ay thynkand til
&thorn;at &thorn;at it lufes; and when it hase
&thorn;at it lufes, &thorn;an it ioyes &amp; na thyng
may make it sary.  [Luf es &yogh;ernyng
Imelle twa, with lastandnes of thoghtes].
Lufe es a st[i]ryng of &thorn;e saule for to luf
god for hym-self, &amp; all other thyng for
god; &thorn;e whilk lufe, when it es ordaynde
in god, it dose away all inordinate lufe
in any thyng &thorn;at es noght gude.  Bot
al dedely syn es inordynate lufe in a
thyng &thorn;at es noght: &thorn;an lufe puttes
out al dedely syn.  Luf es a vertu, &thorn;at
es rightest affection of man saule.  Trowth
may be with-outen lufe: bot it may
noght helpe with-outen it.  Lufe es
perfection of letters, vertu of prophecy,
frute of trowth, help of sacramentes,
stablyng of witt and conyng; Rytches
of pure men, lyfe of dyand men.  Se


<PB N="37">

how gude lufe es.  If we suffer to be
slayne; If we gyf al &thorn;at we haue, til
beggar staf; If we kan als mykel als
al men kan in erth: til al &thorn;is
with-outen lufe es noght bot sorow ordande
&amp; torment. / If &thorn;ou will aske how gode
es he or scho: ask how mykel lufes he
or scho: &amp; &thorn;at kan na man tel &mdash; /
For I hald it bot foly to deme a mans
hert, &thorn;at nane knawes bot god.  Lufe
es a ryghtwis turnyng fra al ert[h]ly
thynges, &amp; es ioynd til god, with-outen
departyng, and kyndelde with &thorn;e fire
of &thorn;e haly gaste; fer fra fylyng, fer
fra corrupcion, oblyst till na vice of &thorn;is
lyfe.  Hegh aboven all fleschely lustes,
ay redy &amp; gredy til contemplacion of
god.  In all thynges noght
ouercomen. /  &THORN;e sowme of al gude affectyons.  Hele
of gude maners, ende of
comawndementes of god; dede of synnes, lyf of
vertues.  Vertu, whils feghtyng lastes;
crowne of ouercomers.  Mirynes til
haly thoghtes.  With-outen &thorn;at, na man
may pay god; with &thorn;at, na man
synnes: For if we luf god in al oure
hert, &thorn;ar es na thyng in vs, thurgh &thorn;e
whilk we serue to syn.  Verray luf
clenses &thorn;e saule, &amp; delyuers it fra &thorn;e
pyne of hell, &amp; of &thorn;e foule seruys of
syn, &amp; of &thorn;e vgly felyschip of &thorn;e
deuels; and of &thorn;e fendes son&macr; makes god
son&macr;, &amp; parcener of &thorn;e heritage of heuen.
/ We sall afforce [vs] at cleth vs in lufe
als &thorn;e yren or &thorn;e cole dose in &thorn;e fyre;
als &thorn;e ayer dose in &thorn;e son&macr;; als &thorn;e
woll dose in &thorn;e hewe. / &THORN;e cole swa
clethes it in &thorn;e fyre, &thorn;at al es fyre.  [&THORN;e
ayre swa clethes it in &thorn;e son &thorn;at al es


<PB N="38">

light].  And &thorn;e woll swa substancialy
takes &thorn;e hewe, &thorn;at it es lik it. / In &thorn;is
maner sall a trewe lufar of Ihesu Criste
do: his hert sal swa byrne in lufe, &thorn;at it
sal be turned in til fyre of lufe, &amp; be
als it war al fire; and he sal sa schyne
in vertues, &thorn;at in na parte of hym he
be myrke in vices. // &THORN;e tother askyng
es: Whare es lufe?  And I answer:
lufe es in &thorn;e hert, &amp; in &thorn;e will
of mane; noght in hys hand, ne in
his mouth, &thorn;at es at say, noght in
hys wark: bot in his sawle. / For
many spekes gode &amp; dose gode, &amp; lufes noght god: als ypocrites, &thorn;e
whilk suffers grete penance &amp; semes
haly at mens syght: Bot for &thorn;ai seke
louyng &amp; honoure of men, &amp; fauoure,
&thorn;ai haue lost &thorn;ar mede, &amp; in &thorn;e syght
of god er &thorn;e deuel sons, &amp; rauysand
wlues.  Bot if a man gyf almose-dede,
&amp; take hym til pouert, &amp; do penance,
it es a signe &thorn;at he lufes god: bot
&thorn;arfore lufes he hym noght, bot when
he forsakes &thorn;e worlde anly for goddes
lufe, &amp; settes al his thoght on god, &amp; lufes al men als hym-self; and al &thorn;e
gude dedes &thorn;at he may do, he dose
&thorn;am in entent forto pay Ihesu Criste,
&amp; to cum til &thorn;e rest of heuen. / &THORN;an
he lufes god: &amp; &thorn;at luf es in his saule,
and sa his dedes schewes with-outen.
If &thorn;ou speke &thorn;e gude &amp; do &thorn;e gude,
men supposes &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes god:
forthi loke wele &thorn;at &thorn;i thoght be in god,
or elles &thorn;ou dampnes &thorn;i-selfe, &amp; deceyues &thorn;e men. / Na thyng &thorn;at I do
with-owten, proues &thorn;at I lufe god. /


<PB N="39">

For a wicked man myght do als mykel
penance in body, als mykel wake and
faste, als I do.  How may I &thorn;an wene
&thorn;at I lufe, or halde me better, for &thorn;at
&thorn;at ilk a man may do?  Certes, mi hert,
whethir it lufe my god or noght, wate
na man bot god, for noght &thorn;at &thorn;ai
may se me do.  Wharfore luf es in will
verraily, noght in warke bot in a signe
of lufe.  For he &thorn;at says he lufes god,
&amp; wil noght do in dede &thorn;at in hym
es to schew lufe: say hym &thorn;at he
lyghes.  Lufe wil noght be ydel: it es
wirkand som gude euer-mare.  If it
sesse of wirkyng: wit &thorn;ou &thorn;at it keles
&amp; wytes away. // &THORN;e thirde askyng es:
&laquo;How sal I verrayli lufe god?&raquo;  I answer:
/ Verray lufe es: to lufe hym in al &thorn;i
myght, stalwortly; In al &thorn;i hert, wysely;
In al &thorn;i sawle, deuowtely &amp; swetely. /
Stalwortly may na man lufe hym, bot
he be stalworth.  He es stalworth &thorn;at
es meke, for al gastly strengh comes of
mekenes;&mdash;on whame restes &thorn;e haly
gaste? in a meke sawle.  Mekenes
gouernes vs &amp; kepes vs in al oure
temptacions, swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai ouercom&macr; vs noght.
Bot &thorn;e deuel deceyues many &thorn;at er
meke thorow tribulacions, &amp; reproues,
&amp; bakebitynges.  Bot if &thorn;ou be wrath
for any anguys of &thorn;is worlde, or for
any worde &thorn;at men says of &thorn;e, or for
oght &thorn;at men says til &thorn;e: &thorn;ou ert
noght meke, ne &thorn;ou may swa lufe god
stalwortly.  For luf es stalworth als &thorn;e
dede, &thorn;at slaes al lyuand thyng in


<PB N="40">

erth; and hard als hell, &thorn;at spares
noght till &thorn;am &thorn;at er dede.  And he
&thorn;at lufes god perfitely, he greues hym
noght, what schame or angwys &thorn;at he
suffers, bot he hase delyte, &amp; couaytes
&thorn;at he war worthy forto suffer torment
&amp; payne for Crystes lufe; and he hase
ioy &thorn;at men reproues hym &amp; spekes ill
of hym.  Als a dede man, what-sa
men dos or sayes, he answers noght:
Ryght swa, wha sa lufes god perfitely,
&thorn;ai er not stirred for any worde &thorn;at
man may say.  For he or scho kan
noght lufe &thorn;at may noght suffer payne
&amp; anger for &thorn;air frendes lufe.  For
wha sa lufes, &thorn;ai haue na [pyne].
Prowde men or women lufes noght
stalworthly: for &thorn;ai er swa wayke, &thorn;at
&thorn;ai fall at ilk a styryng of &thorn;e wynde,
&thorn;at es temptacion. / &THORN;ai seke heghar
stede &thorn;an Cryste: for &thorn;ai wil haue &thorn;air
wil done,  whethir it be with right or
with wrang: and Cryst will nathyng
be done bot wele, &amp; with-outen harme
of othir men. / Bot wha sa es verrayly
meke, &thorn;ai wil noght haue &thorn;air wil in
&thorn;is worlde, bot &thorn;at &thorn;ai may haue it
in &thorn;e to&thorn;er plenarly.  In na thyng may
men sonar ouercom &thorn;e deuel, &thorn;an in
Mekenes, &thorn;at he mykel hates. / For
he may wake &amp; faste, &amp; suffer pyne,
mare &thorn;an any other creature may: Bot
mekenes &amp; lufe may he noght haue.
// Alswa &thorn;e behoues luf god wysely: and
&thorn;at may &thorn;ou noght do bot if &thorn;ou be
wyse. / &THORN;ou ert wyse: when &thorn;ou ert
pore, with-owten couaytyse of &thorn;is world,


<PB N="41">

&amp; dispyses &thorn;i-selfe, for &thorn;e lufe of
Ihesu Cryste; / and dispendes al &thorn;i
witte &amp; al &thorn;i myght in hys seruys. //
For sum &thorn;at semes wysest, er maste
foles, for al &thorn;ar wysdom &thorn;ai spyll in
couayties, &amp; bisynes abowte &thorn;e world. /
If &thorn;ou saw a man haue preciouse stanes,
&thorn;at he myght by a kyngdom wyth; if
he gaf &thorn;am for an appyl, als a barne
wil do: ryghtwysly moght &thorn;ou say &thorn;at
he war noght wyse, bot a grete fole. /
Als swa, if we wyl: we haue preciouse
stanes: Pouert, &amp; penance, and gastly
trauayle: with &thorn;e whilk we may by &thorn;e
kyngdom&macr; of heuen. / For if &thorn;ou lufe
pouert, &amp; dispyse riches, &amp; delytes of
&thorn;is worlde, &amp; halde &thorn;i-self vyle &amp; pure,
&amp; thynk &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase noght of &thorn;i self
bot syn: for &thorn;is pouert &thorn;ou sall haue
rytches with-outen ende. / And if &thorn;ou
haue sorowe for &thorn;i synnes, &amp; for &thorn;ou
ert swa lang in exile, owte of &thorn;i
contre, &amp; forsakes &thorn;e solace of &thorn;is lyfe:
&thorn;ou sal haue for &thorn;is sorow, &thorn;e ioy of
heuen.  And if &thorn;ou be in trauayle, &amp; punysche &thorn;i body, skilwisly &amp; wisely,
in wakyns, fastyngs, &amp; in prayers, &amp; meditacions, &amp; suffer hete, &amp; calde,
hunger &amp; thyrst, mys-es &amp; anguys, for
&thorn;e lufe of Ihesu Cryste: for &thorn;is trauel
&thorn;ou sal com till reste &thorn;at lastes ay, &amp; syt in a setel of ioy, with aungels.
But som er &thorn;at lufes noght wysely,
like til barnes, &thorn;at lufes mare an appel
&thorn;an a castel.  Swa dose many; &thorn;ai gyf
&thorn;e ioy of heuen for a litel delyte of
&thorn;ar flesche, &thorn;at es noght worth a
plowme.  Now may &thorn;ow se &thorn;at wha


<PB N="42">

sa will lufe wysely, hym behoues lufe
lastand thyng lastandly; &amp; passand
thyng, passandly: swa &thorn;at his hert be
sette &amp; festend in nathyng bot in god. //
And if &thorn;ou will luf Ihesu verraly, &thorn;ow
sal noght anly lufe hym stalwortly &amp; wysely: bot also deuowtly &amp; swetely.
Swete lufe es: when &thorn;i body es chaste,
&amp; &thorn;i thoght clene.  Deuowte luf es:
when &thorn;ou offers &thorn;i prayers &amp; &thorn;i
thoghtes til god with gastly ioy, &amp; byrnand
hert in &thorn;e hete of &thorn;e haly gaste, swa
&thorn;at &thorn;e thynk &thorn;at &thorn;i saule es als it
war drunken for delyte &amp; solace of &thorn;e
swetnes of Ihesu, / and &thorn;i hert
conceyues sa mykel of goddes helpe, &thorn;at
&thorn;e thynk &thorn;at &thorn;ow may neuer be fra
hym departyd; and &thorn;an &thorn;ou comes in
til swilk rest &amp; pees in sawle, &amp; quiete,
with-owten thoghtes of vanitese [or] of
vices, als &thorn;ou war in sylence &amp; slepe, &amp; sette in Noe schyppe, &thorn;at na thyng may
lette &thorn;e of deuocion &amp; byrnyng of swete
lufe. / Fra &thorn;ou haue getyn &thorn;is lufe:
all &thorn;i lyf, til dede come, es ioy &amp; comforth, and verrayli Cristes lufer,
and he restes in &thorn;e, whas stede es
maked in pees. / &THORN;e ferth askyng was:
how &thorn;ou moght knaw &thorn;at &thorn;ou war in
lufe &amp; charite. / I answer: &thorn;at na man
wate in erth &thorn;at &thorn;ai er in charite: bot
if it be thorow any priuelege or special
grace &thorn;at god hase gifen til any man
or woman; &thorn;at al other may noght
take ensawmpel by.  Haly men &amp; women
trowes &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue trowth, &amp; hope,
&amp; charite: &amp; in &thorn;at dose als wele als
&thorn;ai may, &amp; hopes certaynly &thorn;at &thorn;ai


<PB N="43">

sal be safe;&mdash;&thorn;ai wate it not als tyte:
for if &thorn;ai wiste, &thorn;air merit war &thorn;e
lesse.  And Salomon says &thorn;at it er
rightwys men &amp; wyse men, and &thorn;air
warkes er in goddes hand.  And
noght-for-&thorn;i [a] man wate noght whethir he be
worthi hateredyn or lufe, bot al es
reserued vncertayne til a nother worlde.
Neuer-&thorn;e-latter, if any had grace &thorn;at
he moght wyn til &thorn;e thirde degre of
lufe, &thorn;at es called syngulere: he sulde
knaw &thorn;at he war in lufe.  Bot in &thorn;at
maner his knawyng es, &thorn;at he moght
neuer bere hym &thorn;e hegher, ne be in
&thorn;e lesse bisynes to lufe god; bot sa
mykel &thorn;e mare, &thorn;at he es siker of
lufe, wil he be bisy to lufe hym and
drede hym, &thorn;at hase made hym swilk
&amp; done &thorn;at godenes til hym; and he
&thorn;at es swa hee, he wil noght halde
hym-self worthier, &thorn;an &thorn;e synfullest
man &thorn;at gaas on erth. // Als-swa,
Seuen experimentes er &thorn;at a man be
in charite. / &THORN;e fyrst es: when al
couatise of ertly thyng es slokkend in
hym. / For whare sa couaityse es: &thorn;are
es na lufe of Cryste. / &THORN;an, if he haue
na couaytyse: signe es &thorn;at he hase
lufe. // &THORN;e secunde es, byrnand &thorn;hernyng
of heuen.  For when men hase feled
oght of &thorn;at sauoure, &thorn;e mare &thorn;ai haue,
&thorn;e mare &thorn;ai couayte; &amp; he &thorn;at noght
hase feled: noght he desires.  For-&thorn;i,
when any es swa mykel gyfen til &thorn;e
luf &thorn;ar-of, &thorn;at he kan fynd na ioy in
&thorn;is lyfe: taken he hase &thorn;at he es in
charite. // &THORN;e thyrd es: if his tung be
chawngyd, &thorn;at was [wone] to speke of &thorn;e


<PB N="44">

erth: now spekes of god, &amp; of &thorn;e lyf
&thorn;at lastes ay. // &THORN;e feerth es: exercise
of gastly profet.  Als, if any man or
woman gyf &thorn;am enterely to goddes
seruyes, &amp; entermetes &thorn;am of nane
erthly bisynes. // &THORN;e fift es: when &thorn;e
thyng &thorn;at es hard in it-selfe, semes
lyght forto do; &thorn;e whilk luf makes.
For als Austyne says: &laquo;Lufreden es &thorn;at
bryngs &thorn;e thyng &thorn;at es fare,
nerehande, and impossibel til possibel
apertly.&raquo; // &THORN;e sext es: hardynes of
thoght to suffer all anguyses and noyes
&thorn;at comes&mdash;with-owten &thorn;is, al &thorn;e o&thorn;er
suffices noght. / For it sal noght make
a ryghtwys man sary: what sa falles
hym.  For he &thorn;at es ryghtwys, he
hates noght bot syn, he lufes noght
bot god, for god, he dredes noght bot
to wreth god. // &THORN;e seuent es:
delitabilite in sawle, when he es in
tribulacion, and makes louyng to god in
ilk anger &thorn;at he suffers.  And &thorn;is
schewes wele &thorn;at he lufes god: when
na sorow may bryng hym downe. / For
many lufes god whils &thorn;ai er in ese:
and in aduersite &thorn;ai grotche, &amp; falles
in swa mykel sarynes, &thorn;at vnneth may
any man comforth &thorn;am; and swa
sclawnder &thorn;ai god, flytand &amp; feghtand
agayne his domes.  And &thorn;at es a caytif
louyng &thorn;at any welth of &thorn;e worlde
makes; bot &thorn;at louyng es of mykel
pryce, &thorn;at na violence of sorow may
do a-way. // &THORN;e fifte askyng was: In
what state men may maste lufe god.  I
answer: In wilk state sa it be &thorn;at men
er in maste rest, of body &amp; sawle, &amp;


<PB N="45">

leest occupied with any nedes or
bisynes of &thorn;is worlde.  For &thorn;e thoght of
&thorn;e lufe of Ihesu Criste, &amp; of &thorn;e ioy
&thorn;at lastes ay, sekes rest wyth-owten,
&thorn;at it be noght lettyd with comers &amp; gangers, and occupacion of worldely
thynges; and it sekes with-in grete
sylence fra &thorn;e noyes of couayties, &amp; of
vanitees, &amp; of ertly thoghtes.  And
namely al &thorn;at lufes contemplatyfe lyf,
&thorn;ai seke rest in body &amp; in saule.  For
a grete doctor says &thorn;at &thorn;ai er goddes
trone &thorn;at dwelles still in a stede, and
er noght abowte rennand: bot in swetnes
of Cristes lufe er stabyld.  And I haue
lufed for to sytt: for na penance, ne
for na fantasy, &thorn;at I wild men spak of
me, ne for na swylk thyng: bot anly
for I knew &thorn;at I loued god mare, &amp; langar lasted with-in &thorn;e comforth of
lufe: &thorn;an gangand, or standand, or
kneleand. / For sittand am I in maste
rest, &amp; my hert maste vpwarde.  Bot
&thorn;ar-fore perauenture es it noght &thorn;e best
til a nother at sitte, als I did &amp; wil
do til my dede: bot if he war disposed
als I was, in his sawle.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. XI<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(S)Euen gyftes of &thorn;e hali gaste er
in men &amp; wymen &thorn;at er ordaynd til
&thorn;e ioy of heuen and ledes &thorn;aire.  life
in &thorn;is worlde rightwisly.  &thorn;ies &thorn;ai er:
/ Wysdom&macr;, / Vnderstandyng, /
Cownsayle, / Strengh, / Connyng, / Pyte, /
&amp; &thorn;e Drede of god. / Begynne we at
Cownsel, for &thorn;arof es maste nede at
&thorn;e begynnyng of owre werkes, &thorn;at vs
myslike noght afterwarde.  With &thorn;ier
seuen gyftes &thorn;e haly gaste towches
sere men serely.  Cownsel es, doyng


<PB N="46">

away of worldes rytches, &amp; of delytes,
&amp; of al thynges &thorn;at man may be
ta[gild] with in thoght or dede; / and
&thorn;par-with be drawne inwardely til
contemplacion of god. / Vnderstandyng es,
to knaw what es forto do, &amp; what for
to leue; and &thorn;at &thorn;at sal be gifen, to
gif it til &thorn;am &thorn;at hase nede, noght til
other &thorn;at hase na myster. / Wysdom
es, forgetyng of ertly thynges, &amp; thynkyng of heuen, with discrecion in al
mens dedes.  In &thorn;is gyft schynes
contemplacion, &thorn;at es, a[ls] saynt Austyn says,
A gastely dede of fleschly affections,
thorow &thorn;e ioy of a raysed thoght. /
Strengh es, lastyng to fulfill gude
purpose, &thorn;at it be noght left, for wele
ne for wa. / Pyte es, &thorn;at a man be
mylde; &amp; agayne-say noght haly writte,
when it smytes his synnes, whethir he
vnderstand it or noght; Bot in al his
myght purge he &thorn;e vilete of syn, in
hym &amp; in other. / Connyng es &thorn;at
makes a man in gude hope noght
rusand hym of his rightwisnes, bot
sorowand of his syn; and &thorn;at man
geder erthly godes anely to &thorn;e honoure
of god, and prow til other men, mare
&thorn;an til his self. / &THORN;e drede of god es,
&thorn;at we turne noght agayne til oure
syn thorou any il eggyng. &amp; &thorn;an es
drede perfyte in vs, &amp; haly: when we
drede to wreth god in &thorn;e leste syn &thorn;at
we may knaw, and flees it as venym.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">m</HI>. XII<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>(T)Wa lyues &thorn;ar er &thorn;at cristen
men lyfes.  Ane es called Actyue lyfe:
for it es in mare bodili warke.
Another, contemplatyue lyfe: for it es in
mare swetnes gastely.  Actife lyfe es
mykel owteward, &amp; in mare trauel &amp;


<PB N="47">

in mare peryle, for &thorn;e temptacions &thorn;at
er in &thorn;e worlde.  Contemplatyfe lyfe
es mykel inwarde, and for-&thorn;i it es
lastandar, &amp; sykerar, restfuller,
delitabiler, luflyer, &amp; mare medeful.  For it
hase ioy in goddes lufe, &amp; sauowre in
&thorn;e lyf &thorn;at lastes ay, in &thorn;is present
tyme, if it be right ledde.  And &thorn;at
felyng of ioy in &thorn;e lufe of Ihesu,
passes al other merites in erth.  For
it es swa harde to com to, for &thorn;e
freelte of oure flesch, and &thorn;e many
temptacions &thorn;at we er vmsett with,
&thorn;at lettes vs nyght &amp; day: al other
thynges er lyght at com&macr; to, in regarde
&thorn;arof; for &thorn;at may na man deserue,
bot anely it es gifen of goddes godenes,
til &thorn;am &thorn;at verrayli gifes &thorn;am to
contemplacion &amp; til quiete for Cristes luf.
// Til men or wymen &thorn;at takes &thorn;am
til actife lyfe, twa thynges falles.  Ane:
for to ordayne &thorn;air meyne in drede
&amp; in &thorn;e lufe of god and fynd &thorn;am
&thorn;aire necessaries, and &thorn;am-self kepe
enterely &thorn;e comandementes of god,
Doand til &thorn;ar neghbur als &thorn;ai wil &thorn;at
&thorn;ai do til &thorn;am.  Another es, &thorn;at &thorn;ai
do at &thorn;ar power &thorn;e seuen werkes of
mercy, / &THORN;e whilk es: to fede &thorn;e
hungry.  To gyf &thorn;e thristi a drynk.
To cleth &thorn;e naked.  To herbar hym
&thorn;at hase na howsyng.  To viset &thorn;e
seke.  To comforth &thorn;am &thorn;at er in
Prysoun.  And to graue dede men.
Al &thorn;at mai &amp; hase) cost, &thorn;ai may
noght be qwyt with ane or twa of &thorn;ir,
bot &thorn;am behoues do &thorn;am al, if &thorn;ai
wil haue &thorn;e benyson on domes-day,


<PB N="48">

&thorn;at Ihesu sal til al gyf &thorn;at dose &thorn;am.
Or els may &thorn;ai drede &thorn;e malysoun
&thorn;at al mon haue &thorn;at wil noght do
&thorn;am, when &thorn;ai had godes, to do
&thorn;am wyth. // Contemplatife lyf hase twa
partyes: A lower &amp; a heer.  &THORN;e lower
party es meditacion, of haly wrytyng,
&thorn;at es goddes wordes, and in other
gude thoghtes &amp; swete &thorn;at men hase
of &thorn;e grace of god, abowt &thorn;e lufe of
Ihesu Criste; and also in louyng of
god in psalmes &amp; ympnes, or in
prayers. // &THORN;e hegher party of contemplacion
es behaldyng, &amp; &yogh;ernyng, of &thorn;e thynges
of heuen, &amp; ioy in &thorn;e haly gaste; &thorn;at
men hase oft, and if it be swa &thorn;at
&thorn;ai be noght prayand with &thorn;e mowth,
bot anely thynkand of god, &amp; of &thorn;e
fairehede of aungels, &amp; haly sawles.
&THORN;an may I say &thorn;at contemplacion es
a wonderful ioy of goddes luf, &thorn;e
whilk ioy es louyng of god, &thorn;at may
noght be talde, &amp; &thorn;at wonderful
louyng es in &thorn;e saule; / and for
abundance of ioy &amp; swettenes it
ascendes in til &thorn;e mouth: swa &thorn;at &thorn;e
hert &amp; &thorn;e tonge acordes in ane, and
body &amp; sawle ioyes in god lyuand. //
A man or woman &thorn;at es ordaynd til
contemplatife lyfe, first god enspires
&thorn;am to forsake &thorn;is worlde, and al &thorn;e
vanite &amp; &thorn;e couayties and &thorn;e vile luste
&thorn;arof.  Sythen he ledes &thorn;am by &thorn;ar
ane, &amp; spekes til &yogh;ar hert: and als &thorn;e
prophete says, He gifes &thorn;am at sowke
&thorn;e swetnes of &thorn;e begynnyng of lufe;
and &thorn;an he settes &thorn;am in will to gyf
&thorn;am haly to prayers &amp; meditacions &amp; teres.  Sithen, when &thorn;ai haue sufferd


<PB N="49">

many temptacions, &amp; [&thorn;e] foule noyes of
thoghtes &thorn;at er ydel, &amp; of vanitees &thorn;e
whilk wil comber &thorn;am &thorn;at can noght
destroy &thorn;am, er passand a-way: he
gars &thorn;am geder til &thorn;am &thorn;air hert &amp; fest anely in hym: and opens til &thorn;e
egh of &thorn;air sawls &thorn;e &yogh;ates of heuen:
swa &thorn;at &thorn;e ilk egh lokes in til heuen;
and &thorn;an &thorn;e fire of lufe verrali ligges
in &thorn;air hert, &amp; byrnes &thorn;arin, &amp; makes
[it] clene of al erthly filth: &amp; sithen
forward &thorn;ai er contemplatife men, &amp; rauyst in lufe.  For contemplacion es
a syght: &amp; &thorn;ai se in til heuen with
&thorn;ar gastly egh.  Bot &thorn;ou sal witt &thorn;at
naman hase perfite syght of heuen
whils &thorn;ai er lifand bodili here.  Bot
als sone als &thorn;ai dye: &thorn;ai er broght
before god and sese hym face til face,
&amp; egh til egh: and wones with hym
with-outen ende.  For hym &thorn;ai soght,
&amp; hym &thorn;ai couayted, and hym &thorn;ai
lufed, in al &thorn;ar myght. //
</P>
<P>Loo, Margarete, I haue schortly
sayde &thorn;e &thorn;e forme of lyuyng: and how
&thorn;ou may com&macr; til perfection, and to
lufe hym &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase taken &thorn;e til.
If it do &thorn;e gude, and profit til &thorn;e:
thank god, &amp; pray for me.  &THORN;e grace
of Ihesu Criste be with &thorn;e, &amp; kepe &thorn;e.
Amen.</P>
</DIV4><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit forma viuendi.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV3>

<DIV3 N="Rawlinson C 285" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="[3]"><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Rawlinson C 285</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="40" UNIT="folio">
<P>IN Ilke a synful man or womman
&thorn;at es bunden in deedly synne, er thre
wrytchednes, &thorn;e whylk brynges &thorn;aim to
&thorn;e deed of helle.  &para; &THORN;e first es, defaut of
gaastly strengthe: &THORN;at &thorn;ai er so wayke


<PB N="4">

wyth-In in &thorn;air hert, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may
nouther stand agayn fandyngs of &thorn;e fynd,
ne &thorn;ay may lift &thorn;aire wille to yherne &thorn;e
lufe of gode and folwe &thorn;are-tille.  &para; &THORN;e
tothir es, vs of flesshely desyres:&mdash;for
&thorn;ay hafe na wille ne myght to stand,
&thorn;ay fall in lustes and lykyngs of &thorn;is
werld; and for &thorn;aim thynke &thorn;aim swete,
&thorn;ay dwelle in &thorn;aim stille, many til &thorn;aire
lifs end: ande swa &thorn;ai com to &thorn;e thrid
wrytchednes.  &para; &THORN;e thride wrytchednes
es schangeyng of lastand gode for a
passand delyte; als wha say &thorn;ai gife
Ioi endles for a litil Ioi of &thorn;is
life.  &para; If &thorn;ai will turne &thorn;aim and ryse til
penaunce, god wil ordaynge &thorn;aim
wonynge with angels and haly men.
Bot for &thorn;ai chese &thorn;e wyle synne of
&thorn;is werld, and has mare delyte in &thorn;e
filth of &thorn;aire flesshe &thorn;an in &thorn;e fayrhede
of heeun, &thorn;ai loose bath &thorn;e werld and
heeuen: for he &thorn;at has nogth Ihesu
Cryst, he tynes al &thorn;at he has, and al
&thorn;at he es, and al &thorn;at he myght gete;
he ne es nogth worthi &thorn;e life, ne to be
fede wyth swynes meet.  Alle creatures
sal be sterde in his wengeaunce in &thorn;e
day of dome.  &para; &THORN;ir wrytchednes &thorn;at I
hafe of tald, er nogth anely in werldisshe
men and womene &thorn;at vses glotory or
lytchery and other appert synnes, bot
&thorn;ai er alswa in som&macr; &thorn;at semes in
penaunce and in gud life.  For &thorn;e


<PB N="5">

deeuel &thorn;at es enemy to al man kynd,
whene he sese a man or a woman
amange a thousand turne &thorn;aim haaly
vnto god and forsake all vanytese and
rytchesce &thorn;at men &thorn;at lufs &thorn;is werld
couaytes, and seke &thorn;e Ioi lastand, a
thousant wyles he has on what maner
he may deceyf &thorn;aim.  And when he
may nogth bryng &thorn;aim in til swylk
synnes &thorn;e whylk mygth ger all men
wonder on &thorn;aim, he bygiles many so
pryuely, &thorn;at &thorn;ai can nogth oft-sythes
fele &thorn;e trap &thorn;at has taken &thorn;aim.  Som&macr;
he takes wyth errour &thorn;at he puttes
&thorn;aim In.  Som wyth synguler witte,
when he gers &thorn;aim wen &thorn;at &thorn;e thyng
&thorn;at &thorn;ai thynk or do es best; and for-[&thorn;i]
&thorn;ai wyl na counsayl haue of other &thorn;at
er better and conander &thorn;an &thorn;ai&mdash;and
&thorn;is es a foul stynkand pryde: for he
wald nogth ells sette his witte bifore
all other.  Som&macr; &thorn;e deeuel deceyfs thurgth
vayne glory, &thorn;at es Idel Ioy; when
any has pryd and delite in &thorn;am-self of
&thorn;e penance &thorn;at &thorn;ai suffre, of gud dedis
&thorn;at &thorn;ai do, of any vertu &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue;
er glad when men loues &thorn;aim, sary
when men lakkes &thorn;aim, has envye to
&thorn;aim &thorn;at er spoken mare gud of &thorn;an
of &thorn;aim; &thorn;ai hald &thorn;aim-self so gloryous
and so fer passand &thorn;e lif &thorn;at other
men ledis, &thorn;at &thorn;aim thynk &thorn;at na man
suld reprehend &thorn;aim in na thyng &thorn;at


<PB N="6">

&thorn;ay do or say, and dyspyses synfull
men &amp; othir &thorn;e whilk wil nogth do als
&thorn;ai bid &thorn;aim.  How may &thorn;ou fynd a
synfuller wreche &thorn;an swylke ane?  and
so mekell es he &thorn;e wers &thorn;at he wat
nogth &thorn;at he es ille, and es halden
and honourd of men als wys and haly.
Som er deceyfd with ouer-mykell lust
and lykyng in meet and drynke, when
&thorn;ai passe mesur and com in til outrage,
and has delyte &thorn;ar-Inne, and wenes &thorn;at
&thorn;ai synne nogth ... and so &thorn;ai distroy
vertus of sawle.  Som&macr; er b;gylled with
ouermykel abstynence of meet and drynk
and slep.  &THORN;at es of temptacyon of &thorn;e
deeuel, for to ger &thorn;aim fall in myddes
&thorn;air werk, swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai bryng it til
nane enddynge, als &thorn;ai suld haue don
If &thorn;ai had knawen skyl and halden
discrecyoun, and swa &thorn;ai tyne &thorn;aire
meryte for &thorn;aire frawardenes.  &THORN;is gilder
lays oure enemy to tak vs with whene
we bygyne to hat wyckednes and turne
vs til god.  &THORN;an many bygynnys &thorn;e
thynge &thorn;at &thorn;ay may neuermare bryng
til end; &thorn;an &thorn;ai wen &thorn;at &thorn;ai may do
what so &thorn;aire hert es set opon.  Bot
oft &thorn;ai fall ar &thorn;ai com In-myddys &thorn;e
gate, and &thorn;at thyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai wene es
for &thorn;aim, es lettyng til &thorn;aim.  For we
haue a lange way til heeuene, and als
many gud dedis als we do, als many


<PB N="7">

prayers als we make, and als many
gud thoghtes als we thynk in trouth
and hoop and charyte, als many paases
ga we til heeuen-ward.  &THORN;an If we make
vs so wayke &amp; so feble &thorn;at we may
nothire wirk ne pray als we suld do,
ne thynk, er we nogth gretely at blame,
&thorn;at faylles when we had mast nede to
be stalward?  And wele I wat &thorn;at it
es nogth goddis wille &thorn;at we so do:
For &thorn;e prophete says: &laquo;Lord, I sal
kype my strength til &thorn;e&raquo;: swa &thorn;at he
mygth sustayne goddis seruyse til his
deed-day; Nogth in a litel and in a
schort tyme waast it and sithene ligge
wanand and granand by &thorn;e wagthe.
And it es mykell mare peril &thorn;an men
wenes: For saynt Ierome says &thorn;at he
makes of Rauyne offerand &thorn;at
outrageously tourmentis his body in ouerlitel
meet or slep.  And saynt Bernard says:
&laquo;Fastyng ne wakyng lettis nogth gaastly
guddes, bot helpis, if &thorn;ai be don with
discrecyoun; wyth-owten &thorn;at, er &thorn;ai
vices.&raquo; For-&thorn;i it es nogth gud to pyne
vs so mykele and sithen haue vnthanke
for oure dede.  &THORN;are has ben many,
and er, &thorn;at wenes &thorn;at it es nogth all
&thorn;at [&thorn;ai] do bot if &thorn;ai be in so mykell
abstynence and fastyng &thorn;at &thorn;ay make
all men at spek of &thorn;aim &thorn;at knawes
&thorn;aim.  Bot oft-sithes it byfalles &thorn;at ay


<PB N="8">

&thorn;e mare Ioy and wonderyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai
haue with-owtene of &thorn;e loouynge of
men, ay &thorn;e lesse Ioy &thorn;ai haue
with-Inne of &thorn;e luf of gode.  At my dom&macr;,
&thorn;ay suld pay Ihesu Crist mykel mare
if &thorn;ai tok for his luf and in thankyng
and loouynge of hym, for to sustayne
&thorn;aire bodys in his seruyse and to hald
&thorn;aim fra mykele speche of men, what
so god sent &thorn;aim for &thorn;e tyme and &thorn;e
steed, and gayfe &thorn;aim sithen entierly
and parfytely til &thorn;e luf &amp; &thorn;e loouynge
of our lourd Ihesu Cryst, &thorn;at wile
stalwardly be lufd, and lastandly be
serued; swa &thorn;at &thorn;aire halynes war mare
sene in goddis eghe &thorn;an in mannes
eghe.  For ay &thorn;e better &thorn;at &thorn;ou ert
and &thorn;e lesse speche &thorn;ou has of men,
&thorn;e mare es &thorn;i Ioy bifor god.  Ha, what
it es mykell to be worthy loouynge and
be nogth loued!  And what wrytchednes
it es to haf &thorn;e n&amacr;me &amp; &thorn;e habyte of
halynes, &amp; be nogth swa, bot turne to
pryd, Ire and envye vnder &thorn;e clathes
of Crystes barnhed!  A foul lytchery it
es to haue likyng and delite in mens
wordes, &thorn;at can no mare deme whate
we er in our saul &thorn;an &thorn;ai wate what
we thynke.  For oft-sithes &thorn;ai say &thorn;at
he or scho es in heghere degre, &thorn;at es
in &thorn;e lagher; and &thorn;at &thorn;ay say es in
&thorn;e laghere, es in &thorn;e heghere.  For-&thorn;i
I hald it bot wodnes to be gladder or


<PB N="9">

saryer, whether &thorn;ai say gud or ille.  If
we be oboutward to hid vs fra speche
and loouynge of &thorn;e werld, god wil
schewe vs til his loouyng, and our Ioy.
For &thorn;at es his Ioy when we ar
strenthfull for to stand agayne &thorn;e pryue and
&thorn;e appert fandyngs of &thorn;e deeuele, and
sekes na thyng bot &thorn;e loouynge and
&thorn;e honoure of hym, and &thorn;at [we] mogth
entierly lufe hym.  And &thorn;at agth to
be our desire, our prayer and our
entent, nygth and day, &thorn;at &thorn;e fyre of
luf kyndell in our hert, and &thorn;e swetenes
of his grace be our comfort and our
solace, in wele and in wa.  &para; &THORN;ou has
herd now a party how &thorn;e fend deceyfs
with his sutell castes vn-quaynt men
and wommen: and if &thorn;ou wil do gud
counsaylle and folow haly lare, als I
hop &thorn;at &thorn;ou wil, &thorn;ou sal distroy his
trappis, and brynn in &thorn;e fyre of lufe.
Alle &thorn;e bandes &thorn;at he wil bynd &thorn;e
with, and alle his malice sal turne &thorn;e
til Ioy, and hym to mare sorow.  God
suffirs hym for to tempe gud men for
&thorn;aire profyte, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may be &thorn;e hegher
coround when &thorn;ai haf thurgth his help&macr;e
ouer-comen so cruel ane enemy, &thorn;at
oft-sithes bath in body and in saul
confoundes many a man.  &para; In thre
maners &thorn;e deeuel has power to be in
a man: &para; On a maner, hortand &thorn;e
gudes &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue of kynd, als in dom


<PB N="10">

men, and in other, blemyssand &thorn;aire
thogth.  &para; On a nother maner, reeffand
&thorn;e gudys &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ai haue of grace:
and swa es sene in synfull men whaim
he has deceyfd thurgth delyte of &thorn;e
werld and of &thorn;air flesshe, and led with
hym til helle.  &para; On &thorn;e thred maner,
tourmentand a mans body, als we red
&thorn;at he was in Iob.  Bot wyte &thorn;ou
wele: If he bygile &thorn;e nogth with-Inne,
&thorn;e thar nogth dred what he may do
&thorn;e with-owtene.  For he may do no
mare &thorn;an god gifs hym leue to do.
&para; Bot for &thorn;ou has forsakene &thorn;e solace
and &thorn;e Ioy of &thorn;is werld and taan &thorn;e vnto
solitary life, for goddis lufe to suffire
tribulacioun and anguys here and sithen
to com to &thorn;e rest and endlesse Ioy in
heeuene, I trowe stedfastly &thorn;at &thorn;e
comfort of Ihesu Cryst and swetenes of
his luf, with &thorn;e fyre of &thorn;e haly gast
&thorn;at purges all synne, sal be in &thorn;e
and with &thorn;e, ledand &thorn;e and lerand &thorn;e
how &thorn;ou sal thynk, how &thorn;ou sal pray,
what &thorn;ou sal wyrke; swa &thorn;at in faa
yheris &thorn;ou sal haue mare delyte to be
by &thorn;ine ane and spek til &thorn;i luf and
&thorn;i spouse Ihesu Cryst, &thorn;an If &thorn;ou war
leeuedy of a thousant werldis.  &para; Men
wenes &thorn;at we er in pyne and in
penance: bot we haue mare Ioy and


<PB N="11">

mare verray delyte in a day &thorn;an &thorn;ay
haf in &thorn;e werld all &thorn;aire life.  &THORN;ai se
our body, bot &thorn;ai se nogth our hert
whare oure solace es.  If &thorn;ai sagth
&thorn;at, many of &thorn;aim wald forsake all &thorn;at
&thorn;ai haf, forto folwe vs.  For-&thorn;i be
comforted and stalward, and drede na
noy ne anguys, bot fest all &thorn;ine entent
in Ihesu, &thorn;at &thorn;i lif be gode to queme;
and at &thorn;are be na thyng in &thorn;e &thorn;at
suld be mys-payand til hym &thorn;at ne
&thorn;ou son amend it.  &THORN;e stat &thorn;at &thorn;ou
ert Ine, &thorn;at es solitude, es mast able
of all other til reuelacyoun of &thorn;e haly
gast.  For when saynt Iohn&macr; was in &thorn;e
Ile of Pathmos, &thorn;an god schewed hym
his preuetese.  &THORN;e gudnes of god it es
&thorn;at he comfortes &thorn;aim wondirfully &thorn;at
has na comfort of &thorn;e werld, If &thorn;ai
gif &thorn;air hertis entierly til hym and
couaytes and nogth sekes bot hym: &thorn;an
he gifs hym-self to &thorn;aim in swetnes
and delite, in brynnyng of luf, and in
Ioy and melody, and dwellis ay with
&thorn;aim in &thorn;aire saule, swa &thorn;at &thorn;e
comfort of hym departis neuer fra &thorn;aim.
If &thorn;ai bygyne ogth to here thurgth
ignoraunce or freyllyte, son he schewes
&thorn;aim &thorn;e rygth way; and all &thorn;at &thorn;ai
haue ned of, he leris &thorn;aim.  Na man
comes til swylke reuelacion and grace
on &thorn;e first day, bot thurgth lang
trauaylle &amp; besynes to lufe Ihesu Crist,


<PB N="12">

als &thorn;ou sal here afterward.
Nogth-for-&thorn;i &thorn;an he suffirs &thorn;aim to be temped
on sere maners, bath slepand and
wakand.  For ay &thorn;e ma temptacions
and &thorn;e greuouser at &thorn;ay stand agayne
and ouer-comes, &thorn;e mare sal &thorn;aire
Ioy be in his luf when &thorn;ai er passed.
&para; Wakand &thorn;ai er vmwhil temped with
foul thoghtis, vile lustes, wikked delites;
with pryd, Ire, Envye, Despayre,
Presumpc&ymacr;on, and other many.  Bot &thorn;aire
remedy sal be prayer, gretyng, fastyng,
wakyng.  &THORN;ir thynges, if &thorn;ai may be
don with discrecioun, &thorn;ai putte away
synne &amp; filthe fra &thorn;e saul, and makis
it clene for to resayfe &thorn;e luf of Ihesu
Cryst, &thorn;at may nogth be lufd bot in
clennes.  &para; Alswa vmwhil &thorn;e fend tempis
men and wommen &thorn;at er solitary by
&thorn;aim ane, on a quaynt maner and a
sutelle: he transfigures hym in lickenes
of ane aungell of ligth, and apperis til
&thorn;aim and says &thorn;at he es ane of god
aungells commen to comfort &thorn;aim; and
swa he deceyfs foles.  Bot &thorn;aim &thorn;at er
wis and wil nogth tyde trowe til all
spirytes, bot askes counsayl of conand
men, he may nogth bygile &thorn;aim.  Als
I fynd wrytene of a recluse, &thorn;at was a
gud woman; til whaim &thorn;e ille aungelle
oft-sithes appered in &thorn;e fourme of a
gud aungell, and sayd &thorn;at he was co-


<PB N="13">

men to bryng hir til heeuen.  Wharfor
scho was rygth glade and Ioyfull.  Bote
neeuer-&thorn;e-latter scho taald it til hir
schrythfader: and he, als wys man and
quaynt, gayf hir &thorn;is counsayl: &laquo;When
he comes&raquo;, he sayd, &laquo;bid hym &thorn;at he
schew &thorn;e our lauedy saynt Mary.  When
he has don swa, say <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aue maria</FOREIGN>&raquo;.  Scho did swa.  &THORN;e feend sayd: &laquo;&THORN;ou has na
ned to se hir: Mi presence suffice vnto
&thorn;e&raquo;.  And [scho] sayd, on all maner
scho suld se hir.  He sagth &thorn;at hym
behoued outhir do hir wil or scho wald
dispyse hym: als tite he brogth forth
&thorn;e fayrest body of woman &thorn;at mygth
be als to hir sygth, and schewed it til
hir.  And scho sete hir on hir knese
and sayd <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aue maria</FOREIGN>: And als tite al waynysht away, and for schame neeuer
sithen com&macr; he at hir.  &THORN;is say I nogth
for I hoppe &thorn;at he sal haue leue to
tempe &thorn;e on &thorn;is maner; bot for I wil
&thorn;at &thorn;ou be war, if any swylke
temptaciouns bifalle &thorn;e slepand or wakand,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou trow nogth ouer-tite til &thorn;ou
knaw &thorn;e sogth.  &para; Mare pryuely he
transfigures hym in &thorn;e fourme of
aungell of ligth&mdash;&thorn;at commonly all men
er tempid with: when he hidis ille
vndire &thorn;e lickenes of gud; and &thorn;at es
in twa maners.  &para; Ane es when he egges
vs til ouer-mykel eese and rest of body,


<PB N="14">

and softnes til our flesshe vndirneethen,
to sustayne our kynd.  For swylke
thoghtes he puttis in vs: bot if we eet
wele and drynk wele and slepe wele
and ligge soft and site warme, we may
nogth serue god ne last in &thorn;e trauaylle
&thorn;at we haf bygune.  Bot he thynkis to
bryng vs til ouer-mykel lust.  &para; A nother
es when he hidis ille vndir lickenes of
gastely gud: he entyces vs til asper and
ouere-mykel penaunce, forto distroy our
self, and says &thorn;us: &laquo;&THORN;ou wat wele &thorn;at
he &thorn;at suffirs maast penaunce for goddis
luf, he sal haue maast mede.  For-&thorn;i eet
litell and feble meet, and drynk lesse,
&thorn;e thynnest drynke es gud Inogthe til &thorn;e.
Recke nogth of slep.  Weer &thorn;e hayer, &thorn;e
haubergeoun.  All thyng &thorn;at es
afflictyoun til &thorn;i flesshe, do it; swa &thorn;at &thorn;are
be nane &thorn;at may passe &thorn;e in penaunce&raquo;.
He &thorn;at says &thorn;e &thorn;us, he es aboute to
sla &thorn;e with ouer-mykele penaunce &amp; abstynence, als he &thorn;at sayd &thorn;e tother,
to sla &thorn;e with ouer-lytele.  For-&thorn;i, if
we wil be rygth dispoosed, vs bihoues
to sete vs in a gud meyne, and &thorn;at
we may distroy our vyces and hald our
flesshe vndir, and neeuer-&thorn;e-latter &thorn;at
it be stalward in &thorn;e seruyse of Ihesu
Cryst.  &para; Alswa our enemy wil nogth
suffir vs to be in rest when we slep:
bot &thorn;an he [es] aboute to bygyle vs in


<PB N="15">

many maners: vmwhyle with vgly
Images, forto make vs rad and ger vs
lath with our state; vmwhile with fayre
Images, fayre syghtes, and &thorn;at at semes
comfortable, forto make vs glad in
vayne, and ger vs wene &thorn;at we er
better &thorn;an we ere; vmwhile telle vs &thorn;at
we er haly and gud, for to bryng vs
in to pryde; vmwhyle say &thorn;at we er
wycked and synfull, for to ger vs falle
in to despayre.  Bot he &thorn;at es ordayner
of all thyng, suffirs nogth &thorn;at oure
slepe be with-owtene mede til vs, if
we adresce our life til his wille.
&para; And wite &thorn;ou wele, &thorn;ou synnes
nogth sleppand, if &thorn;ou be euer-mare
wakand with-owtene outrage of mete and
drynke, and with-outene ille thoghtes.
Bot many has &thorn;e deeuelle deceyfd
thurgth dreemes, when he has gert
&thorn;aym sette &thorn;air hert on &thorn;aim: For
he has schewed &thorn;aim som&macr; sogth and
sithen bigiled &thorn;aim with ane &thorn;at was
fals.  For-&thorn;i says &thorn;e wys man &thorn;at many
bysenes folowes dreemes, and &thorn;ai fel
&thorn;at hoped in &thorn;aim.  Whare-foor, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
be noth bigyled with &thorn;aim, I wile &thorn;at
[&thorn;ou] witte &thorn;at it er sex maners of
dremes.  Twa er &thorn;at na man haly ne
other may etchape, &thorn;at es: if &thorn;air
wambes be ouer-tom or ouer-full, &thorn;an


<PB N="16">

many vanytese in sere maners byfalles
&thorn;aim slepand.  &THORN;e thryd es of
illusyons of our enemy.  &THORN;e fierth es of
thogth byfoor and illusyon folwand.  &THORN;e
fyft thurgth reuelacyone of &thorn;e haly gast,
&thorn;at es don on many maners.  &THORN;e sext
es of thoghtes byfoor &thorn;at falles to Cryst
or haly kyrke, reuelacion command
efter.  In &thorn;us many maners touches &thorn;e
Images of dreemes men when &thorn;ai slep.
Bot swa mekyle we sal &thorn;e latlyer gyf
fayth til any dreeme &thorn;at we may nogth
sone wit whylke es soth, whylke es
fals; whilke es of our enemy, whylke
es of &thorn;e haly gast.  For whar so many
dreemes er, &thorn;ar er many vanytese, and
many &thorn;ai may make to erre: For &thorn;ai
hegth vnquaynt men and swa deceyfs
&thorn;aim.  &para; [I] Knaw &thorn;at &thorn;i lif semes gyfuen
til &thorn;e seruyce of god: &thorn;an es it schame
til &thorn;e bot if &thorn;ou be als gud or better
with-Ine &thorn;i saule als &thorn;ou ert semand
at &thorn;e sigth of men.  &para; Turne for-&thorn;i &thorn;i
thoghtes parfytely til god, als it semes
als &thorn;ou has don &thorn;i body.  For I wil
nogth &thorn;at &thorn;ou wene &thorn;at all er haly
&thorn;at has &thorn;e habyte of halynes and er
nogth occupied with &thorn;e werld, ne &thorn;at
all er ille &thorn;at melles &thorn;aim with erthely
bisenes; bot &thorn;ay er anly haly, what
staate or degre so &thorn;ai be Inne, &thorn;e
whilke despises all erthely thyng, &thorn;at
es at say, lufs it nogth, and brynnes in


<PB N="17">

&thorn;e luf of Ihesu Cryst, and all &thorn;aire
desyres er sette til &thorn;e Ioyes of heeuene,
and haates all synne, and ceeses nogth
of gud werkes, and feles a swetenes in
&thorn;aire hert of life with-outene end; and
neuere-&thorn;e-latter &thorn;ai thynke &thorn;aim-self
vylest of all, and haldes &thorn;aim-self
wrytchedest, last and laghest.  &thorn;is es
halynese of lyfe.  Folow it and be haly!
and if &thorn;ou wil be in mede with
appostells, thynke nogth what &thorn;ou forsakes
bot what &thorn;ou despises.  For als mykell
&thorn;ai forsake &thorn;at folowes Ihesu Cryst in
wilfull poueert, and in mekenes, and
in charyte, and in pacyence, als &thorn;ay
may couayte &thorn;at folwes hym nogth.  And
thynke with how mekyle and how gud
wile &thorn;ou presentes &thorn;i wowes byfor hym
&mdash;ffor til &thorn;at he has his egthe.  And if
&thorn;ou with grete desyre offre &thorn;i prayers
and with grete feruoure couayte to se
hym, and sekes na erthly comfort bot &thorn;e
saueour of heeuene, and in
contemplac&ymacr;on &thorn;aire-of haue &thorn;i delyte.
Wondirfully Ihesu wirkis in his lufers, &thorn;e whilke
he reeues fra &thorn;e lust of flesshe and blod
thurgth tendir lufe; he makis &thorn;aim to
haf wil to na erthly thyng, and dose
&thorn;aim ryse in to solace of hym, and to
for-gete vanytese and flesshely luf of &thorn;e
werld, and to dreede na sorow &thorn;at may


<PB N="18">

fall, to laghte with ouere-mykele bodily
eese.  To suffre for his luf, &thorn;aim thynke
it ioy; and to be solutary &thorn;ay haue
grete comfort, &thorn;at &thorn;ai be nogth letted
in &thorn;aire deuocyone.  &para; Now may &thorn;ou se
&thorn;at many er werre &thorn;an &thorn;ay seme, and
many er better &thorn;an &thorn;ai seme; and
naamly amang &thorn;aa &thorn;at has &thorn;e habyte
of halynes.  For-&thorn;i afforce &thorn;e in all
&thorn;at &thorn;ou may &thorn;at &thorn;ou be nogth were
&thorn;an &thorn;ou semes: and if &thorn;ou wil do als
I lere &thorn;e in &thorn;is schort fourme of lyfyng,
I hop thurgth &thorn;e grace of god &thorn;at if
men hald &thorn;e gude, &thorn;ou sale be wele better.
</P>
<P>AT &thorn;e bigynnyng turn&macr; &thorn;e
entierly to &thorn;i louerd Ihesu Crist.  &THORN;at
turnyng til Ihesu es nogth ells bot
turnyng fra all &thorn;e couaytese and &thorn;e
lykyng and occupac&ymacr;ons and &thorn;e
bysenese of &thorn;e werld and of flesshely lust
and vayne luf; swa &thorn;at &thorn;i thogth &thorn;at
was ay dounward moldand in &thorn;e erth
whiles &thorn;ou was in &thorn;e werld, now be
ay vpward als fyre, sekand &thorn;e heghest
place in heeuene, rygth til &thorn;i spouse &thorn;are
he sittes in his blisse.  Til hym &thorn;ou ert
turned when his grace illum&ymacr;ns &thorn;i hert,
so &thorn;at it forsakes al vices and confourmes
it til vertus and gud thewys and til all
maner of debonerte and mekenes.   And
&thorn;at &thorn;ou may last and wax in gudnesse
&thorn;at &thorn;ou has bygune, with-outene slaw-


<PB N="19">

nes and sarynes and irkynge of &thorn;i lif:
&para; Four thyngs sal &thorn;ou haue in &thorn;i thogth
til &thorn;ou be in parfite luf&mdash;For when &thorn;ou
ert comen &thorn;ar-til, &thorn;i Ioy and &thorn;i desyre
wil ay be brynnand in Cryst.  &para; Ane es:
mesure of &thorn;i life here, &thorn;at so schort
es &thorn;at vnneethes es it ogth.  For we
life bot in a poynt, &thorn;at es &thorn;e lest
thyng &thorn;at may be, and sothely, our
life es lese &thorn;an a poynt if we lickyn
it to &thorn;e lif &thorn;at lastes ay.  &para; Another
es: Vncertaynte of our endyng.  For
we whate neuere when we sal dye ne
how we sal dye, ne whare, ne whidir
we sall ga when we er deed; and &thorn;at
god wil &thorn;at &thorn;is be [vn]certayne til vs,
for he wil &thorn;at we be ay redy to dye.
&para; &THORN;e thrid es: &thorn;at we sal answere
by-for &thorn;e rygthwys Iuge of all &thorn;e
tyme &thorn;at we haue here, how we haf
lifde, what our occupacyons haf bene
and why, and what gud we mygth
haf done when we haf ben Idele.
For-&thorn;i sayd &thorn;e prophete: &laquo;He has
called &thorn;e tyme agayne me&raquo;&mdash;&thorn;at es
ylke day &thorn;at he has lent vs here for
to dispend in gud vse and in penance
and in goddis seruyce.  If we waast
it in erthly luf and vanytese, ful
griefously mon we be demed and punyst.
For-&thorn;i &thorn;at es ane of &thorn;e maast sorowe
&thorn;at may be, Bot if we afforce vs manly
in &thorn;e luf of god and do gud til al
&thorn;at we may to-whyles our schort
tyme lastes.  And ylk a tyme &thorn;at we
thynke nogth on god we may account it
als &thorn;e thyng &thorn;at we haue tynt.  &para; &THORN;e


<PB N="20">

fierth es &thorn;at we thynke how mykel &thorn;e
Ioy es &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue &thorn;e whilk lastis
in goddis luf til &thorn;air endyng: for
&thorn;ai sal be brethire and felaghs with
aungels and haly men, lufand and
hafand, loouand and seand &thorn;e kyng
of Ioy in &thorn;e fayrehed and schynyng
of his maieste; &thorn;e whilke syght sal
be mast mede and delyte &thorn;at any
creatur may thynke, and mare &thorn;an
any man may telle, til al his lufers
withouten end.  It es mykell lyghter
to com to &thorn;at blysse &thorn;an to telle
it.  Alswa thynke what sorow and
what payne and tourment &thorn;ay sal
haue &thorn;e whi[l]k lufs nogth god ouer all
other thynges &thorn;at man sees in &thorn;is
werld, bot files &thorn;aire saules in lust
and lycchery of &thorn;is lif, In pryd and
couaytes and other synnes: &thorn;ai salle
brynne in &thorn;e fyre of helle with &thorn;e
deeuele wham &thorn;ai haue serued, als
lang als god es in heeuen with his
sergeantis, &thorn;at es eeuer-mare.  &para; I
will &thorn;ou be ay clymband til
Ihesu-ward and ekand &thorn;i luf and &thorn;i seruyse
in hym: Nogth als foles dose &thorn;at
bygynnes at &thorn;e heghest degre and
comes doun til &thorn;e lagthest.  I say
nogth for I wil if &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue
by-gune vnskylwys abstynence, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
hald it, bot for many &thorn;at war
brynnande at &thorn;e bygynnyng and able to
&thorn;e luf of Ihesu Cryst, ffor ouer-mykele
penance &thorn;ai haue alledgede &thorn;aim-self,
and made &thorn;aim so feble &thorn;at &thorn;ai mygth
nogth luf god als &thorn;ai suld.  In whilk
luf &thorn;at &thorn;ou wax ay mare and mare es
my couatyng and myne amonestyng.


<PB N="21">

&para; I hald &thorn;e neeuer of &thorn;e lesse meryte if
&thorn;ou be nogth in so mykele abstynence;
Bot if &thorn;ou sette al &thorn;i thogth how &thorn;ou
may luf &thorn;i spouse Ihesu Cryst mare
&thorn;an &thorn;ou has donne, &thorn;an dar I say &thorn;at
&thorn;i mede es waxand and nogth wanande.

Wharefor, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be rygth despoosed
bath for &thorn;i saul and &thorn;i body, &thorn;ou sal
vndirstand four th&ymacr;ngs.  &para; &THORN;e first es,
what thyng files a man.  &para; &THORN;e tother,
what thynge makis hym clene.  &para; &THORN;e
third, what haldis hym in clennes.  &para; &THORN;e
fierth, what thyng drawes [him] for to
ordayne his wile al at goddis wile.
&para; For &thorn;e first, wite &thorn;ou &thorn;at we synne
in [thre] thynges &thorn;at makis vs foul, &thorn;at es
with hert, with mouth, and dede.  &para; &THORN;e
synnes of &thorn;e hert er &thorn;ir: Ille thogth.
Ille delyte.  Assent til synne.  Desire
of ille.  Wikked wile.  Ille suspeccyoun.
Vndeuocyoun.  If &thorn;ou lat &thorn;i hert any
tyme be Idell, with-outen occupacioune
of &thorn;e luf and &thorn;e loouyng of god.  Ile
drede, Ile luf.  Errour.  Flesshly
affeccioun til frendis or til other &thorn;at &thorn;ou
lufs.  Ioy of any mans Ille-fare, whethir
&thorn;ai be enemyse or nane.  Despite of
poure or of synfull men.  To honoure
Ryche men for &thorn;air rychesse.  Vnconable
Ioy of any wordis of vanyte.  Sorow
of other mens wele-fare.
Vnthoolmodenes.  Perplexite, &thorn;at es doute
whate es at do, what nogth&mdash;For ilke
a man agth for [to] be sekir what he
sal do and what he sal leeue.  Obsty-


<PB N="22">

nacyon in ille.  Noy to do gud.  Angre
to serue god.  Sorow &thorn;at he did na
mare ille, or &thorn;at he did nogth &thorn;at lust
or &thorn;at wile of his flesshe &thorn;e whilke he
mygth haue don.  Vnstablenesse of
thogth.  Pyne of penance.  Ipocrysy.
Luf to pleese men, Drede to despleese
&thorn;aim.  Schame of gud dede, Ioy of ille
dede.  Synguler wite.  Couaytice of
honoure or of dignyte, or to be
haldene better &thorn;an other, or rycher or
fayrer, or to be mare drede.  Vayne
glorye of any guddis of kynde, or
of happ, or grace.  Schame of pouer
freyndis, Pryde of ryche kyne or of
gentil&mdash;for all we er ilyke fre byfor
goddis face, bot if our dedis make any
better or wers &thorn;an other.  Dispite of
gude counsayll and of gude teechynge.
&para; &THORN;e synnes of &thorn;e mouthe er &thorn;ir: To
sweer oft-sythes.  Forsweeryng.
Sklaunderyng of Cryst or of any of his halwes.
To neeuen his name with-outene
reuerence.  Gaynesayng and Stryf agayne
Suthfastnes.  Grucchyng agaynes god
for any angwys or noy or trybulacyoun
&thorn;at may bifale in erth.  To say goddis
seruyse vndeuoutely and with-outene
reuerence.  Backbytyng.  Flateryng.
Leghyng.  Myssayng.  Werying.
Deffamyng.  Flytyng.  Manasyng.  Sawyng
of Discorde.  Treeson.  Fals wittenese.
Ille Counsayll.  Heethyng.
Vnbouxsomnes.  With word to turne gud dede
to ille, ffor to ger &thorn;aim be haldene Ile
&thorn;at duse &thorn;aim&mdash;Vs agth to lapp our
negthbur dedis in &thorn;e best, nogth in &thorn;e
werst.  Excytyng of any man til Ire.
To reprehend in a nother &thorn;at he dose


<PB N="23">

hym-self.  Vayne speche, Mikel speche,
fole spe[ch]e.  To spe[k]e Idele wordis
or wordes &thorn;at er na nede.  Rosyng.
Polysyng of worddes.  Defendyng of
synne.  Crying in Laghter.  Mow
makyng on any mane.  To syng seculer
sanges and luf &thorn;aim.  To prayse ille
dedis.  To syng mare to loouyng of
men &thorn;an of god.<PTR TARGET="n1">  &para; &THORN;e synnes of dede
er &thorn;ir: Glotony.  Litchery.
Drunkenhed.  Symony.  Wytchecraft.  Breekyng
of &thorn;e haly days.  Sacrilege.  To receyfe
goddis body in dedly synne.  Breekyng
of wowes.  Apostasy.  Dissolucyon in
goddis seruyse.  To gif ensampile of
ile dedes.  To hurt any man in his body,
or in his guddis, or in his fame.  Theft.
Rauyne.  Vsure.  Deceyte.  Sellyng of
rygthwysenes.  To herken ille.  To gif
to herlotis.  To withhald necessaryse
fra &thorn;i body, or to gif it outrage.  To
bygyne a thyng &thorn;at es abouene our
mygth.  Coustom to syn.  Fallyng oft
in synne.  Fenyng of mare gud &thorn;ane we
haue, ffor to seme halier, or conander,
or wyser &thorn;an we er.  To hald &thorn;e office
&thorn;at we suffice nogth tille, or &thorn;at may
nogth be haldene with-outene syne.  To
lede Carols.  To bryng vp new gyses.
To be Rebelle to his soueraynes.  To
defoule &thorn;aim &thorn;at er lesse.  To synne
in sygth, In heryng, In smellyng, In
touchyng, In handdellyng, In schewyng;
In giftis, in ways, signes, bydynges,
wrytynges.  To Receyf &thorn;e Circumstance,
&thorn;at er Tyme, Stede, Maner, Nombre,
Persone, Dwellyng, Conyng, Eld: &thorn;ir


<PB N="24">

makis &thorn;e synne mare or lesse.  To
couayte to syne ar he be temped.  To
constreyne hym to synne.  &para; Other
many synnes er &thorn;ar of omyssyoun, &thorn;at
es of leeuyng of gud vndone: When
men leeues &thorn;e gud &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld do;
nogth thynkand on gode, ne dredand,
ne lufande hym, ne thankand hym of
his benefyces.  To do nogth al &thorn;at he
dose for goddis luf.  To sorow nogth
for his synne als he suld do.  To dispose
hym nogth to receyf grace, And if he
haf taken grace, to vse it nogth als hym
agth, ne to kype it nogth.  To turne
nogth at &thorn;e Inspiracioun of gode.  To
conforme nogth his wile to goddis wile.  To
gif nogth entent til his prayers, bot rable
on and reke neuer bot at &thorn;ai be sayd.
To do necligently &thorn;at he es halden til
thurgth a vowe or comandement, or es
enioynt in penance.  To drawe on
lenth at es at do son.  Hafand na
ioy of his neighbur profyte als of
his awene, Sorowand nogth for his
illefare.  Standand nogth agayne
temptacions.  Forgifand nogth &thorn;aim &thorn;at haf
don hym harme.  Kepand nogth trouth
to his negthbur as he wald he dede to
hym, and yheldand hym nogth a gud
deide for another if he may.  Amendand
nogth &thorn;aim &thorn;at synnes bi-for his eghen.
Peesand nogth strifes.  Lerand nogth
&thorn;aim &thorn;at er vnconand.  Confortand
nogth &thorn;aim &thorn;at er in sorow, or in
sekenes, or in pouert, or in penance, or
in pryson.  &THORN;ir synnes, and many other,
makes men foule.&mdash; &para; &THORN;e thynges &thorn;at


<PB N="25">

clenses vs of &thorn;at fi[l]th er thre, Agaynes
&thorn;ase thre maners of synnes.  &para; &THORN;e first
es Sorow of hert, agayne &thorn;e syne of
thogth; and &thorn;at be-houes be so parfite
&thorn;at &thorn;ou be in ful wile neuer to syne
mare; and at &thorn;ou haf sorow of alle &thorn;i
synnes; and at al ioy and solace, bot
of god and in god, be pute out of &thorn;i
hert.  &para; &THORN;e tother es Schrith of mouth,
agayne &thorn;e synne of mouthe; and &thorn;at
sal be hasty with-outene delayinge,
nakede with-outene excusyng, and
entier with-outen partyng: als for to tell
a synne til a prest and another til
another.  Say all &thorn;at &thorn;ou wat til ane
or al es nogth worth.  &para; &THORN;e thride es
Satisfaccyoun; &thorn;at has thre partis:
Fastyng, Prayer, and Almus-dede.  Nogth
anly to gif poueer men mete and drynke,
bot for to forgif &thorn;aim &thorn;at dose &thorn;e
wrange, and praye for &thorn;aim, and
enfourme &thorn;aim how &thorn;ai suld do &thorn;at er
in poynt to perisse. &mdash; &para; For &thorn;e thrid
thynge, &thorn;ou sal witte &thorn;at clennes
bi-houes be kepide In hert, and in mouth,
and in werke.  Clennes of hert thre
thynges kepis: Ane es waker thogth
and stable of gode.  Another es bisenes
to kipe &thorn;e fyue wites, swa &thorn;at all &thorn;e
wicked stirynge be closede out of &thorn;i
flesshe.  &THORN;e thrid es honest occupacyoun
and profitable.  &para; Also clennes of mouth
kepis thre thynges: Ane es at &thorn;ou
vmthynke &thorn;e bifoor ar &thorn;ou speke.
Another, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be nogth of mykele
speche bot of litele, and namly ay til
&thorn;i hert be stabled in &thorn;e luf of Ihesu,


<PB N="26">

swa &thorn;at &thorn;e thynk &thorn;at &thorn;ou lokes ay on
hym whether &thorn;ou speke or nogth.  Bot
swylke a grace may &thorn;ou nogth haue on &thorn;e
first day, bot with lang trauayl and grete
bisynes to luf and with costome, swa &thorn;at
&thorn;e eghe of &thorn;i hert be ay vpward: &thorn;an
sal &thorn;ou come &thorn;ar-til.  &THORN;e thrid, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
for na thyng ne for na mekenes legthe on
any mane&mdash;for ilke a leghe es synne and
ille and nogth at goddis wile.  &THORN;e thar
nogth telle al &thorn;e south ay bot if &thorn;ou wil;
bot al leghes hate.  If &thorn;ou say athyng
of &thorn;i self &thorn;at semes &thorn;i loouyng, and
&thorn;ou say it to &thorn;e loouyng of god and
help of o&thorn;er, &thorn;ou duse nogth vnwysely,
for &thorn;ou spekes southfastnes.  Bot if &thorn;ou
wil haue any preue loouyng, tele it til
nane bot swilk ane &thorn;at &thorn;ou be sekir
&thorn;at it sal nogth be schewed bot anely
to &thorn;e loouynge of gode of wham es all
gudnese, and &thorn;at makes sum better &thorn;an
other, and gifs &thorn;aim special graces,
nogth anely for &thorn;aim-self bot alswa
for &thorn;aim &thorn;at wile do wele, til &thorn;aire
ensampil.  &para; Clennes of werk thre thynges
kepis: Ane es assiduele thogth of &thorn;i dede
&mdash;for &thorn;e wyseman says: &laquo;Vmbethynke
&thorn;e of &thorn;i last endynge and &thorn;ou sal noth
syn&raquo;.  Another: fle fra ille felischipe
&thorn;at gifs mare ensampile to luf &thorn;e werld
&thorn;an god, &thorn;e erth &thorn;an heeuene, filthe of
bodye &thorn;an clennes of saul.  &para; &THORN;e thrid es
temperance and discrecion in mette and
drynke, &thorn;at it be nother till outrage, ne
byneethen skylwys sustynance of &thorn;e
body.  For bath comes til ane endyng: outrage
and ouer-mykele fastyng&mdash;For nother
es goddis wile; and &thorn;at wil many nogth


<PB N="27">

wene, ffor nogth &thorn;at man may say.  If
&thorn;ou take sustynance of swylke gud als
god sendes for &thorn;e tyme and &thorn;e day, what
it be, I out-tak [na] maner of mete &thorn;at
crystend men vses&mdash;with discrecyon and
mesure, &thorn;ou duse wele; ffor so did Cryst
hym-self and his Apostels.  If &thorn;ou leeue
many metes &thorn;at men has; nogth dispisand
&thorn;e met &thorn;at god has mad til mans help,
bot for &thorn;e thynke &thorn;at &thorn;ou has na nede
&thorn;arof, &thorn;ou duse wele, If &thorn;ou se &thorn;at &thorn;ou
ert stalward to serue god and at it
breekes nogth &thorn;i stomake.  For if &thorn;ou haue
broken &thorn;at with ouer-mykel abstynence,
&thorn;e es reft appityte of mete, and oft sal
&thorn;ou be in qwaythes, als &thorn;ou war redy
to gif &thorn;e gaste.  And wite &thorn;ou wele
&thorn;ou synned in &thorn;at dede.  And &thorn;ou
may nogth wite son whether &thorn;i
abstynence be agayne or with
&thorn;e.  For-&thorn;i, to-while &thorn;ou ert yhung, I red &thorn;at
&thorn;ou ete and drynke better and ware als
it comes, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be nogth
bygyled.  And afward, when &thorn;ou has proued many
thynges and ouer-comen many
temptacyons and knawys &thorn;i-self and god better
&thorn;an &thorn;ou dose now: &thorn;an, if &thorn;ou se at
it be at do, &thorn;ou may take &thorn;e til mare
abstynence.  And whils &thorn;ou may do
pryue penance, &thorn;at all men thar nogth
wite.  Rygthwy[s]nes es nother in
Fastyng ne in eetynge: Bot &thorn;ou ert
rygthwys If al he-like be to &thorn;e Dispite and
Loouyng, Poeuert and Rychesse, Hunger
and nede als delites and dayntes.  If
&thorn;ou tak &thorn;ir with a loouyng of god, I
hald &thorn;e blyssed and hegh byfor
Ihesu.  Men &thorn;at comes til &thorn;e, &thorn;ai luf &thorn;e for
&thorn;ai se &thorn;i grete abstynence and for &thorn;ai


<PB N="28">

se &thorn;e enclosed: bot I may nogth looue
&thorn;e so ligthly, for ogth &thorn;at I se &thorn;e do
with-outene, bot if &thorn;i wile be
confourmed entierly to goddis wile.  And set
nogth by &thorn;air loouyng ne &thorn;aire lackyng,
And gif &thorn;ou neeuer tale if &thorn;ai spek
lesse gud of &thorn;e &thorn;an &thorn;ai dide: Bot &thorn;at
&thorn;ou &thorn;e brynnander in goddis luf &thorn;an
&thorn;ou was.  For of a thyng I warne &thorn;e:
I hop &thorn;at god has na parfyte seruaunt
in erth with-outene enemys of sum men&mdash;
For anely wrycchedenes has nane
enemy.  &para; For to draw vs &thorn;at we confourme
our wile til goddis wile, &thorn;ar er thre
thyngs: &para; Ane es ensampil of haly men
and haly women, &thorn;e whilk war ententife
nygth and day to serue gode and drede
hym and luf hym; and if we folow
&thorn;aim in erth, we moun be with &thorn;aim
in heeuene.  &para; Ano&thorn;er es &thorn;e gudnes of
our lord &thorn;at despises nane, bot gladly
receyfs all &thorn;at come til his mercy, and
es hamelier to &thorn;aim &thorn;an bro&thorn;er or
sister or any frende &thorn;at &thorn;ai maast luf
or maast traystes on.  &para; &THORN;e thrid es:
&THORN;e woundirfull ioy of &thorn;e kyngdome of
heeuene, &thorn;at es mare &thorn;an tung may
telle or hert may thynke or eghe may
se or eer may heer.  It es so mykell
&thorn;at, als in hell mygth na thyng lyue
for mykel pyne bot at &thorn;e mygth of
god suffirs &thorn;aim nogth to dye, swa &thorn;e
Ioy in &thorn;e sygth of Ihesu in his
gudhede es so mykell &thorn;at &thorn;ai mond die
for Ioy, If it ne war his gudnes &thorn;at
wile &thorn;at his lufars be lifand ay in blysse,
als his rygthwysnes wile &thorn;at all &thorn;at
lufe hym nogth, be ay lifand in fyre,
&thorn;at es horrible til any man at thynke,


<PB N="29">

Lok &thorn;an what [it] es to feele!  Bot &thorn;ai &thorn;at
wile noght thynk it and drede it Now,
&thorn;ai sal suffre it, eeuermare.  &para; Now has
&thorn;ou herd how &thorn;ou may dispoose &thorn;i
life and rewle it to goddis wile.  Bot
I wate wele &thorn;at &thorn;ou desires to here
sum speciale poynt of &thorn;e luf of Ihesu
Cryst, and of Contemplatif lif &thorn;e &thorn;e whilke
&thorn;ou has takene &thorn;e til at mens sigth.
Als I haue grace and conyng I wile
lere &thorn;e.
</P>
<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">AMORE LANGUEO.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;ir twa wordis
er wrytene in &thorn;e bok of luf, or &thorn;e
sange of sanges&mdash;For he &thorn;at mykel lufs,
hym list oft syng of his luf, ffor ioy
&thorn;at he or scho has when &thorn;ai thynke
on &thorn;at at &thorn;ai luf, namely if &thorn;aire lufer
be trewe and lufand.  And es til &thorn;e
Inglisshe of &thorn;is twa wordis: I languysshe
for luf.  Sere men in erth has sere giftis
and graces of god: Bot &thorn;e special gift
of &thorn;ase &thorn;at ledis solitary life, es forto
luf Ihesu Cryst.  &THORN;ou says me: &laquo;All
men lufs hym &thorn;at haldes his
comaundementis.&raquo;  South it es; bot all &thorn;at kepis
his bedyng, kipis noght als his
counsayll; and all &thorn;at dos his counsayll, es
nogth als ful-filled of &thorn;e swetenes of
his lufe ne files nogth &thorn;e fire of
brynnand luf of hert.  For-&thorn;i &thorn;e diuersite
of luf makes &thorn;e diuersyte of halynes
and of mede in heeuen.  &THORN;e Angels
&thorn;at er brynnandest in luf, er nerrest
gode.  Alswa men or women &thorn;at maast
haf of goddis luf, whethir &thorn;ai do
penaunce or nane, &thorn;ai sal be in &thorn;e hegthest
degre in heeuene; &thorn;ai &thorn;at lufs hym
lesse, In &thorn;e lagther order.  If &thorn;ou luf


<PB N="30">

hym mykell, mykel Ioy and swetnes
&thorn;ou felis in his luf &thorn;at es &thorn;i comfort
and &thorn;i strength bath nygth and day;
If &thorn;i luf be nogth brynnand in hym,
litele es &thorn;i delite.  For hym may na
man fele in Ioy and swetnes but If he
be clenne and fillid with his luf.  And
&thorn;ar-til saltow come with gret trauayll
in prayer and thankyng, hafand swylke
meditaciouns &thorn;at er all in &thorn;e luf and
&thorn;e loouyng of god.  And when &thorn;ou ert
at &thorn;i meet, looue ay god in &thorn;i thogth
at ylke a morsell, and say &thorn;us in &thorn;i
hert: &laquo;Looued &thorn;e &thorn;ou kyng, and
thanked be &thorn;ou kyng, and blyssed be
&thorn;ou kyng, Ihesu all my ioying, of
all &thorn;i giftis gude, &thorn;at for me spylt &thorn;i
blode, and dyede on &thorn;e rode.  &THORN;ou gif
me grace to syng &thorn;e sang of &thorn;i
loouyng.&raquo;  And thynk it nogth anely whils
&thorn;ou eettis, bot bath bifoor and after,
ay bot when &thorn;ou prayes or spekes; or
if &thorn;ou haue other thoghtes &thorn;at &thorn;ou has
mare swetnes and deuocyon In &thorn;an in
&thorn;ase &thorn;at I lere &thorn;e, &thorn;ou may thynk
&thorn;aim.  For I hop &thorn;at god wile do
swylke thoghtes in &thorn;i hert als he es
payed of, and als &thorn;ou ert ordaynede.
For when &thorn;ou prays, loke nogth how
mykell &thorn;ou says, bot how wele; &thorn;at &thorn;e
luf of &thorn;i hert be ay vpward and &thorn;i
thogth on &thorn;at &thorn;ou says als mykel als
&thorn;ou may.  If &thorn;ou be in prayers and
meditac&ymacr;ons al &thorn;e day, I wate wele &thorn;at
&thorn;ou mon wax gretly in &thorn;e luf of Ihesu


<PB N="31">

Cryst and mykel fele of delite, and
with-Ine schort tyme.  &para; Thre degrees
of luf I sal telle &thorn;e: For I wil &thorn;at &thorn;ou
mygth wynne to &thorn;e hegthest.  &para; &THORN;e fyrst
degre es called Insuperable.  &para; &THORN;e secund
Inseparable.  &para; &THORN;e third Singuler.  &para; &THORN;i
luf es insuperable when na thyng &thorn;at
es contrary til goddis luf ouer-comes it,
bot es stalward agayne all fandyngs,
and stable, whether &thorn;ou be in eese or
in anguys, or in heele or in sekenes;
swa &thorn;at &thorn;e thynke &thorn;at &thorn;ou wald nogth
for all &thorn;e werld, to haue it with-outene
ende, wreth god ane tyme, and &thorn;e war
leeuer, if other suld be, to suffre al &thorn;e
pyne and &thorn;e wa &thorn;at mygth come til
any creature, or &thorn;ou wald do &thorn;e thyng
&thorn;at suld mys-pay hym.  On &thorn;is maner
sal &thorn;i luf be Insuperable, &thorn;at na thyng
may doun bryng bot springand on hegth.
Blyssed es he or scho &thorn;at es in &thorn;is
degree!  Bot yhete war &thorn;ay blysseder
&thorn;at mygth hald &thorn;is degre and wynne
in til &thorn;e tothyr, &thorn;at es Inseparable.
&para; Inseparable es &thorn;i luf whenn all &thorn;i
hert and &thorn;i thogth and &thorn;i mygth es so
haly, so entierly and so parfytely
festend, sete and stablede in Ihesu Crist,
&thorn;at &thorn;i thogth comes neeuer of hym,
neeuer departyd fra hym, out-taken
slepynge: And als son als &thorn;ou wakkenes,
&thorn;i hert es on hym, sayand <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aue Maria</FOREIGN>,
or<FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> Gloria tibi domin&macr;e</FOREIGN>, or <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater
noster</FOREIGN>, or <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Miserere mei deus</FOREIGN> If &thorn;ou


<PB N="32">

haue bene temped in &thorn;i slepe, or
thynk-and his luf and his loouyng als &thorn;ou
did wakand.  When &thorn;ou may na tyme
forgete hym, what so &thorn;ou duse or
says, &thorn;an es &thorn;i luf Inseparable.  Ful
mykele grace haue &thorn;ay &thorn;at er in &thorn;is
degre of luf!  And me thynk &thorn;at &thorn;ou
&thorn;at has nogth ells at do [but] forto luf
god, may come &thorn;ar-til, if any may it
gete.  &para; &THORN;e thred degre es hegthest, and
maast ferly to wynne: &THORN;at es Called
singuler, ffor &thorn;at has na pier.  Singuler
luf es when all Comforth and solace
es closed out of &thorn;e hert bot of Ihesu
Cryst anely.  Other delyte ne other
Ioy list it nogth.  For &thorn;e swetnes of
hym in &thorn;is degre es swa comfortand
and lastand in his luf, swa brynnand
and gladand, &thorn;at he or scho &thorn;at es in
&thorn;is degre, may als wele fele &thorn;e fyre
of luf brynnand in &thorn;air saule, als &thorn;ou
may feile &thorn;i fynger brynne if &thorn;ou pute
it in &thorn;e fyre.  Bot &thorn;at fyre, if it be
hate, es so delytable and wondirfull
&thorn;at I can nogth telle it.  &THORN;an &thorn;e saul es
Ihesu lufand, Ihesu thynkand, Ihesu
desyrand, anely in couaytes of hym hangand, til
hym sygthand, of hym brennand, in hym
restand.  &THORN;an &thorn;e sang of loouyng and
of luf es comen.  &THORN;an &thorn;i thogth turnys
in to sang and melody.  &THORN;an &thorn;e
bihoues syng &thorn;e psalmes &thorn;at &thorn;ou byfore
sayd.  &THORN;an &thorn;ou mon be lang about fa
psalmes.  &THORN;an &thorn;e wil thynke &thorn;e deide
swetter &thorn;an hony, ffor &thorn;an &thorn;ou ert
ful sekyr to se hym &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufs.  &THORN;an
may &thorn;ou hardyly say: &laquo;I languysshe
for luf.&raquo;  &THORN;an may &thorn;ou say: &laquo;I slep and my


<PB N="33">

hert wakes.&raquo;  In &thorn;e fyrst degre men may
say &laquo;I languysshe for luf&raquo; or &laquo;me
langesforluf&raquo;, and in &thorn;e tother degre
alswa: for languyssyng es, when men
falles for sekenes, and &thorn;a &thorn;at er in
&thorn;is twa degrees, falles fra all couaytese
of &thorn;is werld and fra lust and
lykyng of synfull lif, and settis &thorn;air
entent and &thorn;air hert til &thorn;e luf of god;
for-&thorn;i may &thorn;ay say: &laquo;I languysshe for
luf&raquo; &mdash; and mykel mare &thorn;at er in &thorn;e
secund degre [&thorn;an] in &thorn;e fyrst.  &para; Bot
&thorn;e saul &thorn;at es in &thorn;e thred degre, es
als brynnand fyre, and als &thorn;e nygthgale
&thorn;at lufs sang and melody and falles
for mykele luf.  Swa &thorn;at &thorn;e saul es
anely comforted in loouyng and lufyng
of god, and til &thorn;e dede come, es
syngand gaastly til Ihesu, and in Ihesu,
and Ihesu, nogth bodyly cryand with
&thorn;e mouth&mdash;of &thorn;at maner of syngyng
speke I nogth, ffor &thorn;at sang has bath
gud and ille; and &thorn;is maner of sang has
nane bot if &thorn;ai be in &thorn;is thred degre
of luf: til &thorn;e whilke degre it es
Inpossible to cum bot in a gret multitude
of luf.  For-&thorn;i, if &thorn;ou wil wite
whatkyns ioy &thorn;at sang has, I say &thorn;e &thorn;at
na man wate bote he or scho &thorn;at felis
it, &thorn;at has it, and &thorn;at looues god
syngand &thorn;ar-with.  Ane thyng telle I &thorn;e:
It es of heeuene, and god gifs it til
whame he wille, bot nogth with-outene
gret graces comand bifore.  Wha so has
it, hym thynk all &thorn;e sang and &thorn;e
mynstralcy of erth nogth bot sorow and
waa &thorn;ar-til.  In souerayne rest sal
&thorn;ai be &thorn;at mon get it.  Gangrels and
Ianglers and kepers of comers and


<PB N="34">

gangers arely and lat, nygth and day,
or any &thorn;at taglede es with any synne
wylfully and wetandly, or &thorn;at has delite
in any erthly thyng: &thorn;ay er als fer
&thorn;ar-fra als es fra heeuen til erth.  &para; In
&thorn;e fyrst degre er many; In &thorn;e to&thorn;er
degre er ful faa: bot in &thorn;e thred degre
vnnethes er any&mdash;for ay &thorn;e mare at &thorn;e
perfeccyone es, &thorn;e fouer folowers it
has.  In &thorn;e fyrst degre er men lykened
til &thorn;e sternes; In &thorn;e tothir degre til &thorn;e
mon: and in &thorn;e thred degre til &thorn;e
sonne.  For-&thorn;i says sayne Paul: &laquo;Othir
es of &thorn;e sonne, Othir of &thorn;e mone,
othir of &thorn;e sternes.&raquo;  Swa es it of &thorn;e
lufers of god.  In &thorn;is thred degre, if
&thorn;ou may wynne &thorn;are-til, &thorn;ou sal wite
of mare Ioy &thorn;an I haf taled &thorn;e yhete.
And amang othir affeccyons and sanges
&thorn;ou may in &thorn;i langyng syng &thorn;is in &thorn;i
hert til &thorn;i louerd Ihesu, whene &thorn;ou
couaytes his comyng and &thorn;i gangynge:
&para; &laquo;When wil &thorn;ou come to comfort me
and bryng me out of care, And gif
me &thorn;e &thorn;at I may se, hafand
eeuermare?  &THORN;i luf es ay swetest of all &thorn;at euer
ware.  My hert whene sal it brest? for
luf &thorn;an languyst I no mare.  For luf my
thogth has fest, and I am fayne to fare.  I
stand in stil mournyng of ane, &thorn;e luflyest of
lare; es luflangyng.  It drawes me til my day,
&thorn;e band of swete brynnyng, For it haldes
me ay fra place and fra playn&macr;g, Til &thorn;at I
gete may &thorn;e sygth of my swettyng, &THORN;at
wendys neeuer away, In welth beese our
wakynge, with-outen noy or nygth, My luf
es in lastyng, And langes vnto &thorn;at sigth.&raquo;


<PB N="35">

<PTR TARGET="n2">&para; If &thorn;ou wil be wele with god and haf
grace to rewel &thorn;i lif and com til &thorn;e ioy of
luf, &thorn;is name of Ihesu fest it so fast in &thorn;i
hert &thorn;at it come neeuer out of &thorn;i thogth.
And when &thorn;ou spekis til hym and says
Ihesu thurgth coustome, it sal be in
&thorn;ine eer Ioy, in &thorn;i mouth hony, and
in &thorn;i hert melody: For &thorn;e sal thynk
Ioy to heer &thorn;at name be neeuend,
Swetenes to spek it, Mirth and sang to
thynke it.  If &thorn;ou thynk on Ihesu
contynuelly and haldes it stabilly,
it purges &thorn;i synne, and kyndels
&thorn;i hert.  It claryfies &thorn;i saul.  It
remoues anger, and duse away slawnes.
It woundes in luf, Fulfilles of
charyte.  It chaces &thorn;e deeuel.  It puttes out
drede.  It opens heeuene and makis a
Contemplatif man.  Haf in memor Ihesu:
for all vices and fantoms it puttes fra
&thorn;e lufer.  And hayls oft Marye, bath
day and nygth!  Mikel luf and ioy sal
&thorn;ou fele If &thorn;ou wil do after &thorn;is lare.
&THORN;e thar nogth couayte gretely many
bokes: hald luf in hert and in werk,
and &thorn;ou sal haue all &thorn;at we may say
or wryte: for fulnes of &thorn;e lagthe es
charyte; In &thorn;at hynges all.  &para; Bot now
may &thorn;ou aske me and say: &laquo;&THORN;ou spekis
so mykel of luf: Telle me what luf
es, and whar it es, and how I sal lufe
god veraly, and how I may knawe &thorn;at
I luf hym, and In what state I may
maast luf hym.&raquo;  &THORN;ir er hard qwestyons
to lere to a feble man and a flesshly
als I am.  Bot neeuer-&thorn;e-latter &thorn;are-


<PB N="36">

foore sal I nogth leue &thorn;at I ne sal
schew my witte and als me thynke &thorn;at
it may be: For I hop in &thorn;e help of
Ihesu, &thorn;at es welle of luf and pees of
swetenes.  &para; &THORN;E fyrst askyng es: What
es luf?  And I answer: luf es brennand
yhernyng In god with a woundirful
delite and sikyrnes.  God es lygth and
brynnyng.  Ligth clarifies our skylle,
and brynnyng kyndeles oure couaytese,
&thorn;at we desire nogth bot hym.  Luf es
a lif coupland to-gider &thorn;e lufand and
&thorn;e lufed: For mekenes makys vs swet
to god, Purete Ioynes vs til god, luf makes
vs ane with god.  Luf es fayrest of all
vertus.  Luf es thynge thurgth &thorn;e whilke god
lufs vs, and we god; and ylk ane of vs
other.  Luf es desire of &thorn;e hert, ay
thynk-and til &thorn;at it lufs; and when it has &thorn;at it
lufs, &thorn;an it Ioyese, and na thyng may mak
it sary.  Luf es yhernyng Imelle twa,
with lastandnes of thoghtes.  Luf es a
stiryng of &thorn;e saul for to luf god for
hym-self, and all other thyng for god;
&thorn;e whylk luf when it es ordayned in
god, it dose away all vnordayned luf
in any thyng &thorn;at es nogth gud.  Bot
all dedely [syn] es vnordayned luf in
a thyng &thorn;at es nogth: &thorn;an luf puttes
out all dedly synne.  Luf es a vertu,
&thorn;at es &thorn;e rygth affeccyoun of a mans
saul.  Trouthe nogth(!) may be with-outen
luf, bot it may help with-outen it.
Luf es perfeccyoun&macr; of letters, vertue of
prophetye, fruyte of trouthe, heel of
sacramentis, stablyng of wite and
conyng, Rychesce of pouer men, Lif of
diand men.  &para; Se how god luf es!  If we


<PB N="37">

suffre to be slayne; If we gif all &thorn;at
we haf, til begger stafe; If we can als
mykel als men may cun in erth: til all
&thorn;is with-outene lufe, es nogth bot
sorow ordayned and tourment.  &para; If &thorn;ou
wil ask howe gud he es or scho, ask
how mykel lufs he or scho: and &thorn;at
can na man telle&mdash;For&thorn;i I hald it bot
foly to deme of a mans hert, &thorn;at nane
knawys bot god.  Luf es a rygthwys
turnyng fra all erthly thynges, and es
Ioynt til god, with-outene departyng,
and kyndeled with &thorn;e fier of &thorn;e haly
gast; fer fra filyng, fer fra Corupcyoun,
obliged til na vice of &thorn;is lif, Hegth
aboun all flesshely lustes.  Ay redy
and gredy til Contemplacyoun of god.
In all thynges vnouercommene.  &THORN;e soun
of all gud affeccyons.  Heel of gud
maners.  End of &thorn;e comandementis of
god.  Dede of synnes.  Lif of vertus.
Vertu whils fightyng lastes.  Coroun of
ouercomers.  Armes til haly thoghtes.
With-outene &thorn;at, na man may pay god;
with &thorn;at, na man synnes&mdash;For if we
luf god in all our hert, &thorn;ar es na
thyng in vs thurgth &thorn;e whilke we
serue to synne.  Verray luf clenses &thorn;e
saul, and delyuers it fra &thorn;e payne of
hell, and of &thorn;e foule seruyse of synne,
and of &thorn;e vgly felishipe of deeuels;
and of &thorn;e fendes sone makis goddis
sone, and partyner of &thorn;e herytage of
heeuen.  We sal afforce vs to cleeth vs
in luf als &thorn;e Iren or &thorn;e cool dose in
&thorn;e fyer, Als &thorn;e ayre duse in &thorn;e son,
Als &thorn;e wolle duse in &thorn;e hewe.  &THORN;e
cool swa cleethes it in &thorn;e fyre &thorn;at all
es fyre.  &THORN;e ayre swa cleethes it in &thorn;e


<PB N="38">

sone &thorn;at all es ligth.  And &thorn;e wolle so
substauncyaly takes &thorn;e hewe &thorn;at it es
like it.  In &thorn;is maner sal a trew lufer
of Ihesu Cryst do: his hert sal so brene
in lufe &thorn;at it sal be turnyd in til fyer
of luf and be als it war all fyre; and
sall swa schyne in vertus &thorn;at in na part
of hym he be myrke in vices.&mdash;&para; &THORN;e
tother askynge es: Whar es luf?  And
I answer: luf es in &thorn;e hert and in &thorn;e
wile of a man, nogth in his hand ne
in his mouth, &thorn;at es at say: nogth in
his werke, bot in his saul.  For many
spekes gud and duse gud, and lufs
nogth god: Als Ipocrytes, &thorn;e whilk
suffres grete penance and semes haly
to mens sygth: Bot for &thorn;ay seke
loouyng and honour of men and
fauour, &thorn;ai haf lost &thorn;air mede and in &thorn;e
sygth of god er &thorn;e deeuels son&macr;s and
Rauyschand wolfes.  Bot if a man gif
almus-dede and takys hym til poouert
and duse penance, it es a syng &thorn;at he
lufs god, bot &thorn;are-foore lufs he hym
nogth.  Bot when he forsakis &thorn;e werld
anely for goddis luf and settis all his
thogth on god and lufs all men als
hym-self, and all &thorn;e gud dedes &thorn;at he
may do, he dose &thorn;aim in entent for to
pay Ihesu Crist and to come til &thorn;e
rest of heeuen: &thorn;an he lufs god, and
&thorn;at luf es in his saul, and swa his
dedis schewes with-outen.  If &thorn;ou spek
&thorn;e gud and do &thorn;e gud, men supposes
&thorn;at &thorn;ou lufs god: For&thorn;i lok wele
&thorn;at &thorn;i thogth be in god, or ells &thorn;ou
dampnes &thorn;i-self and deceyfs &thorn;e men.
Na thyng &thorn;at I do with-outen prooues


<PB N="39">

&thorn;at I luf god: For a wykked man
mygth do als mykel penance in body,
als mykel wak and fast als I do.  How
may I &thorn;ane wene &thorn;at I luf, or hald
me better, ffor &thorn;at at ylk a man may
do?  Ceertis, my hert, whethir I luf my
god or nogth, wate na mane bot god,
for nogth &thorn;at &thorn;ai may se me do.
Whaar-foor luf es in wile verrayly,
nogth in werke, bot als synge of luf.
For he &thorn;at says he lufs god and wil
nogth do in dede &thorn;at in hym es to
schew luf, say hym he leghes!  Luf
wil nogth be Idele: It es wirkand some
gud eeuer-mare.  If it cees of wirkyng,
wite &thorn;ou wele it kelis and wytes away.&mdash;
&para; &THORN;E third askyng es: &laquo;How sal I
verrayly luf god?&raquo;  I answer: verray luf es,
to lufe hym in all &thorn;i mygth stalwardly;
In all &thorn;i hert wysely; In all &thorn;i saul
deuoutely and swetly.  &para; Stalwardly may
na man luf hym bot If he be stalward.
He es stalward &thorn;at es meke: For all
gastely strenth comes of mekenes&mdash;on whame
restis &thorn;e haly gast? in a meke saul.  Mekenes
gouernes vs and kepis vs in all our
temptacyons, swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai ouer-come vs nogth.
Bot &thorn;e deeuel deceyfs many &thorn;at er meke
thurgth tribulacyons and reproefs and
backbytynges.  Bot if &thorn;ou be wrathe for
any anguys of &thorn;is werld, or for any
word &thorn;at men says of &thorn;e, or for ogth
&thorn;at men says til &thorn;e, &thorn;ou ne ert nogth
meke, ne &thorn;ou ne may nogth so luf god
stalwardly.  For luf es stalward als &thorn;e
dede, &thorn;at slaas al lifand thyng in erth;


<PB N="40">

and hard als hell, &thorn;at spares nogth to
&thorn;aim &thorn;at er dede.  &THORN;arefoor he &thorn;at
lufs god parfytely, he ne griefs hym
nogth, what schame or anguys so he
suffirs, bot he has delyte and couaytes
&thorn;at he war worthy for to suffre
tourment and payne for Cristis lufe, and he
has Ioy &thorn;at men reproues hym and
speke ille of hym.  Als a dede man,
what so men dose or says, answers
nogth: swa wha so lufs god parfytely,
&thorn;ai er nogth stirid for na word &thorn;at man
may say.  For he or scho can nogth
luf &thorn;at may nogth suffre payne and
angre for &thorn;aire frendys luf: For wha so
lufs, &thorn;ai haf na pyne.  Proud man or
woman lufs nogth stalwardly: For &thorn;ai
er so wayke &thorn;at &thorn;ai fal at ylke
stirynge of &thorn;e wynd, &thorn;at es temptacyoun.
&THORN;ai seke hegther stede &thorn;an Cryst: For
&thorn;ai wile haf &thorn;aire wile done whethir it
be with rygth or with wrange, and
Cryst wil na thyng be done bote wele
and with-outene harme of othir men.
Bot wha so es verrayly meke, &thorn;ai wile
nogth haue &thorn;aire wile in &thorn;is werld,
&thorn;at &thorn;ai may haf it in &thorn;e tothir plenerly.
In na thyng may men soner ouer-come
&thorn;e deeuel &thorn;an in meknes, &thorn;at he mykele
haatis: For he may waak and fast and
suffre pyne, mare &thorn;an any other
creature may, bot mekenes and luf may he
nogth haue.  &para; Alswa &thorn;e bihoues luf
god wysely.  And &thorn;at may &thorn;ou nogth
do, bot if &thorn;ou be wys.  &THORN;ou ert wys,
when &thorn;ou ert pouer, with-outen
couaytese of &thorn;is werld, and despyses &thorn;i-self


<PB N="41">

for &thorn;e luf of Ihesu Crist, and dispendys
all &thorn;i wite and &thorn;i mygth in his seruyse.
For some &thorn;at semes wysest er maast
foles, ffor all &thorn;aire wysdom &thorn;ai spyll
in couaytese and bysenes about &thorn;e werld.
&para; If &thorn;ou sagth a man haue precyous
stanes &thorn;at he mygth by a kyngdome
with; If he gaf &thorn;aim for ane appyl als
a barne wil do, rygthly mot &thorn;ou say
&thorn;at he war nogth wys, bot a grete fole.
Whar-foor, if we wile, we haf precyous
stanes: pouert, and penance, and gastly
trauayle, with &thorn;e whilk we may bye
&thorn;e kyngdom of heeuen.  For if &thorn;at
&thorn;ou luf pouert and despise rychesce
and delyces of &thorn;is werld and haldis
&thorn;i-self vyle and pouer and thynkes &thorn;at
&thorn;ou has nogth of &thorn;i self bot synne:
ffor &thorn;is pouert &thorn;ou sal haf rychesce
with-outen ende.  And if &thorn;ou haf sorow
for &thorn;i synnes and for &thorn;ou ert so lang
in exile out of &thorn;i cuntre, and forsakes
&thorn;e solace of &thorn;is lif, &thorn;ou sal haf for
&thorn;is sorow &thorn;e Ioy of heeuen.  And if
[&thorn;ou] be in trauayl and punysches &thorn;i
body skylwysly and wysely in wakynges
and fastynges and in prayers and
meditacyons, and suffirs hete and cald,
hunger and threst, Mysays and angwys,
for &thorn;e luf of Ihesu Cryst, for &thorn;is
trauayle &thorn;ou sal come til &thorn;e rest &thorn;at
lastes ay, and sitte in a setill of ioy
with aungels.  Bot some er &thorn;at lufs
nogth wysely, lyke til barnes &thorn;at
lufs mare ane appyl &thorn;an a castel; swa
dose many: &thorn;ai gif &thorn;e Ioy of heeuen
for a litil delite of &thorn;aire flesshe, &thorn;at es
nogth worth a ploune.  &para; Now may &thorn;ou


<PB N="42">

se &thorn;at wha so wil luf wysely, hym
bihoues luf lastand thyng lastandly,
Passand thynge passandly; swa &thorn;at his
hert be sette and festend in na thyng
bot in god.  &para; And if &thorn;ou wil luf Ihesu
verrayly, &thorn;ou sal nogth anely luf hym
stalwardly and wysely, bot alswa
deuoutely and swetly.  &para; Swete luf es,
when &thorn;i body es chast and &thorn;i thogth
clenne.  &para; Deuoute luf es, when &thorn;ou
offers &thorn;i prayers and &thorn;i thoghtes til
god with gastly Ioy and brynnand
hert in &thorn;e hete of &thorn;e haly gast, swa
&thorn;at &thorn;e thynk &thorn;at &thorn;i saul es als it war
drunken for delyte and solace of &thorn;e
swetnes of Ihesu, and &thorn;i hert conceyfs
so mykel of goddis help &thorn;at &thorn;e thynke
&thorn;ou may neeuer be fra hym departyde;
and &thorn;ou comes in til swylke rest and
pees in saul and quyete, with-outen
thoghtes of vanytesce or of vyces, als
&thorn;ou war in silence and slepe, and sette
in Noe schipe, &thorn;at na thyng may lette [&thorn;e]
of deuocyoun&macr; and brynnyng of swet luf.
Fra &thorn;ou haf getyn &thorn;is luf, al &thorn;i lif, til
dede come, es Ioy and confort als verray
Chryst lufer, and he restis in &thorn;e whase
steed es maked in pees.&mdash;&para; &THORN;E fierth
askyng was: How &thorn;ou mot knaw
&thorn;at &thorn;ou war in luf and charyte.  I
answer &thorn;at na man whate in erth &thorn;at
&thorn;ai er in charyte, bot if it be thurgth
any priuelage of speciale grace &thorn;at god
has gifen til any man or woman, &thorn;at
all othir may nogth take ensampyl bye.
Haly men and women troues &thorn;at &thorn;ai
haf trouth and hop and charite, and
in &thorn;at duse als wele als &thorn;ai may, and


<PB N="43">

hoopes certaynly &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal be saaf;
&thorn;ai wate it nogth als tyte: ffor if &thorn;ai
wyste, &thorn;aire meryte war &thorn;e lesse.  And
Salamon says &thorn;at it er rygthwys men
and wys men, and &thorn;aire werkis er in
goddis hand.  And nogth-for-&thorn;i a man
wat nogth whethire [he] be worthy
hatred or luf: Bot al es reseerued
vncertayne til anothir werld.
Neeuer-&thorn;e-latter if any had grace &thorn;at he mygth
wynne til &thorn;e thred degre of luf, &thorn;at I
called Singulere, he suld knawe &thorn;at he
war in luf.  Bot in &thorn;at maner his
knawyng es &thorn;at he mygth neeuer beer
hym &thorn;e hegther ne be in &thorn;e lesse bisynes
to luf god, bot swa mykel &thorn;e mare &thorn;at
he es sekir of luf, wald he be bisy to
luf hym and drede hym &thorn;at has mad
swylke bisynes(!), and done &thorn;at gudnes.
And knawe &thorn;at he es so hegthe, he
wald nogth hald hym-self worthyer &thorn;an
&thorn;e synfullest man &thorn;at gas on erthe.
&para; Alswa seeuene experymentis eer &thorn;at a
man be in charyte.  &THORN;e first es, when
all couaytese of erthly thyng es sleckend
in hym.  For whar so couaytyse es,
&thorn;are es na luf of Cryst.  &THORN;an if he haf
na couaytyse, sygne es &thorn;at he has
luf.  &THORN;e secund es, brynnand yhernyng
of heeuene.  For when men has felid
ogth of &thorn;at sauour, &thorn;e mare &thorn;ai haf
&thorn;e mare &thorn;ai couayte, and he &thorn;at nogth
has felid nogth he desyres.  For-&thorn;i when
any es so mykel gifen til &thorn;e luf &thorn;arof
&thorn;at he can fynd na Ioy in &thorn;is lif, Taken
he has &thorn;at he es in Charyte.  &THORN;e thred
es: If his tung be chaunged, &thorn;at was
wone to speke of &thorn;e erth, and now


<PB N="44">

spekes of god and of &thorn;e lif &thorn;at lastes
ay.  &THORN;e fierth es, excercyse of gaastly
profyte, als if any man or woman gifs
&thorn;aim entierly til goddis seruyse and
entirmetis &thorn;aim of nane erthly bisynes.
&THORN;e fift es, when &thorn;e thinges &thorn;at er hard
in &thorn;aim-self, semes ligth forto do.  &THORN;at
luf makes.  For als Calcidor says:
Lufreden es &thorn;e thyng &thorn;at brynges
nerehand inpossible til possible mygth
appeertly.  &THORN;e sext es, hardynes of
thogth to suffre all angwysses and noyse
&thorn;at comes&mdash;with-outene &thorn;is, all &thorn;e tothir
ne suffyces nogth.  For it sal nogth
make a rygthwys man sary what so
bifalles hym.  For he &thorn;at es Rygthwys,
he haatis nogth bot synne, he lufs nogth
bot god, he dredis nogth bot to wrethe
god.  &THORN;e seuent es, delytablete in saul;
when he es in tribulacyoun and makis
loouyng to god in ylk ane angre
&thorn;at he suffres.  And &thorn;is schewys wele
&thorn;at he lufs god when na waa may bryng
hym doun.  For many looues god whiles
&thorn;ai er in eese, and in aduersyte &thorn;ai
grucche and in til so mykel sarynes &thorn;ai
falle &thorn;at vnnethes may any man comfort
&thorn;aim, and swa sk[l]aunder &thorn;ai god, flitand
and figthtand agaynes hys domes.  And
&thorn;at es a caytif loouyng &thorn;at any welth
of &thorn;e werld makes!  Bot &thorn;at loouyng
es of mykel prys &thorn;at na vyolence of
sorowe may do a-way.&mdash;&THORN;E fift askyng
was: In what state men may maast luf
god.  I answer: In whilke state so it
be &thorn;at men er in maast rest of body


<PB N="45">

and saul, and leest occupyed with any
nedis or bisynes of &thorn;is werld.  For &thorn;e
thogth of &thorn;e luf of Ihesu Cryst and of &thorn;e
day &thorn;at lastis ay, sekis rest with-outen,
&thorn;at it be nogth lettid with comers and
gangers and occupacyon of werldisshe
thynges; and it sekis with-Inne gret
silence fra &thorn;e noyse of couaytise and
of vanytese and erthly thoghtes.  And
namely all &thorn;at luf contemplatife lif, &thorn;ai
seke rest in body and in saul.  For a
gret doctor says &thorn;at &thorn;ai er goddis throne
&thorn;at dwellis stille in a stede and er nogth
about rennand, bot in swettenes of
Crystis luf, er stablede.  &para; And I haf
lufd forto sytte, for na penance, ne for
na fantasy &thorn;at I wald men spake of
me, ne for na swilke thyng, bot anely
for I knewe &thorn;at I lufd god mare and
lengar lasted with me comfort of lufe,
&thorn;an gangand or standand or kneland.
For sittand am I in mast rest, and my
hert mast vpward.  Bot &thorn;arfor parauenture
it es nogth &thorn;e best til anothir to sitte
als I haf done and wil do to my dede,
bot if he war disposed als I was in his
saul.</P>
<P> 
<PB N="46">Twa lifs er &thorn;at cristen men lifs:
Ane es called actife lif: for it es [in]
mare werke bodely.  Anothir Contemplatif
lif: for it es in mare swetnes gastly.
&para; Actif lif es mykel outward, and in
mare trauaylle and in mare perille,


<PB N="47">

for temptacyons &thorn;at er in &thorn;e werld.
&para; Contemplatif lif es mykel inward,
and for-[&thorn;i] it es lastander and sikerer,
restfuler, delitabler, luflyer and mare
medfull.  For it has Ioy in goddis
luf, and sauour in &thorn;e lif &thorn;at lastes ay,
in &thorn;is present tyme if it be rygth ledde.
And &thorn;at felyng of Ioy in &thorn;e luf of Ihesu
passes all othir merytes in erthe.  For
it es so hard to cum tille, ffor &thorn;e freyllte
of our flesshe and &thorn;e many temptacyons
&thorn;at we er vmsette with, &thorn;at lettis vs
nygth and day: All othir thynges er
ligth at come to in reward &thorn;areof.  For
&thorn;at may na man deserue: Bot anely it
er gifen of goddis gudnes til &thorn;aim &thorn;at
verrayly gifs &thorn;aim til Contemplacyone and til
quyete for Cristis luf.  Til men or women
&thorn;at takis &thorn;aim til actif lif, Twa thynges
falles: Ane, forto ordayne &thorn;aire menyhe
in drede and in luf of god and fynd
&thorn;aim &thorn;aire necessaryes, and &thorn;aim-self
kepe entierly &thorn;e comaundementis of god,
doand with &thorn;aire neigthbur als &thorn;ai
wil &thorn;at &thorn;ai do til &thorn;aim.  &para; Anothir es
&thorn;at &thorn;ai do at &thorn;aire power &thorn;e seuene
werkys of mercy; &thorn;e whilke es: to fede &thorn;e
hungry, To gif &thorn;e thresty a drynke,
To cleth &thorn;e naaked, To herber hym
&thorn;at has na housyng, To vysete &thorn;e seke,
To comfort &thorn;aim &thorn;at er in preson, and
to graue dede men.  All &thorn;a &thorn;at may,
and has cost, &thorn;ai may nogth be quyte
with ane or twa of &thorn;ir, bot &thorn;aim
bihoues to do &thorn;aim all, If &thorn;ai wil haf
&thorn;e beneson on domes-day &thorn;at Ihesu


<PB N="48">

Crist sal til all gif &thorn;at duse &thorn;aim.  Or
elles may &thorn;ai dred &thorn;e malysoune &thorn;at
all mon haue &thorn;at wil nogth do &thorn;aim
when &thorn;ai had guddes to do &thorn;aim with.
&para; Contemplatyf lif has twa partys, a
lagther and a hegther.  &THORN;e lagher partye
es medytacyone of haly wrytyng&mdash;&thorn;at
es godis wordis&mdash;and in othir gude
thoghtes and swete &thorn;at men has of &thorn;e
grace of god obout &thorn;e luf of Ihesu Cryst;
and alswa in loouyng of god in
psalmes and ympnes, or in prayers.
&para; &THORN;e hegther party of Contemplacyoune
es bihaldyng and yhernyng of &thorn;e thynges
of heeuene, and Ioy in &thorn;e haly gast;
&thorn;at men has of grace, and if it be
swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai be nogth prayand with &thorn;e
mouthe bot anely thynkand on god
and of &thorn;e fayrehed of angells and haly
sauls.  &THORN;an may I say &thorn;at Contemplacyone
es a woundirfull Ioy of goddis luf, &thorn;e
whilke Ioy es loouyng of gode &thorn;at may
nogth be tald, and &thorn;at woundirful
loouyng es in &thorn;e saul.  And for
aboundaunce of ioy and swetnes it ascendis
in til &thorn;e mouthe, swa &thorn;at &thorn;e hert and
&thorn;e tung accord in ane, and body and
saul Ioyse in god lifand.  &para; A man or
woman &thorn;at es ordand til Countemplatif
life, fyrst god enspires &thorn;aim to forsake
&thorn;is werld and all &thorn;e vanyte and &thorn;e
couaytise and &thorn;e vyle lust &thorn;are-of.
Sithen he leddis &thorn;aim by &thorn;aire ane and
spekis til &thorn;aire hert: and als &thorn;e prophete
says, he gifs &thorn;aim at souke &thorn;e swetnes
of &thorn;e bygynnyng of luf; and &thorn;an he
settis &thorn;aim in wille to gif &thorn;aim haally
to prayers and meditacyons and teeris.
Sithen when &thorn;ai haf suffred many


<PB N="49">

temptacyons, and &thorn;e foul noys of
thoghtes &thorn;at er Idell, and of vanytyse,
&thorn;e whilke wile combre &thorn;aim &thorn;at can
nogth distroye &thorn;aim, es passand away,
he gers &thorn;aim gader til &thorn;aim &thorn;aire hertis
and fest &thorn;aim haally in hym: and opens
til &thorn;e egth of &thorn;aire saul &thorn;e yhates of
heeuen, swa &thorn;at &thorn;at ylke egthe lukes
in til heeuen.  And &thorn;an &thorn;e stye of luf
verrayly ligges in &thorn;aire hert and brynnes
&thorn;are-Inne, and makis it clenne of erthly
fylth; and sithen-forthward &thorn;ai er
Contemplatife men and rauyshed in luf.
For Contemplacyoune es a sygth: &thorn;ai
se in til heeuen with &thorn;aire gastly egthe.
Bot &thorn;ou sal wyte &thorn;at na man.has parfite
sigth of heeuen whils &thorn;ai er lifand bodyly
here; bot als sone als &thorn;ai dye, &thorn;ai er
brogth byfore god and seese hym face
til face and eghe til eghe, and wonnes
with hym with-outen end.  For hym
&thorn;ai sogth and hym &thorn;ai couayted and
hym &thorn;ai lufd in all &thorn;aire mygth.
</P>
<P>Lo, Cecil, I haf schortly sayd [&thorn;e]
&thorn;e fourme of lufyng, and how &thorn;ou may
come til perfeccyoune and to luf hym
&thorn;at &thorn;ou has taken &thorn;e til.  If it do &thorn;e
gud and profyte, thanke god, and pray
for me.  &THORN;e grace of Ihesu Cryst be
with &thorn;e and kepe &thorn;e.  Amen.</P></DIV3></DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ego Dormio et Cor Meum Vigilat</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<DIV3 N="Cambridge Dd V.64" TYPE="MS">
<PB N="50"><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Cambr. Dd V. 64</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="122" UNIT="folio">
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">(E)Go dormio &amp; cor meum uigilat.</FOREIGN>
&THORN;ou &thorn;at lyste lufe, herken &amp; here of
luf.  In &thorn;e sang of luf it es writen:
&laquo;I slepe &amp; my hert wakes.&raquo;  Mykel
lufe he schewes &thorn;at neuer is irk to
lufe, bot ay, standand, sittand, gangand
or wirkand, es ay his lufe thynkand,
and oft-syth &thorn;arof es dremande.
For&thorn;i &thorn;at I lufe, I wow &thorn;e, &thorn;at I myght
haue &thorn;e als I walde, noght to me bot
to my lorde.  I wil be-com&macr; &thorn;at
messanger to bryng &thorn;e to hys bed, &thorn;at hase
made &thorn;e &amp; boght &thorn;e, Criste &thorn;e keyng
son&macr; of heuen: for he wil with &thorn;e
dwelle.  If &thorn;ou will lufe hym, he askes
&thorn;e namare bot &thorn;i lufe.  And my dere
syster in Criste, my wil &thorn;ou dose if
&thorn;ou lufe hym.  Criste couaytes ... noght
els bot at &thorn;ou do his wil, and enforce
&thorn;e, day &amp; nyght, &thorn;at &thorn;ou leue al
fleschly lufe, and al lykyng &thorn;at lettes
&thorn;e til lofe Ihesu Crist verraly.  For ay
whils &thorn;i hert es heldand til lufe any
bodely thyng, &thorn;ou may not perfitely
be coupuld with god. / In [heuen] er
neyn orders of aungels, &thorn;at er contened
in thre Ierarchies. / &THORN;e lawest Ierarchi
contenes Aungels, Archaungels, &amp; Vertues. / &THORN;e mydel Ierarchi contenes
Principates, Potestates, &amp; Dominacions.
&THORN;e heest Ierarchi, &thorn;at neest est god,
contenes Thronos, Cherubyn, &amp; Seraphyn.
&THORN;e lawest es aungels, &thorn;e heest es
seraphyn. / And &thorn;at order &thorn;at leste es
bryght, es seuen-sythe sa bryght als
&thorn;e son&macr; es. [And als &thorn;ou sees &thorn;e son]
bryghtar &thorn;an a kandele, &thorn;e kandel
bryghtar &thorn;an &thorn;e mone, &thorn;e mone bryghtar
&thorn;an a sterne: / also er &thorn;e orders in


<PB N="51">

heuen ilkane bryghtar &thorn;an other, fra
aungels to seraphyn.  &THORN;is I say to
kyndel &thorn;i hert for to couayte &thorn;e
felichip of aungels.  For al &thorn;at er gude &amp; haly, when &thorn;ai passe owt of &thorn;is worlde,
sal be taken in til &thorn;ies orders: Som&macr;
in til &thorn;e lawest&mdash;&thorn;at hase lufed mykel;
Som&macr; in til &thorn;e mydelmest&mdash;&thorn;at hase
lufed mare; O&thorn;er in til &thorn;e heest&mdash;&thorn;at
maste lufed god &amp; brynandest es in
hys lufe.  Seraphyn es at say &laquo;brynand:&raquo;
Til &thorn;e whilk order &thorn;ai er receyued &thorn;at
leest couaytes in &thorn;is worlde, &amp; maste
swetnes feles in god, &amp; brynandest
hertes hase in his lufe. // Til &thorn;e I write
[&thorn;is] specialy, for I hope mare godenes
in &thorn;e &thorn;an in a nother, and [&thorn;at] &thorn;ou wil
gyf &thorn;i thoght to fulfil in dede &thorn;at &thorn;ou
seys es maste prophetabel for &thorn;i sawle,
and &thorn;at lyf gif &thorn;e til [in] &thorn;e whilk
&thorn;ow may halyest offer &thorn;i hert to Ihesu
Criste, &amp; leste be in bisynes of &thorn;is
worlde.  For if &thorn;ow stabil &thorn;i lufe, &amp; be byrnande whils &thorn;ou lyfes here:
with-owten dowte, &thorn;i settel es ordaynde
ful hegh in heuen, &amp; ioyful before
goddes face, amang his haly aungels.
For in &thorn;e self degre, &thorn;ar prowde
deuels fel downe fra, er meke men
and wymen, Criste dowves, sett, to
haue rest &amp; ioy with-owten ende, for
a litel schort penance &amp; trauel &thorn;at &thorn;ai
haue sufferd for goddes lufe. / &THORN;e
thynk [now] perauenture hard to gife &thorn;i
hert fra al erthly thynges, fra al ydel
speche &amp; vayne, &amp; fra al fleschly lufe,
&amp; to be al-ane, to walk &amp; pray &amp; thynk of &thorn;e ioy of heuen, &amp; of &thorn;e
passyon of Ihesu Criste, and to ymagyn
&thorn;e payne of hell &thorn;at es ordande for
synful man.  Bot wyterly, fra &thorn;ou be
vsed &thorn;arin, &thorn;e wil thynk it lyghter, &amp; swetter, &thorn;an &thorn;ou dyd any erthly thyng
or solace.  Als sone als &thorn;i hert es
towched with &thorn;e swetnes of heven, &thorn;e


<PB N="52">

wil lytel lyst &thorn;e myrth of &thorn;is worlde;
and when &thorn;ou feles ioy in Criste lufe,
&thorn;e wil lathe with &thorn;e ioy &amp; &thorn;e
comforth of &thorn;is worlde &amp; erthly gamen. /
For al melody, &amp; al riches &amp; delites
&thorn;at al men in &thorn;is world kan ordayne
or thynk, sownes bot noy and anger til
a mans hert &thorn;at verraly es byrnand in
&thorn;e lufe of god: For he hase myrth &amp; ioy &amp; melody in aungels sang, als &thorn;ou
may wele wyt. // If &thorn;ou leue al thyng
&thorn;at &thorn;i fleschly lufe list, for &thorn;e lufe of
god, and haue na thoght on syb
frendes, bot forsake al for goddes lufe,
&amp; anely gyf &thorn;i hert to coueyte goddes
lufe &amp; pay hym; mare ioy sal &thorn;ou
haue &amp; fynd in hym &thorn;an I can on
thynk, how myght [I] &thorn;an w[r]yt it?
I wate neuer if any man be in swilk
lufe: For ay &thorn;e hegher &thorn;e lyfe es, &thorn;e
fewer folowers it hase here, ffor many
thynges drawes man fra goddes lufe,
&thorn;at &thorn;ow may here and se; and god
comfortes his lufers mare &thorn;an &thorn;ai wene
&thorn;at lufes hym noght.  For &thorn;of we
seme in penance with-owten, we sal
haue mykel ioy with-in, if we ordayne
vs wysely to goddes seruyce, &amp; sett in
hym al owre thoghtes, &amp; forsake al
vanyte of &thorn;is worlde. // Gyf &thorn;ien entent
til vnderstand &thorn;is wrytyng: and if &thorn;ou
haue sett al &thorn;i desyre til lufe god,
here &thorn;ies thre degrees of lufe, sa &thorn;at
&thorn;ou may rise fra ane til a nother, to
&thorn;ou be in &thorn;e heest. / For I wil
noght layne fra &thorn;e &thorn;at I hope may
turne &thorn;e til halynes. // &THORN;e fyrst degre
of lufe es when a man haldes &thorn;e ten
commandementes, and kepes hym fra
&thorn;e seuen dedely synnes, &amp; es stabyl
in &thorn;e trowth of hali kyrke; and when
a man wil noght, for any erthly thyng,
wreth god, bot trewly standes in his
seruyce, &amp; lastes &thorn;arin til his lyues


<PB N="53">

ende.  &THORN;is degre of lufe behoues ilk
man haue &thorn;at wil be safe.  For naman
may com til heuen bot if he lufe god
&amp; his neghbor, with-owten pride, Ire,
envy, or bakbityng, &amp; with-owten al other
venemus synne: glotony, lichery, &amp; couayties.  For &thorn;ies vices slaes &thorn;e saule &amp; makes it to depart fra god, ... with-owten
wham na creature may lyf.  For als a
man pusonde of a swete morcell takes
venome &thorn;at slase his body, sa dose a
synful wreche in likyng and luste of hys
flesch: destrues his sawle, &amp; brynges
it to dede with-owten end. / Men thynk
it swete to synne: bot &thorn;aire mede, &thorn;at
es ordand for &thorn;am, es bitterer &thorn;an
&thorn;e gall, sowrar &thorn;an &thorn;e atter, war &thorn;an
al &thorn;e waa &thorn;at we may here se or
fele.</P>
<P>&para; [Al perisches &amp; passes &thorn;at we with
eghe see].  It wanes in to
wrechednes, &thorn;e welth of &thorn;is worlde.  Robes
&amp; ritches rotes in dike.  Prowde
payntyng slakes in to sorow.  Delites &amp; drewryse stynk sal ful sone.  &THORN;air golde
&amp; &thorn;aire tresoure drawes &thorn;am til dede,
Al &thorn;e wikked of &thorn;is worlde, drawes til
a dale, &THORN;at &thorn;ai may se &thorn;are sorowyng
whare waa es euer stabel.  Bot he
may syng of solace &thorn;at lufed Ihesu
Criste: &THORN;e wretchesse fra wele falles in
to hell.&mdash;Bot when &thorn;ou hase wele leued
in &thorn;e ten comandementes of god &amp; styfly put &thorn;e fra al dedely synnes,
&amp; payes god in &thorn;at degre:
vmbethynk &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou wil plese god mare
&amp; do better with &thorn;i sawle, &amp; becom&macr;
perfyte: &thorn;an enters &thorn;ou in to &thorn;e to&thorn;er
degre of lufe, &thorn;at es, to forsake al &thorn;e
worlde, &thorn;i fader &amp; &thorn;i moder &amp; al &thorn;i


<PB N="54">

kyn, &amp; folow Criste in pouerte.  In &thorn;is
degre &thorn;ou sal stody how clene &thorn;ou [may]
be in hert, &amp; how chaste in body, and
gife &thorn;e til mekenes, suffryng, &amp; buxumnes, &amp; loke how fayre &thorn;ou may
make &thorn;i saule in vertues, &amp; hate al
vices: so &thorn;at &thorn;i lyf be gastly, &amp; noght
fleschly.  Neuer-mare speke euyl of &thorn;i
neghbor, ne gyf any euel worde for a
nother, bot al &thorn;at men says, euel or
gude, suffer it mekeli in &thorn;i hert,
with-owten styrryng of wreth: &amp; &thorn;an sal
&thorn;ou be in rest, with-in &amp; with-owte,
and so lyghtly sal &thorn;ou com&macr; to &thorn;e
gastly lyfe, &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal fynde swettar
&thorn;an any erthly thyng. // Perfite life &amp; gastly es, to despise &thorn;e worlde &amp; couete
&thorn;e ioy of heuen, &amp; destroy thorow
goddes grace al wicked desyres of &thorn;e
flesch.  And forgete &thorn;e solace &amp; &thorn;e
lykyng of &thorn;i kynredyn, &amp; lufe [&thorn;am]
noght bot in god;&mdash;whethir &thorn;ai dy or lyfe,
or be pore or riche, [hale] or seke, or
in wa or in hele, thank &thorn;ou ay god,
&amp; blisse hym in al [his] werkis.  For
his domes er so pryue, &thorn;at na creature
may comprehend &thorn;am; // and oft-sithes
som&macr; haues &thorn;ar likyng &amp; &thorn;air wil in
&thorn;is worlde, &amp; hell in &thorn;e to&thorn;er: &amp; som&macr;
men er in pyne &amp; persecucion &amp; anguysch in &thorn;is lyfe, &amp; hase heuen to
&thorn;air mede.  For-&thorn;i, if &thorn;i frendes be
ay in &thorn;aire ese, and hele, &amp; welth of
&thorn;is worlde, &thorn;ou and &thorn;ai bath may
haue &thorn;e mare drede, &thorn;at &thorn;ai lose
noght &thorn;e ioy of heuen with-outen ende.
/ If &thorn;ai be in penance &amp; sekenes, or
if &thorn;ai lyf rightwisly, &thorn;ai may trayste
to com&macr; til &thorn;e blysse. / For-&thorn;i in &thorn;is
degre of lufe &thorn;ou sal be fulfilde with
&thorn;e grace of &thorn;e haly gaste &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal
noght haue na sorow ne grutchyng bot
for gastly thyng, als for &thorn;i synnes &amp; other mennes, &amp; after &thorn;e lufe of Ihesu
Criste, &amp; in thynkyng of his passyon.
And I wil &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue it mykel in


<PB N="55">

mynde, for it wyll kyndel &thorn;i hert to
sett at noght al &thorn;e gudes of &thorn;is worlde,
&amp; &thorn;e ioy &thorn;arof, &amp; to desyre byrnandly
&thorn;e lyght of heuen, with aungels &amp; halowes. / And when &thorn;i hert es haly
ordande to &thorn;e seruice of god, &amp; al
worldly thoghtes put oute: &thorn;an wil &thorn;e
liste stele by &thorn;e al-ane, to thynk on
Criste, &amp; to be in mykel praying.  For
thorow gode thoghtes &amp; hali prayers,
&thorn;i hert sal be made byrnand in &thorn;e lufe
of Ihesu Criste, &amp; &thorn;an sal &thorn;ow fele
swetnes &amp; gastely ioy bath in praying &amp; in thynkyng. / And when &thorn;ou ert by &thorn;e
al-ane, gyf &thorn;e mykel to say &thorn;e psalmes
of &thorn;e psauter, and <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN>, &amp; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aue
maria</FOREIGN>; &amp; take na tent &thorn;at &thorn;ou say many,
bot &thorn;at &thorn;ou say &thorn;am wele, with al &thorn;e
deuocion &thorn;at &thorn;ow may, liftand vp &thorn;i
thoght til heuen. / Better it es to say
seuen psalmes wyth desyre of Crystes
lufe, hauand &thorn;i hert of &thorn;i praying,
&thorn;an seuen hundreth thowsand, suffrand
&thorn;i thoght passe in vanitees of bodyli
thynges.  What gude hopes &thorn;ou may
come &thorn;arof, if &thorn;ou lat &thorn;i tonge blaber
on &thorn;e boke, &amp; &thorn;i hert ren abowte
in sere stedes in &thorn;e worlde? / For-&thorn;i,
sett &thorn;i thoght in Criste &amp; he sal rewle
in til hym, &amp; halde &thorn;e fra &thorn;e venome
of &thorn;e worldly bisynesse. / And I pray
&thorn;e, als &thorn;ou couaytes to be goddes
lufer, &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufe &thorn;is name IHESU, and
thynk it in &thorn;i hert, sa &thorn;at ;&thorn;ou forget
it neuer, whare so &thorn;ou be.  And
sothely I say &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal fynd mykel
ioy &amp; comforth &thorn;arin; / and for &thorn;e
lufe, &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes Ihesu so tenderly &amp; so specialy, &thorn;ou sal be fulfild of
grace in erth, &amp; be Criste dere
seruande in heuen.  For na thyng pays
god swa mykel als verray lufe of &thorn;is
nam Ihesu.  If &thorn;ou luf it ryght &amp; lastandely, &amp; neuer let for na thyng &thorn;at
men may do or say, &thorn;ou sal be
receyued in til a heghar lyfe &thorn;an


<PB N="56">

&thorn;ou can couete.  His godenes es sa
mykel, &thorn;are we inwardely aske hym
ane, he wil gyf fyfe; so wele payde es
he when we wil sett al oure hert to
lufe hym. // In &thorn;is degre of lufe &thorn;ou
sal ouercome &thorn;i enmyse: &thorn;e worlde,
&thorn;e deuel, &amp; &thorn;i flesche.  Bot
neuer-&thorn;e-latter &thorn;ou sal euer haue feghtyng whils
&thorn;ou lyfes; til &thorn;ou dye &thorn;e behoues to
be bysy to stande, &thorn;at &thorn;ou fal noght
in til delites, ne in euel thoghtes, ne in
euel wordes, ne in euel warke: For-&thorn;i, grete
aght &thorn;i &thorn;ernyng be &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufe Criste
verrayly.  &THORN;i flesche sal &thorn;ou ouer-com&macr; with
haldyng of &thorn;i mayden-hede, for goddes
lufe anely; or, if &thorn;ou be na mayden,
thorow chaste lyuyng &amp; resonabel in
thoght &amp; dede, &amp; thorow discrete
abstinence. / &THORN;e worlde &thorn;ou sal ouercom
thorow couaytyng of Cristes lufe, &amp; thynkyng on &thorn;is swete name Ihesus, &amp; desyre til heuen. / For als sone als &thorn;ou
feles sauour in Ihesu, &thorn;e wil thynk
al &thorn;e worlde noght bot vanyte, &amp; noy
for men sawles. / &THORN;ow will noght
couayte &thorn;an to be riche, to haue many
mantels &amp; fayre, many kyrtels &amp; drewryse, bot al &thorn;ou wil sett at noght &amp; despise it als noght it ware, &amp; take na
mare &thorn;an &thorn;e nedes. / &THORN;e wil thynk
twa mantels or ane Inogh; &thorn;ow &thorn;at
hase fyue or sex, gyf some til Criste,
&thorn;at gase naked in a pore wede, and
halde noght all: for &thorn;ou wate noght if
&thorn;ow lif til &thorn;ai be half gane. / &THORN;e deuell
es ouercome, when &thorn;ou standes stabeIy
agaynes al his fandyngys, in sothefast
charite &amp; mekenes. // I will &thorn;at &thorn;ow
neuer be ydel, bot ay owther speke of
god, or wirke som notabil warke, or
thynk on hym principaly, &thorn;at &thorn;i thoght


<PB N="57">

be ay hauand hym in mynde.  And
thynk oft on his passyon:</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">(Meditatio de passione Cristi.)</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>// My keyng &thorn;at water grette, and
blode swette; sythen ful sare bette,
so &thorn;at hys blode hym wette, when
&thorn;air scowrges mette. / Ful fast &thorn;ai
gan hym dyng, and at &thorn;e pyler
swyng, &amp; his fayre face defowlyng(!)
with spittyng. / &THORN;e thorne crownes &thorn;e
keyng, ful sare es &thorn;at prickyng.  Alas
my ioy and my swetyng es demed to
hyng! / Nayled was his handes, nayled
was hys fete, &amp; thyrled was hys syde
so semely &amp; so swete. / Naked es his
whit breste, &amp; rede es his blody syde;
wan was his fayre hew, his wowndes
depe &amp; wyde.  In fyue stedes of his
flesch &thorn;e blode gan downe glyde, als
stremes of &thorn;e strande, hys pyne es
noght to hyde. / &THORN;is to see es grete
pyte, how he es demed to &thorn;e dede,
and nayled on &thorn;e rode-tre, &thorn;e bryght
aungels brede. / Dryuen he was to
dole &thorn;at es owre gastly gude, and
alsso in &thorn;e blys of heuen es al &thorn;e aungels
fude.  A wonder it es to se, wha sa
vnderstude, how god of mageste was
dyand on &thorn;e rude. / Bot suth &thorn;an es
it sayde &thorn;at lufe ledes &thorn;e ryng; &thorn;at
hym sa law hase layde, bot lufe it
was na thyng. / Ihesu, receyue my hert,
&amp; to &thorn;i lufe me bryng: al my desyre
&thorn;ou ert, bot I couete &thorn;i comyng. /
&THORN;ow make me clene of synne, &amp; lat vs
neuer twyn; kyndel me fire with-in,
&thorn;at I &thorn;i lufe may wyn, and se &thorn;i face
Ihesu in ioy &thorn;at neuer sal blyn. / Ihesu,
my saule &thorn;ou mend, &thorn;i lufe in to me
send, &thorn;at I may with &thorn;e lend, in ioy
with-owten end. / In lufe &thorn;ow wownde
my thoght, and lyft my hert to &thorn;e:


<PB N="58">

my sawle &thorn;ou dere hase boght, &thorn;i
lufer make it to be.  &THORN;e I couete, &thorn;is
worlde noght, &amp; for it I fle; &thorn;ou ert
&thorn;at I haue soght: &thorn;i face when may
I see? / &THORN;ow make my sawle clere,
for lufe chawnges my chere: how lang
sal I be here? [when mai I negh &thorn;e
nere, &thorn;i melody to here,] / Oft to
here sang, &thorn;at es lastand so lang?  &THORN;ou
be my lufyng, &thorn;at I [&thorn;i] lufe may syng.
//&mdash; &mdash;If &thorn;ou wil thynk &thorn;is ilk day,
&thorn;ou sal fynde swetnes &thorn;at sal draw
&thorn;i hert vp, &thorn;at sal gar &thorn;e fal in
gretyng, &amp; in grete langyng til Ihesu;
&amp; &thorn;i thoght sal al be on Ihesu, and so
be receyued abouen all erthly thyng,
abouen &thorn;e firmament &amp; &thorn;e sternes, so
&thorn;at &thorn;e egh of &thorn;i hert mai loke in
til heuen.  And &thorn;an enters &thorn;ow in to
&thorn;e thirde degre of lufe. / In &thorn;e whilk
&thorn;ou sal haue grete delyte &amp; comforth:
if &thorn;ow may get grace to com &thorn;artill.
For I say noght &thorn;at &thorn;ou or a nother
&thorn;at redes &thorn;is, sal do it all: for it es
at goddes will to chese wham he will,
to do &thorn;at here es sayde, Or els a
nother thyng on a nother maner, als
he gifes men grace til haue &thorn;aire hele.
For sere men takes seer grace of oure
lorde Ihesu Criste: and al sal be sett
in &thorn;e ioy of heuen, &thorn;at endes in
charite.  Wha sa es in &thorn;is degre,
wisdom he hase &amp; discrecion, to luf at
goddes will.  &THORN;is degre es called
contemplatife lyfe; &thorn;at lufes to be anely,
with-owten ryngyng or dyn, or syngyng
or criyng. / At &thorn;e begynnyng, when
&thorn;ou comes &thorn;artil, &thorn;i gastly egh es
taken vp in til &thorn;e blysse of heuen, &amp; &thorn;ar lyghtned with grace &amp; kyndelde
with fyre of Cristes lufe, sa &thorn;at &thorn;ou
sal verraly fele &thorn;e bernyng of lufe in &thorn;i
hert, euer mare &amp; mare; liftand &thorn;i thoght
to god and feland lufe, ioy &amp; swetnes,


<PB N="59">

so mykel, &thorn;at na sekenes, anguys ne
schame ne penance may greue &thorn;e, bot
al &thorn;i lyf sal turne in tyl ioy; &amp; &thorn;an
for heghnesse of &thorn;i hert [&thorn;i] prayers
turnes in til ioyful sange, and &thorn;i
thoghtes to melody. / &THORN;an es Ihesu al &thorn;i
desyre, al &thorn;i delyte, al &thorn;i ioy,
al &thorn;i solace, al &thorn;i comforth; al
I wate &thorn;at on hym euer be &thorn;i sang,
In hym all &thorn;i rest. // &THORN;en may &thorn;ow
say: &laquo;I slepe and my hert wakes.  Wha
sall tyll my lemman say [&thorn;at] for hys
lufe me langes ay?&raquo; // All &thorn;at lufes
vanytees and specials of &thorn;is warlde,
and settes &thorn;aire hertis on any other
thynges &thorn;an of god, in tyll &thorn;is degre
&thorn;ai may noght come, ne in tyll [&thorn;e] other
degre of lufe before neuynd.  And
&thorn;arfore all worldely solace &thorn;e be-houes
forsake, &thorn;at &thorn;i hert be heldande til na
lufe of any creature, ne til na bysynes
in erth: &thorn;at &thorn;ou may be in sylence, be
ay stabilly &amp; stalwortly with &thorn;i hert in
goddes lufe &amp; hys drede.  Owre lorde
gyfes noght to men fairehede, ritchesse
&amp; delytes, for to sette &thorn;aire hertes on &amp; dispend &thorn;am in synne: bot for &thorn;ai sulde
knaw hym, &amp; lufe hym, &amp; thank hym
of al hys gyftes.  &THORN;e mare es &thorn;aire schame,
if &thorn;ai wreth hym, &thorn;at hase gyfen &thorn;am
gyftes in body &amp; in saule. / For-&thorn;i, if
we couayte to fle &thorn;e payne of
purgatory, vs be-houes restreyne vs perfitely
fra &thorn;e lust &amp; &thorn;e likyng &amp; al &thorn;e il
delytes &amp; wikked drede of &thorn;is worlde;
and &thorn;at worldely sorow be noght in
vs: Bot &thorn;at we halde owre hope faste
in Ihesu Criste, &amp; stande manly agaynes
al temptacions.</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">

<PB N="60"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">(Can[tus] amo[ris]).</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>/ Now I wryte a sang of lufe,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou sal delyte in when &thorn;ow ert
lufand Ihesu Criste. // My sange es in
syhtyng, my lyfe es in langynge, til I
&thorn;e se my keyng, so fayre in &thorn;i
schynyng, / So fayre in &thorn;i fayrehede: in til
&thorn;i lyght me lede, and in &thorn;i lufe me
fede: In lufe make me to spede, &thorn;at
&thorn;ou be euer my mede. / When wil &thorn;ou
come, Ihesu my ioy, &amp; couer me of
kare, &amp; gyf me &thorn;e &thorn;at I may se,
lifand euer-mare?  Al my coueytyng
war commen, if I myght til &thorn;e fare;
I wil na thyng bot anely &thorn;e, &thorn;at all
my will ware. / Ihesu my sauyoure,
Ihesu my comfortoure, of al my fayrnes
flowre, my helpe &amp; my sokoure: when
may I se &thorn;i towre? / When wil &thorn;ou
me kall?  me langes to &thorn;i hall, to se
&thorn;e &thorn;an al: &thorn;i luf lat it not fal, my
hert payntes &thorn;e pall; &thorn;at steds vs in
stal. / Now wax I pale &amp; wan, for luf
of my lemman: Ihesu bath god &amp; man,
&thorn;i luf &thorn;ou lerd me &thorn;an, when I to &thorn;e
fast ran: for-&thorn;i now I lufe kan. / I
sytt &amp; syng of luf-langyng, &thorn;at in my
breste es bredde.  Ihesu, Ihesu, Ihesu,
when war I to &thorn;e ledde?  Full wele I
wate, &thorn;ou sees my state: in lufe my
thoght es stedde; When I &thorn;e se &amp; dwels with &thorn;e, &thorn;an am I fylde &amp; fedde. / Ihesu &thorn;i lufe es fest, &amp; me
to lufe thynk best: my hert when may
it brest, to com&macr; to &thorn;e my rest? /
Ihesu, Ihesu, Ihesu, til &thorn;e it es &thorn;at I
morne: for-[&thorn;i], my lyfe &amp; my lyuyng,
when may I hethen torne? / Ihesu my
dere &amp; my drewry, delyte ert &thorn;ou to
syng: Ihesu my myrth &amp; melody, when
will &thorn;ow com my keyng?  Ihesu my
hele &amp; my hony, my whart &amp; my
comfortyng: Ihesu, I couayte for to


<PB N="61">

dy, when it es &thorn;i payng. / Langyng
es in me lent, &thorn;at my lufe hase me
sent; al wa es fra me went, sen &thorn;at
my hert es brent / In Criste lufe sa
swete, &thorn;at neuer I wil lete, bot euer
to luf I hete: for lufe my bale may
bete / And til hys blis me bryng, &amp; gyf me my &yogh;ernyng, Ihesu my lufe my
swetyng. / Langyng es in me lyght,
&thorn;at byndes me day &amp; nyght, til I it
hafe in syght, his face sa fayre &amp; bryght. / Ihesu my hope my hele, my
ioy euer-ilk a dele: &thorn;i luf lat it noght
kele, &thorn;at I &thorn;i luf may fele, &amp; won
with &thorn;e in wele. / Ihesu with &thorn;e I
byg and belde, leuer me war to dy:
&thorn;an al &thorn;is worlde to welde &amp; hafe it
in maystry. / When wil &thorn;ou rew on
me, Ihesu &thorn;at I myght with &thorn;e be, to
lufe &amp; lok on &thorn;e? / My setell ordayne
for me &amp; sett &thorn;ou me &thorn;ar-in: for &thorn;en
mon&macr; we neuer twyn, / And I &thorn;i lufe
sal syng thorow syght of &thorn;i schynyng,
in heuen with-owten endyng.  AmeN.</P>
</DIV4>
<TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit tractatus Ricardi heremite
de Hampole scriptus cuidam moniali
de &YOGH;edyngham.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV3>

<DIV3 N="Rawlinson A 389" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Rawlinson A 389</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="77" UNIT="folio">
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ego dormio &amp; cor meum vigilat.</FOREIGN>
&THORN;e &thorn;at lyste luf, held &thorn;ine ere and here
of luf.  In &thorn;e sang of luf I fynde it
writen &thorn;at I haue sett at &thorn;e begynnynge
of my wrytynge: &laquo;I slepe and my hert
wakes.&raquo;  Mykell luf he shewes &thorn;at neuere
is irke to luf, bot ay, standande, sittande,
gangande or any other dede doande es
ay his luf thynkand, and oft-sithe
&thorn;erof dremand.  For-&thorn;i &thorn;at I luf &thorn;e, I wogh
&thorn;e, &thorn;at I myght haue &thorn;e as I wilde,
noght tille me bot till my lard.  I wille
be comer and messager to bryng &thorn;e
till his bed &thorn;at has made &thorn;e and boght
&thorn;e, Criste &thorn;e kynges son&macr; of heuen;
for he will wed &thorn;e if &thorn;ou wille luf hym;
he askes &thorn;e na mare bot &thorn;i luf.  And
my wille &thorn;ou dose, if &thorn;ou luf hym.
Crist couaytes &thorn;i fairehede in saule,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou gyf hym halely &thorn;i hert: and I
preche noght ellys bot &thorn;at &thorn;ou do his
will, and afforce &thorn;e day &amp; nyght to lefe
alle fleschely luf and al likyng &thorn;at lettus
&thorn;e to luf Ihesu Crist verrayly; for
I-whils &thorn;i hert is heldande to luf of any
bodyly thyng, &thorn;ou may not parfitly be
cupilde wit god.  &para; In heuen er IX.
ordirs of aungels, &thorn;at are conte[n]yd in
thre Ierarchies: &thorn;e lagheste Ierarchy
contenys aungels, archangels, vertu&yogh;.  &THORN;e
myddes Ierarchi contenys: Potestates,
Principatus, Dominaciones.  &THORN;e heghest
Ierarchi, &thorn;at next is til god, contenys:
Tronys, Cherubyn, and Saraphyn.  &THORN;e
laghest ordir is Aungels, &thorn;e heghest
Seraphyn.  And &thorn;at ordir &thorn;at lest is
bryght, is seuen sa bryght as is &thorn;is
son&macr;.  And as &thorn;ou sees &thorn;e son&macr; bryghter
&thorn;an &thorn;e candel, &thorn;e candel bryghter &thorn;an
&thorn;e mone, &thorn;e mone bryghter &thorn;an &thorn;e
sternys, alswa are &thorn;e orders of aungels


<PB N="51">

in heuen ilkane brighter &thorn;an other, fra
aungels tille Seraphyn.  &THORN;is I say to
kyndel &thorn;i hert to couayte &thorn;e
felawschype of aungels: for alle &thorn;at are
gode and haly, when &thorn;ei passe of &thorn;is
werld, salle be takyn in till &thorn;ire orders,
som til &thorn;e lawest: &thorn;at has lufed god
mykel; som to &thorn;e myddes: &thorn;at has
loued god mare; other til &thorn;e heghest:
&thorn;at mast lufes god and brennandest er
in is lufe. / Seraphyn is at saye
&laquo;brynnande&raquo;: tille whilke ordir &thorn;ai er
receyfede &thorn;at leste couaytes in &thorn;is werld,
and mast swetnes felys in god, and
brennand[est] hertis han in lufe.  &para; Tille
&thorn;e I wryte &thorn;is specialy, for I hope in
&thorn;e mare gudnes &thorn;an in any other, [&]
&thorn;at &thorn;ou wille gyf &thorn;i thoght to
fulfille in dede &thorn;at &thorn;ou sees is profitable
to &thorn;i saule, and &thorn;at lyf gyf &thorn;e tille in
&thorn;e whilke &thorn;ou may halelyeste offer &thorn;i
hert tille Ihesu Cryst and leste be in
bysynes of &thorn;is werld.  For if &thorn;ou wille
stabilly luf god &amp; brennandly whiles
&thorn;ou lyfes here, with-outen doute &thorn;i
setyll es ordaned for &thorn;e ful hegh and
ioyfull before &thorn;e face of god ymanges
haly aungels.  For in &thorn;e self degres &thorn;are
proude deuyls felle downe er meke men
and wymmen, Cristes doufys, sett in, to
haf rest and ioye with-outen ende, for
a littul schort penaunce &amp; trauaile &thorn;at
&thorn;ei hafe suffrede for goddes luf.  &para; &THORN;e
thynke now perauenture harde to gyf &thorn;i
hert fra alle erthly thynge, fraydil speche,
fra al fleschely luf, and ga by &thorn;ine ane
to wake &amp; pray and &thorn;inke &thorn;e ioye of
heuen, &amp; to haue compassion of &thorn;e
passion of Ihesu Crist, and to ymagyn
&thorn;e pyne of helle &thorn;at is ordeyned for
synfulmen.  Bot witterly, fra &thorn;at &thorn;ou
be vsed &thorn;erin, &thorn;e wil &thorn;inke it lighter
&amp; swetter &thorn;en euer &thorn;e did any erthly
solace. / Also sone as &thorn;i hert is toched
wit &thorn;e swetnes of heuen, &thorn;e wil litel


<PB N="52">

liste &thorn;e myrth of &thorn;is werlde; and when
&thorn;ou felys ioye in Cristes luf, &thorn;e wil
lathe wit &thorn;e ioye &amp; &thorn;e comford of
erthly gammyn.  For alle &thorn;e melodye,
alle &thorn;e ryches, alle &thorn;e delites &thorn;at alle
&thorn;e men in &thorn;is world kan ordeyne or
thynke, semes &amp; es bot noy &amp; angyre
til a mannys herte &thorn;at verrayly is brennand
in &thorn;e luf of god, for he has myrth &amp; melodie of aungel sange, as &thorn;ou may
wel wyit.  If &thorn;ou lefe alle thynge &thorn;at
&thorn;e liste fleschely, &amp; haue na thowght
of &thorn;i syb frendys, bot for-sake alle for
goddes luf, and anely gyf &thorn;i herte to
couayte goddes luf and to paye him,
mare ioye &thorn;ou schal fynde in hym &thorn;an
I kan thynke&mdash;howe myght I &thorn;an wryte
hit?  I wat neuer if many men be in
swilke luf; for ay &thorn;e hegher &thorn;at &thorn;e lyfe
es, &thorn;e faer folowers it has here, for
many thynges drawes men fra goddes
luf, &thorn;at &thorn;ou may here &amp; see; [and] god
comfortes his lufers mare &thorn;an &thorn;ei wene
&thorn;at lufes hym noght.  For of we seme
in penance wit-outen, we salle haue ful
mykel ioye within, if we ordeyne vs
wysely to goddes seruys and set in hym
alle oure thoghtes &amp; forsake vanite.
&para; Gyf alle &thorn;ine entente to vnderstonde
&thorn;is wrytyng: [&] if &thorn;ou haue set &thorn;i desire
to luf god, here &thorn;ere thre degres of
luf, swa &thorn;at &thorn;ou may ryse fra ane til
a nother, tille &thorn;ou be at &thorn;e hegheste;
for I ne wil not hil fra &thorn;e &thorn;at I hope
ma torne &thorn;e tille halynes.  &para; &thorn;e first
degre of luf es when a man haldes &thorn;e
ten commaundementes, and kepes him
fra &thorn;e seuen dedly synnes, and is stabul
in &thorn;e trouthe of haly kirke; and when
a man wille noght for any erthly thynge
wreth god, bot trewly standes in his
seruice and lastes &thorn;are-in tille his lyfes


<PB N="53">

ende.  &para; &THORN;is degree of lufe by-houes ilke
man haue &thorn;at wille be safe; for na man
maye come tille heuen bot if he luf god
and his neghbur with-outen pryde, ire
and any bakbytyng, and with-outen alle
other wennymouse synnes as slawnes,
glotery, and lichery, and couaytys: for
&thorn;ere vices slaes &thorn;e saule &amp; makes hit
to depart fra god &thorn;at es lyfe of &thorn;e
saule; and when a wreched man or
wommon es departed fra god, we saye
he is ded, for he is slayne fra god
with-outen wham na creature may lyf.  Als
a man poysunde in a swete morsell takes
venym &thorn;at slas his body, swa dos a
synful wreche in likyng and lust,
destroyes his saule and brynges hit tille
dede with-outen ende.  Men &thorn;inke hit
swete to synne, bot &thorn;aire hire &thorn;at is
ordayned for &thorn;aim, es bitterer &amp; galle,
sowrer &thorn;an atter, wers &thorn;an alle &thorn;e
wa &thorn;at man can thynk in erthe.
&para; Alle perisches &amp; passes &thorn;at we with
eghe see.  Hit wanys in till wrechedhede
&thorn;e wele of &thorn;is worlde.  Robys &amp; riches
rotes in &thorn;e dyche.  Pryde &amp; payntynge
slake salle in sorowe.  Delytes and
drorys stynke sall ful sone.  &THORN;aire gold
&amp; &thorn;aire tresoure drawes &thorn;aim til dede;
Alle &thorn;e wykked of &thorn;is werlde dryues
til a dale, &THORN;at &thorn;ai may see &thorn;aire
sorowynge &thorn;are wa es alle &thorn;e rabel.
Bot he may synge of solas &thorn;at lufed
Ihesu Cryst, When alle &thorn;e wreches fra
wele falles in tille helle.&mdash; &para; Bot when
&thorn;ou has wel lyfed in &thorn;e commaundementes
of god and styffely keped &thorn;e fra alle
dedly synnes, and payde tille Criste in
&thorn;at degre: vmthynke &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou wil
mare luf god, &amp; do better with &thorn;i saule,
and bycome parfite: &amp; &thorn;an enters &thorn;ou
in tille &thorn;e tother degre of luf, &thorn;at es:
to forsake alle &thorn;e worlde and &thorn;i fader
and &thorn;i moder &amp; alle &thorn;i kyn &amp; folowe


<PB N="54">

Crist in pouerte.  &para; In &thorn;is degree &thorn;ou
schalle stody howe clene &thorn;ou may be in
herte, and howe chaste in body, and gyf
&thorn;e tille mekenes, suffryng &amp; bosumnes,
and loke how faire &thorn;ou may make &thorn;i
saule in vertuese, and hate alle vices:
swa &thorn;at &thorn;i lyfe be gastely, noght fleschely;
neuer-mare spekand ille of &thorn;ine neghbur,
ny gyf ane ille word for a nother, bot
alle &thorn;at men says, ille or gode, suffir
hit debonerly in &thorn;i hert, with-outen
stirryng of wreth: and &thorn;an schal &thorn;ou
be in reste within, and lightly come in
to gastely lyfe, &thorn;at &thorn;ou salle fynde
swetter &thorn;an any erthely thyng.  &para; Parfite
lyfe and gastely es, to despise &thorn;e erth,
couayte &thorn;e ioye of heuen, and destroye
thurgh goddes grace alle wikked desires
of &thorn;e flesche.  And forgete &thorn;e solace and
likyng of &thorn;i kynredyne, and luf &thorn;aim
noght bot in god; whethire &thorn;a dye or
lyf, be pore or ryche, be hale or seke,
in wa or in wele, thank &thorn;ou ay god,
and bles hym in alle his werkes: for
his domes are so priue, &thorn;at na creature
may comprehende &thorn;aim; and oftsith
sum men has &thorn;aire likyng and &thorn;aire
wele in &thorn;is world, and hell in &thorn;e
tother: and sum men es in pyne &amp; persecucioun &amp; anguys in &thorn;is lyfe, and
has heuen til &thorn;aire mede.  For-thy, if
&thorn;i frendes be ay in es and hele &amp; in
welth of &thorn;is werlde, &thorn;ou &amp; &thorn;ai bathe
maye &thorn;e mare drede, &thorn;at [&thorn;ai] lose
noght &thorn;e ioie with-outen ende.  If &thorn;ai
be in penaunce, in sekenes, or if &thorn;ei
lyf ryghtwysly, &thorn;ai may trayste in god
to come to his blisse.  For-&thorn;i in &thorn;is
degree of luf &thorn;ou salle sa by filde in
grace of &thorn;e haly gast &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal
noght haue sorowe ne gratyng bot for
gastely thynge, and for &thorn;i synnes and
other mennys, and aftir &thorn;e luf of Ihesu
Crist, and in thynkyng of his passioun&mdash;
and &thorn;at I wille &thorn;at &thorn;ou hafe mykel


<PB N="55">

mynde of, for hit will kyndel &thorn;i hert
to set at noght alle &thorn;e gudes of &thorn;is
werlde and alle &thorn;e ioye, &amp; to desire
brennandly &thorn;e light of heuen with
aungels and haloghys.  &para; And when &thorn;i
hert is ordayned halely to &thorn;e seruice
of god, &amp; alle werldes thoght is putt
oute: &thorn;an wille &thorn;e liste stele be &thorn;i
nane, to thynk of Crist and to be in
mykel prayng; for thorow gode thoghtes
and haly prayers &thorn;i hert salle be made
brennande in &thorn;e luf of Ihesu Crist, and
&thorn;an salle &thorn;ou fele swetnes and gastely
ioye bathe in prayinge and in thynkyng.
And when &thorn;ou arte be &thorn;i nane, gyf &thorn;e
mikel to say &thorn;e psalmes of &thorn;e sawter,
and <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN> and aues; and take
not tent &thorn;at &thorn;ou say many, bot &thorn;at &thorn;ou
say hom wele, and in alle &thorn;e deuocioun
&thorn;at &thorn;ou may, lyftande vp thy thoght
til heuen.  Bettir hit is to say seuen
psalmes in desyre of Cristes luf, hafand
&thorn;i hert on &thorn;i praying, &thorn;an seuen
hundred, suffrande &thorn;i thoght to pas in
vanitees of bodily thynge.  What gode
hopes &thorn;ou may com &thorn;erof if &thorn;ou lat
&thorn;i tonge blabir on &thorn;e boke, and &thorn;i hert
ryn&macr; aboute in sere stedes in &thorn;e werld,
whare hit will?  For-thy set &thorn;i thoght
in Crist and he salle refe it tille hym
and halde hit fra &thorn;e venym of werldes
bysynes.  And I pray &thorn;e, as &thorn;ou couaytes
to be goddes lufer, &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufe &thorn;is
name Ihesu, and thynk hit in &thorn;i herte,
swa &thorn;at &thorn;ou forgete hit neuer, wharsom&macr;
&thorn;ou be: and witterly I hete &thorn;e &thorn;ou
salle fynde mykelle ioye &amp; comfort &thorn;erin,
and for &thorn;e luf &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes Ihesu sa
tendirly and sa specialy, &thorn;ou salle be
filde full of grace in erth, and be Cristes
dere mayden &amp; spouse in heuen.  For
na thynge sa mekill pays god as verray
luf of his name Ihesu.  If &thorn;ou lufe hit
ryght and lastandly, &amp; neuer let for na
thynge &thorn;at men may saye or do, &thorn;ou
salle be raysed in tille a hegher lyfe


<PB N="56">

&thorn;an &thorn;ou can couayte.  His godenes es
sa mekill &thorn;at &thorn;are we inwardly aske
hym of ane, he wille gyf vs thre: sa
wele payed he es when we set alle oure
hert to luf hym.  &para; In &thorn;is degre of luf
&thorn;ou salle ouercom &thorn;i thre enmys: &thorn;e
werld, &thorn;e deuel, and &thorn;i flesche;&mdash;bot
neuer-&thorn;e-latter &thorn;ou schal hafe ay fightyng
whils &thorn;ou lyfes, and ay til &thorn;ou dye
by-houes &thorn;e be bysy to stande &amp; to falle
noght in ille delyte ne in ille thoght or
in ille worde or in ille werkis: for-&thorn;i
grete augh &thorn;i gernynge to be &thorn;at &thorn;ou
luf Crist verraily.  &THORN;i flesche salle &thorn;ou
ouer-com thurgh [haldyng of &thorn;i
maydenhede for goddes luf anely, or, if &thorn;ou
be na maydun, thurgh chast lyfynge
in thoght and in dede, and thurgh
discrete abstinence and resonable seruyse.
&THORN;e werld salle &thorn;ou ouer-com &thorn;orow
couaytyng of Cristes luf, &amp; thynkynge
of his swete name, and desire til heuen;
for als son&macr; as &thorn;ou feles sauowr in Ihesu,
&thorn;e wille thynke alle &thorn;e werlde noght
bot vanite and noye for mennys saules.
&THORN;ou wil noght couayte &thorn;an to be ryche,
to haue many mantils and faire, many
kirtils, many dreurise, bot alle &thorn;ou wil
set at noght and despise alle, and take
na mare &thorn;an &thorn;e nedes.  &THORN;e wille thynke
twa mantils or ane Inogh, &thorn;at nowe
has fyfe or sex; for-&thorn;i gyf som&macr; til
Crist ;&thorn;at gas naked and pore, and hald
noght til &thorn;e alle: &thorn;at wate noght &thorn;i
lyfe tille &thorn;ay be halfe gane. / &THORN;e deuyl
is ouercommen when &thorn;ou standis stabilly
agayns alle his fandynges, in sothfaste
charite ande mekenes.  And thynke on
me &thorn;at I be noght forgeten in &thorn;i prayeres,
&thorn;at is aboute-warde &thorn;at &thorn;ou were dere
with Criste, whas mercy me nedys.  I
wille &thorn;at &thorn;ou be neuer Idel, [bot] be
ay other spekand of god, or wirkand
some notabul warke, or thynkand in
hym and principally, &thorn;at &thorn;i thoght be


<PB N="57">

ay hafand hym in mynde.  And thynk
oft &thorn;is of his passioun:</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">(Meditacio de passione.)</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>&para; My kynge &thorn;e watur grett, and
&thorn;e blod he swett; sithen full sare
him bett, so &thorn;at his blode hym wett,
when &thorn;aire scourges mett.  Ful faste
&thorn;ai gun hym dynge, and at &thorn;e piler
swynge, his faire face fouled with
spittyng.  &THORN;e thorne coronys &thorn;e kynge,
fulle sare es &thorn;at prykkyng.  allas my
ioye and my swetyng, es demed for to
hynge!  Nayled was his hende and
nayled was his fete, &amp; thirled es his
syde sa semely &amp; sa swete.  Naked his
white brest, and red his blody syde;
wan was his faire hewe, his woundes depe
&amp; wyde.  In fyfe stedys of his flesche &thorn;e
blode gan downe glyde, as &thorn;e streme
dos of &thorn;e strande, &thorn;is pyne es noght
to hyde.  To thynke es gret pite, how
demed es tille &thorn;e dede, and nayled on
&thorn;e tre, &thorn;e bryght aungels brede.  Dryuen
he is til dole &thorn;at is oure gastly gode, and
fouled as a fole, in heuen &thorn;e haloghys
fode.  A wondir hit is to se, wha-som
vndurstode, how god of mageste was
dyande on &thorn;e rode.  Bot sothe &thorn;an is
[it] saide &thorn;at luf ledes &thorn;e rynge; &thorn;at
him sa laughe has laide, bot luf hit
was no thynge.  Ihesu, resayue my
hert, and til &thorn;i luf me brynge: alle my
desir &thorn;ou art, I couaite &thorn;i comynge.
&THORN;ou make me clene of synne, and lat
vs neuer twyn&macr;, kyndel me fyre
withinne, &thorn;at I &thorn;i luf may wynne, and se
&thorn;i face Ihesu in blys &thorn;at neuer may
blynne.  Ihesu, my saule &thorn;ou mende,
&thorn;i luf in to me<MILESTONE N="Vernon (Bodl. Eng. poet.a I)" UNIT="MS">
</P>
</DIV4>




<DIV4 TYPE="section"><PB N="60">
<P><ADD>Nou i write a song of loue, &thorn;at
&thorn;ou schalt delyte in whon &thorn;ou
art louyng Ihesu Crist.  &para; My song is
in syngyng (R. sittyng), Mi lyf is in
longing, to &thorn;e (R. &thorn;at) i seo my
derlyng so feir in his schyning, So feir
in his (R. &thorn;i) feirhede: in to &thorn;i li&yogh;t &thorn;ou
me lede, And wi&thorn; &thorn;i loue &thorn;ou me fede,
In loue mak me to spede, And &thorn;ou
beo euere my mede. // Whonne wolt
&thorn;ou come, Ihesu my ioye, &amp; keuere me
of sore, And &yogh;eue me &thorn;e &thorn;at i may se
&amp; haue for euer-more?  Al my
coueiting were comen, &yogh;if i mi&yogh;te to &thorn;e
fare; I wol no &thorn;ing but only &thorn;e, &thorn;at
al my weolnes (R. wilnes) ware.  Ihesu
my saueour, Ihesu my cumfortour, Of
alle feirhede &thorn;e flour, Myn help and
my socour: Whon may i se &thorn;e in &thorn;i
tour?  &para; Whon wolt &thorn;ou me calle?  Me
longe&thorn; to &thorn;in halle, To seo &thorn;e &amp; hem
alle: &THORN;i loue let hit not falle ...  &para; Now
wax I pale &amp; won, For loue of my
lemmon.  Ihesu bo&thorn;e god and mon, &THORN;i
loue (R. lore) &thorn;ou lered me &thorn;on, Whon
i faste to &thorn;e ron: For-&thorn;i nou loue i
con.  &para;I sitte and synge of
loue-longynge, &thorn;at in myn herte is bred.  Ihesu,
Ihesu, Ihesu, whi neore i to &thorn;e led?
For wel I wot &thorn;ou seost my stat, in
loue my &thorn;ou&yogh;t is sted; Whon i seo &thorn;e,
and dwelle wi&thorn; &thorn;e,</ADD><MILESTONE N="Rawlinson A 389" UNIT="MS"><NOTE ID="n2">Ms. Rawl. continues</NOTE>

&thorn;an am I filde and fed.  Ihesu &thorn;i luf es
feste, and me to luf thynke beste: my
hert when may hit brest, til com to &thorn;e
my reste?  Ihesu, Ihesu, Ihesu, tille &thorn;e es
&thorn;at I mourne; For-&thorn;i, my life and my
lyfynge, why ne may I hythen tourne?
Ihesu my dere and my drewry, delite art
&thorn;ou to synge; Ihesu my myrth my melodie,
when wille &thorn;ou com my kynge?  Ihesu my
hele and my hony, my whert, my com-


<PB N="61">

fortynge: Ihesu, I couaite for to dye,
when it is &thorn;i payinge.  Langynge es in
me lente, &thorn;at my luf has me sent; alle
wa fra me es went, sen &thorn;at my hert es
brent &para; In Cristes luf sa swete, &thorn;at
neuer I wille lete, bot euer to luf I
hete: for luf my bale may bete / and
til my blys me brynge, and gyf me my
&yogh;ernynge, Ihesu my luf swetyng.
Langynge es in me light, &thorn;at byndes me
day &amp; nyght, til I hit hafe in sight,
his face so fayre an bryght.  Ihesu my
hope &amp; hele, my Ioie euer-ilka dele,
&thorn;i luf lat it noght kele, &thorn;at I &thorn;i lufe
may fele, and won wit &thorn;e in wele.
Ihesu with &thorn;e I bygge and belde, leuer
me ware to dye, &thorn;an al &thorn;is worlde to
welde and hafe it in maystry.  When
wil &thorn;ou rewe on me, Ihesu &thorn;at I
myght with &thorn;e be, to luf and loke on
&thorn;e? my setill ordayne for me, and sett
&thorn;ou me &thorn;are-in: for &thorn;an we neuer
twynne, and I &thorn;i luf salle synge,
thurgh syght in &thorn;i schynyng, In heuen
wit-outen endyng.  amen.</P>
</DIV4></DIV3>
</DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>The Commandment</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="Cambridge Dd V.64" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Cambr. Dd. V. 64</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="folio">
<P>(&THORN;)E comawndement of god es &thorn;at
we lufe oure lorde, In al oure hert,
In all oure saule, In al oure thoght.


<PB N="62">

// In al oure hert, &thorn;at es, in al oure
understandyng, with-owten erryng. //
In al owre sawle, &thorn;at es, in al oure
will, with-owten gaynsaiyng. // In al
oure thoght, &thorn;at es: &thorn;at we thynk on
hym with-owten forgetyng.  In &thorn;is maner
es verray lufe &amp; trew; &thorn;at es werk of
mans will.  / For lufe es a wilful stiryng
of owre thoght in til god: sa &thorn;at it
receyue na thyng &thorn;at es agaynes &thorn;e
lufe of Ihesu Crist; and &thorn;ar-with, &thorn;at
it be lastand in swetnes of deuocion:
and &thorn;is es &thorn;e perfection of &thorn;is lyfe. /
Til &thorn;e whilk al dedely syn es
contrary &amp; enmy, bot noght venyall syn. /
For venial syn dose noght away charite:
bot anly lettes &thorn;e vsce &amp; &thorn;e byrnyng
&thorn;arof.  For-&thorn;i, all &thorn;at wil lufe god
perfitely, &thorn;aim behoves noght al-anly
fle al dedly synnes, bot alsa, als mykel
als &thorn;ai may, all venial syn, in thoght,
and worde, &amp; dede.  And namly, to be
of lytel speche.  And &thorn;at sylens be in
occupacion of gode thoghtes, it helpes
gretely to goddes lufe. / For Iangelers
&amp; bakbyters, &thorn;at appayres other mens
lyfe with wikked wordes, and all &thorn;at
roses &thorn;ar awne state before all other,
or &thorn;at despises any state in &thorn;e whilke
a man may be safe: &thorn;ai haue na mare
syght of &thorn;e lufe of god in &thorn;aire sawle,
&thorn;en &thorn;e egh of a bak has of &thorn;e sonne.
/ For vayne speche &amp; ill wordes, er
syngne of a vayne hert &amp; ill,
&thorn;at es with-owten grace of god.  And
he &thorn;at spekes ay &thorn;e gode, &amp; haldes
ilk a man better &thorn;an hym-selfe: he
schewes wele &thorn;at he es stabel in
godenes in hys hert, &amp; ful of charite til
god &amp; til his neghbor.  // And &thorn;at &thorn;ou
may wynne til &thorn;e swetnes of goddes
lufe, I sett here thre degres of lufe,
in &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ou be ay waxand.  // &THORN;e
fyrst degre es called Insuperabel, / &thorn;e


<PB N="63">

secunde Inseparabel, / &thorn;e thyrd Singuler.
// &THORN;i luf es Insuperabel: when na
thyng may ouer-come hit, &thorn;at es,
nowther wele ne waa, ese ne anguys, lust
of flesch ne likyng of &thorn;is worlde; bot
ay it lastes in gode thoght, if it wer
temped gretely, &amp; it hates all syn: sa
&thorn;at na thyng may slokken &thorn;at lufe.  //
&THORN;i lufe es Inseparabel: when al &thorn;i
thoghtes &amp; &thorn;i willes er gederd to-geder
&amp; festend haly in Ihesu Criste, swa &thorn;at
&thorn;ou may na tyme forgete hym, bot ay
&thorn;ou thynkes on hym.  And for-&thorn;i it es
called Inseparabel: for it may noght be
departed fra &thorn;e thoght of Ihesu Criste.
// &THORN;i luf es singuler: when al &thorn;i delyte
es in Ihesu Cryste, &amp; in nane other
thyng fyndes ioy &amp; comforth.  In &thorn;is
degre es lufe stalworth as dede, &amp; hard as hell.  For als dede slas al
lyuand thyng in &thorn;is worlde, sa perfite
lufe slas in a mans sawle all fleschly
desyres and erthly couaytise.  And als
hell spares noght til dede men, bot
tormentes al &thorn;at commes &thorn;artill, alswa
a man &thorn;at es in &thorn;is degre of lufe,
noght anly he forsakes &thorn;e wretched
solace of &thorn;is lyf, bot alswa he couaytes
to sofer pynes for goddes lufe.  / &THORN;arfore
if &thorn;e lyst lufe any thyng, lufe Ihesu
Criste, &thorn;at es &thorn;e fayrest, richest, &amp; wysest; whas lufe lastes in ioy endles.
// For al erthly lufe es passand, &amp; wytes sone away... / If &thorn;ou be couetose
after gode: luf hym, &amp; &thorn;ou sal haue
al gode.  Desyre hym trewly, and &thorn;e
sal wante na thyng.  If delites like &thorn;e:
lufe hym, for he gyfes delites til hys
louers &thorn;at neuer may perisch: &mdash; bot al
&thorn;e delytes of &thorn;is world, er faynt and
fals, &amp; fayland in maste nede; &thorn;ai
bygyn in swettnes, &amp; &thorn;air endyng es
bitterer &thorn;an &thorn;e gall.  If &thorn;ou kan noght
lyf with-owten felichip: lyft &thorn;i thoght
til heuen, &thorn;at &thorn;ou may fynd comforth


<PB N="64">

with aungels &amp; halows, &thorn;e whilke wil
helpe &thorn;e til god, &amp; noght lett &thorn;e, als
&thorn;i fleschly frendes dos. / Restreyn &thorn;i
will a while, fra al lust and lykyng of
syn, &amp; &thorn;ou sall haue efterwarde al &thorn;i
will: For it sal be clensed &amp; made sa
fre, &thorn;at &thorn;e lyst do na thyng bot &thorn;at
&thorn;at es payng of god.  If &thorn;e lyste
speke: forbere it at &thorn;e begynnyng for
goddes lufe: For when &thorn;i hert feles
delyte in Criste, &thorn;e wil not liste to
speke ne iangell bot of Criste.  If &thorn;ow
may not dreghe to syt by &thorn;i nane: vse
&thorn;e stalworthly in hys lufe, &amp; he sal
sa stabyly sett &thorn;e, &thorn;at al &thorn;e solace of
&thorn;is worlde sal noght remove &thorn;e, for
&thorn;e will noght list &thorn;arof.  // When
&thorn;ow ert be &thorn;i-self, be ay, till slepe
come, owther in prayer or in gode
meditacioun.  And ordane &thorn;i prayng
&amp; &thorn;i wakyng &amp; &thorn;i fastyng, &thorn;at it be
in discrecion, noght ouer-mykel na
ouer-litel: Bot thynk ay &thorn;at of all
thyng maste coueytes god &thorn;e lufe of
mans hert.  And for-&thorn;i seke mare to
lufe hym, &thorn;an to do any penance.
For vnskylful penance es litel worth or
noght: Bot lufe es ay &thorn;e best, whether
&thorn;ou do penance mykel or lytel.  Be
abowtwarde in &thorn;i myght, &thorn;at &thorn;ou war
swa inwardly gyuen til &thorn;e lufe of
Ihesu Criste, &thorn;at for gastly ioy of &thorn;i
sawle na thyng &thorn;at men may do or
say, make &thorn;e sary; swa &thorn;at &thorn;i thoght
with-in be fed anly in &thorn;e swetnes of
Cristes lufe; &amp; noght in delyte of
erthly ese; ne in louyng of men, when
&thorn;ai begyn to speke gode of &thorn;e, in
ydel ioy.  Trayst in god, &thorn;at he wil
gif til &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou prayse hym skilfully.
// Skylful prayer es til cristen mans
sawle: to seke &amp; aske, nyght &amp; day, &thorn;e
lufe of Ihesu Criste, &thorn;at it may lufe
hym verraly, feland comforth &amp; delyte
in hym; owt kastyng worldes thoghtes


<PB N="65">

&amp; il bysynes.  / And sykir be &thorn;ou, if
&thorn;ou couayte his lufe trewly &amp; lastandly,
swa &thorn;at na lufe of &thorn;i flesche, ne
angers of &thorn;e worlde, ne speche ne
hatreden of men, draw &thorn;e agayne, &amp; caste &thorn;e noght in bisynes of bodily
thyng: &thorn;ou sal haue his lufe, &amp; fynd
and fele &thorn;at it es delitabeler in a
nowre, &thorn;an al &thorn;e welthe &thorn;at we here
se may, til domesday. // And if &thorn;ou
fayle &amp; fall for temptacions, or for
angers, or for ouer-mykel luf of &thorn;i
frendes: it es na wonder if he halde
fra &thorn;e thyng &thorn;at &thorn;ow couaytes noght
trewly.  // He says &thorn;at he lufes &thorn;am
&thorn;at lufes hym; and: &thorn;ai &thorn;at arely
wakes til hym, sal fynde hym. // &THORN;ow
ert arely wakand oft-sythe, why &thorn;an
fyndes &thorn;ou hym noght?  Certes, if &thorn;ou
seke hym ryght, &thorn;ou sall fynde hym.
Bot ay whiles &thorn;ou sekes erthly ioy: if
&thorn;ou wake neuer sa arely, Criste may
&thorn;ou noght fynde: for he es noght
funden in &thorn;air lande &thorn;at lyues in
fleschly lustes.  Hys moder, when he
was willed fra hyr, scho soght hym
gretand, arely and late, ymang his
kynredyn &amp; hirs: bot scho fand hym
noght, for al hyr sekyng, til at &thorn;e
laste scho come in til &thorn;e tempyl, &amp; &thorn;are scho fand hym syttand ymange
&thorn;e maysters, herand and answerand.
Swa behoues &thorn;e do, if &thorn;ou wil fynd
hym: seke hym inwardly, in trouth, &amp; hope, &amp; charite of haly kyrk; castand
owt al syn, hatand it in al &thorn;i hert:
for &thorn;at haldes hym fra &thorn;e, &amp; lettes &thorn;e
&thorn;at &thorn;ou may noght fynd hym.  // &THORN;e
herdes &thorn;at hym soght: fand hym
lyand in a krybbe, by-twyx twa bestes&mdash;
&thorn;at &thorn;ou knawes.  // If &thorn;ou seke hym
verraly: &thorn;e behoues ga in &thorn;e way of
Pouert, and noght of riches.  // &THORN;e
sterne led &thorn;e thre keynges in til
Bedlem: &thorn;ar &thorn;ai fand Criste swedeld in


<PB N="66">

clowtes sympely, as a pore barne.  &THORN;arby
vnderstand: whils &thorn;ou ert in pryde &amp; vanyte, &thorn;ou fyndes hym noght.  How
may &thorn;ou for schame, &thorn;at es bot
seruand, with many clathes &amp; riche folow
&thorn;i spowse &amp; &thorn;i lorde, &thorn;at yhede in a
kyrtel: and &thorn;ou trayles als mykel
behynd &thorn;e, as al &thorn;at he had on? //
For-&thorn;i I rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou parte with hym,
ar &thorn;ou and he mete: &thorn;at he reprove
&thorn;e noght of outrage; for he wil &thorn;at
&thorn;ow haue &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase mister of, &amp; na mare.  He sayde til his discipyls
&thorn;at &thorn;ai sulde noght haue als many
clathes as twa myght be sustend with;
forto traueyle &thorn;are-abowte, es owtrage
bisynes, &thorn;at he forbedes. // &THORN;e lufe of
Ihesu Criste es ful dere tresure, ful
delytabyl ioy, &amp; ful syker to trayst man
on.  For-&thorn;i, he wil not gyf it to folys,
&thorn;at kan noght hald it &amp; kepe it
tenderly: Bot til &thorn;aim he gese it &thorn;e whilk
nowther for wele ne for wa wil lat it
passe fra &thorn;am, bot are &thorn;ai wil dye
or &thorn;ai wolde wrath Ihesu Criste. / And
na wyse man dose precyous lycor in
a stynkand vessell, bot in a clene.  Als
Criste dose noght his lufe in a foule
hert in syn, &amp; bownden in wile lust
of flesche, bot in a hert &thorn;at es fayre
and clene in vertues.  Noght-for-&thorn;i, a
fowle vessel may be made sa clene,
&thorn;at a ful dere thyng sauely may be
done &thorn;arin.  And Ihesu Criste
oftsythes purges many synfull mans sawle,
&amp; makes it abyl thurgh his grace to
receyue &thorn;e delitabel swetnes of hys
luf, &amp; to be his wonnyng-stede in
halynes; and ay &thorn;e clennar it waxes: &thorn;e
mare ioy &amp; solace of heuen Criste
settes &thorn;arin.  For-&thorn;i, at &thorn;e fyrst tyme
when a man es turned to god: he may
not fele &thorn;at swete lycor, til he haue
bene wele vsed in goddes seruys, &amp; his hert be purged thorow prayers &amp;


<PB N="67">

penance &amp; gode thoghtes in god.  For
he &thorn;at es slaw in goddes seruyce, may
noght be byrnand in lufe, bot if he do
al his myght, &amp; trauell nyght &amp; day,
to fulfill goddes will.  And when &thorn;at
blyssed lufe es in a mans hert: it will
not suffer hym be ydel, bot ay it
stirres hym to do som gode &thorn;at myght
be lykand til god, as in praying, or in
wirkyng profitabel thynges, or in
spekyng of Cristes passyon; and principally
in thoght, &thorn;at &thorn;e mynde of Ihesu
Criste passe noght fra his thoght.  For
if &thorn;ou lufe hym trewly: &thorn;ou wil glad
&thorn;e in hym, &amp; noght in other thyng;
and &thorn;ou [wil] thynk on hym, kastand
away al other thoghtes.  Bot if &thorn;ou
be fals &amp; take o&thorn;er &thorn;an hym, &amp; delyte
&thorn;e in erthly thyng, agaynes his wille:
wit &thorn;ou wele, he will forsake &thorn;e as
&thorn;ou hase done hyme, and dampne &thorn;e
for &thorn;i synne. // Wharfore, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
may lufe hym trewly, vnderstand &thorn;at
his lufe es proued in thre thynges:
In thynkyng, In spekyng, In wirkyng.
Chaunge &thorn;i thoght fra &thorn;e worlde, &amp; kast it haly on hym: &amp; he sall
norysche &thorn;e.  Chaunge &thorn;i mowth fra
vnnayte &amp; warldes speche, &amp; speke of
hym: &amp; he sall comforth &thorn;e.  Chaunge
&thorn;i hend fra &thorn;e warkes of vanitese, &amp; lyft &thorn;am in his name, &amp; wyrke anly
for hys lufe: &amp; he sall receyue &thorn;e.  Do
&thorn;us: &amp; &thorn;an lufes &thorn;ou trewly, and gase
in &thorn;e way of perfitenes. / Delyte &thorn;e sa
in hym, &thorn;at &thorn;i hert receyue nowther
worldes ioy, ne worldes sorow; and
drede no anguys ne noy &thorn;at may
befalle bodyly on &thorn;e or on any of &thorn;i
frendes: bot betake all in til goddes
will, &amp; thank hym ay, of all hys sandes:
swa &thorn;at &thorn;ou may haue rest &amp; sauowre
in hys lufe.  For if &thorn;i hert owther be
ledde with worldes drede, or worldes
solace, &thorn;ou ert full fer fra &thorn;e swetnes


<PB N="68">

of Cristes lufe. / And loke wele &thorn;at
&thorn;ou seme not ane with-owten, and be
a nother wyth-in, als ypocrites dose,
&thorn;e whilk er like til a sepulker &thorn;at es
paynted richely with-owten, &amp; wyth-in
rotes stynkand banes.  If &thorn;ou haue
delyte in &thorn;e name of religion: loke
&thorn;at &thorn;ou haue mare delyte in &thorn;e dede
&thorn;at falles til religion.  Thyne abett
says &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase forsaken &thorn;e world,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou ert gyuen till goddes seruys,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou delyte[s] &thorn;e noght in erthly
thyng: lok &thorn;an &thorn;at it be in &thorn;i hert,
als it semes in men syght&mdash;For na
thyng may make &thorn;e religious bot
vertues &amp; clennes of sawle in charite. / If
&thorn;i body be cled wyth-owten as &thorn;ine
order wille, loke &thorn;at &thorn;i sawle be
noght naked with-in&mdash;&thorn;at &thorn;ine order
forbedes: Bot naked be &thorn;i sawle fra
all vices, &amp; warme happed in lufe and
mekenes.  Drede &thorn;e domes of god, sa
&thorn;at &thorn;ou wrath hym noght.  Stabel &thorn;i
thoght in hys lufe, &amp; helld owt of &thorn;e
al synnes.  Kast away slawnes, vse &thorn;e
manly in godenes; be deboner &amp; meke til al men, lat na thyng bryng
&thorn;e til Ire or envy; dyght &thorn;i sawle
fayre &amp; make &thorn;ar-in a towre of lufe
til goddes son&macr;, and gar &thorn;i will be
couaytous to receyue hym, als gladly
as &thorn;ou walde be at &thorn;e commyng of a
thyng &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufed mast of al thyng.
Wasche &thorn;i thoght clene wyth lufe-teres
&amp; brennand &yogh;ernyng, &thorn;at he fynd na
thyng fowle in &thorn;e: for his ioy es
&thorn;at &thorn;ou be fayre &amp; lufsom in his
eghen.  Fayrehede of &thorn;i sawle, &thorn;at he
couaytes, es &thorn;at &thorn;ou be chaste and
meke, mylde and sufferand, neuer irk
to do his wille, ay hatand all
wykkednes.  In al &thorn;at &thorn;ou dose, thynk ay to
com&macr; to &thorn;e syght of his fairehede, &amp; sett al &thorn;ine entent &thorn;arin &thorn;at &thorn;ow


<PB N="69">

may com&macr; &thorn;ar-til at &thorn;ine endyng&mdash;for
&thorn;at aght to be &thorn;e ende of al oure
traueyle, &thorn;at we euermare, whils we
lyue here, desyre &thorn;at syght, in all oure
hert, &amp; &thorn;at we thynk ay lang &thorn;ar-till.
// Als-sa festen in &thorn;i hert &thorn;e mynd of
his passyon &amp; of his woundes: grete
delyte and swetnes sal &thorn;ou fele, if &thorn;ou
halde &thorn;i thoght in mynde of &thorn;e pyne
&thorn;at Cryst sufferd for &thorn;e. / If &thorn;ou
traueyle right in hys lufe, &amp; desyre
hym brennandly: all temptacyons &amp; dredes of ill &thorn;ou sall ouercom, &amp; deful vnder &thorn;i fote, thorow his grace.
/ For al &thorn;at he sees in gode will to
luf hym, he helpes &thorn;am agaynes all
&thorn;ar enmys, and rayses &thorn;ar thoght
abouen all erthly thyng, swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai
may haue sauoure &amp; solace in &thorn;e
swetnes of heuen. // Purches &thorn;e &thorn;e
welle of gretyng, &amp; cees noght till &thorn;ou
haue hym.  For in &thorn;e hert whare
teres sprynges, &thorn;ar wil &thorn;e fyre of &thorn;e
haly gaste be kyndelde: and sythen
&thorn;e fyre of lufe, &thorn;at sal byrn in &thorn;i
hert, wil bryn til noght al &thorn;e rust of
syn, &amp; purge &thorn;i sawle of al fylth, als
clene as &thorn;e golde &thorn;at es proued in &thorn;e
fournes.  I wate na thyng &thorn;at swa
inwardly sal take &thorn;i hert to couayte
goddes lufe and to desyre &thorn;e ioy of
heuen &amp; to despyse &thorn;e vanitees of &thorn;is
worlde, as stedfast thynkyng of &thorn;e
myscheues &amp; greuous woundes [&] of
&thorn;e dede of Ihesu Criste.  It wil rayse
&thorn;i thoght abouen erthly lykyng, &amp; make &thorn;i hert brennand in Cristes lufe,
&amp; pur[ch]es in &thorn;i sawle delitabelte and
sauoure of heuen. // Bot per-aunter &thorn;ou
will say: &laquo;I may noght despyse &thorn;e
worlde, I may not fynd it in my hert to
pyne my body, &amp; me behoues lufe my
fleschly frendes, and take ese when it
comes.&raquo;  If &thorn;ou be temped with swilk
thoghtes, I pray &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou vmbethynk


<PB N="70">

&thorn;e, fra &thorn;e begynnyng of &thorn;is worlde,
whare &thorn;e worldes louers er now, &amp; whare &thorn;e louers er of god.  Certes,
&thorn;ai war men &amp; wymen as we er, and
ete &amp; drank &amp; logh: and &thorn;e wreches
&thorn;at lofed &thorn;is worlde toke ese til &thorn;air
body &amp; lyued as &thorn;am lyst, in likyng
of &thorn;air wikked will, &amp; led &thorn;air dayes
in lust &amp; delyces: &amp; in a poynt &thorn;ai
fel in til hell. / Now may &thorn;ou see &thorn;at
&thorn;ai wer foles, &amp; fowle glotons, &thorn;at in
a few &yogh;eres wasted endles ioy, &thorn;at was
ordand for &thorn;am if &thorn;ai walde haue
done penance for &thorn;air synnes.  &THORN;ou
sese &thorn;at al &thorn;e ryches of &thorn;is world, &amp; delytes vanys a-way and commes til
noght.  Sothely, swa dose al &thorn;e lofers
&thorn;ar-of: For nathyng may stande stabely
on a fals gronde.  &THORN;air bodys er gyn
til wormes in erth, &amp; &thorn;air sawles til
&thorn;e deuels of hell.  Bot all &thorn;at
forsoke &thorn;e pompe &amp; &thorn;e vanite of &thorn;is lyfe,
&amp; stode stalworthly agaynes all
temptacions, and ended in &thorn;e lufe of god:
&thorn;ai ar now in ioy, &amp; hase &thorn;e erytage
of heuen, &thorn;ar to won with-owten end,
restand in &thorn;e delyces of goddes syght.
For here &thorn;ai soght na mare rest ne ese
til &thorn;air body, &thorn;en &thorn;ai had nede of.
// A thyng I rede &thorn;e: &thorn;at &thorn;ou forgete
noght &thorn;is name IHESU, bot thynk it in
&thorn;i hert, nyght &amp; day, as &thorn;i speciall, &amp; &thorn;i
dere tresowre.  Lufe it mare &thorn;an &thorn;i lyfe,
rute it in &thorn;i mynde.  Lufe Ihesu, for he
made &thorn;e, and boght &thorn;e ful dere.  Gyf
&thorn;i hert till hym: for it es his dette.
For-&thorn;i set &thorn;i lufe on hys name Ihesu,
&thorn;at es &laquo;hele&raquo;. // &THORN;er may na ill thyng haue
dwellyng in &thorn;e hert &thorn;ar Ihesu es halden
in mynde trewly: For it chaces deuels,
&amp; destroyes temptacions, and puttes
a-way wykked dredes &amp; vices, &amp; clenses
&thorn;e thoght.  Wha sa lofes it verraly, es
full of goddes grace &amp; vertues; in
gastly comforth in &thorn;is lyfe, &amp; when


<PB N="71">

&thorn;ai dye &thorn;ai er taken vp in til &thorn;e orders
of awngels, to se hym in endles ioy
&thorn;at &thorn;ai haue lufed.  Amen.
</P>
