<DIV3 N="Rawlinson A 389" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="61"><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Rawlinson A 389</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="81" UNIT="folio">

<OPENER>&para; Richard hermit.</OPENER>

<P>&THORN;e commaundement of god is &thorn;at
we lufe oure lord in al oure hert, in
al oure sowle, in al oure thoght.  In


<PB N="62">

al oure hert, &thorn;at is in al oure
vndirstondyng with-outen erryng.  In al oure
sowle, &thorn;at is in al oure wille with-outen
&yogh;eynsaiyng.  In al oure thoght, &thorn;at is, &thorn;at
we thynk on hym with-outen forgetyng.
In &thorn;is manere is verray luf &amp; trewe,
&thorn;at is werke of monnes wille.  For luf
is a wilfu!  stiryng of oure thoght in to
god: so &thorn;at it receyue no thyng &thorn;at is
a&yogh;eyns &thorn;e luf of Ihesu Crist, and
&thorn;are-with &thorn;at it be lastyng in swetnes of
deuocion: and &thorn;is is &thorn;e perfeccion
of &thorn;is lif.  To &thorn;e whiche al dedly
synne is contrary &amp; enemy, bot not
venial synne: for venial synne doth
not awey charite, bot onli letteth &thorn;e
ois and &thorn;e brennyng &thorn;are-of.
&THORN;are-fore alle &thorn;at wil luf god parfitly,
&thorn;aim behouith not onli fle alle dedly
synnes, bot also, als michel als &thorn;ai
may, al veniale synne, in thoght, and
word, and dede; and namely to be
of littul speche&mdash;and &thorn;at silence be
in occupacion of gode thoghtes, It
helpes gretly to goddes luf.  For ianglers
and bakbiters &thorn;at apeireth othir mennes
lif with wicked wordes, and alle &thorn;at
louen &thorn;aire owene state by-foren alle
othere, or &thorn;at despiseth any state in &thorn;e
whiche a man may be sauf: thai haue
no more sight of &thorn;e luf of god in &thorn;aire
sowle &thorn;en &thorn;e egh of a backe hath of
&thorn;e sonne.  For veyn speche and ille
wordes arne signe of a veyne hert &amp; ille &thorn;at is with-outen &thorn;e grace of god.
And he &thorn;at speketh ay &thorn;e gode, and
holdes iche mon better &thorn;en him-self:
he schewith wele &thorn;at he is stable in
godnesse in his hert, &amp; ful of charite
to god and his neghbur.  &para; And &thorn;at
&thorn;ou may come to &thorn;e swetnesse of goddes
luf, I sette here thre degrees of luf, in
&thorn;e whiche &thorn;ou be waxing.  &para; &thorn;e first
degre is cleped Insuperable, &thorn;e tother


<PB N="63">

Inseparable, &thorn;e thridde Singuler.  Thi
luf is insuperable, when no thing may
ouer-com it, &thorn;at is, nouther wele ne
wo, ese ne anguys, luf of flesch ne
likyng of &thorn;is world; bot ay it lasteth
in god, &thorn;ogh it were tempted gretly,
and hit hateth al synne, so &thorn;at no
thyng may slakne &thorn;at luf.  &para; Thi luf
is inseparable, when alle thi thoghtes
and alle thi willes are gaderd to-gedir
&amp; festned holly in Ihesu Crist, so &thorn;at
&thorn;ou may notyme for&yogh;ete hym, bot ay
&thorn;ou thynkest on hym; and &thorn;erfore it
is cleped inseparable, for it may not be
departed fro thoght of Ihesu Crist.
&para; That luf is singuler, when al &thorn;e delit
is in Ihesu Crist, and in non other thing
fynde ioye or comfort.  In &thorn;is degre is
luf stalworthe als ded, and hard als
helle: for als ded slees al lyuyng
thing in &thorn;is world, so parfit luf sleth
in a monnes sowle alle fleschely desires
and erthly couaytise.  And als helle
spareth not to ded menne, bot tormenteth
alle &thorn;at cometh &thorn;erto, so a mon &thorn;at
is in &thorn;is degre of luf, not only he
forsakith &thorn;e wreched solace of &thorn;is lif, bot
also coueiteth to suffre pynes for godes
luf.  &THORN;are-fore if &thorn;e list luf any thing,
luf Ihesu Crist, &thorn;at is fairest, richest &amp; wisest, whos luf lasteth in ioye endeles;
for al erthly luf is passing and witeth
sone a-wey; noht &thorn;at falleth &thorn;erto is
dwellyng, bot pyne &thorn;at it deserued.  If
&thorn;ou be coueitous aftur gude: luf him
and &thorn;ou hast al gude; desire hym trewly
&amp; &thorn;e schal wonte no thyng.  If delites
like the: lufe him, for he &yogh;eueth delites
to his lufers &thorn;at neuer may perisch: bot
alle &thorn;e delices of &thorn;is world are feynt
and fals and failyng in most nede; /
thai bygynne in swetnesse and &thorn;air
endyng is bitterer &thorn;en galle.  If &thorn;ou
kan not lyfe with-outen felashipe: lift
&thorn;i thoght to heuen, &thorn;at &thorn;ou may fele


<PB N="64">

comfort with aungels and halewes, &thorn;e
whiche wil helpe &thorn;e to god, &amp; not lette &thorn;e
als &thorn;i fleschely frendes doth. / Restreyne
&thorn;i wille a while fro al lust and likyng
of synne and &thorn;ou schalt haue afterward
al thi wille: for hit shal be clensed &amp; made so fre, &thorn;at &thorn;e wil lust to do no
thyng bot &thorn;at is paiyng to god.  If &thorn;e
lust speke: for-bere it at &thorn;e bygynnyng
for goddes luf: for when &thorn;i hert feleth
delit in Crist, the wil not lust speke ne
iangle bot of Crist.  If &thorn;ou may not
dreghe to sitte bi thyn one: oise the
stalworthly in his luf and he shal
so stabli sette &thorn;e, &thorn;at al &thorn;e solace
of &thorn;is worlde shal not mowe remewe
&thorn;e, for the wil not luste &thorn;are-of. /
When &thorn;ou art bi thi-self, be ay,
to slep come, outhir in prayer or in
gode meditacioun.  / And ordeyne &thorn;i
wakyng and &thorn;i praying and &thorn;i fasting,
&thorn;at it be in discrecioun, not
ouer-mychel ne ouer-litel: bot thynke ay
&thorn;at of alle thinges most quemeth god
luf of monnys hert.  / And &thorn;are-fore
seche more to luf hym &thorn;en to do any
penance; for vnskilful penance is litul
worth or noght, bot luf is ay &thorn;e best,
whether &thorn;ou do penance mychel or
litel.  &para; Be aboutewarde in al &thorn;i myght
&thorn;at &thorn;ou were so inwardly &yogh;euen to &thorn;e
luf of Ihesu Crist &thorn;at for gostli ioye of
&thorn;i sowle nouht &thorn;at men may say or do
made &thorn;e sory, so &thorn;at &thorn;i thoght withinne
be fed only in &thorn;e swetnesse of Cristes
luf, not in delit of erthly ease, ne in
louyng of men, if &thorn;ai be-gan to speke
gude of the, ne in idel ioye.  / Trust
in god, &thorn;at he wil &yogh;eue to the thingis
&thorn;at &thorn;ou prayes hym skillefully.  Skylful
prayer is to cristen mennes sowle to
seche and aske nyght and day &thorn;e luf
of Ihesu Crist, &thorn;at it may luf him verrali,
feling comfort &amp; delit in him,
oute-kasting worldes thoghtes and Iuel


<PB N="65">

bisines. / And siker be &thorn;ou, if &thorn;ou
coueite his luf trewli &amp; lastyngli, so &thorn;at
no lust of &thorn;i flesche, ne angrynge of
&thorn;e world, ne speche ne hatereden of
men, drawe a&yogh;eyn &amp; cast &thorn;e not in
bisinesse of bodili thynges: &thorn;ou shalt
haue his luf, and fynde and fele &thorn;at
hit is delitabler in an oure &thorn;an alle &thorn;e
welthe &thorn;at we here see, may be to
domes-day.  And if &thorn;ou faille and falle
for temptacions, or for angres, or
for ouer-myche luf of &thorn;i frendes: it es
no wonder if he holde fro &thorn;e thing &thorn;at
&thorn;ou coueitest not trewly.  He sayth &thorn;at
he lufes thaim &thorn;at lufes him; and, &thorn;ei
&thorn;at erly waketh to him schal fynde
him.  &THORN;ou art erely wakyng oftesyth,
whi &thorn;an fyndes &thorn;ou him not?  Certes
if &thorn;ou seche hym ryght, &thorn;ou schalt
fynde him; bot whiles &thorn;ou sechest
ertheli ioye, &thorn;ogh &thorn;ou wake neuer so
erli, Crist may &thorn;ou not fynde: for he
is not founden in &thorn;aire londe &thorn;at lifes
in flescheli lustes.  &para; His moder, when
he was willed fro hire, soght wepyng
erely &amp; late amonge his kynreden and
hires: Bot sche fonde him not for alle
her schetyng and her sorowyng, to at
&thorn;e laste sche come in to &thorn;e temple,
and &thorn;ere sche fonde hym sittyng among
&thorn;e maistres, heryng and onsweryng.
So behoueth &thorn;e do, if &thorn;ou wilt fynde
hym: seche inwardly, in trouthe &amp; hope
and charite of holichirche, castyng oute
al synne and hathing it in al &thorn;i herte:
for &thorn;at holdeth hym fro &thorn;e, and letteth
&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou may not fynde hym.  &para; &THORN;e
herdemen &thorn;at soght, fonde him liggyng
in a crybbe, bi-twene two bestes; &thorn;at
&thorn;ou knowe, if &thorn;ou seche hym verraly,
&thorn;e be-houeth go in &thorn;e way of pouert,
and not of richesse.  &para; &THORN;e sterre led &thorn;e
thre kynges in to Bethleem: &thorn;ere &thorn;ei


<PB N="66">

fonde Crist in swethil-cloutes simpli,
as a poure childe.  &THORN;arby vnderstonde
&thorn;at whiles &thorn;ou art in pryde and vanite,
&thorn;ou fyndest him not.  How may &thorn;ou
for schame, &thorn;at art bot seruant, with
mony clothes &amp; riche folewe &thorn;i spouse
and &thorn;i lord, &thorn;at went in on kirtil: &amp; &thorn;ou trailest as myche bihynde &thorn;e, as
al &thorn;at he had on?  &THORN;are-fore I rede
&thorn;at &thorn;ou part with hym er &thorn;ou &amp; he
mete, &thorn;at he reproue &thorn;e not of outrage;
for he wil &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast
myster of, and nomore.  He said to his
disciples &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulde not haue als
mony clothes als two moght be susteined
with&mdash;for to trauaile &thorn;are-aboute, is
outrageous besenesse, &thorn;at he forbedeth.
&para; The luf of Ihesu Crist is ful dere
tresor, ful delitable ioy, and ful siker
to trust men on.  &THORN;are-fore he wil not
&yogh;eue hit to foles, &thorn;at can not holde hit
and kepen it tenderly: bot to thaim he
&yogh;efeth it &thorn;e whiche nouther for wele
ne for wo wil let it passe fro thaim, bot
&thorn;ei wil die er &thorn;ei wolde wrathe Ihesu
Crist. / And no wysmon dos precious
licour in a stynkyng vessell, bot in a
clene.  Also Crist dos not his luf in a
foule hert(e) in synne, and bonden in
vil lust of flesshe: bot in an herte &thorn;at
is faire and clene in vertues.
Neuer-&thorn;e-latter a foule vessel may be maked
so clene, &thorn;at ful dere thyng sauely may
be don &thorn;ere-in.  And Ihesu Crist
oftesithes purgeth mony synful monnes
soule, &amp; maketh it able thurgh his grace
to resceyue &thorn;e delitable swetnesse of
his luf, and to be his wonyngstede in
holynesse; and ay &thorn;e clenner it waxeth,
&thorn;e more ioy &amp; solace of heuen(e) Crist
setteth &thorn;are-in.  &THORN;arefore at &thorn;e first
tyme when a mon is turned to god, he
may not fele &thorn;at swete licour til he
haue ben wel oised in goddes seruice
and his herte be purged thurgh prayers


<PB N="67">

&amp; penance &amp; gode thoghtes in god;
for he &thorn;at is slowe in goddes seruice,
may not be brennyng in luf, bot if he
do al his myght and trauaile nyght and
day to fulfille goddes wille.  And when
&thorn;at blissed luf is in a monnes herte, it
wil not suffre hym to be idel, bot ay
it stireth hym to do som gode &thorn;at myght
be likyng to god, as in praying, or in
worching profitable thinge, or in spekyng
of Ihesu Crist; and principally in thoght,
&thorn;at &thorn;e mynde of Ihesu Crist passe not
fro his thoght.  For if &thorn;ou lufe hym
trewly, &thorn;ou wil(t) glade &thorn;e in him and
not in other thyng, / and &thorn;ou wilt
thynk on him, castyng awey alle othir
thoghtes. / Bot if &thorn;ou be fals &amp; take
othir &thorn;en him and delite &thorn;e in erthely
thyng a&yogh;eins his wille: witte &thorn;ou
wele he wil forsake &thorn;e as &thorn;ou hast
don hym, &amp; dampne (&thorn;e) for &thorn;i
synne. / Wharfore, &thorn;at &thorn;ou may luf
hym treweli, vndirstonde &thorn;at his luf is
proued in thre thynges: In thynkyng,
in spekyng, in worchyng. / Change
&thorn;i thoght fro &thorn;e world and cast
hit holli on hym, and he schal
norisshe &thorn;e. / Change &thorn;i mouth fro
vnprofitable &amp; wordli speche (&amp; speke)
of hym, and he schal comfort the. /
Change &thorn;ine honden fro werkis of
vanites and lift &thorn;aim in his nome and
worche only for his luf, and he schal
resceyue &thorn;e.  Do &thorn;us and &thorn;ou lufes
him trewly and &thorn;ou gost in &thorn;e wey of
parfitenesse.  Delite &thorn;e so in hym &thorn;at &thorn;i
hert resceyue nouther worldes ioy ne
worldes sorowe; and drede not anguyse
or noy &thorn;at may be-falle bodili on the
or on any of &thorn;i frendes, bot betake al
in to goddes will, and thanke him ay
of all his sondes: so &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue rest
and sauour in his luf; for if &thorn;i herte
outher be led with worledes drede, or
worldes solace, &thorn;ou art ful far fro &thorn;e


<PB N="68">

swetnesse of Crist&yogh; luf.  And loke wele
&thorn;at &thorn;ou seme not on withouten and be
an other withinne, as ypocrites doth,
&thorn;e whiche are like to a sepulcre &thorn;at is
peynted richely with-outen, and
withinne roteth stynkyng bones.  If &thorn;ou
haue delit in &thorn;e [name of religion,
loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue more delyte in
&thorn;e] dede &thorn;at falleth to religion.  &THORN;in
habit saith &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast forsaken &thorn;e
world, &thorn;at &thorn;ou art &yogh;efen to goddes
seruice, &thorn;at &thorn;ou delites &thorn;e not in erthely
thyng: loke &thorn;enne &thorn;at it be in &thorn;i
hert(e) as hit semeth in mennes sight&mdash;for
noth&thorn;ing may make &thorn;e religious bot
vertues and clennesse of soule in charite.
If thi bodi be clothed with-outen as
&thorn;in order wil, loke &thorn;at &thorn;i soule be not
naked withinne&mdash;&thorn;at &thorn;in order forbedeth:
bot naked be thi soule fro alle vices,
and warme happed in luf &amp; mekenes.
Drede &thorn;e domes of god, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou
wretthe him not; stabil &thorn;i thoght in his
luf, and held oute of &thorn;e alle synnes;
cast awey slowenesse, oise &thorn;e monli in
godenes, / be deboner ande meke to
alle men, lete no thing brynge &thorn;e to
ire or enuy(e); dight thi soule faire,
make &thorn;are-inne a trone of luf to goddes
son, and make &thorn;i wille be coueitous to
receyue hym as gladli as &thorn;ou woldest
be at &thorn;e comyng of a thyng &thorn;at &thorn;ou
lufed most of alle thyng.  Wasshe &thorn;i
thoght clene with luf-teres and brennyng
desiryng, &thorn;at he fynde no thyng foul
in &thorn;e: for his ioy is &thorn;at &thorn;ou be faire
&amp; lufesom in his eghen. / Fairehede of
&thorn;i soule &thorn;at he coueiteth, is &thorn;at &thorn;ou
be chast &amp; meke, mylde &amp; suffrynge,
neuer irk to do his will, ay hatyng alle
wrychednesse.  In al &thorn;at &thorn;ou dost think
ai to come to &thorn;e sight of his fairehed,
&amp; sette alle &thorn;in entent &thorn;are-inne &thorn;at
&thorn;ou may come &thorn;are-to at thin endyng&mdash;


<PB N="69">

for &thorn;at oweth to be ende of al oure
trauail &thorn;at we euermore, while we life
here, desire &thorn;at sight in alle oure hert,
and &thorn;at vs ay thynk longe &thorn;ar-to.
&para; Also festne in thin herte &thorn;e mynde
of his passione &amp; of is woundes: gret
delit and swetnes schal &thorn;ou fele, if
&thorn;ou holde &thorn;i thoght in mynde of &thorn;e
pyne &thorn;at Crist suffred for &thorn;e.  &para; If
&thorn;ou trauaill ryght in his luf, and
desire him brennyngli: alle temptacions
&amp; dredes of euel &thorn;ou salt ouercome
and defoule vnder &thorn;i fete thurghe his
grace; for alle &thorn;at he seeth in gode
wille to luf him, he helpeth thaim
a&yogh;eins alle thaire enemys, and reiseth
&thorn;air thoght abouen erthely thynge,
so &thorn;at thei may haue sauour of &thorn;e
swetnesse of heuen.  Purchace the &thorn;e
welle of wepyng, and cese not til &thorn;at
&thorn;ow haue hym: for in &thorn;e hert where
teres spryngen, &thorn;er wil &thorn;e fire of
&thorn;e holigost be kyndelet: and sithen
&thorn;e fire of luf, &thorn;at schal brenne in
&thorn;i herte, wil brynge to noght al &thorn;e
rust of synne, and purge &thorn;i soule
of al filthe, als clene as &thorn;e gold &thorn;at
is proued in &thorn;e fourneys.  &para; I wote
no thinge &thorn;at so inwardly schal
take &thorn;i herte to coueit goddes luf /
and to desire &thorn;e ioy and to despise &thorn;e
vanites of &thorn;is world, as stedfast thynkyng
of &thorn;e mysese &amp; greuous woundes and
of &thorn;e deth of Ihesu Crist: it wil reise
&thorn;i thoght abouen ertheli likyng / and
make thin herte brennyng in Cristes
luf, and purchace in to &thorn;i soule delitablete
and sauour of heuene. / Bot peraunter
&thorn;ou wilt say: &laquo;I may not despise &thorn;e
worlde, I may not fynde it in my hert
to punysshe my bodi, and me behoueth
luf my flessheli frendes, and take ease
when it comes.&raquo;  If &thorn;ou be tempted
with suche thoghtes, I pray &thorn;at &thorn;ou
bethynk &thorn;e, fro &thorn;e bigynnyng of &thorn;is


<PB N="70">

worlde, where &thorn;e worldes luferes are
now, / and where &thorn;e lufers are of god.
Certes, &thorn;ai were men and wemen as we
are, &amp; ete and dronk and loghe: / and
&thorn;e wrecches &thorn;at lufed &thorn;is world toke
ese to &thorn;air body, and lifed as &thorn;aim
luste in likyng of &thorn;aire wicked wille,
and ledde &thorn;air daies in lust and delices:
and in a pointe &thorn;ai felle to helle.  Now
may &thorn;ou see &thorn;at &thorn;ai were foles and
foule glotons, &thorn;at in a fewe &yogh;eres wasted
endles ioye &thorn;at was ordeynt for tham if
&thorn;ai wold han don penance for thaire
synnes. // &THORN;ou seest &thorn;at al &thorn;e riches
and delite of &thorn;is worlde vanisseth awey
and cometh to noght.  Sothli, so doth
alle &thorn;aire lufers: for no thyng may
stonde stabli on a fals gronde.  &THORN;air
bodies are &yogh;euen to wormes in erthe,
and &thorn;aire soules to &thorn;e deuelles in helle. /
Bot alle &thorn;at forsoke &thorn;e pompe and &thorn;e
vanite of &thorn;is lif, and stode stalworthly
a&yogh;eins alle temptaciones, / and ended
in &thorn;e luf of god: &thorn;ai are now in ioye
and haue &thorn;e heritage of heuen, &thorn;ere to
won with-outen ende, restyng in &thorn;e
delices of goddes sight; for here &thorn;ei
soght no more rest ne ese to &thorn;air body
&thorn;en thai had nede of. // O thynge I
rede the: &thorn;at &thorn;ou for&yogh;ete not &thorn;is nome
Ihesu, bot thenk hit in &thorn;i hert nyght
and day, as &thorn;i special and as &thorn;i dere
tresour.  Luf hit more &thorn;an &thorn;i lif, rote
it in &thorn;i mynde.  Luf Ihesu, for he made
&thorn;e, and boght &thorn;e ful dere.  &YOGH;ef &thorn;i hert
to hym: for it is his dette.  &THORN;erfore set
&thorn;i luf on his nome Ihesu, &thorn;at is hele. //
&THORN;ere may non euel thing haue duelling
in &thorn;at hert(e) &thorn;er Ihesu is trewly holden
in mynde: for it chaceth deuelles, it
destruyeth temptacions, it putteth awey
wicked dredes and vices, and clenseth
&thorn;e thoght.  Who so loueth hit verraily,
is ful of goddes grace and vertues, in
gostli comfort in &thorn;is lif, and when &thorn;ai


<PB N="71">

die, &thorn;ai are taken vp in to &thorn;e ordre
of aungels, to se him in endles ioye
&thorn;at &thorn;ai haue lufed.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Deo gracias.</FOREIGN>
</P></DIV3>
</DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="[83]"><HEAD>Meditations on the Passion</HEAD>

<DIV3 N="Cambridge Ll. I.8" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD TYPE="sub">[Text I: shorter version] Ms. Cambr. Ll I. 8</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="201" UNIT="folio ">
<P>SWete lord Ihesu Cryst, I thanke &thorn;e and &yogh;elde &thorn;e graces of &thorn;at swete prayere
and of &thorn;at holy orysoun &thorn;at &thorn;ou madest beforn &thorn;e holy passyoun for vs on &thorn;e
mownt of Olyuete.  Y beseche &thorn;e, swete lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ou here my prayere.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adoramus te Christe &amp; benedicimus tibi.  Pater noster.  Aue maria.</FOREIGN>  &para; Swete lord Ihesu Cryst, y thanke &thorn;e and I &yogh;elde &thorn;e graces of &thorn;at mychel ferdenesse &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddyst for vs whan &thorn;ou become so ful of angwysch &thorn;at an aungel of heuene cam to confortyn &thorn;e, wenne &thorn;ou swattest blod for angwysche.  I preye &thorn;e, lord, and byseche &thorn;e for &thorn;i swete mercy, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be myn help in al myn angwysch and my fondynges, and send me, lord, &thorn;e aungel of red and of confort in alle my
nedys: &thorn;at I my&yogh;te turne thorow &thorn;at swet owt of al sekenesse of soule in to lyf
of hele of body(!).  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adoramus &amp; c. &para; Pater. Aue.</FOREIGN> &para; Swete Ihesu, I thanke &thorn;e and I
&yogh;elde &thorn;e graces of pynes and angwysches and schames and felonyes &thorn;at men
dyden &thorn;e al with tresoun: men bowndyn &thorn;e os a thef, with-owten mercy and
pyte.  &para; Lord, I thanke &thorn;e of &thorn;o swete and pytows pasys &thorn;at &thorn;ow &yogh;ede for owre loue toward &thorn;in owne peyne and &thorn;in owne deth.  I prey &thorn;e, lord, and byseke &thorn;e
&thorn;at &thorn;ou vnbynde vs of bondys of alle owre synnys, os &thorn;ou suffred to be bownde
for owre loue.  &para; Adoramus.  &para; Pater. Aue.  &para; I thanke &thorn;e, swete lord Ihesu
Cryst, of &thorn;e pynus and of &thorn;e schamus &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffryd before &thorn;e byschopus and
maystres of &thorn;e lawe, and of &thorn;ine enemys of buffetys and of neckedyntes, and
of many o&thorn;er schamus &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffred.  &para; And among o&thorn;ere I thanke &thorn;e, lord,
of &thorn;at lokynge &thorn;at &thorn;ou lokyd to &thorn;i decyple &thorn;at &thorn;e hadde forsakyn, seynt Petyr:
&thorn;ou lokyd to hym with sy&yogh;t of mercy when &thorn;ou were in &thorn;i most angwysch and
in &thorn;i most peyne; opynly &thorn;ou schewyd &thorn;ere &thorn;e loue and &thorn;e charyte &thorn;at &thorn;ou hadde
to vs, &thorn;at schame no peyne ne no thyng may drawe &thorn;in herte fro vs, in also
mykel os in &thorn;e is.  &para; Swete lord ful of mercy and of pyte, &thorn;ere we thorow &thorn;i
blessyd lokyng may turne to &thorn;i grace and repent vs of owre trespas and of owre
mysdede, so &thorn;at we may come with seynt Petyr to &thorn;i mercy.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adoramus. &para; Pater.  &para; Aue.</FOREIGN>  &para; I thanke &thorn;e, swete lord Ihesu Cryst, of alle peynes and tormentys /


<PB N="84">

and scornynges and sclawndrynges &amp; schamys &thorn;at men dyde &amp; seyde to &thorn;e &thorn;at
ny&yogh;t in &thorn;at harde prisoun &thorn;at &thorn;ei helde &thorn;e Inne.  Lord, I pray &thorn;e and beseke
&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;eue me sofferynge and strenkethe for to with-stande stedefastely
a&yogh;eynes alle &thorn;e assaylynges &amp; fondynges of my foos and of myn enemys gostely
and bodyly.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adoramus.  &para; Pater.  &para; Aue.</FOREIGN>  &para; Lord Ihesu Cryst, I thanke &thorn;e of alle
&thorn;e peynes and schamus &thorn;at &thorn;ou soffred beforn Pylate, and of alle &thorn;i pases and &thorn;i
steppys &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;edyst for me in al &thorn;at sorewe, now hyderward now &thorn;iderward,
now byfore on and now byfore ano&thorn;er.  I thanke &amp; beseche &thorn;e, lord, for alle &thorn;eise
peynes and &thorn;ese schamus and &thorn;eise greuawnces &amp; &thorn;e pases &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;ede &thorn;enne in &thorn;at ilke tyme for &thorn;e loue of vs, &thorn;at &thorn;ou drawe and ry&yogh;te owre gatys and
owre steppys to &thorn;e-ward &amp; to &thorn;i seruyce.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adoramus.  &para; Pater.  &para; Aue.</FOREIGN>  &para; Swete lord Ihesu Cryst, I thanke &thorn;e of peynes &thorn;at &thorn;ou soffred for vs, and for &thorn;e swete blod &thorn;at &thorn;ou bledde for vs, whan &thorn;ou were so sore betyn and bownden to &thorn;e
pyler, &thorn;at &yogh;yt it is sene &thorn;e blood on &thorn;e pyler.  I prey &thorn;e and byseke &thorn;e as my
dere lord, &thorn;at swete blood &thorn;at &thorn;ou bledde so largely for me, may be ful remyssyoun
for my soule.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adoramus.  &para; Pater.  &para; Aue.</FOREIGN>  &para; Swete lord Ihesu Cryst, I thanke &thorn;e of &thorn;e peynes and schamys &thorn;at &thorn;ou thorow &thorn;i swete wylle soffred for vs whan
&thorn;ou were clad in purpre for to schame &thorn;e, and &thorn;e corowne with thornys for to
pyne with &thorn;i swete hed, and &thorn;ei on knelyng on skorn callyd &thorn;e, lord, kyng
and mayster, and with al &thorn;at on &thorn;i swete face spytted so fouly, and so fouly
engleymede &thorn;i fayre face with &thorn;e foule styngynge spyttynge of &thorn;e foule cursyd
Iues, &amp; bofetede &amp; smyten and betyn on &thorn;i swete hed with Inne(!); and of &thorn;i
byttere woundes I thanke &thorn;e, of &thorn;i peynes and of &thorn;i swete blood &thorn;at ran doun
&amp; stremyd fro &thorn;i blessyd face.  I praye and byseche &thorn;e, dere lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
defende vs fro synne, and fro schame &thorn;at we han deseruyd for synne.  &para; Adoramus.
&para; Pater.  &para; Aue.  &para; Swete lord Ihesu Cryst, I thank &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou were so by-bled &thorn;anne, so crownyd with thornys before alle &thorn;e folc, and &thorn;i swete face so spytted &amp; so beclemyd with &thorn;e fowle &amp; &thorn;e styngynge spyttynge of here corsede mouthes. &THORN;an were &thorn;ou on eche a syde forcryed and hyed to stronge deth, and to foule deth
of hangynge demyd, blessyd and thankyd be &thorn;ou.  I beseche &thorn;e, dere lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
for &thorn;i mychel mercy gyue me grace and wysdom my-self for to Iugge and deme,
to sauacion of my soule.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adoramus.  Pater.  &para; Aue.</FOREIGN>  &para; Swete lord Ihesu Cryst, I thanke &thorn;e of peynes and of schamus &thorn;at &thorn;ou soffrede so swetely &amp; so gladly, now for to drawe &thorn;e, now for to putte &thorn;e so schamely, now for to smyte &thorn;e, now for to bete &thorn;e so sore &amp; so felly; and for to bere &thorn;ine owne rode on &thorn;i swete nakede bac, as it were a thef &thorn;at bare hys owne galewys for to be hangyd onne hym-selue at &thorn;e mownt of Caluarye, &thorn;ere men hedyd wyckede men and theuys whe&thorn;ur he were &thorn;ef or mansleere: and &thorn;ere &thorn;ou soffryd hem to do &thorn;e on &thorn;e cros.  &para; Dere lord Ihesu mercy, &thorn;at welle art of mercy, why wyl not myn herte breste and cleue
in-two?  whou schal it euere laste, whan it rennyth in myn herte at &thorn;i
kyrtel-chaungynge whou woo &thorn;ou were begon: whan &thorn;e fals Herode let tak it of &thorn;e,
&thorn;at clemyd faste with &thorn;e blood of &thorn;at harde scowrgynge to &thorn;e flesch of &thorn;i body
&thorn;at sore was betyn and rowyd, and rent &thorn;i sely skyn; &thorn;e kyrtel clemyd &thorn;ere-to,
and dryed was &thorn;ere-to; &thorn;i flesch was so tendur, so seek and so soor, &thorn;at &thorn;ei
drow it of &thorn;i body pytously and harde, ne hadde &thorn;ei no reward whow soore &thorn;e


<PB N="85">

bystood &thorn;e stryppynge: for &thorn;ere-with folewyd somme of &thorn;e pecys of bledderys
and of &thorn;e rent skyn.  &THORN;an was &thorn;i seke body, precyous lord, al reufully rowed
and bled, &thorn;e stem stood of &thorn;i body &amp; rekyd al-abowte, &thorn;e dew-dropys &thorn;at &thorn;anne
roos &thorn;ere-with it is to thenke.  &para; A, lord, I [se] &thorn;i rede blod renne be &thorn;i chekys,
stremys after yche a strook, byforn &amp; behynde.  &THORN;e skyn of &thorn;in hed &thorn;i
crowne hath al to-rente, eche a thorn &thorn;at &thorn;ere is sytteth to &thorn;i brayn-panne.
Alas &thorn;at I schal lyue and se my gracyous lord so soffrenge and so meke, &thorn;at
neuere trespasyd, so schamely bedy&yogh;t!  &thorn;e grucchynge &amp; &thorn;e gronynge, &thorn;e sorwe &amp; &thorn;e syschynge, &thorn;e rewthe of hys chere, I wolde were my deth.  &THORN;e crowne of al
blysse, &thorn;at crownes alle blessede, &amp; kyng is of alle kynges, &amp; lord is of lordys,
is of helle-houndys crowned with thornys; &thorn;e worchype of heuene despyced and
defouled; he &thorn;at schop &thorn;e sonne &amp; al &thorn;at is ou&yogh;t, of al &thorn;e gode in er&thorn;e &thorn;at
al is of hys gyfte, he hadde not were-Inne hys heed he my&yogh;te hyde, but is so
porely become, vs to make ryche, &thorn;at al nakyd he goth, in sy&yogh;t of alle &thorn;e folk.
&para; A, lord, &thorn;i sorwe, why were it not my deth?  now &thorn;ei lede &thorn;e forthe, nakyd
os a worm, &thorn;e turmentoures abowtyn &thorn;e, &amp; armede kny&yogh;tes.  &THORN;e prees of &thorn;e
peple was wonderly strong; &thorn;ei hurled &thorn;e and haryed &thorn;e so schamefully, &thorn;ei
spurned &thorn;e with here feet os &thorn;ou hadde ben a dogge.  I se in my soule how
reufully &thorn;ou gost, &thorn;i body is so blody, so rowed and so bledderyd, &thorn;i crowne is
so kene &thorn;at sytteth on &thorn;i hed; &thorn;i heere meuyth with &thorn;e wynde clemyd with &thorn;e
blood; &thorn;i louely face so wan &amp; so bolnyd with bofetynge and with betynge,
with spyttynge with spowtynge, &thorn;e blood ran &thorn;ere-with, &thorn;at grysyth in my sy&yogh;t;
so lothly and so wlatsome &thorn;e Iues han &thorn;e mad, &thorn;at a mysel art &thorn;ou lyckere &thorn;an
a clene man.  &THORN;e cros is so heuy, so hye, and so stark, &thorn;at &thorn;ei hangyd on &thorn;i
bare bac, trossyd so harde.  &para; A, lord, &thorn;e gronyng &thorn;at &thorn;ou made, so sore and so
harde it sat to &thorn;e bon.  &THORN;i body is so seek, so febyl and so wery, what with gret
fastynge before &thorn;at &thorn;ou were take, and al ny&yogh;t wooke with-owten ony reste; with
betynge with bofetynge so fer ouur-take, &thorn;at al stowpynge &thorn;ou gost, &amp; grym
is &thorn;i chere. &thorn;e flesch &thorn;ere &thorn;e cros sytteth is al rowed, &thorn;e bleynes and &thorn;e bledderys are wanne and bloo; &thorn;e peyne of &thorn;at byrden sytteth &thorn;e so sore, &thorn;at iche foot
&thorn;at &thorn;ou gost it styngyth to &thorn;in herte.  &THORN;us in &thorn;is gronynge and in &thorn;is mychel
pyne, &thorn;ou gost owt of Ierusale&yogh; toward &thorn;i deth.  &THORN;e cyte is so noble, &thorn;e pupyl
is so mychel, &thorn;e folk comyth rennynge owt of iche a strete, &thorn;anne stondyth
vp &thorn;e folk, and &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="203" UNIT="folio">grete reke, &thorn;at wonder men may &thorn;at
&thorn;ere-onne thynke.  With swyche a processyoun of worldely wondrynge, was neuere no
thef to &thorn;e deth lad.  Somme &thorn;ere were of &thorn;e comown peple &thorn;at sysched sore and
grette for &thorn;i wo, &thorn;at wysten &thorn;e so turmentyd and &thorn;at it was for envye, for &thorn;e
princes and &thorn;e byschopys &thorn;at ladden &thorn;e lawe, &thorn;ei dyden &thorn;e to &thorn;e deth for &thorn;i soth
sawes, whan &thorn;ou of here erroures wolde hem repreue.  &THORN;ei knewe it was owtrage
and wrong &thorn;at &thorn;ou soffrede, and folwyd &thorn;e wepyng and syschyng sore.  &THORN;ou &thorn;an
seyde thyng &thorn;at after fel: &thorn;ou bad hem wepe for hem-selue, and for &thorn;e grete
vengeaunce &thorn;at scholde falle for &thorn;i deth on hem and vp-on here chyldren, and
vpon al &thorn;e cyte, &thorn;at sythen was fordon &amp; for &thorn;e vengeaunce of here owne gylt
chasyd owt of here place.  &para; A, lord, &thorn;e sorewe &thorn;at fel to &thorn;i herte, whan &thorn;ou
on &thorn;i modur caste &thorn;ine eyen.  &THORN;ou saw hyre folewe after among &thorn;e gret prees,


<PB N="86">

os a womman owt of hyre-selue hyre handys sche wrong, wepynge and syschynge
hyre armys he caste, &thorn;e watur of hyre eyen dropped at hyre feet; he fel in
dede swowne ofter &thorn;an onys, for sorewe of &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at to hyre herte smyten.
&THORN;e sorewe &thorn;at he made and &thorn;e mykel dool agreggyd many-fold alle &thorn;in o&thorn;ere
peynes.  So whan heo wyste &thorn;at it so was, &thorn;an was hyre wel wers, and &thorn;ou
also for hyre wepyst; so was &yogh;oure sorewe eyther for o&thorn;er waxenge manyfold with
hepynge sorewys.  &THORN;e loue of &yogh;owre hertys &thorn;at ouer alle o&thorn;ere loues was
wyth-owte make brennyng kene, made &yogh;ow to brenne eyther for o&thorn;er with vnlyke sorewe
to ony o&thorn;er woo; as &thorn;e loue was makeles, so &thorn;e sorewe was perelees, it stykyd
at &yogh;owre hertys os it were deth.  &para; A, lady, mercy, why were &thorn;ou so bolde
among so manye kene foos to folewe so ny? how was it &thorn;at arwenesse of
wommankynde or maydenhed schamynge ne hadde &thorn;e with-drawyn? for it was not
semely to &thorn;e to folewe swych a rowte, so vyle and so schamefully, so grysly to
see!  But &thorn;ou ne hadde no reward to no mannys drede, ne to nou&yogh;t ellys &thorn;at &thorn;e
schulde lette, but as owt of &thorn;i-self for dool and for sorewe of &thorn;i sonys passyoun
was al &thorn;in herte set.  &YOGH;owre loue was so kene eythyr to other, and so brennynge
hot, &thorn;i syschengys were so fer fet, &thorn;e dool of &yogh;owre chere was dedly woo.  &THORN;e
loue and &thorn;e sorewe &thorn;at styked in &thorn;i breest, refte &thorn;e &thorn;e reckyng of bodyly drede
and of worldes schame and alle maner of lettynges, &thorn;at os owt of &thorn;i-selue &thorn;i
sorwe hath &thorn;e mad.  &para; A, lady, for &thorn;at sorewe &thorn;at &thorn;ou soffryd of &thorn;i sonys
passyoun&mdash;for &thorn;at schulde haue bien myn owne, for I it hadde deseruyd and
manye werse, I was cause &thorn;ere-offe and he gylteles: os &thorn;e dere woundes were
myn owne ry&yogh;t, gete me for &thorn;i mercy on of hem alle, a prikke at myn herte of
&thorn;at ilke peyne, a drope of &thorn;at rewthe to folewe hym with.  &YOGH;yf al &thorn;at wo is my
ry&yogh;t, gete me of myn owne, ne be &thorn;ou not so wrongful to with-holde al. / &THORN;ow
al &thorn;i woo be &thorn;e leef, ne art &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t swythe large? parte with &thorn;e poore &thorn;at
lytel hath or non; gyf me of &thorn;i sykynges &thorn;at sykest so sore, &thorn;at I may syke with
&thorn;e, &thorn;at began &thorn;at woo.  I aske not, dere lady, kastelys no towrys ne o&thorn;er
worldys wele, &thorn;e sonne nor &thorn;e mone ne &thorn;e bry&yogh;t sterrys, but woundys of reuthe
is al my desyr, peyne and compassyoun of my lord Ihesu Cryst.  Werste and
vnworthyest of alle mennys haldyng, I haue appetyte to peyne, to beseke my
lorde a drope of hys reed blod to make blody my soule, a drope of &thorn;at watur to
waschyn it with.  &para; A, lady, for &thorn;at mercy, &thorn;at modur art of mercy, socoure of
al sorewe and bote of alle bale, modur mad of wrecchys and of [al] wooful: herken
to &thorn;is wrecche &amp; vysyt [&thorn;]y chyld: soue in myn herte, &thorn;at is hard os ston, a sparcle
of compassyoun of &thorn;at dere passyoun, a wounde of &thorn;at reuthe to souple it with.
&para; A, lord, &thorn;at peyne &thorn;at lyther Iues so cruel &amp; so kene at &thorn;e mownt of Caluarye with-owten ony mercy pynyd &thorn;e with.  &THORN;ei cast &thorn;e cros doun flat on &thorn;e grounde, and with stronge ropys knyt to &thorn;ine handys and to &thorn;i feet, &amp; layde &thorn;e &thorn;ere-onne; &thorn;ei drow and streynyd &thorn;e strey&yogh;te on brede and on lenkthe by handys and by feet, and dryue In &thorn;e nayles, fyrst in &thorn;e ton hand, and drow harde, and after dryue &thorn;at
o&thorn;er.  &THORN;e nayles were blonte at &thorn;e poynt, for &thorn;ei schulde breste &thorn;e skyn &amp; &thorn;e flesch; &thorn;ei grauyd &thorn;ine handys &amp; &thorn;i feet al with &thorn;e blonte nayles, for &thorn;e more peyne. &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Foderunt manus meas &amp; pedes meos.</FOREIGN>  &para; Gloryouse lord so doolfully dy&yogh;te, so rewfully streynyd vp-ry&yogh;t on &thorn;e [rode]: for &thorn;i mykel mekenesse, &thorn;i mercy &thorn;i mi&yogh;t,


<PB N="87">

&thorn;ou bete al my bale with bote of &thorn;i blood.  &para; A, lord, &thorn;e pyte &thorn;at I now se: &thorn;i
woundys in &thorn;i streynynge reche so wyde, &thorn;i lymes and &thorn;i nayles(!) are so tendre.  &THORN;ou
lyst rowyd and reed streyned on &thorn;e cros, &thorn;e kene crowne on &thorn;in hed &thorn;at sytteth
&thorn;e so sore, &thorn;i face is so bolnyd &thorn;at fyrst was so faire; &thorn;i synwes &amp; &thorn;i bonys
styrten owt so starke, &thorn;at &thorn;i bonys may be nowmbryd; &thorn;e stremys of &thorn;i reede
blood rennyn as &thorn;e flood, &thorn;i woundys are for-bled and grysly on to se.  &THORN;e
sorewe &thorn;at &thorn;i modur makyth encresuth &thorn;i woo.  &para; A, lord kyng of my&yogh;t, &thorn;at
leuyn woldust &thorn;i my&yogh;t &amp; os vnmy&yogh;ty become my wrongys to ry&yogh;te: what is it
&thorn;at I speke &amp; bete &thorn;e wynd?  I speke of &thorn;e felyng of &thorn;e &amp; fynde I no taste,
I blondre in my wyrkyng os man &thorn;at is blynd, I studye in my thou&yogh;tes and
&thorn;ei wyrken al wast: it is tokenyng of my deth, and fylthe of my synne, &thorn;at slayn
hath my sowle &amp; stoke is &thorn;ere-Inne, and stoppyth al &thorn;e sauoure, &thorn;at I may nou&yogh;t
the fele, &thorn;at so schamely haue ben &thorn;i tretoure vntrewe; it my&yogh;t be a prisoun,
gloryouse lord, to &thorn;i godhed; &thorn;e stynke of my schame, &thorn;e sorwe of my soule,
&thorn;e fylthe of my mouthe, &yogh;yf I lykke &thorn;ere-onne it fylyth &thorn;i name: so may I no
manere &thorn;e swetnesse of the taste, &thorn;at I haue lost thorow synne to han lykyng of
swyche comfort&mdash;for I blondre gladly in lustys of many dyuerse blamys.  But &thorn;ou
