my ry&yogh;t: grawnte me of &thorn;i grace a sy&yogh;t of &thorn;i sorewe, a poynt of &thorn;i peyne to
playe me with: &thorn;at I may in a poynt som-what fele, and a part of &thorn;i sorewe, &thorn;at
I haue al mad.  &para; A, lord, &thorn;ei cast loot on &thorn;i clo&thorn;es, os &thorn;e boke sayde longe
before: an[d] lefte &thorn;e nakyd by-twene two theuys&mdash;so foule os &thorn;i deth was soffred
neuere man.  &THORN;anne began &thorn;e folc to flocke toward &thorn;e towne fro &thorn;e mownt of
Caluarye, on &thorn;e rode &thorn;ere &thorn;ou hengede.  &THORN;at sy&yogh;t is so wonderful, &thorn;ei wawe so
thykke, eche man to hys owne hom, by eche a way.  &THORN;an was &thorn;ou in &thorn;i godhede
ful smertely at helle, to glade &thorn;e soulys &thorn;at kepten &thorn;i comynge.  &THORN;e blysse and
&thorn;e gladynge, &thorn;e myrthe and &thorn;e lykynge, &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;anne hadde, with tonge no
man may telle.  &THORN;ou openyd helle-&yogh;atys, lord thorou &thorn;i my&yogh;t, and took owt of
peyne manye &thorn;at were &thorn;ere: Adam and Eue, and alle &thorn;at &thorn;e were leue, &thorn;at had
in here lyues kept &thorn;i lawys.  Lord, aftur &thorn;at Ioseph ab Aramathye tok leue at
Pylate to take &thorn;e doun, os it were tyme of euynsonge, with help of Nychodemus,
of &thorn;i modur and of Iohan, &thorn;at stood &thorn;ere sorewfully.  &THORN;ei toke of &thorn;e rode &thorn;i
blessyd body, &thorn;ei ry&yogh;ttyd owt &thorn;ine armys &thorn;at were bycome starke, and strekyd
hem doun after &thorn;i sydes.  &THORN;ei bare to &thorn;e place &thorn;at &thorn;ou were beryed Inne;
&thorn;ei weschen of &thorn;e cold blod and made &thorn;e clene, layde &thorn;e in &thorn;e monument &thorn;at
was newe, &thorn;at Ioseph hadde ordeynyd for hym-selue; &thorn;ei onoynte &thorn;e with
oynement &thorn;at smellyd swete.  &THORN;e sorwe &thorn;at &thorn;i modur hadde, is sorwe to here.
&para; Lady, &thorn;e terys &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;ere grette, &thorn;i brest and &thorn;i chekys mad al watur!
&thorn;ou fel doun to hys feet, and kyssed hem ful swete, and ouere os &thorn;ou kyssyd
sore &thorn;ou grete.  &para; &THORN;enne was &thorn;ere warde set of armede kny&yogh;tes, to kepe &thorn;e
monument tyl &thorn;e thrydde day.  &amp;c.  Amen.  Ihesu.
</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">&para; Explicit quedam Meditacio Ricardi Heremite de Hampolo de passione domini:
Qui obiit anno domini M.CCC<HI REND="sup">o</HI> xl<HI REND="sup">o</HI> VIII<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. &amp;c.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="Cambridge Add. 3042" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="92"><HEAD>[Text II: longer version] Ms. Cambr. Addit. 3042</HEAD>

<OPENER>Here bigynne&thorn; deuote meditaciouns of &thorn;e passioun of Crist whiche weren compilid of Richard Rolle hermyte of Hampol, &thorn;at diede in &thorn;e &yogh;eere of oure lord M.CCC. &amp; xlIx &yogh;eer.</OPENER>

<P>LOrd &thorn;at madist me of nou&yogh;t, I biseche &thorn;ee to &yogh;eue me grace to serue &thorn;e
wi&thorn; al myn herte, wi&thorn; al my my&yogh;t, wi&; al my strenk&thorn;e, wi&thorn; al my kunnynge,
wi&thorn; al myn entencioun, wi&thorn; al myn vndirstondinge, wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e my&yogh;tis of my
soule, wi&thorn; al my &thorn;ou&yogh;t, wi&thorn; al my speche, wi&thorn; alle my wittis, wi&thorn; alle my
werkis, wi&thorn; al myn ocupacioun, wi&thorn; al my bisynes, &amp; wi&thorn; al my reste.
</P>
<P>LOrd &thorn;at madist me lich to &thorn;ee, I biseche &thorn;ee to &yogh;eue me grace to loue &thorn;ee
wi&thorn; al my soule, wi&thorn; al my loue, wi&thorn; al my wil, wi&thorn; al my lust, wi&thorn; al my
likinge, wi&thorn; al my mynde, wi&thorn; al my wische, wi&thorn; al my deuocioun, wi&thorn; al my
longinge, wi&thorn; amendinge of my liif wi&thorn; al my disirynge, wi&thorn; lastinge in goodnes,
wi&thorn; contricioun &amp; confessioun to &thorn;ee &amp; penaunce for my synnes.
</P>
<P>LOrd &thorn;at madist me &amp; alle my lymes, I biseche &thorn;ee, &yogh;eue me grace to serue
&thorn;ee wi&thorn; alle my lymes, &amp; alle to be ocupied in &thorn;i seruice, &amp; euere bowinge to
&thorn;i biddingis, euere redi to meue or to reste at &thorn;i wille, euere lame to dedis of
synne, &amp; euere freisch &amp; redi to &thorn;i biddingis.
</P>
<P>LOrd &thorn;at madist me &amp; hast &yogh;ouen me manye &yogh;iftis, gostly, bodili and wordili,
I biseche &thorn;ee, graunte me grace to vsen hem alle in &thorn;i seruice &amp; to &thorn;at eende
to whiche &thorn;ou &yogh;aue hem to me, &thorn;at I euere worschipe &thorn;ee in &thorn;i &yogh;iftis; &amp; graunte me grace euere to meken me in &thorn;i &yogh;iftis, to holde me apaied wi&thorn; &thorn;i
&yogh;iftis, &amp; neuere to be presumptuous ne proud of &thorn;i &yogh;iftis, but euere to knouleche
me for sich as I am, a sinful wrecche.
</P>
<P>LOrd &thorn;at ali&yogh;tist fro heuene to er&thorn;e for loue of mankynde, from so hi&yogh; to
so low, / from so hi&yogh; lordschip to so low pouert, / from so hi&yogh; noblei to so
lowe myscheef, / from so hi&yogh; wele to so low&yogh; wo, / from so hi&yogh; blis to so low&yogh;
peyne, / from so hi&yogh; myr&thorn;e to so low&yogh; sorewe, / from so likinge a liif to so
peyneful a dee&thorn;: / Now, lord, for al &thorn;at loue &thorn;at &thorn;ou schewidist to mankinde
in &thorn;in incarnacion &amp; in &thorn;i passioun, I biseche &thorn;ee of merci and help. /
</P>
<P>Swete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;ee, lord, wi&thorn; al myn herte, for &thorn;ou profredist &thorn;ee to &thorn;at
place where &thorn;ou wistist &thorn;i dee&thorn; ordeyned, &amp; I &thorn;anke &thorn;e, lord, for &thorn;ere &thorn;ou
schewedist weel &thorn;at &thorn;ou were willi to die for vs; &amp; so I bileeue, lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
chees &thorn;e day &amp; &thorn;e tyme whanne &thorn;ou woldist die, &amp; euery poynt of &thorn;i passioun
was doon at &thorn;in ordinaunce; &amp; I bileeue, lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ou leftist &thorn;i soule whanne
&thorn;ou woldist, &amp; whanne &thorn;ou woldist &thorn;ou took it a&yogh;en.  Now here, swete Ihesu,
I biseche &thorn;ee, graunte me grace to profre me to &thorn;ee wi&thorn; hool wil, in sorewe
of herte for my synnes, &amp; criynge merci in wil to amende me, in schrift to
&thorn;ee &amp; penaunce for my synnes, in contynuauance of good lyuynge, in hool loue
to &thorn;ee &thorn;at madist me: &amp; graunte me to turne to &thorn;ee bi often schrifte, in ech
tribulacioun, in ech temptacioun of man, fleisch, world, or enemy: &amp; graunte
me grace &thorn;at ech &thorn;ou&yogh;t of me, word, or werk, schewe &thorn;at I am turned to &thorn;ee:


<PB N="93">

&amp; &yogh;eue me grace fayn to turne to &thorn;e dedis wi&thorn; ful wil &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ordeyned
for me. / Swete lord, I biseche &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou heere my preier.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster Et ne nos / set libera nos a malo.  Adoramus te Christe &amp; benedilimus tibi, Quia per sanctam crucem tuam re[de]misti mundum. / Oremus:</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P><Q><FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> DOmine Ihesu Christe fili dei uiui, pone passionem, crucem &amp; mortem tuam inter iudicium tuum et animas nostras nunc &amp; in hora mortis nostre: &amp; largire digneris uiuis misericordiam et gratiam, defunctis ueniam &amp; requiem, ecclesieque regnis pacem et misericordiam, &amp; nobis peccatoribus uitam, leticiam, et gloriam sempiternam: Qui uiuis et regnas deus, Per omnia secula seculorum.  Amen.</FOREIGN></Q>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;ee wi&thorn; al myn herte &amp; kunnynge of &thorn;at swete preier
&amp; of &thorn;at holy orisoun &thorn;at &thorn;ou madist bifore &thorn;i passioun so holi upon &thorn;e mount
of olyuete, / &amp; lord, I &thorn;anke &thorn;ee, for &thorn;ere &thorn;ou tau&yogh;tist us to preie, whanne &thorn;ou seidist: / &laquo;fadir, not myn, but &thorn;i wille be fulfild&raquo;&mdash; / for &thorn;i wil!, lord Ihesu, &amp; &thorn;i fadris wil, ben al oo will. / &THORN;anne &thorn;ou preiedist not for &thorn;ee, but for us / to teche us, &thorn;at han often contrarious willis to &thorn;e fadir of heuene, for to leue
oure wil, &amp; to preie &thorn;at &thorn;e fadris wil in us be fulfild. / Now here, swete Ihesu,
I biseche &thorn;e &thorn;at I be euere redi at &thorn;i wille, &amp; not at myn, but whanne my
wille acordi&thorn; to &thorn;in &thorn;at is my ioie; and graunte me grace euere to seche what
is &thorn;i wille, &amp; so to turne to &thorn;ee.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Et ne nos.  Adoramus te. Domine.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete lord Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;ee as I can of al &thorn;e drede &amp; anguisch &thorn;at &thorn;ou
suffridist for us whanne an aungil of heuene come to counforte &thorn;ee, &amp; whanne
&thorn;ou swettist blood for anguisch. / Here, swete Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee for &thorn;i swete
merci, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be myn help &amp; counfort in al my temtacioun, anguisch, or
tribulacioun; &thorn;at I mowe turne &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;i swete counfort out of al myscheef of
soule &amp; of bodi / in to hel&thorn;e of vertu &amp; of meeknes.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;e for &thorn;e disese &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddist whanne Iudas
bitraide &thorn;ee: &amp; &thorn;ou toldist it him biforen &amp; warnedist him faire, &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;at was oon of &thorn;e grettist synnes &thorn;at euere was. / Now, lord Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee, scheelde me fro grete synnes, as ouerhope, wanhope, &amp; alle maner synnes a&yogh;ens
kynde, &amp; &yogh;eue me grace to &thorn;enke ech synne greet &thorn;at in ony maner wise my&yogh;te
greue &thorn;e, Ihesu.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;e for al &thorn;e disesis &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffridist whanne &thorn;ou
were taken of &thorn;e iewis: / for summe pulliden &thorn;ee, summe schouen &thorn;ee, drowen
&thorn;ee, dispisiden &thorn;ee, scorneden &thorn;ee, toggiden &amp; teere &thorn;ee: &amp; swete Ihesu, I
&thorn;anke &thorn;ee for al &thorn;at mekenes &thorn;at &thorn;ou schewedist &thorn;ere, whanne &thorn;ou letist hem
doon as &thorn;ei wolden. / Now, swete Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee to take me to &thorn;e &amp; make me al &thorn;in: &amp; if I fle to ony synne of &thorn;e world, of &thorn;e fleisch or of &thorn;e
feend, swete Ihesu fecche me soone hoom a&yogh;en, as a lord doo&thorn; his
bondeman, &amp; dryue me wi&thorn; tribulacioun soone to penaunce. / Swete Ihesu, in &thorn;ee is
al souereyn medicyn, &amp; I, lord, am al siik in synnes: &THORN;erfore, swete Ihesu, take
me to &thorn;ee &amp; sette me vndir &thorn;i cure, &amp; come neer to me wi&thorn; grace, as &thorn;e


<PB N="94">

Samaritan dide, &amp; hilde in to my woundis oile of merci and wyn of counfort,
and brynge me in to &thorn;e stable of charite, &amp; euere holde me vndir &thorn;i
cure. /&yogh;it, lord swete Ihesu, &thorn;is liff is ful of temptaciouns and enemyes, &amp; &thorn;ere is no socour but in &thorn;ee, swete Ihesu: &thorn;anne, swete Ihesu, take me to &thorn;ee wi&thorn;-ynne
&thorn;i gouernaunce and schildinge, &amp; lat neuere &thorn;in hondwerk be for-loren. /&para; &yogh;it, swete Ihesu, &thorn;ou art al good, &amp; to &thorn;ee longi&thorn; al loue: / &THORN;anne take to &thorn;ee myn herte hoolli, &thorn;at al my loue be on &thorn;ee &thorn;at al bou&yogh;tist; so &thorn;at myn herte
neuere turne fro &thorn;e for no temptacioun, but euere cleue fast upon &thorn;ee, for to loue
&thorn;ee swete Ihesu, moost needful, moost meedful, &amp; moost spedeful.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster. Et ne nos.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &yogh;elde to &thorn;ee &thorn;ankingis &amp; gracis for &thorn;at tresoun &amp; schames
&thorn;at &thorn;ou haddist whanne &thorn;ei bonden &thorn;ee to a &thorn;eef.  &para; Now, swete Ihesu, I
biseche &thorn;ee, bynde me to &thorn;e, so &thorn;at neuer temptacioun ne tribulacioun parte
us a-sundir; / binde me to &thorn;ee, swete Ihesu, in bileeue, hope, &amp; harite. / In
bileeue fastne me to &thorn;ee, swete Ihesu, &thorn;at neuere noon errour ne eresie turne
me fro my bileeue; &amp; graunte me swete Ihesu, &thorn;at my bileeue be in mesure,
not to large: bileeuynge &thorn;at schulde not be bileeued; / ne to streite: leuynge
&thorn;at schulde be bileeued; / &, swete Ihesu, make me bileeue in alle &thorn;e
sacramentis of holi chirche &amp; in alle &thorn;e ordinauncis, &amp; in trist to god of al my
sauacioun.  &para; Swete Ihesu, binde me to &thorn;ee in hope: so &thorn;at al myn hope &amp; trist be oonli in &thorn;ee; / late neuere myn hope be to streite: lest I falle in
wanhope; / ne to large: lest I rise in to ouerhope; / and graunte me grace,
swete Ihesu, to continue in good werkis in &thorn;i seruice wi&thorn; discresioun, &thorn;at I
mai skilfulli hope &amp; triste in &thorn;ee. / &para; Swete Ihesu, binde me to &thorn;e in
charite: &thorn;at al my loue be hole to &thorn;ee, in wil, word, &amp; werk, &amp; lete me no
&thorn;ing loue but &thorn;e, or for &thorn;ee; &amp; lete me loue after &thorn;in heeste frend &amp; foo; &amp; graunte me grace &thorn;at noon vnskilful wra&thorn;&thorn;e, ne hate, ne enuie, breke &thorn;e bond
of my charite; &amp; graunte me, lord, to loue &thorn;ee euere lengir &thorn;e betere, &thorn;e more
kunnyngli, &thorn;e more bisili, &thorn;e more stidfastli, &amp; graunte me to loue &thorn;at &thorn;ou
louest, &amp; hate &thorn;at &thorn;ou hatist.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &yogh;eelde to &thorn;e &thorn;ankingis &amp; gracis for alle &thorn;e steppis &amp; pacis
&thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;edist toward &thorn;in owne peyne &amp; &thorn;in owne dee&thorn;.  I biseche &thorn;ee, swete Ihesu, &thorn;at &thorn;ou rule alle my goinges, and alle &thorn;e affecciouns of myn herte.
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;ee for alle &thorn;e schames, anguischis, &amp; felonyes, &thorn;at
&thorn;ou suffridist biforen Annas &amp; Caifas, Pilat &amp; Eroud, / &amp; nameli I &thorn;anke &thorn;ee, swete Ihesu, for &thorn;at merciful lokinge, &thorn;at &thorn;ou turnynge a&yogh;en biheld upon seint
Petir &thorn;i disciple &thorn;at forsook &thorn;ee / &amp; &yogh;it in myche anguische &thorn;ou schewedist
&thorn;i loue openli to him, so &thorn;at nei&thorn;er schame ne peine my[&yogh;t] drawe &thorn;in herte fro
him. / Now, swete Ihesu, turne &thorn;in i&yogh;e of merci toward us synful, so &thorn;at &thorn;oru
&thorn;i merci and grace we moun repente of oure trespas &amp; mys-dedis with seint Petir.
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;e for &thorn;at meke &amp; stille stondinge aforen Pilat &amp; alle
&thorn;e false accusaciouns of &thorn;e iewis. / Now here, swete Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee,


<PB N="95">

graunte me grace fei&thorn;fully to haue mynde in ech temptacioun &thorn;at I stonde
bifore &thorn;ee my domisman; &amp; graunte me grace to suffre pacientli accusaciouns,
snybbingis &amp; yuel wordis of foos for &thorn;i loue; / &amp; graunte me to knouleche ech
man for betere &thorn;an me, &amp; to meke me euere &amp; holde me lowe; / &amp; swete Ihesu,
whanne I schal be demed, haue merci on me / &amp; lete &thorn;i meeknes &amp; &thorn;at doom
&thorn;at &thorn;ou vnskilfulli suffridist, excuse me fro &thorn;at doom &thorn;at I skilfulli schulde haue.
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Et ne nos.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &yogh;elde &thorn;ee &thorn;ankingis for al &thorn;at schame &amp; anguisch &thorn;at &thorn;ou
suffridist whanne &thorn;ei spitten in &thorn;i face, / in &thorn;at swete myrrour &amp; bodili blis of
heuene, upon which aungels &amp; seintis haue deinte to loke. / Now, swete Ihesu,
&yogh;eue me grace to haue most deinte inwardli to loke &amp; &thorn;enke upon &thorn;at blissid
face; / and, swete Ihesu, restore &thorn;e liknes of &thorn;i face in my soule &thorn;at foule
synnes han fadid; / &, leue lord, lete me neuere haue likinge in &thorn;e face of
synne in temptacioun, &amp; graunte me grace neuere to assente to lust of synne; &amp; &yogh;eue me grace to worschipe &thorn;ee in ech creature; &amp; lete me neuere haue pride
of chere of my face, ne lust to synne for semblaunt of ony o&thorn;irs face; and,
swete Ihesu, graunte me to se &thorn;i blisful face in heuene, amen.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster. Et ne nos.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &yogh;elde &thorn;ee &thorn;ankingis as I can of alle yuel wordis, sclaundris,
scornis, mowis, &amp; schames, &thorn;at &thorn;e iewis seiden to &thorn;ee in al &thorn;e time of &thorn;i
precious passioun; &amp; of alle &thorn;e housis and prisouns &thorn;at &thorn;ei heelden &thorn;ee ynne /
whanne &thorn;ou were drawen &amp; haried [now] to Annas and Caifas, now to Eroud &amp; Pilat, &amp; closid wi&thorn;-ynne in her placis. / Now, swete Ihesu, here I biseche &thorn;ee,
graunte me suffringe &amp; strenk&thorn;e to stonde stidfastli &amp; pacientli to suffre wordis
of dispite &amp; rebukinge for &thorn;i loue, &amp; neuere to grucche for tribulacioun ne angir
ne siiknes of &thorn;i sonde; &amp; graunte me, swete Ihesu, stifli to stonde in alle &thorn;e
assailingis &amp; temptaciouns of my foos, goostli and bodili.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster. Aue maria.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;e for alle &thorn;e steppis &amp; pacis &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;edist
hidirward &amp; &thorn;idirward in tyme of &thorn;i passioun.  &amp; I biseche &thorn;ee, graunte me grace in alle my weies &amp; gatis &thorn;at &thorn;ei be ordeyned to &thorn;i worschip &amp; to saluacioun of my soule; / &amp; graunte me grace wilfulli to go to &thorn;i seruice, &amp; spare for no peyne ne penaunce; &amp; make me loth to meue, swete Ihesu, to ony lust a&yogh;ens &thorn;i wille. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Et ne nos.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &yogh;eelde &thorn;ee &thorn;ankingis for &thorn;at dispiteous blindfelling &thorn;at &thorn;e
iewis diden to &thorn;ee.  &amp; here I preie &thorn;ee, swete lord Ihesu, scheelde me fro
blindfelling of synne, in custum, in long vnschrift, in ouerhope in wanhope, in
latinge to myche bi my-silf; &amp; schelde me from perpetuel blindfelling of
dampnacioun, &amp; excludinge fro &thorn;e blisful si&yogh;t of &thorn;i glorious face; &amp; graunte me cleerli to se in to &thorn;e face of my conscience; / &amp; &yogh;eue me grace, swete Ihesu, to
kepe myne i&yogh;en from alle yuele si&yogh;tis &thorn;at eggen to synne; &amp; graunte me to
se &thorn;i blissid presence endelesli.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;e euermore for &thorn;at schame &amp; schenschip &thorn;at &thorn;ou
suffridist in &thorn;i buffetinge: / for manye a soor strook &thorn;ou suffridist &thorn;anne, /


<PB N="96">

for ech of hem stroof to smyte bifore o&thorn;ere. / Now, swete Ihesu, graunte me
here wilfulli to suffre disese &amp; tribulacioun for &thorn;i sake, &amp; neuere to grucche for
siiknessis ne for wrongis of man, but euere to &thorn;anke god of al his sonde; / &amp; graunte me, lord Ihesu, to be p[yn]ede for my synnes or I die, &amp; continuel herte
lord, &thorn;at to preie; / &amp; whanne it come&thorn;, lord, &yogh;eue me pacience, &amp; herte hoolli to &thorn;anke &thorn;ee of &thorn;i sonde.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &yogh;eelde &thorn;ee gracis &amp; &thorn;ankingis for al &thorn;at sore &amp; long &amp; egre peyne &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffridist for us, &amp; for al &thorn;at precious blood &thorn;at &thorn;ou bleddist, whanne &thorn;ou were bounden fast to a piler and scourgid ful sore;&mdash;for &thorn;at was a
bittir peyne: / for &thorn;e scourgers weren chosen men and stalwor&thorn;e, &amp; willi to sle
&thorn;ee, &amp; it was longe or &thorn;ei weren weri; / &amp; &thorn;e scourgis weren mad ful stronge
&amp; smerte: so &thorn;at al &thorn;i bodi was but woundis, &amp; manye woundis in oo wounde /
for &thorn;e knottis smiten so ofte in oo place, &amp; at ech strok smoot deppir.  &amp; &thorn;at was, swete Ihesu, a large &amp; a plenteuous schewinge of &thorn;i loue! / &THORN;anne was &thorn;i bodi lijk to heuene: for as heuene is ful of sterris, so is &thorn;i bodi ful of woundis. / But, lord,
&thorn;i woundis ben betere &thorn;an sterris: for sterris schinen not but bi ny&yogh;tis, &amp; &thorn;i
woundis ben ful of vertu ny&yogh;t &amp; day; / alle &thorn;e sterris bi ny&yogh;te ne li&yogh;ten but a
litil, &amp; o cloude may hide hem alle: / but oon of &thorn;i woundis, swete Ihesu, was
&amp; is Inou&yogh; to do awey cloudis of synne, &amp; to clere &thorn;e conscience of alle sinful
men. / here, swete Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee &thorn;at &thorn;ise woundis be my medicacioun
for ech disese of soule. / Also, swete Ihesu, &thorn;e sterris ben cause in er&thorn;e of ech
&thorn;ing &thorn;at is grene, or growi&thorn;, or beri&thorn; fruy&yogh;t: / now, swete Ihesu, make me
grene in my bileeue, growinge in grace, &amp; beringe fruy&yogh;t of gode werkis. / Also
sterris ben cause of mynes of metals &amp; of precious stonys: / now, swete lord
Ihesu, make me tou&yogh; as metal a&yogh;ens temptaciouns, &amp; precious as perre in to &thorn;e
hi&yogh; degre of charite.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Et ne nos inducas.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>ANd &yogh;it, lord swete Ihesu, &thorn;i bodi is lijk a nett: / for as a nett is ful of
holis, so is &thorn;i bodi ful of woundis. / Here, swete lord Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee,
catche me in &thorn;e nett of &thorn;i scourginge, &thorn;at al myn herte &amp; loue be to &thorn;ee; &amp; drawe me euere to &thorn;ee &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;ee as a net drawi&thorn; fisch, til I come to &thorn;e
bank of dee&thorn;: &thorn;at neuere temptacioun, tribulacioun ne prosperite pulle me fro
&thorn;ee; / and as a net drawi&thorn; fisch to londe, so, swete Ihesu, brynge me to &thorn;i
blis. / Catche me, lord, in &thorn;e net of holi chirche; &amp; kepe me, lord, &thorn;at I
neuere breke out of &thorn;e bondis of charite. / Cacche me, lord swete Ihesu, in &thorn;i
net, &thorn;at neuere synne haue me out of &thorn;e cloce of vertues.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster. Et ne.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>&YOGH;It, swete Ihesu, &thorn;i body is lijk a dufhous: / for as a dufhous is ful of
dowue holis, so is &thorn;i bodi ful of woundis: / &amp; as a dowue pursued of an
hauke, if sche mai a-reche to an hole of hir hous, sche is sikir I-now&yogh;: so,
swete Ihesu, in temptacioun &thorn;i woundis ben best refute.  &para; Now, swete Ihesu,
I biseche &thorn;ee in ech temptacioun graunte me grace of sum hole of &thorn;i woundis,
&amp; likinge to abide in mynde of &thorn;i passioun. / Also, swete Ihesu, &thorn;i bodi is lijk
an hony-comb: for &thorn;at is ech weies ful of cellis, &amp; ech celle ful of hony, so


<PB N="97">

&thorn;at it may not be touchid wi&thorn;outen &yogh;eldinge of swetnes: / so, swete Ihesu, &thorn;i
bodi is ful of cellis of deuocioun, &thorn;at it may not be touchid of a clene soule
wi&thorn;oute swetnes &amp; likinge. / Now, swete Ihesu, graunte me grace to touche &thorn;ee
wi&thorn; criynge merci for my synnes, wi&thorn; desiris to gostly contemplacioun, wi&thorn;
amendinge of my lijf &amp; contynuaunce in goodnes, in stodie to fulfille &thorn;in heestis,
&amp; delicat abidinge in mynde of thi passioun.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Et ne.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>MOre &yogh;it, swete Ihesu, &thorn;i bodi is lijk a book writen wi&thorn; reed enke: so is
&thorn;i bodi al writen wi&thorn; rede woundis. / Now, swete Ihesu, graunte me grace often
to rede upon &thorn;is book, &amp; sumwhat to vndirstonde &thorn;e swetnes of &thorn;at writinge,
&amp; to haue likinge in stodious abidinge of &thorn;at redinge; &amp; &yogh;eue me grace sumwhat
to conseyue of &thorn;at perles loue of Ihesu Crist, &amp; to lerne bi &thorn;at ensaumple to loue
god a&yogh;enward as I schulde; / and, swete Ihesu, graunte me &thorn;at stodie in ech tide
of &thorn;e day, &amp; graunte me grace &thorn;at I may haue upon &thorn;is book matyns, pryme,
houris, euesong &amp; complin, my meditacioun, my speche, &amp; my daliaunce.
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Et ne nos.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, &yogh;it &thorn;i bodi is lijk to a mede ful of swete flouris &amp; holsum
herbis: / so is &thorn;i bodi ful of woundis, swete saueringe to a deuout soule, &amp; holsum as eerbis to ech sinful man. / Now, swete Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee, graunte
me swete sauour of merci, &amp; &thorn;e holsum reseite of grace.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &yogh;eelde &thorn;ee &thorn;ankingis of alle &thorn;e peynes &amp; schames &thorn;at &thorn;ou
suffridist &thorn;oru &thorn;i swete wille for us whanne &thorn;ou were clo&thorn;id in purpur for to
schame &thorn;ee, &amp; [&thorn;ei] crowned &thorn;in heed wi&thorn; &thorn;ornes for to preue &thorn;i swete suffraunce &amp; pacience, / and &thorn;anne &thorn;ei fellen on knees &amp; scorneden &thorn;ee &amp; calliden &thorn;ee lord &amp; maistir, &amp; spitten in &thorn;i face &amp; buffetiden &thorn;ee, &amp; as myche schame as &thorn;ei coude seiden to &thorn;ee. / Here, swete Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee for alle &thorn;e schameful turnes &thorn;at we haue wrou&yogh;t, for&yogh;eue us al &thorn;at schame &amp; peyne &thorn;at we haue discerued bi oure synne; &amp; graunte us grace to worschipe &thorn;ee in as many wise &amp; as hertili, as &thorn;e eiwis schameden &thorn;ee in &thorn;i passioun; / and, swete Ihesu, graunte us grace of sich clo&thorn;inge &amp; aray as moost plesi&thorn; &thorn;ee, &amp; neuere to desire disgisynge ne pride of atire; / and, swete Ihesu, graunte me grace to bere myn heed lowe, &amp; neuere to schewe pride in semblaunt ne chere; / &, swete Ihesu, graunte me
grace to kepe my fyue wittis to &thorn;e worschip of &thorn;ee, &amp; graunte me grace neuere
to desire state ne degre for&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;ou hast ordeyned for me.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster. Et ne nos.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;ee wi&thorn; al myn herte for al &thorn;at blood &thorn;at &thorn;ou so
plenteuousli bleddist in &thorn;i crownynge biforen al &thorn;at folk, whanne &thorn;i swete face
was al blood, / and on ech side &thorn;ou were forcried &amp; dispisid &amp; hastid to &thorn;at
strong and foule dee&thorn;, &amp; deemed so wrongfulli &thorn;erto, / blessid &amp; &thorn;ankid be
&thorn;ou, swete Ihesu &amp; wor&thorn;i to be loued of alle creaturis.  Here, swete Ihesu,
I biseche &thorn;ee, waische my soule wi&thorn; &thorn;at blood, &amp; anoynte &amp; depeynte my
soule &amp; my mynde wi&thorn; &thorn;at precious blood; &amp; graunte me grace for &thorn;i mychel
merci to iuge my-silf wiseli &amp; deme, to saluacioun of my soule.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>
<PB N="98">SWete Ihesu, I &yogh;eelde &thorn;ee &thorn;ankingis for alle &thorn;e peynes and schameful turnes
&thorn;at &thorn;ou suffridist whanne &thorn;ou bere &thorn;in owne cros &amp; iugement upon &thorn;in nakid
bak: / for &thorn;ei drowen &thorn;ee &amp; pulliden &thorn;ee so felli &thorn;at greet ru&thorn;e was to se, /
&amp; &thorn;erto, swete Ihesu, &thorn;ei putten &thorn;ee, smyten &thorn;ee so schamefulli, as it were a
&thorn;eef &thorn;at bare his owne galowis. / A, dere lord swete Ihesu, &thorn;at &thorn;ou were
wobigoon whanne at &thorn;e biddinge of Eroud &thorn;i kirtil was taken from &thorn;ee, &thorn;at
cleuede so faste to &thorn;i bodi wi&thorn; blood of &thorn;ir scourginge whanne &thorn;ou were racid
and rent &amp; beten so sore and so longe til al &thorn;in vtter blood was bled and &thorn;i
skin vnne&thorn;e hangide to-gidere. / &THORN;anne whanne &thorn;ei drowen of &thorn;e cloo&thorn;
&thorn;at cleuede to &thorn;i skyn wi&thorn; drie blood, and &thorn;ou so tendre, and in &yogh;ong and
freisch age: &thorn;[ei] took no reward how sore it greuede &thorn;ee &thorn;at dispiteuous
strepinge, whanne manie a pece of &thorn;i tendre skyn folowide. / &THORN;anne was ru&thorn;e
to se &thorn;i bodi al stremed of blood. / &para; A, lord swete Ihesu, me &thorn;inki&thorn; I se
&thorn;i reed blood renne doun bi &thorn;i chekis, stremynge aftir ech strook of &thorn;i
crownynge, bifore and bihinde and on ech side. / &THORN;e skyn of &thorn;in heed &thorn;ornes
al to-renden, ech &thorn;orn sitti&thorn; to &thorn;e brain-panne. / Alas, swete Ihesu, how may
a cristen soule se his lord suffre so myche peyne, &thorn;at neuere trespasside? / &thorn;i
grintinge &amp; gronynge, &thorn;i sorewinge &amp; si&yogh;ynge, &thorn;e ru&thorn;e of &thorn;i chere persi&thorn; myn herte. / &THORN;e crowne of al blis, &thorn;at crowne&thorn; al blissid, &thorn;e king of alle kingis,
&thorn;e lord of alle lordis, &thorn;e emperour of helle, is now hound crowned wi&thorn; &thorn;ornes,
/ &thorn;e worschip of heuene is dispisid &amp; defoulid; / he &thorn;at schope sunne and alle
creaturis, &amp; al &thorn;ing is of his &yogh;ift, he ha&thorn; nott where he mai hide his heed, /
and he is so pore &thorn;at he goo&thorn; al nakid in &thorn;e si&yogh;t of al folk. / Here, swete
Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee, &yogh;eue me grace to bere wi&thorn; &thorn;ee &thorn;e cros of penaunce for
&thorn;i loue &amp; my synnes, &amp; lete me bere it to my dee&thorn;-tyme as &thorn;ou didist, &amp; lete me neuere be grucchinge for &thorn;at I suffre for &thorn;i loue; and &yogh;eue me grace to do
penaunce in &thorn;is lijf for my synnes, &amp; graunte me my purgatorie here; &amp; &yogh;eue
me grace to suffre esili wordis of dispite for &thorn;i loue.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster. Et ne nos.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &yogh;eelde &thorn;ee &thorn;ankingis for al &thorn;at angir and sorewe &thorn;at &thorn;ou
suffridist whanne &thorn;ou bere &thorn;i cros toward &thorn;i dee&thorn;. / &amp; me &thorn;enki&thorn;, lord, I se
how &thorn;ei leden &thorn;ee for&thorn; nakid as a worm, turmentours aboute &thorn;ee &amp; armed
kny&yogh;tis, &thorn;e prece of &thorn;e peple wondir miche, &thorn;ei harien &thorn;ee schamefulli, &thorn;ei
spurnen &thorn;ee wi&thorn; her feet as &thorn;ou weere a dogge. / A, &thorn;is is a ruful si&yogh;t!  &thorn;in
heed is ful of &thorn;ornis, &thorn;in heer is ful of blood, &thorn;i face is al wan, &thorn;i lokinge is
morninge, &thorn;i cheekis and heed al bolned wi&thorn; buffetis, &thorn;i visage al be-soilid wi&thorn;
spotil: / &thorn;e iewis han so biseie &thorn;ee &thorn;at &thorn;ou art likir a mesel &thorn;an a clene man. /
&THORN;e cros heuy &amp; huge, &amp; so hard trust upon &thorn;i bak, &thorn;at &thorn;ou art cruyschid to hepe &amp; schrinkist &thorn;er-vndir.  &para; A, swete Ihesu, &thorn;ou gronedist ful harde whanne it sat so sore to &thorn;i nakid bodi, &thorn;at is so sijke, so ful frau&yogh;t of peynes, so feble
so weri, what for longe and greet fastinge bifore, what wi&thorn; wakinge al ny&yogh;t
biforen wi&thorn;outen reste, what wi&thorn; betinge &amp; buffetinge and schameful wordis &amp; dedis bifore. / &THORN;e fleisch &thorn;ere &thorn;e cros sittith is skinles &amp; ouer-runne wi&thorn;
blood-rowis. / &THORN;e peyne of &thorn;at bir&thorn;en greue&thorn; &thorn;ee so sore, &thorn;at ech foot &thorn;at &thorn;ou goost


<PB N="99">

stingi&thorn; to &thorn;in herte.  &para; &THORN;us &thorn;ou goost, swete Ihesu, [out of] Ierusalem toward
&thorn;i dee&thorn;, / al &thorn;e peple cometh &amp; folewi&thorn; and gouli&thorn; upon &thorn;ee &amp; wondri&thorn;;
wi&thorn; sich a processioun was neuere &thorn;eef led to his dee&thorn;! / Here, swete Ihesu, I
preie &thorn;ee, graunte me grace to folewe &thorn;e in mynde of &thorn;i passioun, &amp; in
suffringe sumwhat for &thorn;i loue, and in hauinge compassioun of &thorn;ee.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN> /</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, what sorewe fel to &thorn;in herte whanne &thorn;ou castist &thorn;in i&yogh;e
toward &thorn;i modir so dere! / &thorn;ou si&yogh; hir folewe among &thorn;e greet prees as a
womman out of hir-silf.  Now sche wrong hir hondis, wepinge &amp; si&yogh;ynge, / now
sche casti&thorn; hir armes abrood, the watir of hir i&yogh;en droppide at hir feet, / sche
fel in deed swoun ofte-si&thorn;is for peynes and sorowis. / Hir sorewe, swete Ihesu,
and hir dool a-greggide greetli &amp; manyefold alle &thorn;ine o&thorn;ere peynes; / and
whanne sche knewe &thorn;at hir sorewe greuede &thorn;ee so soore, &thorn;anne was sche weel
worse: / and so sorewe of ei&thorn;er of &yogh;ou for o&thorn;ere wexi&thorn; manye-foold; / &thorn;e hi&yogh;
loue of &yogh;oure hertis ei&thorn;ir to o&thorn;ere, &thorn;at was perles brenninge, kindeli made &yogh;oure
sorewe ei&thorn;er for o&thorn;ere vnlike to ony o&thorn;ir sorewe or wo on er&thorn;e, / for as &yogh;oure
loue was makeles, so was &yogh;oure sorewe peerles, / it stiki&thorn; at &yogh;oure hertis as itt
were dee&thorn;.  &para; A, ladi, mercy, how were &thorn;ou so bold among so manye kene
foos to folewe him so ny&yogh;? / how was it &thorn;at &thorn;e arownes of wommans kinde, or
schamynge of maidenheed, ne hadde wi&thorn;drawe &thorn;ee? and it was not semeli to
&thorn;ee to folewe sich a route! / But &thorn;ou haddist no reward to mannis drede, ne
to nou&yogh;t ellis &thorn;at schulde lette &thorn;ee, / for &thorn;ou were out of &thorn;i-silf for sorewe of
&thorn;in owne sone. / &THORN;i si&yogh;his weren so fer fet, &thorn;i brest so ful of dole and sorewe,
&thorn;i cheer so dreri for deedli wo, &thorn;at it bire[fte] &thorn;e reckinge of bodili wo or
drede and of wordli schame &amp; of alle maner lettingis. / Now, ladi, &thorn;at peyne &amp; passioun schulde haue be myn: for I hadde deserued it &amp; [was] cause &thorn;erof. /
&THORN;erfore, swete ladi, as &thorn;o peynes &amp; woundis were myn owne wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t, gete me
of &thorn;i merci oon of hem alle, &thorn;at it may abide as a pricke at myn herte; /
gete me, swete lady, a drope of &thorn;at ru&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddist, to folewe him wi&thorn;
as &thorn;ou didist. / Al &thorn;at wo is myn bi ri&yogh;t: sette me on myn owne, / be &thorn;ou not
so daungerous to wi&thorn;holde al.  &THORN;ou&yogh; al &thorn;i wo be &thorn;ee leef, &thorn;ou art ful large:
&thorn;an parte wi&thorn; &thorn;e pore &thorn;at litil ha&thorn;, and &yogh;eue me of &thorn;i si&yogh;yngis &thorn;at si&yogh;hist so sore, &amp; lete me si&yogh;e wi&thorn; &thorn;ee, si&thorn;en I bigan al &thorn;at wo. / I axe, derewor&thorn;e ladi, nou&thorn;ir castels ne townes ne noon o&thorn;ir worldis wele, ne sunne ne moone ne noone of &thorn;e bodies of heuene, ne no &thorn;ing: but woundis of ru&thorn;e, of peyne and
of cumpassioun of swete Ihesu my lordis passioun is al my desire. / I haue
apetite to peyne, &amp; I biseche my lord a drope of his rede blood to make my
soule blodi, / or ellis a drope of his watir to waische wi&thorn; my soule. / A, modir
of wrecchis &amp; of alle woful, visite my sike soule &amp; sette in myn herte &thorn;i sone
wi&thorn; hise woundis; / sende a sparcle of cumpassioun in to myn herte &thorn;at is
hard as stoon, / a drope of &thorn;at passioun to souplen it wi&thorn;.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;e wi&thorn; al myn herte for al &thorn;at peyne &thorn;at &thorn;ou
suffridist whanne &thorn;e cros was cast doun on &thorn;e grounde, &amp; &thorn;e[i] leiden &thorn;ee flat
&thorn;eron, &amp; wi&thorn; cordis drowen &thorn;in hondis &amp; feet to &thorn;e holis, &amp; nailiden fast &thorn;at


<PB N="100">

oon hond, &amp; streyned &thorn;at o&thorn;ir to &thorn;at o&thorn;er hole, / and &thorn;anne, swete Ihesu, &thorn;ei
drowen al &thorn;i bodi doun til &thorn;i feet rau&yogh;ten to the holis; / and &thorn;e nailis, lord,
weren blunte, for &thorn;ei schulden tere &thorn;i skyn / &amp; bruse &thorn;i fleisch. / Now, swete
Ihesu, me &thorn;inki&thorn; I se &thorn;i bodi on &thorn;e rode, al bled, and streyned &thorn;at &thorn;e ioyntis
twinnen; &thorn;i woundis now openen, &thorn;e skyn al to-drawen recchi&thorn; so brode &thorn;at
merueile is it halt; &thorn;in heed crowned wi&thorn; &thorn;ornis, &thorn;i bodi al ful of woundis,
nailis in &thorn;in hondis &amp; feet so tendre, &amp; in &thorn;i synewis, &thorn;ere as is moost peinful
felinge; / &thorn;ere is no leninge to &thorn;in heed, &thorn;i bodi is streyned as a
parchemynskyn upon &thorn;e harowe; / &thorn;i face is al bolned &thorn;at first was so fair; / &thorn;i iointis vndoon; / &thorn;ou hongist and stondist on nailis; / stremes of blood rennen doun bi
&thorn;e rode; / &thorn;e si&yogh;t of &thorn;i modir encresi&thorn; &thorn;i peyne. / A, lord swete Ihesu, &thorn;at
woldist vnmy&yogh;ti bicome to make me my&yogh;ti &amp; mende my synne, / I speke, lord,
of &thorn;i passioun and of hi&yogh; deuocioun &amp; I fynde no swetnes, but speke as a iay
&amp; noot what I meene; / I studie in &thorn;i passioun &amp; I fynde noo taast: / my
synnes ben so manye and so wickid &thorn;at &thorn;ei han schit out deuocioun &amp; han
stoppid al &thorn;e sauour of swetnes fro my soule, / &amp; &thorn;erfore I speke &amp; blundere
for&thorn; as a blinde creature, &amp; speke wi&thorn;outen wisdom or kunnynge of so deuoute
mater. / <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>BVt &thorn;ou, swete Ihesu, &thorn;at quikenest &thorn;e dede, &amp; turnest to good lijf fro dee&thorn;
of synne: so quike me, lord swete Ihesu, &amp; &yogh;eue me grace to fele sum of &thorn;at
swete sauour &amp; goostli deuocioun; / sende me, lord, &thorn;e li&yogh;t of grace, to haue
sum ynsi&yogh;t in soule.  &para; But, lord, I woot weel &thorn;at who so desiri&thorn; &thorn;ee ari&yogh;t:
&thorn;ou&yogh; he fele nou&yogh;t, he ha&thorn; &thorn;at he woot nou&yogh;t, &thorn;e loue of &thorn;i godhede; / &amp; if a man may no feruour fynde: &thorn;enke him-silf feble &amp; outcast, and holde him-silf
vnwor&thorn;i to haue deuocioun or ony sich specialte of oure lord god: / &amp; so he
schal gete sunnest &thorn;e &yogh;ift of his grace.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, &thorn;anne &thorn;e iewis heuen up &thorn;e cros and maden it to falle sore
in to &thorn;e hole &thorn;at was maad &thorn;erfore, &amp; brast &thorn;i woundis &amp; al to-schoke &thorn;i bodi &thorn;at hangide so sore. / Lord swete Ihesu, wo was &thorn;ee &thorn;anne, whanne &thorn;i sore
woundis of hondis &amp; feet bare al &thorn;e peis of &thorn;i bodi! / Swete Ihesu, &thorn;anne &thorn;i
modir was wo Inow &thorn;at si&yogh; &thorn;is, / sche si&yogh;ede &amp; wrong hir hondis, sche weep
teris Inowe: / &amp; al &thorn;at, lord, was eking of &thorn;i wo.  &para; And &thorn;at place was so
wlatsom wi&thorn; stinche of diuers careines, &thorn;at it lo&thorn;ide ony man to nei&yogh;e ny&yogh;. /
&amp; &thorn;us weren alle &thorn;i fyue wittis ocupied wi&thorn; peynes: to bote &thorn;e trespace of
oure fyue wittis.  &para; In si&yogh;t &thorn;ou were blindfeld, for &thorn;ou si&yogh; &thorn;i modir so wo, and for &thorn;ou si&yogh; hem &thorn;i foes &thorn;at weren moost holden to be &thorn;i frendis, as &thorn;e iewis.
&para; In &thorn;i smellinge, wi&thorn; stink of careynes &thorn;at were so manye: for &thorn;ou were doon
to &thorn;e dee&thorn; in &thorn;e foulist place of Ierusalem, &thorn;ere alle &thorn;e careynes of &thorn;e toun
weren cast out; / and &thorn;at smyl, swete Ihesu, was ful greuous in &thorn;i nose.  &para; In
&thorn;i taast, lord, greuede &thorn;ee &thorn;e galle aftir &thorn;rist&mdash;for, swete Ihesu, plente of peyne
is cause of &thorn;rist &amp; of drienes&mdash;&amp; [gal] is bittir in taast: / &amp; &thorn;e iewis &yogh;euen &thorn;ee &thorn;erto eisil, to echin &thorn;i bittir taast.  &para; In heeringe, swete Ihesu, &thorn;ou were greued wi&thorn; false accusingis, &amp; scornes, whanne &thorn;ei seiden &laquo;heil king&raquo; &amp; spitten in &thorn;i face; wi&thorn; heeringe of foul cri, whanne &thorn;ei crieden to hange &thorn;ee swete Ihesu on


<PB N="101">

&thorn;e rode, / and whanne &thorn;ei crieden &laquo;he coude o&thorn;ere men saue: now lete him
saue him-silf if he can&raquo;.  &para; In felinge, swete Ihesu, &thorn;ou were peined in &thorn;i
bindinge and hariynge, buffetinge, blindfelling, scourginge, crowninge, in beringe
of &thorn;e cros, in drawinge of cordis on &thorn;e cros, in nailinge of &thorn;i feet &amp; hondis
on &thorn;e cros. / &THORN;ere heng &thorn;ou so pore, swete Ihesu, &amp; so wobigoon, so &thorn;at of al
good on er&thorn;e &thorn;ou ne haddist but a litil cloo&thorn; to hilen wi&thorn; &thorn;i lendis: / and &yogh;it
&thorn;ou art king of kingis &amp; lord of lordis, &amp; heuene &amp; er&thorn;e &amp; helle is &thorn;in. / &amp; &yogh;it, lord, &thorn;ou woldist be so pore &thorn;at tyme, &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne haddist noon er&thorn;e to die upon, but on the cros in &thorn;e eir. / &amp; &thorn;erfore, swete Ihesu, of &thorn;ee was seid: /
&laquo;Foxis han dennys and briddis han nestis: but &thorn;ou at &thorn;i dee&thorn;-tyme ne hast not
to reste &thorn;in heed upon.&raquo;  &para; A, swete Ihesu, &thorn;at was a ruful word whanne &thorn;ou
seidist: / &laquo;Alle &yogh;e &thorn;at passen bi &thorn;e weie, abidi&thorn; and biholdi&thorn; if &thorn;er is ony sorewe lijk to my sorewe, &thorn;at I suffre for man.&raquo; / &amp; &yogh;it, swete Ihesu, &thorn;ou preiedist to &thorn;i fadir to for&yogh;eue hem &thorn;e gilt of &thorn;i dee&thorn;&mdash;so miche is &thorn;i merci. / And, swete Ihesu, not-wi&thorn;stoondinge al &thorn;i greet peyne, &yogh;it &thorn;ou tendist to &thorn;e &thorn;eef upon &thorn;i ri&yogh;thond whanne he axkide merci, &amp; grauntidist him betere &thorn;an he askide. / &THORN;anne, swete Ihesu, now &thorn;ou art in blis, &amp; not in peyne: be not now to
daungerus ne straunge of &thorn;i merci&mdash;for ceelden is a man more gracious in wo
&thorn;an in blis. / A, lord, wo were &thorn;ou for &thorn;i modir, whanne &thorn;ou took &thorn;i leue
of hir and woldist die, &amp; bi-took hir to seint Ioon to kepe &amp; to counforte. /
Here, swete Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee &thorn;at am ful of synnes: now lord in blis haue
merci on me, &amp; graunte me grace, whanne it is &thorn;i wille, to be wi&thorn; &thorn;ee in
paradice.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Aue maria.  Et ne.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete ladi maiden &amp; modir, wo was &thorn;ee bigoon whanne Crist hadde take
his leue at &thorn;ee &amp; bitook &thorn;ee to Ioon: &thorn;at sorewe my&yogh;te haue be &thorn;i dee&thorn;, in &thorn;at leue takinge. / &THORN;e teeris of &thorn;in i&yogh;en runnen doun ful faste, si&yogh;ingis &amp; sorewingis saten ful ny&yogh; &thorn;in herte; / &thorn;ou fel doun in swoun, &thorn;in heed hangid doun, &thorn;in armes fellen doun bi &thorn;i sidis, / &thorn;i colour wax al wan, &thorn;i face wax al pale: / &thorn;e
swerd of &thorn;i sones dee&thorn; smoot &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;in herte.  &THORN;at chaunginge, ladi, whanne
&thorn;ou haddist Ioon for Crist, was ful doleful as a &thorn;rowe of dee&thorn; to &thorn;in herte. /
A, swete ladi, whi hadde I not ben bi &thorn;ee, &amp; herd &thorn;at &thorn;ou herdist, &amp; seen &thorn;at
si&yogh;t wi&thorn; &thorn;ee, &amp; of &thorn;at myche sorewe haue take my part: if I my&yogh;te in caas
haue slakid &thorn;i wo/&mdash;for men seien it is solace to haue cumpanie in peyne. / Now,
swete Ihesu, si&thorn;&thorn;e I my&yogh;te not be &thorn;ere at &thorn;i dee&thorn;, so graunte me grace to
haue &thorn;at dee&thorn; continuely in mynde, in deuocioun &amp; in daliaunce; &amp; graunte me
mynde of &thorn;i de&thorn; often, &amp; to amende my lijf &amp; to haue sorewe in herte for my
mysdedis.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, &thorn;anne criedist &thorn;ou dolefulli on &thorn;e rode and seidist &thorn;ou were
a&thorn;rist: &amp; &thorn;at was no wondir, for peine is &thorn;ristlewe; &amp; &thorn;ei, lord, &yogh;auen &thorn;ee eisil and galle. / Swete Ihesu, &thorn;at was no &thorn;ristis kelinge, but ekinge. / A, swete Ihesu, &thorn;ei &yogh;auen &thorn;ee poisoun to kele &thorn;i &thorn;rist wi&thorn;: &amp; &thorn;ou &yogh;aue hem &thorn;in herte blood to quenche her synnes, &amp; to hele her soulis. / But, swete Ihesu, &thorn;i &thorn;rist was manye-fold: in bodi for peyne, &amp; in soule &thorn;ou &thorn;ristidist amendement of her
synnes &thorn;at diden &thorn;ee to dee&thorn;, / and &thorn;ou &thorn;ristidist deliueraunce of soulis in helle
&thorn;at here in lijf hadde kept &thorn;i lawis.  &para; Here, swete Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee, &yogh;eue
me grace to suffre hungir &amp; &thorn;urst for &thorn;i loue, &amp; to wi&thorn;stonde lustis &amp;


<PB N="102">

temptaciouns of ech foundinge of fleisch, &thorn;e world, or &thorn;e fend; / &amp; &yogh;eue me grace
in suffraunce, to folewe &thorn;e schadewe of &thorn;i cros, &amp; to &thorn;riste aftir &thorn;i seruice, &thorn;i
loue, &thorn;i presence to myn herte, in desire &amp; willinge of &thorn;i charite.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster. Aue maria gracia.  Et ne nos.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I &thorn;anke &thorn;ee wi&thorn; al my soule for &thorn;at doleful word &thorn;at &thorn;ou
seidist an hi&yogh; to &thorn;i fadir aforen &thorn;i deeth: / &laquo;dere god, whi hast &thorn;ou forsake
me, &thorn;at no-&thorn;ing &thorn;ou sparist me?&raquo; / Swete Ihesu, &thorn;i manhede for us was al
forsaken, so foule dee&thorn; and so peynful suffride neuere man. / &THORN;ere is no bodili
peyne &thorn;at is lich &thorn;in: / &thorn;i manhode was tendre; &thorn;i dignete excellent: &thorn;e fadris
sone of heuene hangi&thorn; bitwene two &thorn;eues; &amp; amyddis the world: for alle men
schulden wite; / and on &thorn;e hi&yogh; holy-day whanne alle men comen to &thorn;at citee: /
and so it was no priuy schame. / &thorn;ou hangist al nakid, &thorn;i skin al to-rent, ech
lith from o&thorn;ere wi&thorn; cordis drawen, crowned wi&thorn; &thorn;ornes, woundis wide, manye
&amp; griseli. / &THORN;e sorewe of &thorn;i modir was to &thorn;ee more peyne &thorn;an al &thorn;in o&thorn;er wo. / lo, &thorn;e los of mannys soule: &thorn;at peyned &thorn;ee so sore. / Swete Ihesu, &thorn;i mychil
merci, &thorn;in eendles loue and ru&thorn;e may no man telle ne bi&thorn;enke, si&thorn;en &thorn;ou
suffridist so sore for hem &thorn;at weren &thorn;i foos.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Aue maria. Et ne.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, I wole in my &thorn;ou&yogh;t leie me flat on &thorn;e er&thorn;e, &amp; ne&thorn;erer if y
mai, for I am cause &amp; gilti of &thorn;at peinful dee&thorn; / I wole take &thorn;e rode foot in
myn armes, flat on &thorn;e grounde, as &thorn;ou lay swete Ihesu, among &thorn;o stinkinge dede
bonys &thorn;at laien &thorn;ere wlatsumli to se: no &thorn;ing schal it greuen me, but is schal be
loue &amp; likinge to me; / so myche &thorn;at I wole not upward caste myn i&yogh;en to &thorn;at
glorious si&yogh;t of &thorn;i woundis, / for I &thorn;at am cause of hem alle, am vnwor&thorn;i to loken
on hem. / &THORN;us wole I lie to kepe of &thorn;i blood, swete Ihesu: from &thorn;ens wole I not
flitte, til I be wi&thorn; &thorn;i precious blood bicomen al reed, / til I be markid wi&thorn; &thorn;i
precious blood as oon of &thorn;in owne, &amp; my soule softid in &thorn;at swete ba&thorn;: / and so
may falle, swete Ihesu, &thorn;at myn hard herte it may opene, &thorn;at now is hard as stoon
to bicome neische, / &thorn;at deed was bi synne to quikene towardus &thorn;ee bi vertu.
&para; Swete Ihesu, &thorn;i precious passioun reiside dede men out of her graues, / it openede
heuene, it braste helle-&yogh;atis, er&thorn;e tremblide &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &thorn;e sunne lost his li&yogh;t: &amp; my sori herte of &thorn;e fendis kynde is hardir &thorn;an stones: for &thorn;ei cleueden in &thorn;i passioun,
&amp; myn herte may not fele of &thorn;i passioun a litil point, ne rise wi&thorn; &thorn;e dede in ru&thorn;e
&thorn;erof.  &para; Now is &thorn;e malice of my wickid herte more &thorn;an &thorn;i precious de&thorn;,
&thorn;at wrou&yogh;te siche wondris &amp; manye-foold more, &amp; &thorn;e mynde &thorn;erof stiri&thorn; not my soule? / But, swete Ihesu, a drope of &thorn;i blood droppid on my soule in mynde
of &thorn;i passioun, mai souplen &amp; softe my soule, &thorn;at is so hard, to melte bi &thorn;i
grace. / I woot weel, swete Ihesu, &thorn;at myn herte is not wor&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldist
come &thorn;erto &amp; &thorn;ere-ynne ali&yogh;te; / I ne aske it not of dignite of &thorn;i sepulture: but
swete Ihesu, &thorn;ou ali&yogh;tist in to helle to visite &thorn;ere and to ri&yogh;ten &thorn;e holi soulis of
oure holi fadris: &amp; in &thorn;at lijk maner I axe &thorn;i comynge to my soule. / Swete
Ihesu, I knowe weel also &thorn;at I was neuere wor&thorn;i to be &thorn;i modris felow, to
stonde at &thorn;i passioun wi&thorn; hir &amp; wi&thorn; Ioon: / but, swete Ihesu, if I may not be
&thorn;ere in &thorn;at maner for my greet vnwor&thorn;ines, I holde me wor&thorn;i for my greet
trespace to honge bi &thorn;i side as oon of &thorn;e &thorn;eues.  &para; And so, swete Ihesu, if I
may not as wor&thorn;i be &thorn;ere, I aske itt as gilti to haue part of &thorn;i dee&thorn;: / &amp; so,


<PB N="103">

&thorn;ou&yogh; I be not wor&thorn;i in herte to be li&yogh;tid: my nede, lord, &amp; my wickidnes
aski&thorn; to be ri&yogh;tid. / Come &thorn;anne, swete Ihesu, at &thorn;i wille, &amp; li&yogh;te in to my
soule as &thorn;ou for best knowist a sparcle of loue, a ru&thorn;e of &thorn;i passioun to kindle
in myn herte, &amp; quike me &thorn;erwi&thorn; &thorn;at I were brennynge in &thorn;i loue ouer al &thorn;ing;
&amp; ba&thorn;e me in &thorn;i blood, so &thorn;at I for&yogh;ete al wordli wele &amp; fleischli liki[n]gis.
&THORN;anne mai I blisse &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at I fele me stirid to &thorn;e of &thorn;i grace: so &thorn;at none
o&thorn;ir wele ne like me, but oonly &thorn;i dee&thorn;.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.</FOREIGN> /
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou seidist: &laquo;Fadir, in to &thorn;in hondis I bitake my spirit.&raquo; / Here, swete Ihesu, I biseche &thorn;ee, haue &amp; holde in &thorn;in hondis euere my soule:
&thorn;at it neuere wi&thorn; hool purpos desire fulli ony &thorn;ing but &thorn;ee or for &thorn;ee; / and
lete neuere wele ne wo turne my soule out of &thorn;i gouernaunce; &amp; at my laste
eende, swete Ihesu, resceyue my soule in to &thorn;in hondis, &thorn;at no fend ne lette me
fro &thorn;i blis. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> Pater noster.  Aue maria.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>SWete Ihesu, &thorn;anne seidist &thorn;ou last: &laquo;Al is endid:&raquo; / &thorn;an fel &thorn;in heed doun, &thorn;i goost passide from &thorn;e; &thorn;e er&thorn;e tremblide, &thorn;e sunne lost his li&yogh;t, dede men risen out of her graues, &thorn;e temple to-cleef, stones al to-bursten:&mdash;&thorn;o weren
witnessis of &thorn;i godhede.  Swete Ihesu, &thorn;anne &thorn;e scharp spere perside &thorn;i side: &amp; blood &amp; watir ran out. / A, swete Ihesu, &thorn;anne were &thorn;ere fyue grete flodis of
blood: in hondis, foot, and side. / &THORN;i chin hangi&thorn; on &thorn;i brest, &thorn;e white of &thorn;in
i&yogh;en is cast upward, &thorn;i lippis schrinken, &thorn;i white tee&thorn; schewen, &thorn;i loueli face is
bicomen al pale, &thorn;in heer clo&thorn;ed al wi&thorn; blood. / &THORN;e mynde of &thorn;is mater I
wolde were my deep. / A, swete Ihesu, &thorn;anne was &thorn;i modir ful wo: / now sche
lokide upon &thorn;in heed &amp; on &thorn;e crowne, / now on &thorn;i face, now on &thorn;in hondis
wi&thorn; &thorn;e nailis, now on &thorn;e wounde upon &thorn;i side, now on thi feet nailid on &thorn;e
rode, now upon &thorn;i bodi scourgid: / &amp; at euery place sche fond a newe sorewe; /
sche weep, sche wrong hir hondis, / sche si&yogh;ede, sche sobbide: sche falli&thorn; doun.
Ioon upon &thorn;e o&thorn;er half, is ful of sorewe. / &THORN;e si&yogh;t of &thorn;e crucifix stiki&thorn; in her
hertis as it were her de&thorn;. / Now, swete ladi, for &thorn;i merci, si&thorn;en &thorn;at I am cause
of al &thorn;at wo &amp; peyne, graunte me of &thorn;i grace a point of &thorn;i peyne, a si&yogh;t of &thorn;i
sorewe, to si&yogh;en &amp; sorewen wi&thorn; &thorn;ee: &thorn;at I mowe sumwhat fele, &thorn;at al haue
maad; / graunte me, swete ladi, to haue &amp; to holde &thorn;is passioun in mynde as
hertili &amp; as studiousli in al my lijf, as &thorn;ou, ladi, &amp; Ioon, hadde it in mynde
whanne &thorn;e peple weren goon &amp; &yogh;e abiden bi &thorn;e rode foot.  Amen.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Et ne nos in.  Adoramus te Christe.  Quia per sanctam crucem.
Domine Ihesu Christe.</FOREIGN>
</P></DIV3>
</DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="part">

<PB N="193"><HEAD>Short Prose Tracts</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>The Bee and the Stork</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="MS">Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD><MILESTONE N="194" UNIT="folio">
<HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Moralia Richardi heremite de natura apis, vnde quasi apis argumentosa.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>The bee has thre kyndis.  Ane es &thorn;at scho es neuer ydill, and scho es noghte
with thaym &thorn;at will noghte wyrke, bot castys thaym owte and puttes thaym
awaye.  A-nothire es &thorn;at when scho flyes scho takes erthe in hyr fette, &thorn;at
scho be noghte lyghtly ouer-heghede in the ayere of wynde.  The thyrde es
&thorn;at scho kepes clene and bryghte hire wynge&yogh;.  Thus ryghtwyse men &thorn;at lufes
god, are neuer in ydyllnes: ffor owthyre &thorn;ay ere in trauayle, prayand or
thynkande or redande or othere gude doande, or withtakand ydill mene and
schewand thaym worthy to be put fra &thorn;e ryste of heuene ffor &thorn;ay will noghte
trauayle here.  &THORN;ay take erthe, &thorn;at es &thorn;ay halde &thorn;am-selfe vile &amp; erthely that
thay be noghte blawene with &thorn;e wynde of vanyte and of pryde.  Thay kepe
thaire wynges clene, that es &thorn;e twa commandementes of charyte &thorn;ay fulfill in
gud concyens, and thay hafe othyre vertus vnblendyde with &thorn;e fylthe of syne
and vnclene luste.  Arestotill sais &thorn;at &thorn;e bees are feghtande agaynes hym
&thorn;at will drawe &thorn;aire hony fra thayme.  Swa sulde we do agaynes deuells &thorn;at
afforces thame to reue fra vs &thorn;e hony of poure l[u]fe &amp; of grace.  For many
are &thorn;at neuer kane halde &thorn;e ordyre of lufe ynesche &thorn;aire frendys sybbe or
ffremmede, bot outhire &thorn;ay lufe &thorn;aym ouer-mekill, settand thaire thoghte
vnryghtwysely on thaym: or &thorn;ay luf thayme ouer-lyttill, yf &thorn;ay doo noghte all as
&thorn;ey wolde till &thorn;ame.  Swylke kane noghte fyghte for thaire hony, ffor-thy &thorn;e


<PB N="194">

deuelle turnes it to worme[d] and makes &thorn;eire saules ofte-sythes full bitter in angwys
and tene, and besynes of vayne thoghtes and o&thorn;er wrechidnes, ffor thay are so
heuy in erthely frenchype &thorn;at &thorn;ay may noghte flee in till &thorn;e lufe of Ihesu Criste,
in &thorn;e wylke &thorn;ay moghte wele for-gaa &thorn;e lufe of all creaturs lyfande in erthe. /
Whare-fore, accordandly Arystotill sais &thorn;at some fowheles are of gude flyghyng,
&thorn;at passes fra a lande to a-nothire, Some are of ill flyghynge for heuynes of body
and for[-&thorn;i] &thorn;aire neste es noghte ferre fra &thorn;e erthe.  Thus es it of thayme &thorn;at
turnes &thorn;ame to godes seruys.  Some are of gude flyeghynge for thay flye fra erthe
to heuene and rystes thayme thare in thoghte, and are fedde in delite of goddes
lufe, and has thoghte of na lufe of &thorn;e worlde.  Some are &thorn;at kan noghte flyghe
fra &thorn;is lande bot in &thorn;e waye late theyre herte ryste and delyttes &thorn;aym in sere
lufes of mene and womene, als &thorn;ay come &amp; gaa, nowe ane &amp; nowe a-nothire,
and in Ihesu Criste &thorn;ay kan fynde na swettnes or if &thorn;ay any tyme fele oghte
it es swa lyttill and swa schorte for othire thoghtes &thorn;at are in thayme, &thorn;at it
brynges thaym till na stabylnes; [f]or &thorn;ay are lyke till a fowle &thorn;at es callede
strucyo or storke, &thorn;at has wenges and it may noghte flye for charge of body.
Swa &thorn;ay hafe vndirstandynge, and fastes and wakes and semes haly to mens
syghte, bot thay may noghte flye to lufe and contemplacyone of god, &thorn;ay are so
chargede wyth othyre affeccyons and othire vanytes.
</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV3>

<DIV3 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Desyre and Delit</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="MS">Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD><MILESTONE N="196b" UNIT="folio"><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Item Idem de dilectacione in deo.</FOREIGN>Also of &thorn;e same: delyte and &yogh;ernyng of gode.</HEAD><OPENER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ihesus Marie filius, sit michi clemens &amp; propecius.  Amen.</FOREIGN></OPENER>

<P>Gernyng and delite of Ihesu Criste &thorn;at has na thyng of worldes thoghtes, es
wondyrfull, pure, haly, and faste, and whene a man felis hym in &thorn;at degre than es
a man Circumsysede gastely.  [It es haly] whene all o&thorn;er besynes and affeccyons and
thoghtes are drawene away owte of his saule, that he may hafe ryste in goddes lufe
with-owttene tagillynge of o&thorn;er thynges.  &para; The delyte es wondirfull [when] it es
sa heghe &thorn;at na thoghte may reche &thorn;ar-to to bryng it doune.  &para; It es pure when
it es noghte blendid with na thynge &thorn;at es contrayrie thare-to.  &para; And it es faste
whene it es clene and stabill delitande by it-selfe.  &para; Thre thynges makes delite
in gode heghe: Ane es restreynynge of fleschely luste in complecioune.  Ano&thorn;er
es restreynynge or repressynge of ill styrrynge and of temptacione in will.  The
thirde es kepynge or hegheynge of &thorn;e herte in lyghtenynge of &thorn;e halygaste, &thorn;at
haldis his herte vpe fra all erthely thoghtes, &thorn;at he sette nane obstakill at the
comynge of Criste in till hyme. // Ilkane &thorn;at couaytes endles hele, be he besy
nyghte and daye to fulfill &thorn;is lare or elles to Criste&yogh; lufe he may noghte wynne //
ffor it es heghe, and all &thorn;at it duellis in, it lyftes abowne layery lustes and vile
couaytes and abowne all affeccyouns and thoghtes of any bodily thynge. // Twa
thynges makes oure delyte pure. // Ane es tornynge of sensualite to the skyll;
ffor whene any es tornede to delite of hys fyve wittes alson&macr;e vnclennes entyrs
in to his saule. // Ano&thorn;er es &thorn;at &thorn;e skyll mekely be vssede in gastely thynges,
als in medytacyons, and orysouns, and lukynge in haly bukes. / For-thy &thorn;e delyte
&thorn;at has noghte or vnordaynde styrrynge and mekely has styrrynge in Criste, and
in whilke &thorn;e sensualyte es tournede to &thorn;e skyll, all sette and oysede tyll god, makys
a mans saule in ryste &amp; sekirnes, and ay to duell in gude hope, &amp; to be payede
with all godis sandes with-owttene gruchynge or heuynese of thoghte&yogh;, &amp;c.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit.</FOREIGN>
</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit carmen.  Qui scripsit sit benedictus.  Amen.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV3>

<DIV3 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Gastly Gladnesse</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="MS">Ms. Cambridge Dd V. 64</HEAD><MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio">
<P>(G)astly gladnes in Ihesu &amp; ioy in hert with swetnes in sawle of &thorn;e sauor of heuen in hope es helth in til hele.  And my lyfe lendes in luf, and lyghtsumnes vnlappes my thoght.  I drede noght &thorn;at me may wyrk wa, sa mykel I wate of wele.  It war na wonder if dede war dere, &thorn;at I myght se hym &thorn;at I seke.  Bot now it es lenthed fra me, &amp; me behoues lyf here, til he wil me lese.  Lyst &amp; lere of &thorn;is lare, &amp; &thorn;e sal noght myslike.  Lufe makes me to melle, &amp; ioy gars me iangell.  Loke &thorn;ow lede &thorn;i lyf in lyghtsumnes, &amp;heuynes helde it a-way.  Sarynes lat it noght sytt wyth &thorn;e: bot in gladnes of god euermare make &thorn;ow &thorn;i gle.  AmeN.
</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Expliciunt cantica diuini amoris secundum Ricardum Hampole.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV3>

<DIV3 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Seven Gifts of the Holy Spirit</HEAD>
<DIV4 N="Arundel 507" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD>Ms. Arundel 507</HEAD><MILESTONE N="43" UNIT="folio">
<P>&THORN;is are &thorn;e .VII. giftes of &thorn;e hali gast: Wysdom, Vnderstandynge, Consail, Strenth,
Conynge, Pite, Drede of god.  &THORN;ir ordeyne man til lede his life rightwisli in &thorn;is
werld. Bigyn we at consail: for &thorn;erof is mast mister.  Consail / is doyng a-wai: of
werld riches &amp; delices / &amp; of al thinge &thorn;at man mai be tagild with in thought or
dede; &amp; steringe inwardli til contemplacion of god. / Vnderstandynge is: til knawe
what is for to do: &amp; what is for to leue; &amp; to gife &thorn;at sal be gyuen: til &thorn;e nedy /
noght til &thorn;a &thorn;at haues na nede. / Wisdom: is forgetynge of erthli thinges &amp; thinkynge of heuen / with discrecion in alle oure dedes; in &thorn;is gifte: schynes
contemplacion, &thorn;at is as saynt Austyn sais, a gasteli dede of affeccions: thorugh &thorn;e
ioie of a raisid thought. / Strynth: is lastynge to fulfil gode purpos &thorn;at it be
noght left / for wele ne waa. / Pyte: is &thorn;at a man be mylde, &amp; gayne-sai noght
hali writte: when it smytis his synnes / whether he vnderstand it or noght; bot
in al his might: purge he &thorn;e vilete of synne / in him &amp; in o&thorn;er. / Conynge: makis
a man noght rosand him of his rightwisenesse / bot sorowand for his synne; &amp; &thorn;at he gedir erthli godes / aneli til &thorn;e honour of god &amp; prow til o&thorn;er men as
til him-selfe. / Drede: is &thorn;at we turne noght agayn til oure synne; &amp; &thorn;en is
drede perfite in vs: when we drede til wrath god in &thorn;e leste synne &thorn;at we can
knawe, &amp; flees it as venyme.
</P></DIV4>

<DIV4 REND="Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="196"><HEAD>Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="196" UNIT="folio"><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Item Idem de septem donis spiritus sancti.</FOREIGN> Also of the gyftes of the haly gaste.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;e seuene gyftes of &thorn;e haly gaste &thorn;at ere gyfene to men and wymmene &thorn;at
er ordaynede to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene and ledys theire lyfe in this worlde
reghtwysely: Thire are thay: / Wysdome / Vndyrstandynge / Counsayle / Strenghe /
Connynge / Pete / The drede of god. / Begynne we at consaile, for &thorn;are-of es
myster at the begynnynge of oure werkes &thorn;at vs myslyke noghte aftyrwarde. /
With thire seuene gyftes &thorn;e haly gaste teches sere mene serely.  &para; Consaile es
doynge awaye of worldes reches, and of all delytes of all thynge&yogh;, &thorn;at mane may
be tagyld with in thoghte or dede, and &thorn;a[r]-with drawynge in till contemplacyone


<PB N="197">

of gode.  &para; Vndyrstandynge es to knawe whate es to doo and whate es to
lefe; and &thorn;at that sall be gyffene to gyffe it to thaym &thorn;at has nede / noghte till
o&thorn;er &thorn;at has na myster.  &para; Wysedome es forgetynge of erthely thynges and
thynkynge of heuen, with discrecyone of all mene dedys. / In &thorn;is gyfte schynes
contemplacyone, &thorn;at es, saynt Austyne says, a gastely dede of fleschely affeccyones
thurghe &thorn;e Ioye of a raysede thoghte.  &para; Strenghe es lastynge to fullfill gude
purpose, &thorn;at it be noghte lefte for wele ne for waa.  &para; Pete es &thorn;at a man be
mylde; and gaynesay noghte haly writte whene it smyttes his synnys, whethire he
vndyrstand it or noghte, bot in all his myghte purge he &thorn;e vilte of syne in hyme
and o&thorn;er.  &para; Connynge es &thorn;at makes a man of gude [hope] noghte ruysand hyme
of his reghtewysnes, bot sorowand of his synnys; and &thorn;at man gedyrs erthely
gude anely to the honour of god, and prow to o&thorn;er mene &thorn;ane hym-selfe.  &para; The
drede of god es &thorn;at we turne noghte agayne till oure syne thurghe any ill
eggyng. / And &thorn;a[n] es drede perfite in vs and gastely / when we drede to
wrethe god in &thorn;e leste syne, &thorn;at we kane knawe, and flese it als venyme.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit.</FOREIGN>
</P></DIV4>
</DIV3>

<DIV3 TYPE="text">

<PB N="195"><HEAD>Commentary on the Decalogue</HEAD>
<DIV4 N="Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD>Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub">A notabill Tretys off the ten Comandementys: Drawene by Richerde the hermyte off Hampull.</HEAD>

<P>The fyrste comandement es: &laquo;Thy lorde god &thorn;ou sall loute and til hym anely
&thorn;ou sall serue.&raquo; / In this comandement es forboden all mawmetryse, all
wychcrafte and charemynge, / the wylke may do na remedy till any seknes of mane,
womane or beste; ffor &thorn;ay erre &thorn;e snarrys of &thorn;e deuelle by &thorn;e whilke he
afforces hym to dyssayue mankynde. / Alswa in &thorn;is commandemente es forbodyne to
gyffe trouthe till so[r]cerye or till dyuynynge&yogh; by sternys or by dremys or by any
swylke thynges. / Astronomyenes by-haldes &thorn;e daye and &thorn;e houre and &thorn;e poynte
&thorn;at mane es borne In, and vndyr whylke syngne he es borne and &thorn;e poynte &thorn;at
he be-gynnes to be In, / and by &thorn;ire syngnes and o&thorn;er &thorn;ay saye, &thorn;at &thorn;ay say that
sall be-fall &thorn;e man aftyrwarde: bot theyre errowre es reproffede of haly doctours. /
Haly crosses mene sall lowte ffor thay are in syngne of Cryste crucyfiede; To
ymages es &thorn;e louynge &thorn;at es till theyme of whaym &thorn;ai are &thorn;e ymage&yogh;, ffor
&thorn;at Entent anely &thorn;ai are for to lowte.  The tothire comandement es: &laquo;&thorn;ou sall
noghte take &thorn;e name of god in vayne.&raquo;  Here es forbodene athe with-owttene
chesone. / He &thorn;at neuenes god &amp; sweris fals, dispyse god. / In thre maners mane
may syne in swerynge: / That es, if he swere agayne his concyence, Or if he swere
be Cryste wondes or blude&mdash;That es euermare gret syne / &thorn;ofe it be sothe &thorn;at he
sweris, / ffor it sounes in irreu[er]ence of Ihesu Cryste; / Also if he come agaynes his
athe noght fulfilland &thorn;at he has sworne. / The nam of gode es takyne in vayne one
many maners: With herte / with mouthe / with werke. / With herte takes false
crystyne mene it in vayne &thorn;at rescheyues &thorn;e Sacrament with-owttene grace in sawle. /
With mouthe es it tane in vayne with all athes; brekynge of new prechynge &thorn;at es
vanyte and vndeuocyone; prayere when we honour god with oure lyppys and oure
hertys erre ferre fra hym. / With werke ypocrittes takes goddes nam in vayne: / ffor
they feyne gud dede with-owttene, and &thorn;ey erre with-owttene charyte and vertue and
force of sawle to stand agayne all ill styrrynges.  The thirde commandement es:
&laquo;Vmbethynke the &thorn;at thow halowe &thorn;i halydaye!&raquo; / This commandement may be takyne in thre maneres: / Firste generally &thorn;at we sesse of all vyces.  [Sithen speciali, &thorn;at we cesse of alle bodili werkis] &thorn;at lettys deuocyone to god in prayenge and thynkynge.
The thyrde es specyall, als in contemplatyfe mene &thorn;at departis &thorn;ayme fra all werldly
thynges swa &thorn;at &thorn;ey hally gyfe &thorn;ayme till god. / The fyrste manere es nedfull vs to
do / The tothire we awe to do / The thirde es perfeccyone. / For-thi one &thorn;e halydaye
men awe, als god byddys, to lefe all syne, and do na werke &thorn;at lettis thayme to
gyffe &thorn;aire herte to godd, thatt &thorn;ay halowe &thorn;e daye in ryst and deuocyone and
dedys of charyte.  The ferthe comandement es: &laquo;Honoure thy fadyre and &thorn;i


<PB N="196">

modyre.&raquo; / That es in twa thynges, &thorn;at es bodyly and gastely. / Bodyly in
sustenance / &thorn;at &thorn;ay be helpede and sustaynede in &thorn;aire elde / and when &thorn;ay are
vnmyghtty of &thorn;ayme-selfe. / Gastely in reuerence and bouxomnes: &thorn;at &thorn;ay say to
&thorn;ame na wordes of myssawe ne vnhoneste ne of displesance vnauyssedly, / bot
serue &thorn;ame mekely and gladly and lawlyly; &thorn;at &thorn;ay may wyne &thorn;at godde hyghte to
swylke barnes / &thorn;at es [&thorn;e] lande of lyghte. / And if &thorn;ay be dede / thaym awe to helpe
&thorn;aire sawles with almous-dedes and prayers.  The fifte commandement es &thorn;at &laquo;thow slaa na mane;&raquo; nowthire with assente, ne with werke, ne with worde or fauour.  And also here es forbodene vn-ryghtewyse hurtynge of any persone. / Thay are slaers
gastely / &thorn;at will noghte feede &thorn;e pouer in nede / and &thorn;at defames men / and &thorn;at
confoundes Innocentys.  The sexte commandement es: &laquo;thow sall be na lichoure.&raquo; / &THORN;at es / thow sall haue na man or womane bot &thorn;at &thorn;ou has takene in fourme
of haly kyrke. / Alswa here es forbodene all maner of wilfull pollusyone procurede
one any maner agaynes kyndly oys, or o&thorn;er gates.  The seuende commandement
es: &laquo;thow sall noghte do na thyfte.&raquo;  In the whylke es forbodene all manere of
with-draweynge of o&thorn;er mene thynges wrangwysely agaynes &thorn;aire wyll &thorn;at aghte
it, / bot if it ware in tyme of maste nede, when all thynges erre comone. / Also
here es forbodene gillery of weghte / or of tale / or of mett or of mesure, / or thorow
okyre, or violence or drede / als bedells or foresters duse and mynystyrs of &thorn;e
kynge, / or thurghe extorcyone als lordes duse.  The aughtene commandement es
/ that &laquo;thow sall noghte bere false wyttnes agaynes thi neghteboure&raquo;, als in assys / or cause of matremoyne. / And also lyenges ere forbodene in &thorn;is commandement / and forswerynge. / Bot all lyenges are noghte dedly syne, bot if &thorn;ay noye till som
man bodyly or gastely.  The nynde commandement es: &laquo;thow sall noghte couayte
&thorn;e hous or o&thorn;er thynge mobill or in-mobill of &thorn;i neghtbour with wrange,&raquo; / ne
&thorn;ou sall noghte hald o&thorn;er mens gude if &thorn;ou may &yogh;elde thayme, / elles &thorn;i penance
saues &thorn;e noghte.  The tend commandement as: &laquo;thow sall noghte couayte &thorn;i
neghtebour wyefe, ne his seruande, ne his maydene, / ne mobylls of his&raquo;. / He
lufes god &thorn;at kepis thire commandementes for lufe. / His neghtebour hym awe
to lufe als hym-selfe, &thorn;at es till &thorn;e same gude &thorn;at he lufes hym-selfe to, /
nathynge till ill; / and &thorn;at he lufe his neghtbour saule / mare &thorn;ane his body or any
gude&yogh; of &thorn;e worlde &amp;c. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> Explicit.</FOREIGN></P></DIV4></DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>

<DIV1 TYPE="part">

<PB N="[132]"><HEAD>Works of Doubtful Authenticity</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>On Grace</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="Arundel 507" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD>Ms. Arundel 507</HEAD><MILESTONE N="41" UNIT="folio"><HEAD TYPE="sub">De gracia</HEAD>
<P>Three degree&yogh; of grace: are.  &THORN;e first: god gifs til alle creatures / til vphald
&thorn;aim with, &amp; &thorn;is is callid goddis help / freli gyuen til alle creatures; &amp; with-outen


<PB N="133">

&thorn;is gifte of grace: creatures mai noght do nor last in &thorn;aire kynde; for als water is
made hate thorugh fire / &amp; bicomes calde agayn / if &thorn;e fire be withdrawen: swa,
als saynt Austyn sais, alle creatures / als &thorn;ai are of noght made: als &thorn;ai worthe
til noght in a littil tyme / bot god &thorn;aim vphalde with &thorn;is grace thorugh whilke
&thorn;ai are.  For-&thorn;i sais &thorn;e apostill: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracia dei sum: id quod sum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;thorugh goddis grace i am: &thorn;at i am&raquo;.  Als if he said: &laquo;&thorn;at i life / &thorn;at i fele / &thorn;at i speke or here or see / &amp; al &thorn;at i am: al &thorn;is i haue aneli thorugh goddis grace&raquo;. // &THORN;e second degree of grace is mare speciale, &thorn;at god gyues freli til ilke man &thorn;at is gode &amp; skilful creature.  &amp; &thorn;is grace standis euer atte &yogh;ates of oure hertes: &amp; knokkys on oure free-wille / &amp; biddis / lat him inne.  &THORN;is sais god &thorn;at he dose, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ego sto ad ostium pulsans,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;I stand atte &thorn;e dore of &thorn;i herte &amp; knokkis / lat me inne&raquo;.  And &thorn;is grace is gyuen freli til man: or he it deserue.  Make &thorn;en ilke man him worthi &amp; redi til resceyue &thorn;is gifte of &thorn;e hali gast: &thorn;at euer steres til gode mannes free-wille / &amp; callis it fra ille.  Twa thinges are nedeful: til hele of mannes saule.  &THORN;e first is &thorn;is grace &thorn;at i speke ofe; &thorn;at o&thorn;er: is manes free-wille acordant &thorn;er-tille.  And with-oute &thorn;ire twa: na man mai do, thorugh
ought &thorn;at in him is: &thorn;at suld helpe him til hele of his saule; for noi&thorn;er
free-wille with-oute &thorn;is grace sterand, nor &thorn;is grace with-oute free-wille assentand:
mai do ought &thorn;at paies god.  And for-&thorn;i sais saynt Austyn: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui fecit te sine te: non iustificabit te sine te,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;he &thorn;at made &thorn;e with-outen &thorn;e: wil noght
make &thorn;e rightwise / bot if &thorn;ou help &thorn;erto&raquo;.  And &thorn;of &thorn;e free-wille of man mai
noght make &thorn;e grace of god in man: nere-&thorn;e-lesse / do man &thorn;at in him is / &amp; graithe him swa, &thorn;at he be redy &amp; abill / til resceyue &thorn;e grace when it comes. /
If &thorn;ou ware in a merke house / on day, &amp; doris &amp; wyndowes ware stoken: if &thorn;ou
wold noght late &thorn;e sonne come inne / wha ware til blame / if &thorn;e house ware
mirke?  Als swa, wyte nane bot &thorn;i-selfe: if &thorn;i grace be lesse.  For saynt Anselme
sais: &laquo;Man wantis noght &thorn;is grace: for god gifs it him; bot he haues it noght:
for he makis him noght redy til resceyue &thorn;is grace als he suld&raquo;.  God is na
chynche of his grace: for he haues ynogh &thorn;erofe&mdash;for &thorn;ofe he dele it neuer so
ferre / ne to so mony: he haues neuer &thorn;e lesse; for him wantes noght bot clene
vessels: til do his grace inne.  &THORN;erfor sais saynt Austyn: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Deus ingenti libertate atque vbertate: replet omnes creaturas, i. secundum capacitatem earum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;God thorugh his grete fredome of his mykel grace: fulfilles all creatures / after &thorn;at &thorn;ai are abill til resceyue his grace&raquo;.  If man oppenyd his hert til &thorn;is grace / when god sendis it til him: he wold schew it in werke; for &thorn;e apostle when he had
won it: said: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracia eius in me vacua non fuit,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;&thorn;e grace &thorn;at god haues gyuen me: is noght vnnayt in me&raquo;&mdash;for he notid it euer in werke. / We felaschip with god of his grace: as marchandis dose to-gyder; for god settis his grace: agayn oure werke; bot for his grace &amp; his dede: he wil noght bot oure louynge &amp; thankynge, &amp; he wil &thorn;at &thorn;e man: haue al &thorn;e prowe &thorn;at mai rise &thorn;erofe. Bot &thorn;a fandes til reue god his parte: &thorn;at wold be loued of men for &thorn;aire gode
dede.  Agayn &thorn;aim sais god: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gloriam meam alteri non dabo,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;Louynge &amp; worschip &thorn;at til me fallis: i wil gife til nane o&thorn;er&raquo;.
</P>
<P>&THORN;ow sal vnderstand / &thorn;at fre-wille of man: is frely til turne til gode or
til ille.  Thre statis are of man: bifore synne; after mannes synne; &amp; after man
is confermyd, &thorn;at is after man is departid oute of &thorn;is dedli life: &amp; comen til


<PB N="134">

&thorn;at ioie / &thorn;at neuer sal ende.  In &thorn;e first state / bifore man synned: was mannes
wille so free / &thorn;at he might synne &amp; noght synne; in his free wille it was: til
do wele or ille.  In &thorn;e last state &thorn;at is confermid: sal man noght mow synne.  In
&thorn;e second state / in &thorn;e whilke he mai synne / &amp; mai noght bot he synne: mannes
wille is free til ille / til it be strynthid with grace; &amp; when grace ledis &thorn;e wille:
&thorn;en is it free til wirke &thorn;e gode.  Bifore man synned: na lettyng had he til do &thorn;e
gode, nor na nedynge til do &thorn;e ille; bot now has synne copild with oure flesh
a brodde / &thorn;at saynt Paule callis <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Legem carnis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is, &laquo;&thorn;e lagh of &thorn;e flesh&raquo;:
&thorn;at it es maister of &thorn;e flesh / swa &thorn;at it withstandis goddis lagh in al &thorn;at it
mai.  &THORN;is lettis oure wille til assent til &thorn;e gode: &amp; steres it to &thorn;e ille; &thorn;at it mai
noght wirke &thorn;e gode: bot if grace help &amp; vse him oute of synne. / Ilk a man
or he synne: haues a free wille til do gode or ille; bot when he is bonden to
&thorn;e fende thorugh werkys of synne: he mai thorugh na might of him-selfe / come
oute of his bandes, &amp; &thorn;en he fares as a schippe &thorn;at in tempest had lost al &thorn;at
suld helpe it / &amp; is casten fra wawe til wawe: whider tempest dryues<MILESTONE N="42" UNIT="folio"> it. Right swa a man &thorn;at wantis goddis grace / fra he be fallyn in dedly synne: he
dose noght &thorn;at he walde, bot ai wayues fra hand til hand: at &thorn;e fendes wille;
&amp; bot god gif him grace til rise oute of his synne: he sal be in synne til
his liues ende, &amp; after: be lost bodi &amp; saule / &amp; dampned til endles pyne.
If &thorn;e folk or &thorn;e commune chese &thorn;aim a kynge / &amp; he be confermid in his
kyngdome: be he neuer so ille to &thorn;aim / &thorn;ai mai noght do him doune, bot it be
thorugh o&thorn;er: &thorn;at haues mare powere &thorn;en he; &amp; swa bihoues &thorn;aim suffre: do he
&thorn;aim neuer so mykel ille.  Right swa, man or he synne: haues a free wille til
chese wether he wil be vnder god or &thorn;e fende; &amp; when he chesis with his wille
for to serue &thorn;e fende: he mai noght after when he wold / come oute of his
bandis.  And &thorn;erfore werldli men &thorn;at are bonden in synne / sais til &thorn;a &thorn;at
conseils &thorn;aim til amend &thorn;air life: &laquo;fayn we wold rise: bot we mai noght&raquo;.  No / &thorn;ai mai noght thorugh might of &thorn;aim-selfe; bot thorugh goddis grace helpand:
&thorn;ai mai. // &THORN;e thrid grace is maste special: for it is gyuen aneli til &thorn;a: &thorn;at
resceyues &thorn;e second grace, &amp; with &thorn;aire free wille: fillis it in dede, &amp; mai sai
as saynt Paule said: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracia dei: in me vacua non fuit,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;goddis grace: was noght vnnayt in me&raquo;.  And saynt Austyn sais: &laquo;god with vs wirkand: fulfillis &thorn;at he thorugh grace sterand / bigan in vs&raquo;.  For nou&thorn;er with-outen him helpand: mai we do gode til vs selfe / nor paie til him; as god sais him-selfe: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sine me: nichil potestis facere,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;with-outen help of mi grace: &yogh;e mai noght do&raquo;.  Goddis grace sterand gase bifore gode wille: &amp; steres it til do &thorn;e gode / &amp; leue &thorn;e ille.
</P>
<P>Grace when he comes first til visite mannes saule: he wakyns him as of a
slomerynge / &amp; spires at him with .III. scharp wordes / &amp; sais: &laquo;Whare art &thorn;ou? Whethen comes &thorn;ou?  &amp; Whider sal &thorn;ou?&raquo;  First he sais: &laquo;Whare art &thorn;ou?&raquo; as if he said: &laquo;vmbithink &thorn;e / vnhappi wreche: how foule &thorn;ou art castyn doune / &amp; what peril &thorn;ou art inne.  For for &thorn;i synne: &thorn;ou art fallyn in til &thorn;i enemy handes: &thorn;at ouer alle thynge couaitis til wirke &thorn;e waa; &amp; noght mai deliuere &thorn;e oute of &thorn;i faes handes: bot almighti god / &thorn;i gode lauerd / &thorn;at &thorn;ou haues forsaken&raquo;. / After he sais: &laquo;Whethen comes &thorn;ou?&raquo; as if he said: &laquo;&thorn;ou wreche / bihald how &thorn;ou


<PB N="135">

haues wastid al &thorn;i life in synne; &thorn;ou comes fra &thorn;e fendes tauerne.  Whare are
alle &thorn;e godes &thorn;at god hase &thorn;e gyuen / til help &thorn;e with / &amp; worschip him?  Sarili
&thorn;ou haues &thorn;aim loste.  &THORN;i lauerd made &thorn;e riche: &amp; &thorn;ou art bicomen a pouer
wreche&raquo;.  After he spires: &laquo;Whider wendes &thorn;ou?&raquo; &laquo;Waful wreche / &thorn;ou wendes to &thorn;at waful dome: &thorn;at god demes wreches to; for as &thorn;ou haues seruid: sal &thorn;ou be demed.  Swa auful sal &thorn;ou see god &thorn;are: &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal for ferde / be oute of &thorn;i
witte, &amp; til &thorn;e montayns &amp; hilles &thorn;ou sal crie with a grisli noice, &amp; prai &thorn;aim til falle on &thorn;e &amp; hide &thorn;e: &thorn;at &thorn;ou noght on him see.  Waful wreche, &thorn;ou wendes til helle: if &thorn;ou do forth / as &thorn;ou haues bigunne; whare &thorn;ou sal fynde fire so hate
&amp; so wodeli: &thorn;at al &thorn;e water in &thorn;e see, &thorn;of it ranne thorugh it, might noght
slokyn a sparke &thorn;erofe.  &amp; for &thorn;ou stynkes here til god / for &thorn;i foule synnes: &thorn;ou
sal fele &thorn;are stynke ai-lastand; &amp; for &thorn;ou loued here mirknes / &amp; ai til be in
synne: &thorn;are sal &thorn;ou fele sa thike mirknesse / &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai it grape; &amp; for &thorn;ou
restid &thorn;e here in synne agayn goddis wille: &thorn;are sal &thorn;ou grete ma teres / &thorn;en
motes are in &thorn;e sonne.  &THORN;ou sal suffre payne ai after payne / ai til new &thorn;i waa&raquo;. // When goddis grace haues stered man &amp; wakenid him with &thorn;is three / &amp; haues
made him til knawe &thorn;e peril &thorn;at he is inne: &thorn;en he conceyues a ferdenesse of
goddes auful dome; &amp; &thorn;are-thorugh he bigynnes til forthinke: &thorn;at euer he did
ille, &amp; couaitis til amend him thorugh goddis grace / &thorn;at steres him til flee &thorn;e
ille, &amp; gif him til &thorn;e gode; &amp; &thorn;en comes grace folowand til helpe &thorn;e gode wille
of man: to fulfil it in dede.  For &thorn;ofe man haue a gode wille til do &thorn;e gode /
thorugh grace bifore-sterand &thorn;e gode wille: &yogh;it mai he noght do in dede
with-oute goddis grace folowand &amp; helpand.  &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;e apostle affermes bi him-selfe: &thorn;are he says: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Non autem ego: set gracia dei mecum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;&thorn;e gode &thorn;at i do is noght: bot goddis grace dose it with me&raquo;, als if he said: &laquo;na gode mai i do: bot if goddis grace me helpe&raquo;.  Gode wille is als hand-maiden til grace: to wirke al hire wille.  Goddis grace whare it is: wil noght be vnnayt, bot euer wirkand / &amp; waxand ai mare &amp; mare: til mikel &thorn;e mede.  For-&thorn;i do we as &thorn;e apostle vs redis: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hortamur vos fratres: ne in vacuum graciam dei rec[ipiatis],</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;I prai &yogh;ow &amp; biddes &yogh;ow as mi brether in god, &thorn;at &yogh;ee resceyue noght goddis grace in vayne&raquo;.  He resceyues goddis grace in vayne: &thorn;at notis it noght in gode / when god sendis it til him; &amp; &thorn;erfore percase: he sal neuer after wynne &thorn;erto. // Ysidore telles of a litel flie: &thorn;at is cald Saura, &amp; &thorn;is flie bitakenes grace bifore-sterand.  &THORN;e kynde of &thorn;is flie: is til be enemi til alle wormes of venyme;
swa &thorn;at whare he sees ani worme to-ward man til stang him &thorn;are he slepes in
wildernes: he flies bifore to &thorn;e man &amp; lightis opon his face / &amp; bites him a litell; &amp; &thorn;are-thorugh he<MILESTONE N="43" UNIT="folio"> wakys: or &thorn;e beste come til stange him.  Bi &thorn;is Saura: is
vnderstanden grace &thorn;at god sendis til man: agayn &thorn;e fandynges of &thorn;e fende / &thorn;at
stanges oft venemously; it cries apon &thorn;e: as &thorn;e apostle sais in &thorn;is wordes: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Surge qui dormis, &amp; exurge a mortuis: &amp; illuminabit te Christus,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;Rise &thorn;ou &thorn;at slepis in synne, wakyn &amp; rise fra &thorn;i deade: &amp; Crist sal help &thorn;e thorugh his worthi grace&raquo;.  Bot &thorn;e vnkynd dose agayn &thorn;is grace / &amp; fordose it: als Virgil did with &thorn;is litell flie: &thorn;at sauid him fra &thorn;e deade.  He lai at slepe: &amp; a neddre come til him-ward / til stang him, bot &thorn;is flie Saura flied bifore &amp; lightid on his forheuid &amp; prikkid him a litell, &amp; &thorn;are-with he wakenid: als &thorn;e neddre come; bot &thorn;is Virgil in his wakenynge / he felid his forheuid smerte: &amp; smate him-selfe in &thorn;e


<PB N="136">

fronte / &amp; swa he slogh &thorn;e flie; &amp; &thorn;us he qwitte him his seruice: &thorn;at sauid his life.  For-&thorn;i / fordo &thorn;ou noght goddis grace / when it comes to &thorn;e: til warne &thorn;e
of &thorn;i harme / &amp; stere &thorn;e til gode.  Fayn aght man to be of goddis grace: when
god sendis it til him, &amp; til &yogh;eme ful warli: so riche a gifte; for grace is erlis of
&thorn;at lastand ioie: &thorn;at is to come; as &thorn;e apostle says: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracia dei: vita eterna,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;goddis grace is as help &amp; waie: to &thorn;e lastand life&raquo;.  For-&thorn;i he settis grace bifore as waie &thorn;at ledis til lastand ioie; &amp; als a wedde if we kepe it wele: til make in vs sikernesse of endelesse ioie; as &thorn;e apostle sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui dedit pignus spiritum suum in corporibus nostris,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;god has gyuen til vs &thorn;e hali gaste / as wedde of &thorn;e endeles ioie&raquo;.  Hald we &thorn;en &thorn;is heuenli wedde: &amp; note we it wele in werke; for wele is vs in &thorn;is life: if goddis grace vs lede; &amp; when grace vs leuis: we faile of &thorn;at wele.  For-&thorn;i / fordo we in vs thorugh help of grace: al &thorn;at is agayn grace / be it lesse or mare: &thorn;at oure skille sais is agayn goddis wille, &thorn;at is, al &thorn;at synne is: or mai stere to synne; &amp; haue we forthynkynge in herte / schrifte in mouthe / &amp; gaynstandynge: with wille til neauer turne agayne.</P>
</DIV3>

<DIV3 N="Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="305"><HEAD>Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD><MILESTONE N="240" UNIT="folio"><HEAD TYPE="sub">De gracia dei</HEAD>
<OPENER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Assit principio sancta Maria meo.</FOREIGN></OPENER>

<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<P>Off goddis grace stirrand and helpand, and &thorn;at na thyng may be
done with-owttene grace.
</P>
<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracia dei vita eterna, ad R<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. V<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>: thir are &thorn;e wordis of &thorn;e haly appostill saynt Paule; &thorn;at thus are on Ynglysche: &laquo;&thorn;e grace of god es lastand lyfe&raquo;. Grace &thorn;e appostille settis be-fore as ledare, ffor with-owttyne wyssynge &amp; stirrynge of grace nane may wyne to &thorn;e lastand lyfe: for als saynt Austyne sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omne bonum nostrum nichil facit in nobis nisi gracia dei,</FOREIGN> &laquo;alle &thorn;e gude we do to wyne with heuenly mede, grace by-fore sent it makis&raquo;; for ellis oure dedis are noghtes bot als false moneye whare-with mene may noghte by. And for-thi wene we no gud to do with-owttyne grace, or &yogh;it haue gud wille,
for noghte es gud &thorn;at mane dose &thorn;ofe it gude seme, bot goddes grace it
lede.  This the prophete witnes be god &thorn;are he sayse thus: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Scio domine quia non est via hominis vt ambulet et dirigat gressus suos:</FOREIGN> &laquo;I knawe wele, lorde, sayse the prophete, &thorn;at the gude wayes of mane are [noght] of hyme-selfe, to styrre his fotsteppis to walke in the waye&raquo;.  For-thi wete &thorn;ay wele the fende &thorn;ame foully bygylis, that wenys by &thorn;ame-selfe any gude to do, with-owttene grace byfore commande and stirande &thorn;e gude, &amp; by-twene seand &amp; helpande.  And &thorn;at this be sothe, god thurgh &thorn;e prophete sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Perdicio tua ex te Israel; in me est auxilium tuum:</FOREIGN> &laquo;Of thi-selfe, he sayse, &thorn;ou hase &thorn;at &thorn;ou may be loste, bot
with-owttyne my grace helpande bese &thorn;ou neuer saufe&raquo;.  Goddes grace command
to mane wirkis in hym whare-thurgh he may be saufe, &thorn;at in his firste commyng
fyndes in mane whare-fore he myghte hym d&amacr;mpne thurgh his ryghtewys dome.
Whate garte oure forme-ffadir Paradyse wyne of Cryste, &thorn;at with his blody handis
was done one the croyse? now certis bot grace helpande, &thorn;at stirrid hyme &thorn;at
tyme to forthynke hys syne &amp; made hym mercy to crye for his mysdede.
</P>
<P>Off thre degrees of grace fynde we in haly write.  For &thorn;e begynnyng of
oure speche es of grace, it es for to wete of thre degrees of grace.  Ane &thorn;er es &thorn;at
till creatours es comone, that god gyffes till all creatours to vp-halde &thorn;ame with,
and this es called goddis helpe freely gyffene till all creatours; and for-owttene


<PB N="306">

this gyfte of grace creatours may noghte do, ne laste in thayre kynde.  For als
&thorn;ou may se &thorn;at water es mad hate thurgh strenghe of ffyre, &amp; with-drawe &thorn;e
fyre &thorn;are-fraa, it turnes agayne als it was &amp; by-commes calde: righte sa it fares
of creatours, als saynt Austyne sayse: &laquo;All creatours, als &thorn;ay are of noghte made,
bot if god &thorn;ame vp-halde thurghe his grace in &thorn;at &thorn;ay ere, worthe to noghte
with-in a littill stounde&raquo;.  &THORN;is vndirstode &thorn;e appostill by skill, &amp; for-thi he sayse:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracia dei sum id quod sum,</FOREIGN> &laquo;thurgh goddes grace, quod he, I am &thorn;at I am,
anely thurgh goddes grace alle this I haue&raquo;.  // Bot &thorn;ar es ano&thorn;er grace of god
&amp; mare specyale, &thorn;at god gyffes till ilk mane &thorn;at es gud &amp; skilfull creature, do
it wha sa will: and this grace standis euer at the &yogh;ates of oure hertis &amp; knokkes
on oure fre will and byddes late hym Ine.  This sayse god &thorn;at he duse &thorn;er he
thus sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ego sto ad hostium &amp; pulso;</FOREIGN> he standis, he sayse, at &thorn;e dore of thyne herte &amp; knokkes &thorn;at &thorn;ou late hym Ine.  &amp; this es calde goddes grace frely gyffene to mane or he &thorn;er-after serue; &thorn;at thurgh stirrynge of this grace mane graythe hym swa &thorn;at he be worthy to resceyue &thorn;e gyfte of &thorn;e haly gaste, &thorn;at euer stirres the to &thorn;e gude &amp; calles fra &thorn;e the ille of man&macr;s free wille.
</P>
<P>TWa thynges are nedfull to &thorn;e hele of manes saule.  The firste es &thorn;is [grace]
&thorn;at I now of speke, the to&thorn;er es manes fre wyll accordand &thorn;er-till: &amp; with-owttene thir twa na mane may do, thurgh oghte &thorn;at in hym es, &thorn;at helpe hym
sulde to &thorn;e hele of his saule.  For no&thorn;er free will forowtene this grace stirrande,
ne this grace forowttene free will assentande &amp; helpeand, noghte may do &thorn;at god
may paye.  For saynt Austyne sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui fecit te sine te, non viuificabit te sine te,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es at say: &laquo;he &thorn;at made the with-owttene the, he wille noghte make the
ryghtwyse to be bot if &thorn;ou will helpe &thorn;er-to&raquo;.  And &thorn;ofe &thorn;e fre will of mane
ne may not mak the grace of god in mane, neuer-the-lesse do mane &thorn;at in hym
es and graythe hym swa, &thorn;at he be redy &amp; abyll to resceyue &thorn;e grace whene it
commes.  Als &thorn;ou may see by thi-selfe if &thorn;ou ware in a myrke house one the
daye, &amp; alle the thirlles, dores &amp; wyndows ware stokyne, &thorn;at na sone myght enter:
if &thorn;ou stod styll &amp; walde noghte late &thorn;e sonne come In, wha were to blame if
&thorn;e house were myrke? for if &thorn;ou opynde the dores and wyndouse, als-tyte &thorn;e
sone walde come Ine &amp; lyghte alle &thorn;e house.  For-thi wyte nane bot thi-selfe
if &thorn;ou gracelese be; ffor saynt Anselme sayse: &laquo;Man wanttes noghte &thorn;is grace,
for god gyffes it hyme; bot he hafes it noghte, &amp; whi? for he resceyues it noghte,
&amp; &thorn;at es, for he redies hym noghte to resceyue &thorn;is grace als he sulde; for if
he graythede hym als he sulde, with-owttene grace ware he noghte&raquo;.  God es
no chynche of his grace, for he hase &thorn;erof ynoghe&mdash;for if he dele it neuer sa
ferre ne to sa many, &yogh;itt leues hym neuer &thorn;e lesse; ffor it wanttis bot clene
vesselle to resceyue it.  For-[&thorn;i] saynt Austyne sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Deus ingenti libertate atque vbertate replet omnes creaturas, in capacitate earum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say:
&laquo;God thurgh the gret fredome of his mekill grace helpfull: fillis alle creaturs
after &thorn;at &thorn;ay are abyll to resceyue his grace&raquo;.  If mane opene his herte to this
[grace] when god it sendis to hym, in werke he walde it schewe, with-owttene
any drede.  For-thi the appostill by hym-selfe sayse whene he hys grace had
wonn&macr;e: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracia eius in me vacua non fuit,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es: &laquo;&thorn;e grace &thorn;at god hase me gyfene es noghte vanyte in me&raquo;, ffor he noted euer in werke &thorn;e grace &thorn;at he


<PB N="307">

hade.  We felawchipe with god of hys grace als merchaundes duse to-gedir &thorn;at
hase chafere in mene: ffor god settis his grace agayne oure werke, to chafere
with &thorn;ame bathe; bot for his dede he will noghte elles, be &thorn;e byet neuer sa
gret, bot louynge &amp; thankynge, &amp; alle &thorn;e prowe he will &thorn;at mane haue &thorn;at
&thorn;erof may ryse.  Bot many fandis to be-gyle god &amp; refe hym his dale, &thorn;at will
be loued of mene for &thorn;ayre gud dede; &amp; for-thi are &thorn;ay worthi to lose if &thorn;ay
any gude hafe, for &thorn;ay stele fra &thorn;aire lorde &thorn;at falles to his dale.  Agaynes
whayme god sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gloriam meam alteri non dabo,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to saye: &laquo;the wirchipe
&thorn;at falles to me I will gyffe nane o&thorn;er&raquo;.  / And forthi &thorn;at oure speche es now of
manes fre will, &thorn;ou sall vndirstande &thorn;at &thorn;er es called ffre will of mane, &thorn;at frely
may turne to gude or till ille, &thorn;at mane wele knawes.
</P>
<P>THre statys are of mane: be-fore syne; &amp; efter [manes syne]; and efter mane es
confermed, that [es] efter mane es departede owte of this dedly lyfe and wone to that
Ioy &thorn;at neuer sall hafe ende.  Mannes will was mare fre in the firste state &thorn;an in
the secunde, and in the thirde mare free thane in the firste or in the secunde.  In &thorn;e
firste state, by-fore mane synned, was mannes will so fre &thorn;at he myghte syne &amp; noghte syne; in his free will it was whethir sa he wolde do wele or ille.  In
the laste state, &thorn;at es confermede, &thorn;an sall mane noghte mow syne ne do ill
one none-kyn wyse.  In the secund state, in &thorn;e wylke he may syne and may
noghte bot he syne: manes will es fre till ill, to it be streyned &amp; turned agayne
with grace; and whene grace ledis &thorn;e will, &thorn;ane es it free to wirke &thorn;e gude.
Euer es manes will fre: bot be-fore grace it es free to wirke &thorn;e ill, &amp; thurgh
grace it es made fre to wirke &thorn;e gude; and &thorn;us es mannes will fre euer one
some wyse.  Bot mannes will es noght gude, bot it be fre fra syne, thus es
mannes fre will fyled with syne.  For-thi by-fore &thorn;at mane synnede, na lettynge
hade he &thorn;at myghte marre hyme to do &thorn;e gude.  Bot now slyke a bro&thorn;er hase
syne copled with oure flesche &thorn;at saynt Paule calles <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Legem carnis,</FOREIGN> &laquo;&thorn;e lawe of &thorn;e flesche&raquo;, &thorn;at es mayster of the flesche, swa &thorn;at euer he withstandis goddis lawe in alle &thorn;at he may; &thorn;at lettis oure will to assente to &thorn;e gude &amp; stirris &thorn;ame to &thorn;e ill, &thorn;at he may noghte wirke &thorn;e gude, bot if grace helpe &amp; vse hym owte of syne.  Ilke a mane, or he syne, hase a fre will to folowe &thorn;e fendis rede or goddes rede whethir sa he chesys: bot fra mane thurgh werke of syne byndes
hym to &thorn;e fende, he ne may thurgh na myghte of hyme-selfe wyne owte of his
bandes; and &thorn;ane he fares as a schippe &thorn;at thurgh tempeste hase loste alle &thorn;at
sulde hyme helpe, and es castene fra wawe to wawe whedir tempeste hym dryues.
And righte swa it es by mane &thorn;at goddes grace wanttis fra he be fallene in
dedely syne: he duse noghte &thorn;at he walde, bot aye waywes fra hande to hande
at the fendis will, and bot god gyffe hym grace to ryse owte of his synne, he
sall be lefte in syne till his lyfes end; and efter he sall be loste bathe lyfe &amp; saule, and dampned till endeles pynne.  And this may &thorn;ou see in werldly thynges:
nane may make hym-selfe kynge bot &thorn;e folke of &thorn;e comone chese &thorn;ame slyke a
kynge als &thorn;ay walde hafe; bot whene he es chosene of &thorn;e folke and confermede
in his rewme, &thorn;ane slyke powere he hase ouer &thorn;ame &thorn;at hym chase, &thorn;at, be he
neuer sa ill to &thorn;ame, &thorn;ay may noghte do hym doune, bot if it be thurgh o&thorn;er
&thorn;at hase mare powere &thorn;ane he; and thus thurghe &thorn;aire awene chose,<MILESTONE N="242" UNIT="folio"> be


<PB N="308">

he neuer so ill, nedly by-houys &thorn;ame thole.  Ryght so mane, or he syne, hase
a fre will to chese whe&thorn;er he will be vndir god or &thorn;e fende.  Bot whene he
cheses with his will &thorn;e fend to serue, efter he may noghte whene he will come
owte of his banddis, &amp; swa &thorn;e firste fre will in till nedfulnes turnes.  And one
&thorn;is maner werldly mene sayse &thorn;at are boundene in syne to &thorn;ame &thorn;at consaylles
&thorn;ame to amend &thorn;aire lyfe: &laquo;fayne we walde ryse, &thorn;ay say, bot we may noghte&raquo;, ne &thorn;ay ne may thurgh myghte of &thorn;ame-selfe; bot thurghe goddes grace helpand &thorn;ay may.
</P>
<P>The thirde grace es maste specyalle, ffor it es noght gyffene to ilke skilfull
creature bot anely to tha &thorn;at resceyues &thorn;e secunde grace &amp; with &thorn;aire fre will
filles it inded, &amp; may say by &thorn;ame-selfe als saynt Paule sayde: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracia eius vacua non fuit in me,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es at say: &laquo;goddes grace ne was noghte vanyte in me&raquo;.  And
saynt Austyne sayse &thorn;at god in vs wyrkande fulfillis &thorn;at he thurgh grace stirrand
by-gane in vs: for now&thorn;er with-owttene hym helpande may we do gude vn-till
oure-selfe ne till hyme pay.  And this by-houes be thoghte by-fore, for god sayse
hym-selfe: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sine me nichil potestis facere:</FOREIGN> &laquo;with-owttene helpe of my grace, he sayse, &yogh;e may noghte spede ne do&raquo;.  Goddes grace stirrande gase be-fore gud will, &amp; stirres hyme to do &thorn;e gude &amp; leue his syne.
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Whate grace dose whene he vesettis mannes saule.</HEAD>

<P>Grace, whene he firste commes to vesete mans saule, he wakkyns hyme als
of a slomerynge &thorn;at lange hase lyggene in syne: and spyrres at hyme with thre
scharpe worddes, sayande: &laquo;Whare art &thorn;ou, he sayse, and whethene commes &thorn;ou,
and whedir wendis &thorn;ou?&raquo;  Firste he sayse: &laquo;Whare arte &thorn;oue?&raquo;, als wa say: &laquo;Vmbythynke the, vnhappy wreche, how foule &thorn;ou arte dounne castyne, &amp; whate perelle &thorn;ou arte in; for thurgh thi syne &thorn;ou arte fallene in till thyne enemys
handes, &thorn;at ouer all thynge couaytes to wyrke the waa; and noghte may helpe
ne delyuer the owt of thy faaes handes, bot almyghtty god thi gud lorde, &thorn;at
&thorn;ou hase forsakene&raquo;.  Sythene he spyrres &amp; sayse: &laquo;Whethyne commes &thorn;ou?&raquo;, als [if] he till the sayd: &laquo;&THORN;ou wrechid caytefe, by-halde all thi lyfe als &thorn;ou hase wastede it in syne: thou commes fra &thorn;e fendis tauerne of helle.  Whare es alle &thorn;e gudes god hase &thorn;e gyffene to [help] &thorn;e &amp; wirchipe hym with? sa saryly &thorn;ou hase &thorn;ame loste so riche als thi lord the made, &amp; &thorn;ou arte by-comene a pure wriche&raquo;.  Sythene he spyrres: &laquo;Whedir weyndis &thorn;ou?&raquo;  &laquo;Wafull wreche&raquo;, he sayse, &laquo;&thorn;ou wyendis to &thorn;e wafull dome &thorn;at he demes to wofull wreches; for als &thorn;ou hase seruede, ryghte swa sall &thorn;ou be demyde.  Sa awefull &thorn;are-to &thorn;ou sall god see, &thorn;at &thorn;ou sall be [for] ferde owt of thi wytte, and to &thorn;e montaynnes &amp; hillis &thorn;ou sall luke &amp; crye with a grylle voyce &amp; pray &thorn;ame &thorn;at &thorn;ay one the falle &amp; hyde the, &thorn;at &thorn;ou noghte one hym see.  Wafull wreche, &thorn;ou wendis till helle, &amp; &thorn;ou do forthe als &thorn;ou hase by-gonne.  Whare &thorn;ou sall wende es fyre, so hate brynnande &amp; sa wodly, &thorn;at all the water of &thorn;e see, if it thorowe it rane, &thorn;e leste sparke of the fyre it myghte neuer slokene.  For &thorn;ou stynkkes here to godd for thi foule synnes, &thorn;arefore &thorn;ou sall fele foule stynke &thorn;are lastande for euer; &amp; for &thorn;ou luffed here myrknes &amp; ay to be in syne, thare sall &thorn;ou fele so thikke myrkenes &thorn;at &thorn;ou may


<PB N="309">

it grape; &amp; ffor &thorn;ou restede the here in syne agaynes goddes will, thare sall &thorn;ou
wepe ma thykkere &amp; more glowande teres thene motes ere in the sonne; a
thowsande of thowsande&yogh; &yogh;eris payne sall &thorn;ou thole, euer payne after payne, to
newe thy waa&raquo;.  // Whene goddes grace hase styrrede mane and wakkenede
hyme with thir thre, &amp; hase mad hyme to knawe the perelle &thorn;at he es in: thane
he conseyues a ferdenes of goddes awefull dome, &amp; &thorn;are-thorowe he be-gynnes
to sorowe &thorn;at euer he dyd amyse, and &yogh;ernys to amende hyme, thurgh goddes
grace &thorn;at stirres hym to fle &thorn;e euyll &amp; gyf hym to do &thorn;e gude.  Than commes
grace folowande to helpe &thorn;e gud will of mane to fulfill it in dede.  For &thorn;ofe &thorn;ou,
mane, hafe a gud will to do &thorn;e gude thurgh grace byfore stirrande, the gud will
&thorn;ou may noghte do in dede with-owttene goddes grace folouande &amp; helpeande.
And [&thorn;at] the appostill affermes by hym-selfe &thorn;are he &thorn;us sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Non autem Ego, sed gracia dei mecum:</FOREIGN> &laquo;the gud I do es noghte, he sayse, bot goddes grace
do it with me&raquo;, as if he sayde: &laquo;na gude may I do if ne goddes grace me
helpe&raquo;.  Than es gud we do &thorn;e firste &thorn;at grace stirres oure wyll to do, and
sythene thurgh grace feloande to wyrke gude: &amp; thane hase &thorn;ou &thorn;at grace &thorn;at
gase by-fore gud will, and gude wyll es als a hande-maydene to grace to wyrke
alle hir wille.  Goddes grace, &thorn;are he es, will noghte be vnmayte, bot euer he
es wyrkkande; and he es waxeand ay mare &amp; mare, to mekill the mede.  For-thi
of this helpand grace sayse saynt Paule: &laquo;Goddes grace es noghte vanyte in me&raquo;.
Note we &thorn;an this grace &thorn;at god vs sendis, &thorn;at god for-thynke hym noghte of
his sande &amp; haue it euer in pyne for we note it noghte.  For-thi do we als the
appostill vs redis &thorn;are he sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hortamur vos, fratres, ne in vacuum graciam dei recipiatis:</FOREIGN> &laquo;I pray &yogh;ow, he sayse, &amp; byddes &yogh;owe als my brethir in god, &thorn;at &yogh;e
resceyue noghte [goddis] grace in vayne, &thorn;at notes it noghte in gud whene god till
&yogh;ow it sendis&raquo;.  For percas if &thorn;ou it with-skape &amp; it tyne, &thorn;ou sall neuer after &thorn;er-till wyne.  // Isodere telles of a littill fle &thorn;at es called Saura, &amp; this fle by-takyns grace be-fore stirrand; whase kynd it es &thorn;at he [es] enemy to all wormes of venome, sa &thorn;at whare he seese any worme to-warde mane for to stange hyme whare he
slepis in wildirnes or in woddes, he flees by-fore to &thorn;e mane, or &thorn;e worme hym
stange, and lyghttes appone &thorn;e slepand face and byttes hym a lyttill, &amp; &thorn;ar-thurgh he wakyns hym or &thorn;e best comme, &thorn;at he may be warre or he be
stangede.  Now by this Saura es vndirstande grace &thorn;at god sendis to mane, agayne
the fandynge&yogh; of &thorn;e fende &thorn;at ofte venemosely stangges; he cryes appone the
als &thorn;e appostill witnes in [t]his wordes &amp; sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Surge qui dormis, &amp; exsurge a mortuis, &amp; illuminabit te Christus;</FOREIGN> he sayse: &laquo;ryse &thorn;ou [&thorn;at] slepis so faste, owt
of thi syne wakkene &amp; ryse fra thi dede: &amp; Criste sall helpe the thurgh his
dere-worthi grace&raquo;.  Bot the vnkynde creatours duse agayne &thorn;is grace, &amp; for-duse it with-alle, als Vergill did with this littill flee &thorn;at I are of spake, &thorn;at saued
hym fra &thorn;e dede.  He this Virgill als he slepid, a neddere come to hyme-warde
for to stang hyme, as it es his kynde.  Bot this littill flee, &thorn;is Saura, &thorn;at sawe
&thorn;e neddire, flow by-fore &amp; lyghtted in his forheuede &amp; prykede hyme a littill:
&amp; &thorn;are-with he wakenede, ryghte als &thorn;e worme come.  Bot &thorn;is Virgill in his
wakynnynge he feled his forheued smerte: he smate hym-selfe in &thorn;e fronte, &amp; sa he slewe &thorn;e fle, &amp; &thorn;us qwyte he hym his gud seruyse &thorn;at sauede his lyfe.


<PB N="310">

For-thi for-do &thorn;ou noghte grace whene he to &thorn;e commes to warne &thorn;e of thi
harme &amp; stirre &thorn;e to &thorn;e gude.  Fayne aughte mane to be of goddes grace whene
god sendis it to hym, and sa riche a gyfte of god warely to &yogh;eme; for bot man
hafe goddes grace in this dedly lyfe &amp; reule hym &thorn;er-after, wele better it ware
to hyme &thorn;at he ware vnborne, &thorn;an lyfe with-owttene grace.  For grace es harls
of &thorn;at lastand Ioye &thorn;at is to come, als &thorn;e appostill sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracia dei vita eterna:</FOREIGN>
&laquo;Goddes grace, he sayse, es als helpe &amp; waye to ay-lastand lyfe&raquo;: &amp; for-thi he settis grace by-fore as waye &thorn;at ledis to &thorn;e lastande lyfe &amp; Ioye, &amp; als a wedde, if we it wele &yogh;eme, to make in it sekirnes of Endles Ioy to welde, als &thorn;e appostill sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui dedit pingnus spiritum suum in corporibus nostris:</FOREIGN> &laquo;God, he sayse, hase gyffene till vs &thorn;e halygaste als a wedde here in vs to welde of &thorn;at Endles Ioye&raquo;.  Halde we &thorn;ane this heuenly wede &amp; note it wele in werke, and schape oure lyfe &thorn;are-after, in whate sa we do.  For wele es vs in &thorn;is lyfe whiles goddis grace vs ledis; ffor whene grace vs leues, we faile of &thorn;at wele.  For-thi for-do
we in vs thurgh helpe of grace alle &thorn;at es agaynes grace what so euer it be,
lesse or mare, &thorn;at oure synfull witte sayse es agaynes goddes will; ffor-do we
&thorn;ane by-dene, &thorn;at &thorn;ay lettis vs noghte to accorde to goddes will; &thorn;at es, &thorn;at
we fordo all &thorn;at syne es, or &thorn;at may stirre to syne, with forthynkkynge of herte
&amp; scrifte of mouthe &amp; withstandyng with will neuer to turne agayne.
</P></DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="136"><HEAD>Our Daily Work</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="Arundel 507" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD>Ms. Arundel 507</HEAD>
<P><NOTE><P>The following "false start" to "Our Daily Work" is found in the MS several folios in advance of the complete text printed below: <Q><MILESTONE N="48" UNIT="folio">"Thre thinges are nedeful: til mykel mannes mede with.  &THORN;e first: &thorn;at he be
in honeste werke: with-oute losynge of his tyme / &thorn;at is schorte; &amp; despend
noght &thorn;e tyme in idelnesse: &thorn;at god haues gyuen him til serue him inne: &amp; gedere tresore of grace / til bie heuen with.  Noght aneli oure tyme is schorte:
bot alswa oure elde flees as &thorn;e wiseman sais: Nostra etas volat.  And saynt
Gregor sais: &laquo;oure life is like a man in a schippe: sitte he / stand he / slepe
he / wake he: eauer is he &thorn;iderward / as &thorn;e schip dryues with &thorn;e strinth of &thorn;e


<PB N="137">

weder.  Swa we in &thorn;is schorte life / what-so we do: we dryue ai til oure ende.
Als, oure enemy, &thorn;at is &thorn;e deade: folows vs atte &thorn;e bak with a scharp spere, as
Senek sais: Vita fugit: &amp; mors sequitur.  And saynt Austyn sais, &thorn;at &laquo;life is bot
a swift rennynge, to &thorn;e dead&raquo;.  For-&thorn;i is it noght to telle bi how lange a man
lifes: bot how wele. // &THORN;e second is: &thorn;at he do his werke with a fredome of
hert &amp; spirite / in stede &amp; tyme &thorn;at til ilke werke fallis. // &THORN;e .III. is: &thorn;at his
vtter berynge whare-so he comes / be so honeste &amp; faire: &thorn;at louynge be to
god / &amp; sterynge of gode / til alle &thorn;at &thorn;aim sees; for swa biddes &thorn;e apostle:
Omnia in vobis honeste &amp; secundum ordinem fiant, &thorn;at is: &laquo;&THORN;at &yogh;ee do: honestli
be it done &amp; in ordre&raquo;."</Q></P></NOTE></P>
<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio">
<P>T[h]ree thinges are nedeful til ilk man: til mikil his mede / &thorn;urgh goddis
grace helpand: &thorn;at him sal lede.  &THORN;e first: &thorn;at man be in honest werke /
with-oute losyng of his tyme. / &THORN;e .II.: &thorn;ai he his werk do with a fredome of spirite,
in stede &amp; in tyme / als til ilk werk fallis. / &THORN;e .III.: &thorn;at his vtter beryng whare-so
he comes / be so honest &amp; faire: &thorn;at louyng be to god / &amp; steryng of gode / til
alle &thorn;at him sees, as &thorn;e apostle biddis: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnia in vobis honeste / &amp; secundum
ordinem fiant,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;&THORN;at &yogh;e do: honestli, &amp; in ordre be it done&raquo;.
</P>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Prima pars libri]</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>Atte &THORN;e first: man sal loke &thorn;at he tyne noght his schort tyme, nor wrang
dispend it, nor in idelnesse: lat it ouer-passe.  God has lent man &thorn;is tyme: to
serue god in, &amp; to gedere with gode werkes grace: til bi heuen with.  Noght
aneli &thorn;is schorte tyme flees fra vs: bot al-swa oure elde / as &thorn;e wiseman sais:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nostra etas volat.</FOREIGN>  And saynt Gregor sais: &laquo;oure lif is like a man in a schip; sit
he / stand he / slepe he / wake he: euer he is &thorn;iderward &thorn;er &thorn;e schip dryues / with
strynth of &thorn;e weder&raquo;.  Swa we in &thorn;is schorte tyme, what so we do: we dryue
euer til oure ende&raquo;.  And oure enemy / &thorn;e dead / folows vs ai at &thorn;e bak: with
a scharp spere til stike vs thorugh ffor-&thorn;i sais Seneke: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vita fugit, mors sequitur.</FOREIGN>
And saynt Austyn sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nichil aliud est vita: quam velox cursus ad mortem.</FOREIGN>
For-&thorn;i is noght to tell bi / how lang man lifs: bot how wele.  &YOGH;it &thorn;is schorte life
is vncertayn: how lange it sal last; ffor-&thorn;i sais Iob: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nescio quamdiu subsistam, &amp; si post modicum tollat me factor meus.</FOREIGN>  And saynt Gregor sais: &laquo;I ne wate &thorn;e tyme i sal dwell, ne when i sal be taken heyn &amp; led to &thorn;e dome&raquo;.  And saynt Ierom sais: &laquo;na thing so mikil bigilis man: as &thorn;at he knowis noght &thorn;e tyme of his life / &thorn;at to him is vncertayn&raquo;. &amp; &yogh;it hightis he him-self lang life: as he might at his will / dryue dead obake.  &THORN;us was &thorn;e riche man deceyuid of wham &thorn;e gospel spekis of saynt Luke XVIo.  For-&thorn;i biddis &thorn;e psalme: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diuicie si affluant: nolite cor apponere.</FOREIGN>  For riches failis &amp; lastis noght with man: bot glidis awai as
fantoum.  Bot when men has getin godes to-gedir / with right or wrange / &amp; pouer
mennis malisons: &thorn;en sodaynli &thorn;ai ga fra &thorn;aire godes / or ellis &thorn;e godes fra &thorn;aim.


<PB N="138">

And hali writte sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mundus transibit: &amp; concupiscencia eius.</FOREIGN>  A man &thorn;at is fallin in &thorn;e water / &amp; thorugh strinht of &thorn;e water is borne forth &amp; reft &thorn;e gronde: if he mai gete ani thing &thorn;at has gode festenynge / as rote or stake: he mai lete &thorn;e water to bere him forth bot bi &thorn;at thing &thorn;at fletis as he dose: mai he
noght festyn him. &amp; sotheli, wil we nil we, in &thorn;is lif as in a water / with &thorn;e
godis of &thorn;is werld / eauer are we passand, &amp; noght is in &thorn;is werld to festyn vs
bi: &thorn;at we ne sal pas; ffor &thorn;e wis man sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnes morimur, &amp; quasi aqua dilabimur in terram.</FOREIGN>  And Iob sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ego opulentus quondam, repente contritus sum, &amp; ecce leues amici mei transierunt, &amp; semitam quam non reuertor ambulo;</FOREIGN> and is as if he said: &laquo;Richesse &amp; frendes had i mani, bot<MILESTONE N="55" UNIT="folio">&thorn;ai all might noght lete: &thorn;at me ne bihouid wende forth / with-oute agayn-come&raquo;.  And bi whilk pase man sal wende: &thorn;e prophete schewis: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnis caro fenum, &amp; omnis gloria eius: quasi flos agri,</FOREIGN> &laquo;Mannis flesh / is as hay, &amp; al his ioi &amp; noblay: as &thorn;e flour of &thorn;e medow&raquo;. Hay: first is grene gresse, &amp; sone after: bringes forth floures; &amp; a while after: &thorn;e floures dries &amp; fallis; after: is it mowen doune with &thorn;e sithe, &amp; dried &amp; led to house / to bestes fode.  &THORN;us it fallis bi man; in his childhede: he springis &amp; waxis as dose &thorn;e gres; after / he waxis to man &amp; floris in fairenes &amp; strinth &amp; wite &amp; hafyng of godes; after / he drawis til elde, &amp; &thorn;en failis his flouris, &thorn;at are / his vertu&yogh;, fairehede / strinth / wite &amp; o&thorn;er vertu&yogh;; after / he is striken downe with &thorn;e sithe of deade, after led to house to bestes fode, &thorn;at is, duluen in erth to fede wormes. For-&thorn;i sais &thorn;e hali man: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cum moritur homo: habitabit serpentes &amp; bestias.</FOREIGN>  Man dead / is so wlatsome to &thorn;e werld: &thorn;at he mai nogh lat him be in his hous. .III. daies to-gider, bot beres him oute: &thorn;at he harme nane with stinke. / For-&thorn;i is it
now tyme for to wirke: ffor in &thorn;e tyme to come: is na tyme to swynke, bot to
receyue mede: for are-done dede.  And &thorn;is affermes &thorn;e angel with athe &amp; sais:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iurauit enim angelus / quod non erit tempus amplius.</FOREIGN>  Do we &thorn;en as &thorn;e apostle sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dum tempus habemus, operemur bonum ad omnes.</FOREIGN>  And as &thorn;e apostle redis vs: he did him-selfe: for fra &thorn;e first houre of &thorn;e daie: vn-to &thorn;e fift: he trauaild with his handes / til wyn his fode; &amp; fra &thorn;e fift to &thorn;e tende: he prechid to &thorn;e folke; fra &thorn;e x. til euen: he seruid &thorn;e pouer &amp; pilgrimes with swilk gode as he had; bi night: was he praiand; &amp; &thorn;us spend he his tyme. // In .III. maners / man tynes his tyme: In idelnes, or in werks &thorn;at na gode comes of, or in gode werks
bot noght ordeynd as &thorn;ai suld be.  Agayn idelnes: sais Salomon: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Multam maliciam docuit ociositas.</FOREIGN>  And hali write sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui sectatur ocium: stultissimus est.</FOREIGN>
A grete fole he is: &thorn;at forberis noght &thorn;e thing &thorn;at him harmis; Mare fole he is:
for he wynnis him na mede; Mast fole he is: for he wynnis him payne.  For-&thorn;i
god blamis &thorn;e idel: &amp; sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quid hic statis tota die ociosi?</FOREIGN>  Idelschip wastis &thorn;e godis &thorn;at are ware geten, &amp; tillis &thorn;e fend til hows; for als thorugh gode werkis &thorn;e fend is lettid til entre mannis herte: so idelnes drawis him in
&thorn;erto.  And Seneke sais: &laquo;he lifs noght to him-selfe: &thorn;at lifs to his wambe &amp; to eise of his flesh in al &thorn;at he mai&raquo;.  For Iob sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Homo ad laborem natus est.</FOREIGN>  To trauail was man bonden / after he had synnid: thorugh goddis biddinge / &thorn;at to him said:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In sudore v[ultus] t[ui] ves[ceris]pa[ne] tuo, donec reuertaris in terram de qua
assumptus es: quia de terra es: &amp; in terram ibis.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;ou sal trauail stalwordli &amp; noght fayntli, for he biddis &thorn;e trauail / &laquo;with swete of &thorn;i face, ay til &thorn;ou torne to &thorn;e erth&raquo;, &thorn;at is, al &thorn;i life-tyme, / &thorn;at &thorn;ou lose na tyme in idelnes.  Idelnes smitis a man as


<PB N="139">

he ware in paralsi, &amp; makis his lymes drie / &thorn;at he mai noght wirke.  For-&thorn;i
sais &thorn;e psalmwrighte: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Manus habent &amp; non pal[pabunt], pe[des] habent &amp; non
amb[ulabunt], os habent &amp; non lo[quentur], oculos h[abent] &amp; non v[idebunt], aures
h[abent] &amp; non audient;</FOREIGN> ffor &thorn;aire lymes are so bonden in syn: &thorn;at to all gode /
are &thorn;ai as deade; &amp; to il: are &thorn;ai light.  Idelnesse is norice til all vices, &amp; makis
man rekles to do: &thorn;at he is halden to do.  And when &thorn;e fend fyndis man idel: he
puttis in his hert / foule thoughtis of fleshli filth, or o&thorn;er folys &thorn;at mai bring him
to syn; after he eggis him til do &thorn;aim in dede.  &amp; &thorn;us he dose agayn &thorn;e apostles
biddyng, &thorn;at is: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nolite dare locum diabolo.</FOREIGN> / &THORN;e idel man makis him vnwhorthi to dwell in ani stede / bot hell.  In heuen mai he noght dwell: for heuen is ful mede to &thorn;a / &thorn;at here spendis &thorn;are tyme in werkis &thorn;at &thorn;ai hope are Criste to paie.  In purgatorie mai na idel dwell: for &thorn;are are aneli &thorn;e gode purgid / in &thorn;at clensand fire / til &thorn;ai be als klene of syn: as when &thorn;ai cristend ware; for-&thorn;i sais &thorn;e psalmwright: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In labore hominum non sunt: &amp; cum h[ominibus] non flag[ellabuntur].</FOREIGN>  Grete schame is to be idel in &thorn;is tyme of grace: in &thorn;e whilk we are hired to wirke, &amp; if we wirk as vs agh: grete mede vs abidis.  God gifs vs ensample to wirk: bi him-selfe, as &thorn;e apostle witnes &thorn;er he sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Exinaniuit semetipsum: for[mam] ser[ui] ac[cipiens]; in similitudinem hominum factus / &amp; habitu inuentus vt homo; humiliauit semetipsum factus obedi[ens] vsque ad m[ortem], m[ortem] autem cru[cis]: propter quod &amp; deus ex[altauit] il[lum] &amp; dedit il[li] nomen quod est s[uper] o[mne] nomen, vt in no[mine] Ihesu: omne ge[nu] fl[ectatur] ce[lestium] t[errestrium] &amp; inf[ernorum], &amp; omnis lingua con[fiteatur] quia dominus Iesus Christus in g[loria] est dei patris.</FOREIGN>
Ouer-proude &thorn;en &amp; ouer-delicate is &thorn;e seruant / &thorn;at in batail wil rest / &amp; sees his lauerd / of his enemys assailid &amp; iuel woundid. / Alswa vs agh to wirk in &thorn;is tyme
of grace: for we are goddis boght thrallis / with &thorn;e price of his deorworthi blode:
to wirk in his wyne-&yogh;erde. &amp; &yogh;it he hightis vs mede: if we do with gode will /
&thorn;at we thorugh dette agh for to do.  Til his priue frendis bifore &thorn;e tyme of grace:
god hight bot erthli godis / if &thorn;ai wele did; til vs: &thorn;e blisse of heuen / if we
wele do. &amp; if he hight ani of his priue frendis &thorn;e blisse of heuen: it was lang
after or &thorn;ai might come &thorn;erto, for &thorn;ai went to hell &amp; abade &thorn;are / some a
thousand &yogh;ere, some twa, some thre: or &thorn;ai til heuen come; bot now mai men
in a littil while wyn heuen, as if ani deie: sone after he is cristend, or if he hafe
done ful penance for his misdede, or be martird for goddis lufe.  The tyme of
soper &thorn;at &thorn;e gospel of saynt Luke spekis of / to &thorn;e whilk god bad his seruant&yogh;,
kall all &thorn;at ware bidden: is &thorn;e tyme of grace / &thorn;at is now, in &thorn;e whilk al is
redi; so &thorn;at &thorn;er is noght els to do: bot wash / &amp; ga to mete, &thorn;at is, clense &thorn;aim of all &thorn;aire synnes &thorn;at &thorn;ai hafe done / sen &thorn;ai ware borne. // What losyng of
tyme it is: to trauail aboute thinges &thorn;at na profit comes of! / Man agh to trauail
aneli to &thorn;e worschip of god: &amp; his saule-hele.  Thou sal noght deme &thorn;e man
has lang lifid / &thorn;of he gang with a stafe stoupand / &amp; be grai-harid: bot deme
him so halde / as he has wele lifid.  For-&thorn;i answerid Barlaham til Iosaphath his
disciple when he askid him how alde he was: &laquo;I am, quod he, of xlv &yogh;ere&raquo;.
&laquo;Maister, quod Iosaphath, me thinke &thorn;ou art of .lx. &yogh;ere &amp; mare&raquo;.  &THORN;an said<MILESTONE N="56" UNIT="folio">
Barlaham: &laquo;Sen I was borne: hase bien lx. &yogh;eres; bot &thorn;as &yogh;eres &thorn;at i spendid
in idelnes &amp; syn / or i toke me to &thorn;is life: I hald as &yogh;eres of dede.  Bot all
&thorn;as I tell &yogh;eres of life: &thorn;at i hafe seruid Ihesu Crist mi lauerd in / thorugh his
dereworthi grace&raquo;. / Wha-so wald vmthink him / what tyme stelis fra him in lang


<PB N="140">

etyng &amp; drynkyng / in outrage &amp; vnnayt werkis / idel speche / idel thought &amp; foule / vnnayt bourdis / &amp; o&thorn;er vanitees &thorn;at men delitis &thorn;aim in: he mai sotheli
vnderstand / &thorn;at &thorn;of he be alde of &yogh;eris: &thorn;at litill tyme he has lifid / of &thorn;e maner
he suld haf lifed; for he lifid noght til his profit / ne wan him mede / bot
peraunter payn / for losyng of tyme.
</P>
<P>// Wonder it ware &thorn;at man &thorn;at gifs him to bisynes of &thorn;e werld / mare &thorn;en
nedis: had na lettyng in praier, in rest of hert, in sothefastnes of worde, in
perfeccione of gode werks, in luf to god &amp; all cristen men.  For-&thorn;i hali men
bifore &thorn;is tyme &thorn;at knew &thorn;ir lettyngs: &thorn;ai fled &thorn;e werld with all &thorn;e vanitees / as
it had bien cursid, for &thorn;aim thoght &thorn;at &thorn;ai might noght lede rightwise life &thorn;erin;
&amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai went in to wildernesse / whare &thorn;ai trowid to serue god to paie.
For-&thorn;i sais Seneke: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Auarior redeo &amp; crudelior &amp; inhumanior: quia inter homines fui.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>&para; Thre maners of occupacions are, as sere Iangling &amp; mikil, Raykyng aboute,
Mikil trauailing aboute werldli thinges.  &para; Agayn mikil Iangling: sais Salomon:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui dimittit aquam: caput est iurgii.</FOREIGN>  &laquo;Lat &thorn;e water oute&raquo;: is lat &thorn;e tonge flete oute in Ianglinge.  Bot to &thorn;e knowyng of god / ne of him-selfe mai nane come: &thorn;at latis his hert flete oute / with mikil vnnaite speche; for he makis waie to &thorn;e fende in him-selfe.  &THORN;erfore Salomon likyns slike til a Cite with-outen wall:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sicut vrbs sine murorum ambitu: ita vir qui non potest cohibere spiritum in
loquendo.</FOREIGN>  And for so mikil lettyng of gode / is in mikil speche: &thorn;e Philosophir
byndis his discipils with silence / &thorn;aire first fyue &yogh;ere.  Alswa, abbot Agathon
bare .III. &yogh;ere a stane in his mouth / to lere to hald him still.  &para; Agayn &thorn;as &thorn;at
eauer raikis aboute to fede &thorn;aire wittis with vanitees and lustis: is &thorn;e leryng of
&thorn;e angel / how he lerde &thorn;e hali Abbote Arsenius &amp; said: &laquo;Arseni / flee &thorn;e werld &amp; his &yogh;ernyngs, hald &thorn;e in reste, bridil &thorn;i tonge&raquo;: &thorn;at it flete noght oute in Ianglynge / ne idel speche.  / Whare &thorn;ir .III. are: is waie to gode / &amp; with-drawynge fra iuel.  It tellis of an Abbot &thorn;at fulli .XX. &yogh;ere sat in his scole: &amp; neuer lift vp his heued to see &thorn;e scole-rouf.  &para; Agayn &thorn;as &thorn;at trauails ouer-mikil
aboute werldli godes: sais Salomon &thorn;us: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vana est spes eorum / &amp; labor eorum sine fructu: Quia nichil auferunt secum / de vniuerso labore suo.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;is is ilk dai sene: bi &thorn;e deade / &thorn;at with &thorn;aim beris / be &thorn;ai neuer so riche: bot a
wyndyng (cl)athe.  &para; &THORN;e thrid maner of men are / &thorn;at has likyng til do gode,
bot for &thorn;ai do it noght in &thorn;e maner &thorn;ai suld do it in: &thorn;ai lose &thorn;aire mede; for
are &thorn;aire entent fallis in ani gode dede: &thorn;e mede &thorn;at to &thorn;e gode werke suld
falle: failis.  And &thorn;at mai be on .iiii. Maners.  First / for &thorn;e wik[i]dnes of &thorn;e
wirkand; as &thorn;e offrand of Caym, &thorn;at &thorn;of he offird to god of &thorn;e frute &thorn;at him
newid: god wold noght loke &thorn;erto; bot to &thorn;e offrand of Abel his bro&thorn;er god
lokid.  &THORN;erfor sais saynt Gregor: &laquo;bi &thorn;e hertis wille of him &thorn;at offirs: is &thorn;e gift
receyuid of god / or reprouid; &amp; god was noght paied of Abel for &thorn;e offrand,
bot he was paied of &thorn;e offrand for Abel, &thorn;at in al his werk: was trew &amp; gode;
bot to Caym &amp; his offrand god wold noght loke: for he &thorn;at made &thorn;e offrand /
mispaied god greteli&raquo;.  And whi oure offrand / or what we do &thorn;at gode is in
kynde / mispaies god: &thorn;e prophete sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cum multiplicaueritis oraciones: non exaudiam, quia manus vestre / sanguine plene sunt.</FOREIGN>  // &THORN;e .ii. &thorn;at reuis man mede for his gode dede: is vanite / &thorn;at steris man to do &thorn;e gode: for he wald be


<PB N="141">

praisid.  For vayn glorie mase of gode: yuel; als, if almesdede / &thorn;at is gode in
kynde / be done for praisyng: it wynnis bot syn.  // &THORN;e .iii. &thorn;at reuis mede fra
gode dede: is rosyng of him &thorn;at dose &thorn;e gode dede; as &thorn;e phariseyn did, of
whaim god said to &thorn;e folk &thorn;at stode bifore him: &laquo;Sotheli &thorn;is man has lost his
mede for al his gode dede&raquo;.  Nedeful for-&thorn;i it is / &thorn;at man do &thorn;e gode he mai
&amp; ne pride him noght &thorn;erof in thoght nor in worde; for he has noght &thorn;e doyng
of gode dede: of him-selfe, nor of his deseruynge.  // &THORN;e .iiii. [&thorn;at] reuis man his
mede fra his gode dede: when he dose it in &thorn;at entent / for to be halden
better &thorn;en o&thorn;er, or to lesse gode dede of o&thorn;er, or for to fordo it in &thorn;at he mai.
Bi slike tellis saynt Gregor a tale in &thorn;e dialoges: &THORN;at on a tyme / &thorn;e hali bischop
Fortunate chasid &thorn;e fend oute of a man in an euenynge, &amp; &thorn;e fend when he
was chasid oute: put him in liknes of a pilgrim / &amp; went thorugh &thorn;e cite &thorn;are
&thorn;e bischop dwellid / wepand &amp; &yogh;elland as a pouer wreche, as he &thorn;at was wil of
his herberi &thorn;at night; &amp; &thorn;us cried he: &laquo;Lo what &yogh;our bischop has done to me:
&thorn;at &yogh;ee hald so gode! he come to &thorn;e hous &thorn;ar i had tane my herberi: &amp; put
me oute with force; &amp; now als a pouer wrech: of herberi am i wil; oueral I
seke herberi: &amp; nane wil on me rwe&raquo;. A man of &thorn;at cite &thorn;at &thorn;is herd: toke him in to hous / &amp; set him bi &thorn;e fire &amp; esid him on his wise.  When &thorn;e man had spird
at him of ferre thinges / as men dose at pilgrimes: &thorn;e fend stert to &thorn;e child in
&thorn;e credil / &amp; wrathe &thorn;e nek in twa / &amp; kast it in &thorn;e fire: &amp; vanyst a-wai.  Of &thorn;is spekis saynt Gregor &amp; sais: &laquo;Mani semes gode dedes / &amp; are noght gode, for &thorn;ai are noght done with a gode wille.  And &thorn;is man herberied &thorn;e pilgrime / for
na pite he had of him: bot for he spake yuel of &thorn;e bischop; &amp; &thorn;at he suld be
halden better &amp; of mare pite / &thorn;en &thorn;e bischop&raquo;.  // &YOGH;ite gode dede is lost: if man be it cou(ete) to haue of man: riches / or state / or honours / or ani werldis gode.  /
&YOGH;it thorug(h) syn filand: gode dede is lost; &amp; here-to acordis hali writ / &thorn;at sais:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui in vno peccauit: multa bona perdit,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;he &thorn;at in a thing deadli synnes: mani god(is) he tynis&raquo; / bot he amend him with schrift / &amp; do penance &thorn;erfore.</P>
</DIV4>
<MILESTONE N="57" UNIT="folio">
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Secunda pars libri]</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e second parti of &thorn;is boke: techis man til do his gode wer(k with) a
fredome of spirite, in stede &amp; in tyme / as til ilk werk fallis, nog(ht) be-nedid
&thorn;erto, nor do [it] with anger, ne with a deade herte.  For hali writ says: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hillarem datorem diligit deus,</FOREIGN> &laquo;God lufs &thorn;a / &thorn;at ought gifs him with a glad hert&raquo;. &amp; nameli &thorn;a werks &thorn;at fallis to goddis louynge / &amp; hele to mannis saule, as praiers &amp; hali thoughtis / &amp; clere mynde of god / &amp; of gode dedis; thir &amp; o&thorn;er slike / wil haue litil rest: if &thorn;ai wele sal be.  // Praier is a sacrifice &thorn;at mikil paies god: if it be
made o &thorn;e maner it agh to be; for-&thorn;i god askis it of vs / as dette, &thorn;ar he &thorn;us sais:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gentes creauit deus in laudem &amp; gloriam suam.  Et: sacrificium laudis ho[norificabit]
me.</FOREIGN>  And &thorn;e apostle: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oportet semper orare &amp; nunquam deficere.</FOREIGN>  For-&thorn;i bihoues man eauer to prai &amp; neauer faile.  He is eauer praiand: &thorn;at is ai gode doand.  And nameli men of religion are halden to worschip god with praier, &amp; men of hali
kirke / for &thorn;ai life bi almes &amp; tendis&mdash;for al &thorn;e werld trauails to bring &thorn;aim to
hand &thorn;at &thorn;aim nedis, so &thorn;at &thorn;ai mai serue god with rest &amp; with &thorn;aire hali bedis
make saghtlyng bitwix god &amp; man.  And alswa maydens &amp; wydows: &thorn;at has avowid
chaste; all &thorn;ir bifore o&thorn;er are halden to prai.  / He &thorn;at wil pai god with praier:
offir it to god with a free wil &amp; louand hert; &amp; graith him bifore as Salomon


<PB N="142">

redes:<FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> Ante oracionem: prepara animam t[uam], &amp; noli esse quasi homo temptans deum.</FOREIGN>
He temptis god: &thorn;at &yogh;ernis noght to wyn &thorn;at he for praies, or despaires to spede
&thorn;erof; &amp; &thorn;at makis syn &amp; yuel life: &thorn;at man thinkis noght to leue.  Bi slike sais
sayn Gregor: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quid mirum si tarde a domino exaudimur: cum precipientem dominum
tarde aut nullo modo audimus?  Et Ysidorus: Non potest habere certam fiduciam
precum: qui adhuc in preceptis dei pigritat, &amp; quem recordacio peccandi delectat.</FOREIGN>  // Wha s(a) wil spede of his praier: do &thorn;e gode he mai, flee syn, call his hert fra
&thorn;e werld. &amp; hald it at hame / as &thorn;e gospel techis: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cum oraueris: intra in cu[biculum] t[uum] &amp; clauso os[tio] ora p[atrem] t[uum].</FOREIGN>  &laquo;Entre, he sais, &thorn;i bed&raquo;, &thorn;at is, call &thorn;i hert hame, &laquo;&amp; &thorn;en steke &thorn;i dore&raquo;, &thorn;at is, hald &thorn;i wittis in &thorn;e: &thorn;at nane wend oute. For it is bot folie to prai god com to vs nedeful wreches &amp; pouere / to dele vs almis of his deorworthi grace / &amp; noght abide his come, bot turne him &thorn;e bak. Saynt Isidore sais &thorn;e saule is to clense of &thorn;e teche of syn, &amp; t;e hert to withdraw fra tariing of &thorn;e werld: &thorn;at &thorn;e praier with-oute lettynge mai rise to god. For ferre is &thorn;at man fra god / prai he neauer so mikil: &thorn;at praiand is taried with werldli thoughtis; for-&thorn;i sais &thorn;e psalm..: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vacate, &amp; videte quoniam ego sum.</FOREIGN>
&THORN;is aght to stere vs to prai with a (gret) drede &amp; avisement: for we speke with
al-mighti god / when we (er bot) vnworthi wreches.  For so did Abraham, goddis
priue frende, &thorn;at s(aide): <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Loquar ad dominum meum / cum sim puluis &amp; cinis?</FOREIGN>
And Ysidore sais: &laquo;W(e mon) prai with sighings &amp; teris &amp; bitter mynde of oure
grimli synes, &amp; of (&thorn;e) mani pynes &amp; bitter / we sal for &thorn;aim thole, bot we
vs amend (&) on vs rwe&raquo;.  &para; Alswa &thorn;e praiand sal hope to spede of &thorn;at he for
praies, (for Crist him)-self sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnia possibilia sunt credenti;</FOREIGN> for-&thorn;i we sal prai til god (as til oure fa)der, &amp; hope certaynli to spede at oure fader / of &thorn;at we him (pray, if we lu)f him as oure fader, &amp; kynd to him be.  For he sais to all
his ..... he sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Si quid petieritis patrem in n[omine] m[eo], dabit vobis.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>Sex thinges (a)re to wite in praier: ffirst: how man sal graith hi(m) bifore.  &THORN;e
.ii.: wham he sal prai.  &THORN;e .iii.: for wham he sal prai.  &THORN;e .iiii.: what he sal
aske in praier.  &THORN;e .v.: what lettis praier.  &THORN;e .vi.: what might &amp; vertu praier is
of.  &THORN;e first: is writen bifore, &amp; bigynnes at <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ante oracionem prepara a[nimam] t[uam]</FOREIGN> &amp; lastis h(id)er.  // The .ii., to wham &thorn;ou sal prai: Sothli / bifore alle o&thorn;er:
to god al-mighti; as &thorn;e prophete biddis: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Subditus esto domino &amp; ora eum.</FOREIGN>  And in &thorn;e gospel god sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dominum deum tuum adorabis.</FOREIGN>  Halughs we honour &amp; prai, noght as gifars of godenessis: bot as goddis frendis / to help vs to wyn [of] him &thorn;at we after prai.  For-&thorn;i in al oure hert in gode bileue, &amp; certayn hope, &amp; perfite charite: oure lauerd god is to lufe.  // &THORN;e .iii., for wham men sal prai: a grete clerke vndose.  Ilk cristen man / is a quyk lym of hali kirk: for-&thorn;i is he halden
to prai for all, bot speciali for men of hali kirk, as &thorn;e pape, cardinals, &amp; bischops, &amp; all &thorn;at haues cure of mannes saule; alswa, for oure faas &amp; frendes; &amp; all &thorn;at are in deadli syn: &thorn;at &thorn;ai thorugh grace mai rise; for all &thorn;at are in
purgatorie: &thorn;at goddis merci abidis; &amp; sithen for all &thorn;at mister has / quyk &amp; deade. And sayn Gregor sais &thorn;at soner he sal be herd &amp; of his praier sped: &thorn;at for all
praies. &amp; saynt Ambrose: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Si pro omnibus roges: pro te omnes rogabunt.</FOREIGN>  And saynt Ierom: &laquo;Nede byndis man til prai for him-selfe, bot charite of brotherhede steris til prai for all; &amp; charite steris mare god til here: &thorn;en nedefulness&raquo;.  // &THORN;e .iiii., what


<PB N="143">

men sal ask in praier: Certis / grace in &thorn;is life, &amp; endles ioi in &thorn;at o&thorn;er; for &thorn;us
techis god vs &amp; sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Primum querite r[egnum] dei &amp; ius[ticiam] eius, &amp; hec o[mnia] ad[icientur] vobis.</FOREIGN>  God is dettour to &thorn;aim &thorn;at are rightwise: to fynd &thorn;aim &thorn;at &thorn;aim nedis of erthli godis; for rightwisenes mase of men: goddis childre, &amp; &thorn;e fader
thorugh kynde: is halden to fynd his childre.  Erthli godis are noght to ask in
praier, for &thorn;ai haue done harme to mani; for-&thorn;i sais Salomon: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsquequo stulti / ea que sibi sunt noxia cupiunt?</FOREIGN>  &THORN;erfor ilk man aske of god with drede: &thorn;at he askis, &amp; prai his lauerd / if he see &thorn;at his praier be nedeful &amp; skilful: &thorn;at he it fulfill;
&amp; if it ne be nedeful ne skilful: &thorn;at he it withdrawe; for what mai help &amp; what
(mai) harme: wate better &thorn;e leche &thorn;en &thorn;e seke.  Bot ane of &thorn;ir twa (sal) we traist
at haue thorugh praier: oi&thorn;er &thorn;at we for prai: or &thorn;at &thorn;at better (is) for vs.  // &THORN;e
.v., what lettis oure praier to be herd of god: Se(x &thorn;in)ges.  &THORN;e first is, syn of
&thorn;e praiand; as god sais thorugh &thorn;e prophete: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">(Cum) multiplicaueritis oraciones: non
exaudiam, manus enim v[estre] s[anguine] p[lene] s[unt].  Et Dauid: (Iniqui)tatem
si as[pexi] in corde m[eo], non ex[audiet] dominus.  Et propheta: Peccata nostra
absconderunt (faciem) eius a nobis.  Et euangelium: Scimus quoniam peccatores non
ex[audit] dominus.</FOREIGN>  / &THORN;e .ii. is, &thorn;e (vn)worthines of &thorn;as &thorn;at men praies fore; &amp; &thorn;at defendis god to prai for (&thorn;aim) thorugh &thorn;e prophete: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Noli orare pro populo isto, neque assumas pro eis (laudem &) oracionem: quia non exaudiam.</FOREIGN>  It tellis in lif of hali faders &thorn;at (ane &thorn;at wa)s bonden in syn: come to &thorn;e hali Abbot saynt An(tone)<MILESTONE N="58" UNIT="folio">
&amp; said: &laquo;hali fader, haf merci on me, &amp; prai for me&raquo;; / to whaim &thorn;e
abbot said: &laquo;I wil haf na merci on &thorn;e: bot &thorn;ou help &thorn;e selfe &amp; leue &thorn;i syn&raquo;.  / &THORN;e .iii. is, foule thoughtis &amp; idel, &thorn;at lettis vs to think on oure praier.  Of slike fals praiand sais god thorugh &thorn;e prophete: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Populus iste labiis me honorat, cor autem eius longe est a me.</FOREIGN>  It is grete wikidnes of vs vnworthi wreches / &thorn;at when we speke with praier til almighti god, &amp; we als vnwitti / herknes noght what we sai.  Sotheli grete despite we do to god / when we prai him til here oure praier / &amp; we wil noght here it vs-self, bot, &thorn;at wers is: in foule thoughtis and idel / wastis oure tyme.  Abraham when he made sacri(fi)se to god: foulis lightid &thorn;er-on / &amp; wold haf filde it, &amp; he chasid &thorn;e foules awai, &thorn;at nane durst it negh: to al &thorn;e tyme ware passid / &amp; &thorn;e sacrifice made.  Do we swa with &thorn;is fleand thoughtis: &thorn;at filis &thorn;e sacrifice of oure praier.  &THORN;is sacrifice is ful queme to god: when it comes of a clene &amp; a louand hert.  God biddis: &laquo;send to me
praier: &amp; I sal send to &thorn;e grace; &amp; what sa &thorn;ou to me dose: I forget
it noght&raquo;.  / &THORN;e .iiii. &thorn;at lettis oure praier to be herd: is hardnes of hert.
&amp; &thorn;at is on .ii. maners: first hardnes of hert agayn &thorn;e pouer, &amp; &thorn;erbi
&thorn;e prophete sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui opturat aures s[uas] ad clamorem pauperis: clamabit &amp; ipse
&amp; non exaudietur.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;at o&thorn;er is hardnes of &thorn;aim &thorn;at wil noght forgife to &thorn;aim &thorn;at has misdone &thorn;aim; to slike Salomon sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Relinque proximo tuo nocenti te, &amp; tunc deprecanti tibi: peccata soluuntur.</FOREIGN>  &amp; in &thorn;e gospel god sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cum stabitis ad orandum: dimittite si quid habetis aduersum aliquem, vt pater vester qui in celis est dimittat vobis p[eccata] v[estra].</FOREIGN>  / &THORN;e .v. &thorn;at lettis oure praier to be herd: is littil &yogh;ernyng after &thorn;e thing men praies fore; &amp; saynt Austyn sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vt ex toto corde desideretur / hoc seruat tibi deus; quod non vult tibi cito dare, vt discas magna magne desiderare.</FOREIGN>  And saynt Gregor sais: &laquo;if we with mouthe prai after &thorn;e blisse of heuen / &amp; noght &yogh;erne it with hert: criand we are still&raquo;.  / &THORN;e .VI. &thorn;at lettis oure praier: is foule speche &amp; idel / &thorn;at we file oure lippis with; for if &thorn;ou gif


<PB N="144">

a grete lord drink in a slutti cup: ware &thorn;e drink nere sa gode, him wold wlat
&thorn;er-with, &amp; bid do it awai / thrist him nere sa sare; sa god dos with &thorn;e praier
&thorn;at comes of a foule mouth: he latis noght &thorn;erbi / bot turnes him &thorn;erfra.
For&thorn;i sais sayn Gregor: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Os nostrum a deo tanto minus auditur in prece: quanto plus polluitur stulta loqucione.</FOREIGN> // (&THORN;e vi. what might &amp; vertu praier is of).  Men &thorn;at ware bifore &thorn;is tyme, &thorn;at held &thorn;aim in sothefastnes / &amp; noght idel spake: wan of god what so &thorn;ai praied.  &amp; &thorn;at was schewid til a hali hermite &thorn;at hight Florentius, &thorn;at woned in wildernes vnknowen fra men.  Sa mikil vermyn was aboute &thorn;is hermite stede: &thorn;at nane durst come &thorn;ider / bi a fer wai.  A deken was in &thorn;at land &thorn;at of &thorn;is hermite herd &amp; come at &thorn;e last to &thorn;e place whare &thorn;e heremite was duelland; bot sa mikil vermyn he sagh &thorn;er aboute: &thorn;at he durste come na ner, bot cried after help for ferde.  &THORN;e hali man come oute to wite what it was &thorn;at cried, &amp; he sagh a man standand &thorn;are / &amp; he sperid what he wold.  &amp; &thorn;e deken said: &laquo;hali fader, I haf soght &thorn;e of fer, &amp; now I haf founden &thorn;e: I haf ioi inogh / might I com to &thorn;e; bot I mai noght for &thorn;is venemouse bestes &thorn;at here are so mani&raquo;.  When &thorn;e hali man &thorn;is herd: he fel downe on knees &amp; praied god / he wold fordo &thorn;as wormes.  &amp; als sone / a grisli storme
rase with a thoner: &amp; slogh all &thorn;e wormes.  &THORN;en said &thorn;e hermite til oure lauerd:
&laquo;lauerd / &thorn;is bestis liggis here sa thik / &thorn;at I ne mai come til him / ne he to
me: bot we be envenemode of &thorn;aim.  Lo lauerd / &thorn;ai lig here dead / bot wha
sal lift &thorn;aim away?&raquo;  At &thorn;is worde: mani foulis come &amp; bare &thorn;aim all away
clene.  Here-of spekis saynt Gregor &amp; sais: &laquo;For-&thorn;i &thorn;at goddis seruant&yogh; /
withdraw &thorn;aim fra &thorn;e werld &amp; his werkis: vnnayte kan &thorn;ai noght speke; sa &thorn;ai
bynd &thorn;aim to silence: &thorn;at &thorn;ai dar na worde say / bot it be lerynge til o&thorn;er /
or louyng to god.  &amp; &thorn;erfore / when &thorn;ai ought askid god: he grantid &thorn;aim
alsone.  Bot we waful wreches &thorn;at with &thorn;e werld delis / &thorn;at al dai chaters as
pies, now lies, now wries, now yuel spekis, now flitis, now bakbitis, now sweris
grete athes: &thorn;ir filis oure praier &amp; lettis it to be herd; for als fer is oure mouth
praiand / fra god: as it is nere &thorn;e werld / with idel speche&raquo;. / Praier is so
mightful / if he haf his right: &thorn;at he maistirs &thorn;e fend &amp; lettis him til do his will.
For so it did &thorn;e fende &thorn;at Iuliane &thorn;e Emperour comandid to wende to &thorn;e vttre
side of &thorn;e werld / to bryng him tithandis / how it was &thorn;are.  When he had
flowen ten iournes &thorn;iderward / he come ouer &thorn;e place &thorn;at Publius &thorn;e hermite
dwellid in: &thorn;at praiand was &thorn;at tyme.  &amp; his praier ouertoke &thorn;e fende &amp; held him &thorn;are fast / fulli ten daies&mdash;for al &thorn;at tyme: &thorn;e hermite was in praier; &amp; when he cessid: &thorn;e fend turnid agayn, for he might na ferrer wende, for praier him lettid.
</P>
<P>When &thorn;ou has gederid hame &thorn;i hert / with his wittis, &amp; has fordone &thorn;as
thinges &thorn;at might let &thorn;e to prai, &amp; won til deuocion &thorn;at god to &thorn;e sendis
thorugh his dereworthi grace: quykli rise of &thorn;i bed at &thorn;e bel ryngynge.  &amp; if
na bel be &thorn;are: cok be &thorn;i bel; if &thorn;are be noi&thorn;er cok ne bel: goddis luf wakyn
&thorn;e, for &thorn;at paies mast to god.  And gelusye in luf rotid: wakens bifore bathe
cok &amp; bel, &amp; has waschen hire face: with swete luf-teris, &amp; hire saule with-inne has ioie in god with deuocion &amp; likyng &amp; morneyng to him, &amp; with o&thorn;er heuenli gladdyngs: &thorn;at god to his lofars sendis.  Sely are &thorn;a bifore o&thorn;er: &thorn;at luf wakens, for mani gladdyngis &thorn;ai haf / when o&thorn;er fast slepis; for &thorn;ai fynd bifore &thorn;aim /


<PB N="145">

&thorn;at gladdis all / rise &thorn;ai neauer so sone; for god him-self &thorn;us sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui mane vigilauerint ad me: inuenient me,</FOREIGN> &laquo;he &thorn;at erli wakyns to me: he sal fynde me, to speke with him,<MILESTONE N="59" UNIT="folio">&amp; glad him with me, &amp; haf me at his wille&raquo;.  Be &thorn;en ai waker; &amp; rise quikli &amp; thank hertli &thorn;i gode louerd: for &thorn;e rest &thorn;ou had, for &thorn;e &yogh;emyng
of angels.  Sen a knyght has grete likyng to be cald to come speke with &thorn;e
kynge / when he knowis it is for his grete profit: with grete[r] skil goddis knight /
&thorn;at is ilk cristen man / at &thorn;e callyng of his lauerd god agh redi to be, &thorn;at
callis him for his mikil prow, &amp; for na thing ellis.  Soberli &thorn;ou rise with a glad
chere, &amp; think &thorn;ou heris god call &thorn;e with &thorn;is wordis: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Surge prop[er]a amica mea, formosa mea, &amp; veni; ostende michi faciem tuam, sonet vox tua in auribus meis,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at is: &laquo;Rise mi leefe, mi faire thinge, &amp; schew me &thorn;i face; I &yogh;erne &thorn;at &thorn;e voice of &thorn;i praier / ring in mi nere&raquo;. // Think in &thorn;i risyng: how mani men &thorn;at
night / perist in life, &amp; some in saule, / &amp; some in bodi &amp; saule; some brent,
some drounyd, some sodanli dead / with-oute repentance or schrift: &amp; &thorn;are saulis
drawyn with fendes til hell; some fallyn in deadli syn, as lucheri, glotonie, thift,
couaitise, manslaghter &amp; o&thorn;er sere synnes.  And of alle &thorn;is perils &thorn;i gode god
has delyuerid &thorn;e / of his godenes &amp; noght of &thorn;i dessert.  What has &thorn;ou done
to god / &thorn;at he suld &yogh;eme &thorn;e so / &amp; suffre so mani o&thorn;er be loste?  &amp; per-auntere &thorn;ou has done wers / &thorn;en &thorn;ai haf done.  If &thorn;ou wele loke what god dose
to &thorn;e / &thorn;of &thorn;ou noght haf seruid: &thorn;ou mai fynd &thorn;at god is als bisy til do &thorn;i
prow: as he had noght ellis to do, &amp; as he had al &thorn;is werld forgetyn: &amp; aneli
thoght on &thorn;e. // When &thorn;ou has &thorn;us thoght: lift vp &thorn;i hert to god &amp; sai:
&laquo;I thank &thorn;e, dereworthi lorde, with al mi hert: &thorn;at me so vnworthi wreche /
&thorn;us has &yogh;emid &thorn;is night, &amp; tholid me with life &amp; hele / &thorn;us abide &thorn;is daie.  I thank &thorn;e, lorde, of &thorn;is grete gode &amp; mani o&thorn;er: &thorn;at &thorn;ou has done to me /
sa vnkynde &amp; vnworthi wreche, of all o&thorn;er; &thorn;at &thorn;ou swilk kyndnes schewis to me /
agayn mine yuel dedis&raquo;.  And put &thorn;e &amp; all &thorn;i frendes: in goddis handes, &amp; sai &thorn;us: &laquo;In &thorn;i dere-worthi handes, mi lorde, I &yogh;elde mi saule &amp; mi bodi, &amp; all mi frendis / sib &amp; fremmed / &amp; all &thorn;at me gode has done bodili or gastli, &amp; all &thorn;at cristendome has tane: &thorn;at &thorn;ou for &thorn;e lufe of &thorn;i moder &thorn;at dere-worthi
maiden / &amp; &thorn;e bisekyng of all &thorn;i halughs: &yogh;eme vs &thorn;is dai, or &thorn;is night, fra all
perils of bodi &amp; saule, &amp; fra all deadli synnes, fra fandyng of &thorn;e fende, &amp; sodane deade, &amp; fra &thorn;e paynes of hell, &amp; make vs &thorn;aim to drede.  &THORN;ou halugh oure hertis with &thorn;e grace of &thorn;i hali gast, &amp; make vs here eauer what so we do, &thorn;at we do &thorn;i will; &thorn;at we neauer twynne fra &thorn;e: dere lorde, amen&raquo;.
When &thorn;ou has &thorn;us done: wende to &thorn;e kirk or oratori; &amp; if &thorn;ou mai wyn to nane:
&thorn;i chambre make &thorn;i kirk.  In &thorn;e kirk is mast deuocion til prai, for &thorn;are is god in
&thorn;e auter / til here &thorn;at till him praies, &amp; grante &thorn;aim &thorn;at &thorn;ai ask: or &thorn;at better is; &amp; in presence of halows, &amp; in worschip of kirkis &thorn;at are halughid; Mynd of angels &thorn;at &thorn;are are to serue &thorn;aire lorde &amp; &thorn;e&mdash;for &thorn;aire office is / to receyue &thorn;i praier: &amp; bere it to god &amp; bring &thorn;e grace fra him, as sayn Bernard sais.  Rise &thorn;en quikli at goddis calle &amp; put fra &thorn;e al heuynes, &amp; answere &thorn;i lorde with &thorn;e wordis &thorn;at Samuel said to god &thorn;at callid him be night: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Loquere domine, quia audit seruus tuus.</FOREIGN> For .viii. thinges aght vs to wake &amp; eauer be doand gode: &thorn;is schorte life; &thorn;e straite wai we haf to ga; oure gode dedes &thorn;at are so faa; oure synnes &thorn;at


<PB N="146">

are so many; deade &thorn;at we are siker of &amp; wate noght when; &thorn;e straite dome of
domesdai / &amp; so hard, for ilk idel thoght sal &thorn;are be schewid, &thorn;en sal ilk foule
worde &amp; synful werk be greteli chargid, for god sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">De omni verbo ocioso &amp;c.,</FOREIGN>
&amp; saynt Anselm: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quid facies in illa die quando exigetur a te omne tempus tibi
impensum: qualiter a te sit expensum / vsque ad minimam cogitacionem.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;e .vii. thing is, &thorn;e strang pyne of hell; &thorn;e .viii. is, &thorn;e ioie of heuen.
</P>
<P>After &thorn;i vprisynge: prai for &thorn;e saulis &thorn;at are in pyne of purgatorie, &amp; think &thorn;ou
heris &thorn;aim cry on &thorn;e: &thorn;e wordes of Iob: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Miseremini mei, miseremini mei vos [saltem] a[mici] mei: quia m[anus] d[omini] te[tigit] me,</FOREIGN> &amp; help &thorn;aim with <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">De profundis, &amp; Absolue.</FOREIGN>  After: &thorn;ou grete oure leuedi with <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Salue regina:</FOREIGN> on &thorn;i knees.  Wend &thorn;en to &thorn;e kirk; &amp; bid &thorn;i vayn thoghtis &amp; bisynes of &thorn;e werld: hald &thorn;aim &thorn;er oute, &amp; sai to &thorn;i saule at &thorn;i incomyng: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Intra in gau[dium] domini tui, vt audias vo[cem] eius: &amp; vi[deas] templum eius.</FOREIGN>  Hali kirke is entre and &yogh;ate of heuen.  After: fal doune bifore &thorn;e croice, &amp; anoure him &thorn;at for &thorn;e was done on &thorn;e croice, &amp; say: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adoramus te Christe &amp; bene[dicimus] tibi, quia per sanctam crucem t[uam]
re[demisti] m[undum].</FOREIGN>  And haf &thorn;en, or &thorn;ou vp rise, in mynde / how hate luf him brente: &thorn;at deied for &thorn;e on &thorn;e crosse.  After: bigyn &thorn;i matyns; bot first: crosse &thorn;i lippis &amp; sai: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Domine, labia m[ea] a[peries],</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;lorde / oppen mi lippis: &thorn;at al night has bien stoken fra louyng of &thorn;e; &amp; I mai noght oppyn &thorn;aim: bot &thorn;ou me help&raquo;.  And &thorn;en sai: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Deus in adiutorium;</FOREIGN> with &thorn;is wordes: &yogh;ette oute &thorn;i herte bifore god / &amp; sai: &laquo;lord / als mi domesman / bifore &thorn;e I stand: &thorn;ou wreke me of mi faas: &thorn;at lettis me to serue &thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;ai assaile me keneli, so &thorn;at I be sone ouer-comen: bot &thorn;ou me help&raquo;.  And at <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gloria patri:</FOREIGN>
bowe doune &amp; sai with &thorn;i hert: &laquo;lord, of &thorn;i blissyng I biseke &thorn;e&raquo;.  Torn &thorn;e &thorn;en to &thorn;e angels &thorn;at aboute standis til &thorn;i comfort &amp; helpe &amp; als &thorn;i wardeyns til kepe &thorn;e fra &thorn;i faas: &amp; &thorn;us til &thorn;aim say: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Venite exultemus domino</FOREIGN>.  After: cast &thorn;in iee on sum-what: &amp; hald it &thorn;er-on til &thorn;ou makis &thorn;i praiers: for &thorn;is helpis mikil / til stabelyng of &thorn;e hert; &amp; paynt &thorn;are &thorn;i lord: as he was on &thorn;e
croice; think on his fete &amp; handes &thorn;at ware nailid to &thorn;e tree, &amp; on &thorn;e wide
wounde in his side, thorugh &thorn;e whilk: wai is made to &thorn;e / til wyn til his herte;
thank &thorn;i lorde &thorn;erof: &amp; luf him &thorn;erfore; for &thorn;are &thorn;ai fynde tresour of lufe: &thorn;at
&thorn;ider mai wyn.  Think &thorn;ou sees his woundes<MILESTONE N="60" UNIT="folio"> stremand of blode: &amp; falland
downe on &thorn;e erth, &amp; fal &thorn;ou downe &amp; lik vp &thorn;at blode / sweteli with teres
kissand &thorn;e erth; with mynde of &thorn;at riche tresour &thorn;at for &thorn;i synnes was sched: &amp; sai &thorn;us with hert: &laquo;Whi liggis &thorn;is blode here as lost / &amp; I perisch for thrist? Whi drink I noght of &thorn;is riche pyment / &thorn;at mi lorde to me birlis, / &amp; cole mi
tonge, / &amp; here what god to me spekis: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui sitit: veniat &amp; bibat.  Gustabis &amp; videbis quam suauis est dominus, quam dulcis, quam mitis, quam misericors&raquo;.</FOREIGN> / With slike meditacions angels comes to &thorn;e saule: &amp; god is &thorn;are / &amp; sais til his
lufar: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quid vis vt faciam tibi?</FOREIGN>  &amp; &thorn;ou answer: &laquo;Lauerd: it is inogh to me synful
wreche &amp; oute-cast of &thorn;i folk / &thorn;at &thorn;ou, lorde, o-fer / wil loke to me, &amp; suffre
me, lorde, so synful wreche: to loue &thorn;e &amp; luf &thorn;e if I couthe, for so me wele
aght&raquo;.  If &thorn;ou mai wyn to slike thinkyngs in &thorn;i praiers: &thorn;ou sal haue slike
gladdyngs / &thorn;at it sal be a payn to &thorn;e to think oght ellis.  Sayn Bernard / for
&thorn;e likyng &thorn;at he had in slike steryngs: gerned &thorn;at matyns tyme might haue


<PB N="147">

lastid til domesdai.  Think, &thorn;er &thorn;ou standis or knelis in praier, &thorn;at &thorn;ou sees
Ihesu Crist come with angels  &amp; hali halughs on ilk a side / &amp; angels berand
bifore him lepis ful of relife &thorn;at is left of &thorn;e fest of halughs &thorn;at duellis with
god in heuen / &thorn;at god bad gedir vp to help &thorn;e pouer with / &thorn;at it be noght
lost.  &THORN;is relif: is mete til vs pouer wrechis / &thorn;at suld perisch for defaute: bot
god on vs rued.  Think &thorn;ou heres god cri: &laquo;Wha so has nede of mete: put
forth &thorn;e hand &amp; hafe&raquo;.  And loute &thorn;ou with &thorn;i heued to god / &amp; mene &thorn;i pouert to him &amp; sai: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Non est in domo mea panis,</FOREIGN> &amp; sai als: &laquo;lorde / so lang meteles haf I bien: I die for hunger, bot &thorn;ou on me rue; &amp; noght mai hald mi lif: bot mete &thorn;at &thorn;ou delis&raquo;.  Stere &thorn;i-selfe in slike myndes &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at mai kyndel &thorn;i deuocion &amp; raise it to him, ay til &thorn;e think &thorn;ou heris him sai to &thorn;e: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dilata os t[uum] &amp; im[plebo] illud.</FOREIGN>  And &thorn;en sal &thorn;ou thorugh goddis grace: fele som dele of &thorn;at heuenli fode / &thorn;at all halughs fedis; &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai with likynge: synge &thorn;e maiden sange / &thorn;at is goddis moder: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Magnificat anima mea dominum, &amp; exultauit s[piritus] m[eus] in deo s[alutari] m[eo].</FOREIGN> / When god sendis &thorn;e slike likyngs thorugh his grace: torne &thorn;e kyndli to &thorn;e angels &thorn;at bifore &thorn;e standis, &amp; to &thorn;aim sai: &laquo;I prai &yogh;ow als mi kepers &thorn;at god has to me send: &thorn;at &yogh;e thank &yogh;oure gode lorde for me&raquo;.  And turne &thorn;e &thorn;en to &thorn;e auter, &thorn;are god sotheli is: &amp; sai: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vere domine / magna est misericordia tua super me,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;sothli lorde / mikil is &thorn;e merci: &thorn;at &thorn;ou to me schewis&raquo;.  With slike luf-steryngs: god comes to his lufars; &amp; bidis noght to &thorn;e praier be made: bot pressis in / in &thorn;e middes &amp; softis &thorn;e languisand saule: with a dewynge of heuenly swetenes; &amp; teres &amp; sihings are messangers of goddis come.  Cely are &thorn;ai &thorn;at &thorn;us murnys &amp; languys to god, for &thorn;ai sal neauer twyn fra god, bot haf him ay at &thorn;aire will.
</P><LB>
<P>How god comes to his lofars, &amp; how he some-tyme fra &thorn;aim partis.  God
when he comes to his lufars: he gifs &thorn;aim to taste how swete he is; &amp; are
&thorn;ai mai fulli fele: he fra &thorn;aim wendis, &amp; als an Egle he spredis his wengis
&amp; aboue &thorn;aim risis / als if he said: &laquo;som dele mai &yogh;e fele: how swete I am;
bot if &yogh;e wil fele &thorn;is swetenes to &thorn;e full: flies vp after me, &amp; lift &yogh;oure hertis
vp to me / &thorn;ar I am sittand on mi fader right hand: &amp; &thorn;are sal &yogh;e be fulfillid
in ioie of me&raquo;.  God comes til his lufars: til comforte &thorn;aim; he partis fra &thorn;aim:
for &thorn;ai suld &thorn;e mare meke &thorn;aim, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld noght ouer-mikil pride &thorn;aim
of &thorn;e gladdyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai haf of his come; for if &thorn;i spouse ware ai with &thorn;e: &thorn;ou
wold late ouer-wele of &thorn;e selfe &amp; despice o&thorn;er; &, if he ware ai with &thorn;e: &thorn;ou
wold rete it to kynde / &amp; noght to grace.  For-&thorn;i thorugh his grace: he comes
when he wil / &amp; to whaim he wil, &amp; departis when he wil; so &thorn;at his lang
duellyng make him noght mare vnworthi, bot after his departynge: be &thorn;e mare
&yogh;ernid &amp; soght with geluse luf &amp; sighinges &amp; teres.  Bot be war &thorn;ou goddis
lufar / &thorn;of &thorn;i spouse withdraw him fra &thorn;e for a while: he sees all &thorn;i dedes,
&amp; &thorn;ou mai na thing fra him hide; &amp; if he wite &thorn;ou luf ani bot him / bot if it
be for &thorn;e luf of him / or if &thorn;ou make ani luf-semblant til o&thorn;er &thorn;en him: als
sone he partis fra &thorn;e.  Gelouse is &thorn;i spouse / delicate / nobill &amp; riche, seuen
sithe brighter &thorn;en &thorn;e son; in fairenes &amp; might: all o&thorn;er he passis; &amp; what so
he wil: is done / in heuen in erth &amp; in hell.  If he see ani teche of filth / in
him &thorn;at his lefe suld be: he turnis him fra him sone, for vnclenes mai he nane


<PB N="148">

see.  For-&thorn;i be &thorn;ou chaste / shameful &amp; milde of hert; &amp; with luf-langyng:
&yogh;erne him ouer al thing.  And when god with-drawis &thorn;is heuenli likyns &amp; swetenes
fra &thorn;e / als some-tyme nedis in &thorn;is deadli lif: gif &thorn;e noght til fleshli lustis ne
likyngs of &thorn;e werld: bot to praier &amp; meditacions / redyng of hali writ / or honest
wirkyng; &amp; eauer &thorn;ou mourne after &thorn;i lefe: as &yogh;ong child &thorn;at his moder missis.
For &thorn;a &thorn;at after slike knowyng of god / &amp; tastyng of his swetenes / turnis him
&thorn;e bak &amp; gifs &thorn;aim to syn: has na defense agayns god of &thorn;aire syn.  Ane vnhappy
chaunce &amp; careful it is to lefe &thorn;e felaschip of god &amp; his angels &amp; halughs: &amp; serue &thorn;e fend &amp; folow his rede / with lustis &amp; likyngs &amp; werkis of syn; &thorn;at hert &thorn;at was halughid thorugh &thorn;e hali gast goddis temple to be / &thorn;at was raisid here
ouer his kynd for to hafe with god heuenli likyngs &amp; mirthis: al-sone with foule
thoughtis make it laith &amp; foule; &thorn;as eres &thorn;at herd &thorn;is wordis &thorn;at to nane is
lefesom to speke: oppyn &thorn;aim to here bakbityng[s] &amp; lesyngs &amp; o&thorn;er idel speche;
&thorn;as ien &thorn;at right now was bapti&yogh;ed with teres: oppyn &thorn;aim to see vanitees; &thorn;at
tonge &thorn;at right now spake<MILESTONE N="61" UNIT="folio"> to god with praier: al-sone after with &thorn;at tong wary / forswere / bakbite &amp; speke foule wordes.  Prai we to god for his godenes: he kepe vs fra &thorn;ir vnthewes.  Of goddis comyng mai men wit: bi &thorn;is &thorn;at sayn Bernard sais: &laquo;When &thorn;ou art sterid of man with-oute / or with-in of spirite / for to &yogh;eme rightwisenes &amp; stand &thorn;erfore, for to be meke &amp; tholemode, to luf &thorn;i bro&thorn;er in god, to be buxom to &thorn;i ouerlyngs, to luf chastite &amp; clenes in bodi &amp; saule: takenyng it is / &thorn;at al-mighti god comes to visite &thorn;i saule&raquo;.  If &thorn;ou take godeli chastying of &thorn;i frende for &thorn;i syn / or wordes &thorn;at steris &thorn;e to vertues &amp; gode thewes: &thorn;is make way &amp; takenyng of goddis comynge.  &THORN;an if &thorn;ou put fra &thorn;e slawnes &amp; heuynes / &amp; with a luf-&yogh;ernynge likis slike wordes: &thorn;en dereworthi god &thorn;i lorde hastis him to &thorn;e; for &thorn;e &yogh;ernynge god has to &thorn;e: kyndels &thorn;i &yogh;ernyngs til haf likyng in slike wordes, &amp; makis &thorn;e bitterli to forthink &thorn;i syn: &amp; amend &thorn;i lif.  For at his income: he wakkyns &thorn;e saule / steris it &amp; softis it &amp; waschis hire wondes with wyne: &amp; softis &thorn;aim with oile; &thorn;at is, steris it to forthink bitterli &thorn;at it has misdone, &amp; softis it with hope of merci &amp; forgifnes of synnis.  He ryuis synnis vp bi &thorn;e rotis: as gardener dos &thorn;e iuel wedis, &amp; ympis gode trees &amp; sawis gode sede: &thorn;are &thorn;e wedis grewe.  So dos god &thorn;at is callid gardener / whil he is in mannis saule: he ryuis vp synnes bi &thorn;e rotis, &amp; ympis in &thorn;at saule vertues &amp; gode thewis; &thorn;at was drie: he dewis it with grace; &thorn;at blak was &amp; mirke: he makis it white; &thorn;at bonden was: he lousis; &thorn;at calde was: he makis warme with lufe.  Bi &thorn;ir steryngs mai &thorn;ou knowe &thorn;i lordis come: bi
steryng of &thorn;i herte, fordoyng of vices, withdrawyng of lustis, amendyng of life,
forthinkynge of misdede, bigyning of a new man in gode / ilk dai mare &amp; mare.
And bi &thorn;is mai &thorn;ou wite: when he fra &thorn;e wendis: &thorn;i gladdyng wanis, slaw &thorn;ou
waxis &amp; dri &amp; heuy as a stane, luf in &thorn;e colis: as a pot &thorn;at had wellid / &amp; &thorn;e fire ware drawen &thorn;erfra.  Bot &thorn;en nedis &thorn;e saule to morne sare / ai til he come
agayn.  If foule thoughtis egge &thorn;e to leue &thorn;i gode god: sai &thorn;us: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cuius est ymago hec &amp; suprascriptio?</FOREIGN>; if he sai, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cesaris,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is, &thorn;e prince of &thorn;is werld, &thorn;at is &thorn;e fend of hell: sai to him: &laquo;Wend agayn &thorn;ou foule fende with &thorn;i fals monee / bere it agayn with &thorn;e to hell; for mi &yogh;atis are stokyn / &amp; mi lorde duellis here-in, for-&thorn;i haf I na tome to dele with &thorn;e&raquo;.  // Think on &thorn;at hali gretyng &thorn;at Gabriel made to &thorn;at maiden Mari in Na&yogh;areth, how ioiful she was in bodi &amp;


<PB N="149">

saule in &thorn;at tyme; she was thorugh &thorn;at gretyng with assent: fulfillid of grace,
&thorn;at sche wan might &amp; power: in heuen &amp; erth &amp; hell; &amp; on hire: hingis al &thorn;is werldis hele / &amp; restoring of &thorn;as &thorn;at fell.  Think on &thorn;e birth of hire childe /
how she bare him with-oute sorugh &amp; site / &thorn;at all o&thorn;er wymen has kyndli in
tyme of birth; &amp; sche clene maiden after.  Think when he borne was: &thorn;ai laid
him in a crib bifore an ox &amp; an asse / o&thorn;er credil had he nane.  Was &thorn;er nane
to serue him of light with torches / as men dose bifore grete lordis; for-&thorn;i come
a fire fra heuen &thorn;at lightid &thorn;e howse he was in / &amp; Bethleem; &amp; angels come
fra heuen / to syng &thorn;e child o slepe / with a meri steuyn.  Think how .iii.
kynges come fra ferre landis thorugh wissyng of a sterne &amp; offird him gold, rekils,
&amp; mirre; think how sweteli &thorn;e child on &thorn;aim smylid, &amp; with his loueli ien:
sweteli on &thorn;aim lokid.  Think how poreli his moder was clad / when &thorn;e kynges
bifore hire knelid, for on hir sche had bot a white smoke as &thorn;is clerkis sais,
mare til hill hir with: &thorn;en to schewing of pride.  Think how his moder come
with him to &thorn;e temple / to make &thorn;e offring of clensynge / &amp; bowid to fulfill
&thorn;e lawe: as &thorn;ai sinful were.  Think &thorn;e alde preste Symeon toke &thorn;e child in his
armes &amp; blissid god; for &thorn;are he sagh thorugh steryng of &thorn;e hali gaste: &thorn;e
salueour of al &thorn;is werld bitwene his handes, &amp; praied &thorn;at he might passe oute
of &thorn;is werld: &laquo;for mine ien sees / &thorn;at &thorn;e folk sal saue&raquo;.  Think of &thorn;at sorugh his moder had when sche missid him &amp; soght him .iii. daies, &amp; &thorn;en fande him sittand amange &thorn;e maisters, herand &amp; sperand of poyntis of &thorn;e lawe.  Think
how he come to be cristenid of sayn Ione; how &thorn;e hali gaste light &thorn;ar on him
in liknes of a dowue, &thorn;e fader &thorn;ar with voice recordid: &thorn;at he was his son.
Think how he halowid wedlaik in architriclynes howse, &amp; &thorn;are, to schew &thorn;at
he was al-mighti god: chaungid water in to wyne.  In wildernes how he fastid
xl. daies withouten mete; how he ouercome &thorn;e fende &thorn;at fandid him with three:
with glotonie, &amp; couaitise, &amp; vayne glorie.  &amp; of &thorn;e wonder / men had of his
prechinge, for all &thorn;e wordes he to &thorn;aim spake: ware ful of grace.  How he helid
&thorn;e seke, raisid &thorn;e deade, gaf blynd &thorn;e sight, &thorn;e dumbe speche, &thorn;e mesels hale:
with touching of his handes; and mani o&thorn;er sekenes &thorn;at vncurable ware of kynde:
he helid thorugh might of his worde, for he might mare &thorn;en kynde.  How he
as wery for mikil gangynge: rest him at &thorn;e well, &amp; &thorn;are he bad gif him water
to drink / for him thristid sare.  Sethen oppyn &thorn;i herte with sare sighinges /
&amp; think on &thorn;e passion &amp; pynes &thorn;at Ihesus Crist suffrid / as &thorn;ai are writen bifore in &thorn;e .xviii. lefe.
</P>
<P>He mai god biseke of grace / &amp; sikerli traist to spede: &thorn;at here steris him
in gode werkis, &amp; with deuocion &amp; likyngs: poudirs &thorn;aim so, &thorn;at &thorn;ai mai be
sauori til his dere lorde. / Werkis of penance / as fastyng, wakynge, hard
werynge, forberyng of fleshli lustes, praier, almose-dede, &amp; o&thorn;er slike as we do
with deuocion &amp; likyngs in god: bihoues be swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai be done with a glad
hert &amp; with a fredome of spirit.  Deuocion: is a worthi drurie / &thorn;at god
sendis to &thorn;e hert to glad it with; bot vnworthi is he til haf &thorn;is gift: &thorn;at wil
make na duellyng-stede in his hert / til it.  We seke &thorn;at abouen vs is / with
oure bileue, bot it sauours vs noght / for we are so full of erth: &thorn;at we haue
lost oure tast.  Whi felis so mani men &thorn;e steryngs &thorn;at &thorn;e fend forgis / &amp; tholis


<PB N="150">

his enemis sa oft him ouer-cast?  I see &thorn;at noght makis &thorn;is: bot wantyng of grace.
Amang all o&thorn;er, I trowe we greue god mast: for we wil noght swynk<MILESTONE N="62" UNIT="folio">to wyn &thorn;is grace of god; and god hightis &thorn;is grace til all &thorn;at wil seke it, [with] &thorn;at
&thorn;aire vessel be clene &amp; voide til resceyue it in.  Bot sayn Bernard sais: &laquo;&THORN;at hert &thorn;at chargeid is with couaitise of &thorn;e werld: deuocion ne likyng in god / mai it
nane hafe; ffor sothefastnes &amp; vanite, lastand thing &amp; failand, gastli thing &amp; bodili: na mai noght be to-geder na while&raquo;.  Sa worthi thing is &thorn;e comforte of
god: &thorn;at it wil noght rest in &thorn;at breste / &thorn;are o&thorn;er comfort is.  Sa delicious
is &thorn;e likyng in him: &thorn;at with nane o&thorn;er likyng mai it acorde.  Wha-so &yogh;ernis
o&thorn;er comfort to glad him with: he witnes agayn him-selfe / &thorn;at goddis grace
he with-standis; bot it honest comfort be / be tymes to glad his kynd with, &thorn;at
he mai &thorn;ar-thorugh: better serue god.
</P>
<P>After &thorn;ou has spendid &thorn;i tyme in praiers, &amp; hali thoughtis, &amp; gode werkis:
in goddis hali drede / graith &thorn;e to &thorn;e mete / to strinth &thorn;i kynd: &thorn;at wold ellis
faile.  And in &thorn;is entent sal ilk cristen man / his bodi klethe &amp; fede: &thorn;at it
mai &thorn;e better serue his lorde / in what so he dose. / With morneing &thorn;ou sal
wende to &thorn;i mete; sobirnes &amp; mesure: &thorn;ou &yogh;eme in &thorn;i mete-while; &amp; after mete: &thorn;ou make louyng to &thorn;i lorde &thorn;at &thorn;e has fedde, &amp; als bifore mete, &amp; for alle &thorn;e gode dedis &thorn;at he to &thorn;e has done. / First or &thorn;ou ga to mete: &thorn;ou sal morne /
as hali Iob did / &thorn;at &thorn;us sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Antequam comedam: suspiro,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;bifore I ete: I sigh for mi kynd is made waike &amp; feble for Adam syn, &amp; ilk dai nedes bodili mete / til vphald &thorn;e kynd / &thorn;at ellis wold faile in a litel stounde&raquo;.  And as it tellis in &thorn;e life of hali faders: Isidorus &thorn;at hali man / when he hete: he wepid sare &amp; said: &laquo;Me schamis with me selfe, for I life with bestli mete / as o&thorn;er bestis dose &thorn;at na skill has of kynde, &amp; I goddis skilful creature / made like to him-self, &thorn;at suld hafe dwellid in paradise / &amp; &thorn;are hafe bien fed with heuenli fode&raquo;.  When &thorn;ou fyndis delite or sauour in mete or drynke: think on &thorn;e heuenli fode &thorn;at fedis all halughs / &thorn;at all likyngs ouer-passis, &amp; we be neauer fulfillid: or we &thorn;erof fele.  Men of religione heris lessons of hali mennis lyues at &thorn;aire
mete, so &thorn;at as &thorn;e bodi is fed with bodili fode: so &thorn;e saule be fed with hali
wordis.  Mannes bodi is as a fornace brennand / &amp; nameli of &thorn;e &yogh;onge; &amp; delicious &amp; hate metis &amp; drynkis: makis &thorn;is fire to brenne hatter; ffor-&thorn;i sais
saynt Ion: &laquo;Plente in &yogh;outhhede: is double fire&raquo;.  For-&thorn;i / al &thorn;at in &thorn;e flesh kyndels syn: is to flee.  &THORN;e wise man sais: &laquo;If &thorn;ou wil abate &thorn;e flawme: abate &thorn;e brandis&raquo;.  And saynt Ion: &laquo;flesh mete &amp; wyne: are kyndelyng of licherous steryngs&raquo;.  And saynt Austyn: &laquo;&THORN;e flesh is as a wild colt / &thorn;at is to teme with bridel &amp; hunger&raquo;.  &amp; Salomon: &laquo;Wand &amp; birden: fallis to &thorn;e asse&raquo; / &thorn;at bitakenes oure flesh. / Wiseli suld man note of &thorn;e mete / &thorn;at bifore him comes, &amp; take of &thorn;aim sa in mesure: &thorn;at &thorn;ai him noght greuid, bot &thorn;at he thorugh &thorn;aim: serue god &thorn;e better.  For-&thorn;i biddis sayn Ion: &laquo;ay when &thorn;ou etis: ay &thorn;at &thorn;ou hunger; &thorn;at after mete: &thorn;ou rede &amp; prai &amp; serue god &thorn;e better&raquo;.  Hali men / &thorn;at bifore vs has bien / notid store mete &amp; scharpe, mare til abate hunger: &thorn;en for ani lust.  Some lifd bi grace, some bi rotis, some bi spices &amp; herbis &amp; frute &thorn;at &thorn;e erth bare; &amp; in what so &thorn;ai ete: &thorn;ai fordid al sauour &thorn;at might stere to lust. Als sayn German menged askis in his brede, &thorn;at na likyng suld he haue in his mete-while.  O&thorn;er saus &thorn;en hunger: toke &thorn;ai nane.  Saynt Gregor sais: &laquo;brede


<PB N="151">

made of branne &amp; water / with cale or o&thorn;er symple potage: is gode fode to &thorn;e
wele-taght wambe, with saus of goddis luf / if he it haue &thorn;er-with; with-outen
&thorn;is saus: has na sustenance sauour / &thorn;at man notis&raquo;.  Some ete na mete / bifore
&thorn;e night; some: bot ilk o&thorn;er dai; some: fastid .iii. daies to-gedir.  Machari
fastid al &thorn;e lentyn-tide: bot &thorn;e sonendaies; and ete noght bot rawe leues.  Some
toke na kepe wha[n] &thorn;ai ete / ne what &thorn;ai ete, flesh ne fish, al sauorid &thorn;aim
ilike; so &thorn;at after: &thorn;ai ne wist what &thorn;ai ete.  Some when &thorn;ai ware sette to &thorn;e
mete &amp; mete before &thorn;aim broght: &thorn;ai forgate til ete; for so &thorn;ai spendid &thorn;e dai
&amp; &thorn;e night in hali speche: &thorn;at &thorn;ai thoght of noght ellis, to &thorn;e vndir-tide of &thorn;e
second dai / &thorn;at &thorn;aire brether come to &thorn;aim &amp; askid whi &thorn;ai wold noght ete; &amp; &thorn;en first: thoght &thorn;ai of mete, &amp; &thorn;ai ete &thorn;en as &thorn;aim gode thought / in goddis hali drede.  When &thorn;ou art set to &thorn;i mete: make bifore &thorn;e a crosse on &thorn;e borde
with .v. cromes, to stere &thorn;e to think on him: &thorn;at for &thorn;e deied on crosse; &amp; think, &laquo;here liggis his heued: &thorn;at corond was with thornes; &thorn;are his handes /
&thorn;are his fete: &thorn;at nailid was fulfast; &thorn;are was his swete side &thorn;at oppenid was
with &thorn;e spere, fra whilk come bathe blode and water / to hele mi wari woundes&raquo;.
When &thorn;ou has so done / if &thorn;ou mai so forthe: take parte of &thorn;i brede &amp; of &thorn;i
soule &amp; lai it be it ane, &amp; sai &thorn;us stilli in &thorn;i hert to god &thorn;i lorde: &laquo;Lorde: what wil &thorn;ou gif me for &thorn;is pitaunce / I to &thorn;e make?  how mani teres / how mani
luf-&yogh;ernyngs &amp; langyngs to &thorn;e?  how mani comfortes of &thorn;e hali gast, how mani
steryngs to gode, how mani lokyns to me with &thorn;i loueli ien?  lord, wil &thorn;ou for
&thorn;is mete &thorn;at &thorn;e pouer hungri sal haue for &thorn;e / gif me &thorn;e luf of &thorn;e?&raquo;  When
&thorn;ou has etyn &thorn;at &thorn;e gode think: loue &thorn;i lord &thorn;at &thorn;e has fed.  After mete: honest
&thorn;ou bee, and &yogh;eme &thorn;e fra mikil speche &amp; idel gamens, &amp; hald &thorn;i wittis inward vnder goddis drede.  Semeli it is to man / &amp; to god it pais: &thorn;at his beryng be
mare honest &amp; atempre / after mete &thorn;en bifore; &thorn;at na takenyng of outrage: be
in him sene; &thorn;at &thorn;e flesh / better mai serue &thorn;e saule in redyng / praiing &amp; o&thorn;er gastli werkis: &thorn;at mai helpe to gode. // &THORN;ine euen-sange: sai with &thorn;e deuocion
&thorn;at god &thorn;e sendis / in kirk or oratori or whare &thorn;ou mai best sai / fra noice &amp; thrang of &thorn;e werld.  After / if &thorn;e nede: ga soupe, &amp; schort be &thorn;i souper-tyme;
so in mesure &thorn;ou take mete &amp; drink: &thorn;at it be na charge ne greuance to &thorn;i
kynde / ne lettyng<MILESTONE N="63" UNIT="folio"> to serue &thorn;i lorde, or in tyme of rest: reue &thorn;e &thorn;i slepe, or with foule fandynge in &thorn;i slepe: &thorn;e fende &thorn;e file, as he dose oft with &thorn;a &thorn;at with a ful wambe gas to bed.  Ilk man ete as sayn Ion sais, &laquo;after he is of strenth, &amp; of elde, &amp; after his bodi is mare or lesse, or hale or seke; take &thorn;at him nedis to sustenance of his kynde: &amp; noght as lust askis&raquo;.  After souper: ga to &thorn;e kirk / or to o&thorn;er stede / whare &thorn;ou mai be mast in rest / &amp; &thorn;are sai &thorn;i complyn, for in &thorn;is tyme as saynt Ambrose sais: &laquo;foules in &thorn;aire lede loues &thorn;aire lord, &amp; thankis him in &thorn;aire kynde: for &thorn;e godes he has &thorn;aim done&raquo;.  Kal &thorn;ou &thorn;en on &thorn;i god &amp; sai: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Conuerte nos deus sa[lutaris] noster,</FOREIGN> as if he said: &laquo;lord, I haf bien &thorn;is dai taried with &thorn;e werld, &thorn;at has mikel lettid me to serue &thorn;e; thorugh fandyng of &thorn;e fend &amp; mi flesh, oft &thorn;is dai I haf done mis; for-&thorn;i, lord, turne me now fra &thorn;e werld / &amp; fra all &thorn;at mai me let til loue &thorn;e with pure hert &amp; all mi wittis, so &thorn;at &thorn;ai be entendant to &thorn;e: to wirk &thorn;i will&raquo;.  And sai forth &thorn;en &thorn;i Complyn, &amp; after: o&thorn;er praiers with deuocion &thorn;at god &thorn;e sendis.  And after / or &thorn;ou ga to bed: hald a chapeter with &thorn;i hert, &amp; ask it in what thing


<PB N="152">

it is better &thorn;en it was.  Has &thorn;ou schryuen &thorn;e &yogh;it of &thorn;at syn &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;en &amp; &thorn;are did? of &thorn;a wordes &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;are spake?  of &thorn;at iuel will / &thorn;ou was &thorn;en in?  of &thorn;at wrange &thorn;ou &thorn;are did / &amp; said to him?  of &thorn;at handelynge, of &thorn;at lakkynge, of &thorn;at foule thought, of &thorn;at thing &thorn;ou left vndone &thorn;ou suld haf done?  &amp; art &thorn;ou in will to leue swilk vnthewis?  What fandyngs withstode &thorn;ou &thorn;is day?  in what art &thorn;ou mekar &thorn;en &thorn;ou was?  in what mare chaste, mare sober, mare suffrand, mare
atempre, mare lufand god in &thorn;i bre&thorn;er, or mare likyng has in god &thorn;en &thorn;ou had?
Lefe &thorn;at syn &thorn;at &thorn;ou thorugh custume: so oft fallis in?  &amp; o&thorn;er mani vnthewis
&thorn;ou has done &amp; paied &thorn;e fende with: &amp; greuid &thorn;i gode god, &amp; has forbarrid &thorn;e of grace &thorn;at suld helpe &thorn;e?  And &thorn;en with a forthinkynge of &thorn;as synnes &thorn;at
bitis &thorn;ine inwit: knok on &thorn;i breste &amp; sai a <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster,</FOREIGN> with <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Aue Maria,</FOREIGN> on &thorn;i knees; and sone on &thorn;e morne: &thorn;ou schryue &thorn;e of &thorn;as synnes.  And if &thorn;ou &thorn;us
do: I hope &thorn;e fend sal be afferd / &thorn;e for to fande; for &thorn;ou art vnder goddis
warde: whil &thorn;ou &thorn;us &thorn;e beris.  After &thorn;is rekenyng whar-thorugh &thorn;i saule is raisid
in a celi hope to &thorn;e fader of merci &amp; &thorn;i flesh waxes heuy: ga to &thorn;i rest; for if
&thorn;ou let &thorn;i flesh of &thorn;e nedefulnes &amp; trauail it oute of might: faynteli wil it help
&thorn;e / or let with-all.  And or &thorn;ou ga to rest: biteche &thorn;e &amp; al &thorn;i frendes in til
goddes handes / &thorn;at for vs ware nailid to &thorn;e tree, &amp; biseke him for his merci:
he &yogh;eme &thorn;e fra all perils of bodi &amp; saule, &amp; arme &thorn;e with &thorn;e takenyng of &thorn;e crosse; for whare &thorn;e fend sees &thorn;is merke: sone he flees.  Of &thorn;is merk is writen
in &thorn;e life of saynt Edmund, &thorn;at as he went an tyme al ane: a child aperd to
him &thorn;at was wonder faire, / &amp; said: &laquo;Hayle, mi frende: wham I luf in god&raquo;.
Saynt Edmund was awondred of &thorn;is gretyng.  &amp; &thorn;e child said to him: &laquo;Knawes
&thorn;ou me noght?&raquo;  &amp; saynt Edmund said to &thorn;e child: &laquo;How suld I know &thorn;e? / I saw &thorn;e neuer are&raquo;.  &THORN;en &thorn;e child said: &laquo;When &thorn;ou lerde in &thorn;e scole: I sate ai bi &thorn;i side; &amp; euer sithen I haf bien with &thorn;e: whare-so &thorn;ou has duellid; for so mi lord has festenid &thorn;e with me: &thorn;at I might neuer part fra &thorn;e / slike is mi lordis will.  Bot bihald in mi fronte: &amp; rede what &thorn;ou sees &thorn;are&raquo;.  He lokid as he him bade / &amp; with heuenli letters: &thorn;is .IIII. wordes / he sagh &thorn;are writen:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ihesus na&yogh;arenus, Rex iudeorum.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;en said &thorn;e child: &laquo;&thorn;is is mi lordis name / &thorn;at &thorn;ou sees &thorn;us writen.  &THORN;is name I wil &thorn;ou haf in mynde / &amp; prente it in &thorn;i saule; &amp; croice &thorn;i fronte with &thorn;is name: or &thorn;ou ga to slepe: &amp; fra drecchings of &thorn;e fend: it sal &thorn;e &yogh;eme &thorn;at night, &amp; fra sodayn dede; &amp; all &thorn;as &thorn;at bi night: croicis &thorn;aim &thorn;erwith&raquo;.  &amp; when he had &thorn;is wordes spoken: he vanist awai. / Bere some hali thoughtis with &thorn;e to bed / &amp; sai &thorn;i praiers / til slepe fal on &thorn;e. Til hafe soft slepe &amp; swete: souerayn helpe is mesure &amp; sobernes of mete &amp; drink: with mynde of goddis law &amp; hali write; as god thorugh &thorn;e prophete sais:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Custodi legem meam &amp; consilium meum: &amp; si dormieris, non timebis; quiesces: &amp; suauis erit sompnus tuus.</FOREIGN>  And euer as &thorn;ou wakyns: lift &thorn;i hert to god / with som hali thought, &amp; rise &amp; prai to &thorn;i lorde / &thorn;at he grante relesse of paynes / to &thorn;e dead, &amp; grace to &thorn;e quyk / &amp; lif with-outen ende.  If fandyng of licheri stere &thorn;e in bed: think &thorn;at &thorn;i gode lord / for &thorn;e hyngis on rode; think on his .v. wondes / &thorn;at stremid downe of blode; think &thorn;at his bed: was &thorn;e hard knotti tree, &amp; in stede of a cod: he had a croune of thornis.  And sai &thorn;en with sighing sare: til cole &thorn;i lust: &laquo;Mi dere-worthi lord / for me hinged on rode / &amp; I lig in &thorn;is soft bed / &amp; weltris me in syn: as a foule swyne / &thorn;at loues bot
filth&raquo;.  Rise &thorn;en tide: &amp; halde with praiers &amp; loue-sighings &amp; teris.
</P>
<P>
<PB N="153">Of .iii. poyntis be warre.  &THORN;e first / &thorn;at &thorn;as deuocions &thorn;at &thorn;ou has thorugh grace
sterand: be noght knowyn of o&thorn;er; hide &thorn;aim in &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai: with will &amp; dede,
for drede of vayn-glorie. / &thorn;e .ii: &thorn;at &thorn;ou think noght it is in &thorn;i might / slike
deuocions &amp; steryngs til haue / ai when &thorn;ou wil; bot aneli thorugh goddis grace /
when he wil &thorn;aim send.  &THORN;e .iii.: &thorn;at &thorn;ou late noght ouer-wele of &thorn;e-self for
slike steryngs, ne think &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou art dere with god; ne deme nane o&thorn;er mare
vnworthi: &thorn;at dose noght as &thorn;ou dose; bot when &thorn;ou has all wele done: think
sotheli bi &thorn;e-selfe / &amp; grant it with worde: &laquo;it is noght worth, lord, &thorn;at I do:
for I am bot an vnnaite thrall&raquo;.  If &thorn;ou wil tyne na mede: deme nane o&thorn;er,
bot hald &thorn;e-self mast vnworthi; for if &thorn;ou fast / or prai mare &thorn;en an o&thorn;er,
per-case an o&thorn;er passis &thorn;e in mekenes &amp; suffrance &amp; lufyng.  &THORN;erfore / think of &thorn;at &thorn;e wantys / &amp; noght aneli of &thorn;at &thorn;ou haues.  Noght-for-&thorn;i / god wil &thorn;ou think on &thorn;as graces &amp; godes he has &thorn;e done: to stere &thorn;e til knowe &thorn;e endettid til him for &thorn;aim / &amp; serue him &amp; luf him &thorn;e mare; or if &thorn;ou in angir be: til glad &thorn;e with.  Some-while it fallis / &thorn;at he is better in goddis dome<MILESTONE N="64" UNIT="folio">&thorn;at man demes iuel: &thorn;en some &thorn;at man demes gode.  Mani are honest with-oute: &amp; vnclene with-in; Some werldli &amp; dissolute: &amp; hali with-in / as goddis priue
frendes.  And some beris &thorn;aim in mannis sight / as angels, &amp; in goddis sight &thorn;ai stynk as synful wrechis; And some semes synful til mannes dome: &amp; are ful dere til god
almighti, for &thorn;aire indre berynge: is heuenli in goddis bright sight.  &THORN;erfore deme we nane o&thorn;er: bot vs-selfe.  And prai we for vs-selfe &amp; all o&thorn;er til Ihesu Crist Mari son / &thorn;at for vs was nailid on rode, &thorn;at wha-so is bonden in dedli syn: he louse &thorn;aim; &amp; &thorn;a &thorn;at are in gode life: he grant &thorn;aim end &thorn;erin.
</P><LB>
<P>Twa messagers are comen to &thorn;e: to tell &thorn;e tithandis.  &THORN;at ane hat &laquo;Drede&raquo;,
&thorn;at comes fra hell to warne &thorn;e of &thorn;i harme; &thorn;at o&thorn;er: hat &laquo;Hope&raquo;, &thorn;at comes fra heuen til tell &thorn;e of blis &thorn;ou sal haue / if &thorn;ou wele do.  Drede sais he sagh
in hell so mani synful be pyned / &thorn;at if all &thorn;e wittes of men ware in an: ne
might he &thorn;aim tell; &laquo;of glotones, licheours, robbeours, theues; Riche men with
&thorn;aire seruant&yogh;: &thorn;at &thorn;e pouer harmed; Domesmen &thorn;at wold noght deme: bot it
ware for mede; Countours &thorn;at &thorn;e wrange bi &thorn;aire sotilte mayntiend; Demesters
&thorn;at leal men dampnid: &amp; delyuerid starke theues; Werkmen &thorn;at falsli swynkis:
&amp; takis ful hire; Tilmen &thorn;at falsli tendis; Prelates &thorn;at has cure of mannes saulis:
&thorn;at noi&thorn;er chastis ne techis &thorn;aim; Of all lede of men &thorn;at wrangli has wroght:
&thorn;are I sagh &thorn;at ilkan bitterli it boght.  For &thorn;are I sagh defaute of al godenes,
&amp; plente of pyne &amp; sorugh, as: hate fire ai brennand, brinstane stynkand, gredi
deuels as dragons: wide gapand, hunger &amp; thrist for eauer lastand, nedders &amp; tadis: on &thorn;e synful gnawand.  Slike sorugh &amp; &yogh;elling &amp; gnaystyng of tethe I herd
&thorn;are: &thorn;at nere for ferid: I lost mi wit.  Slike mirknes &thorn;ar was: &thorn;at I might it
grape; &amp; sa bitter was &thorn;e smoke: &thorn;at it made &thorn;e waful wrechis til grete glowand
teres; &amp; bitterli I herd &thorn;aim banne &thorn;e tyme: &thorn;ai ware borne in.  Now &thorn;ai &yogh;erne
til deie: &amp; &thorn;ai mai noght deie; dead &thorn;at &thorn;ai some-tyme hatid: had &thorn;ai now
leuer / &thorn;en all &thorn;e gode of &thorn;is werld.  And &thorn;erfore I warne &thorn;e / bot &thorn;ou amend
&thorn;e of &thorn;i synnes / with scrift &amp; penance / &amp; haue a stedfast will to leue &thorn;aim
for euer: a sege I sagh in helle made for &thorn;e of brinnand fire, whare deuels &thorn;e
sal pyne / euer withouten ende&raquo;. // &THORN;at o&thorn;er messager &thorn;at hat &laquo;Hope&raquo;: sais he


<PB N="154">

is comen fra heuen til tell &thorn;e of &thorn;at vntelland mikil ioie: &thorn;at goddis frendis
weldis; &laquo;to tell &thorn;erof as it is: mai nane erthli man speke, &thorn;of his tonge ware
of stele.  For &thorn;are is a gracious felawschipe of all goddis frendis, ordirs of angels
&amp; of hali halughs, &amp; almighti god abouen: &thorn;at gladdis &thorn;aim all.  Of all godenes
I sagh plente: fairenes &amp; riches &thorn;at ai lastis, honour and power &thorn;at neuer sal
faile, wisdome &amp; luf / &amp; ai-lastand ioie.  &THORN;are I herd melodi &amp; sange of angels bright.  So worthi is &thorn;at ioie / &amp; so grete with-al, &thorn;at wha-so might taste of
it a cely drope: he suld be so rauyst in liking of god / &amp; slike &yogh;ernyng he suld
haue / &thorn;ider to wyn: &thorn;at al &thorn;e ioie of &thorn;is werld / ware to him
payne.  With sa grete a lufe he suld be ouertane in &yogh;ernynge to wyn to &thorn;at blisse: &thorn;at be
a hundreth sithes it suld mare stere him to luf vertu&yogh; &amp; flee syn / &thorn;en ani drede
he might haue of &thorn;e payne of hell.  And I say &thorn;e for sothe / if &thorn;ou wil leue
syn &amp; do goddis biddyngs &amp; luf him as &thorn;e agh: a riche sege &amp; a faire / god to
&thorn;e has made, whare-in &thorn;ou sal dwell with him / with-outen ende&raquo;. &mdash;
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Tercia pars libri</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e thrid parti &amp; &thorn;e last of &thorn;is boke: techis a man to bere him sa / whare-so
he comes, &amp; what-so he dose: &thorn;at it be louyng to god &amp; ensample of gode /
til all &thorn;at him sees; for &thorn;e apostle redis &thorn;us: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnia in vobis honeste &amp; secundum ordinem fiant,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;al &thorn;at &yogh;e do: honesti &amp; ordeynli / loke &thorn;at &yogh;e it do&raquo;. &THORN;en at &thorn;e first / ilk a goddis lufar loke &thorn;at he noght &yogh;erne to mangil him with &thorn;e werld / &thorn;at taris &amp; desceyuis: all &thorn;at with it delis, &amp; lettis &thorn;aim of mani godis: &thorn;at &thorn;ai might do.  And &thorn;a men &thorn;at wil nouther reste bot ai raikis
aboute: &thorn;aire ien sees mani thinges &thorn;at &thorn;e iee sendis to &thorn;e herte; &amp; &thorn;ein come
&thorn;ai noght lightli / after &thorn;ai are &thorn;are inprintid.  Sayn Bernard pleynis him of &thorn;e
harmes &thorn;at he felid in &thorn;e werld / whils he was &thorn;erin, &amp; sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mundus circumcinxit me &amp; obsedit,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;&THORN;e werld has bisegid me on ilk a side, &amp; thorugh &thorn;e &yogh;atis of mi .v. wittes: he to me shotis / &amp; woundes me ful sare, &amp; thorugh &thorn;e woundes / dead pressis in: to sla mi sari saule.  Mine ien lokes: &amp; mi thought
chaungees, &amp; kyndels me in syn.  Mine eris heris: &amp; mi hert bowes &thorn;erto.  I smell
with mi nese: &amp; it likis mi thought.  With mi mouth I speke: &amp; in mi speche
I like, or o&thorn;er bigilis.  &amp; with a litil ouer-soft felyng: licheri kyndels in mi flesh.
&amp; &thorn;e fende mi faa, &thorn;at I mai noght see: standis euer agayns me / with his
bowe bente&raquo;.  For-&thorn;i / if nede stere man to wende in to &thorn;e werld / &thorn;are so
mani steryngs are to syn: with grete drede he sal wende / as in to a batail to
fight with his faas.  It nedis he be wele armid agayn &thorn;e arowis of his faa: &thorn;at
thrali to him shotis; &amp; &thorn;e mare he mai him drede: for he mai noght him see;
with caltrappis &amp; gildirs: &thorn;e wai is ful sette.  For-&thorn;i / arme him with goddis
hali drede: &thorn;at oute sal wende.  God warnid his disciples to be warre in &thorn;e
werld / when he &thorn;us said: &laquo;Sotheli &thorn;e werld sal withstand &yogh;ow / with sere
fandyngs&raquo;.  For-&thorn;i / if &thorn;ou sal nedis wende oute for &thorn;ine awne profit or o&thorn;eris:
colour noght &thorn;i wendyng with na fals hewe / to feyne &thorn;e an encheson to dali
with &thorn;e werld / for likyng or biete, or to be knowen with lordis bifore o&thorn;er...
&amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai make contenance with worde &amp; feyne in &thorn;at &thorn;ai mai: to be haldyn hali of all &thorn;at &thorn;aim sees; or puttis &thorn;aim to daliance of &thorn;e werld: mare &thorn;en
nedis, as to biyng / or sellyng / or Iangling of werldli thinges.  And all &thorn;aire
vtter bering / swa acordis to &thorn;e werld: &thorn;at &thorn;ai make sothe / &thorn;at Dauid sais:


<PB N="155">

<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Commixti sunt inter gentes: &amp;<MILESTONE N="65" UNIT="folio">didicerunt opera eorum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;&thorn;ai menge &thorn;aim with &thorn;e folk of &thorn;e werld / &thorn;at has na knowyng of god; &amp; slike werkis as &thorn;ai see &thorn;aim do: slike &thorn;ai wirke&raquo;.  &THORN;erfore when &thorn;ou nedis to ga forthe: croice &thorn;e with &thorn;e hali name of IHESU Mari son &thorn;at deied on &thorn;e rode, for &thorn;en art &thorn;ou mare siker: whider-so &thorn;ou ga; as saynt Austyn said til his brethir: when &thorn;ai forth wente.  And saynt Ion sais: &laquo;Whider-so &thorn;ou ga / &amp; what-so &thorn;ou dose: &thorn;i forheued &amp; &thorn;i breste &thorn;ou merk with &thorn;e croice; for it is na merk: &thorn;e fend so mikil dredis&raquo;.  Loke &thorn;ine vttir klathing / noi&thorn;er be ouer-laith ne ouer-curious / in schap nor in hu.  Hald &thorn;i lymes in &thorn;aire office: &thorn;at &thorn;ai are made to, ne cast noght &thorn;ine ien ouer-al as a barne; flish noght &thorn;i handes: ne lepe noght with
&thorn;i fete.  When &thorn;e hert of man is oute of warde: &thorn;e lymes somdele failes in
&thorn;aire office.  And as &thorn;ou ordayns &thorn;ine vtter beryng in outeyng: als loke &thorn;ou be
with-in / deuote, &amp; nameli in praying / &amp; louyng of &thorn;i lorde.  If &thorn;ou mai noght
in outeyng rest whil &thorn;ou makis &thorn;i praiers: ga &thorn;e softer.  Mani thinges lettis &thorn;e
trauailand to prai: werynes of lymes, men &thorn;at he metis &thorn;at with him spekis; &thorn;e
.v. wittis &thorn;en fletis oute of warde / &amp; &thorn;en kelis &thorn;e deuocion of &thorn;e praiand.
When &thorn;ou has said &thorn;i praiers walkand &thorn;at &thorn;ou art halden to sai: lift vp &thorn;i hert
to god &amp; prai him in &thorn;i thought in a celi mynde; think on &thorn;e godes god has
&thorn;e done / &amp; sal do if &thorn;ou him truli serue; think on his biddyngs: &amp; do &thorn;aim
in dede after &thorn;i might; for so god biddis &thorn;are he &thorn;us sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Erunt verba hec que precipio tibi / in corde tuo, &amp; enarrabis ea filiis, &amp; meditaberis ea / sedens in domo tua, &amp; ambulans in itinere, dormiens &amp; consurgens.</FOREIGN>  Or in trauailing: tell faire talis to &thorn;i felawes, or sum-what of hali write, &thorn;at mai soft &yogh;oure wai &amp; glad &yogh;ow in god.  And sai sum-tyme &thorn;e .vii. psalmes for &thorn;e quik &amp; &thorn;e dead, &thorn;at god gif grace to &thorn;e quike: &amp; rest to &thorn;e dead. / When &thorn;ou comes to &thorn;e toune til ese &thorn;i bodi: seke &thorn;ider &thorn;are &thorn;ou mai mast honestli duell for &thorn;ine state, &amp; in mast pece, &amp; &thorn;are &thorn;ou mai mast profit til &thorn;e-selfe &amp; til o&thorn;er.  Flesh lust &amp; vanite: till &thorn;e to na stede; bot spere whare ani is &thorn;at mast lufis god: &amp; &thorn;ider &thorn;ou draw. Seke noght whare &thorn;ou mai best be fed: for &thorn;are per-auenture are mani sterings to syn.  Herbery &thorn;e with na woman: bot if &thorn;ou knowe &thorn;aim for gode / of lang tyme.  When &thorn;ou art comen to &thorn;e house &thorn;ou sal rest in: hald &thorn;i wittis in &thorn;aire warde in goddis hali drede, so &thorn;at &thorn;ine vtter bering be so rulid with grace: &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai stere to gode / all &thorn;at &thorn;e sees, &amp; fordo thorugh goddis grace: merknes of syn; &amp; so fulfill goddis teching: &thorn;at &thorn;us sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sic luceat lux v[estra] c[oram] h[ominibus] vt vi[deant] o[pera] u[estra b[ona] &amp; g[lorificent] p[atrem] v[estrum] qui in celis est.</FOREIGN>  And sayn Gregor: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Neque valde laudabile est / esse bonum cum bonis,
set bonum esse cum malis; sicut enim grauioris culpe est / inter bonos bonum non
esse: sic immensi preconii est / bonum inter malos extitisse.</FOREIGN>  Kepe wele &thorn;ine ien when &thorn;ou art comen to herbiri: fra all thing &thorn;at mai kyndel syn; &amp; make foreward with &thorn;ine ien / as Iob did, &thorn;at said: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pepigi fedus cum oculis meis: ne cogitarem de virgine.</FOREIGN>  After sight: comes thought, &amp; &thorn;er-after: dede.<MILESTONE N="66 " UNIT="folio"> &amp; &thorn;erfore said &thorn;e prophete Ieremie: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oculus meus depredatus est animam meam.</FOREIGN>  When so hali prophete menid him of his ieesight: sare mai an o&thorn;er him pleyn / &thorn;at oft synnes &thorn;erwith.  Augus[tinus]: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Inpudicus oculus: inpudici cordis est nuncius.  Gregor: Non licet respici: quod non licet concupisci.</FOREIGN>  Dauid: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Auerte oculos m[eos] ne vi[deant] va[nitatem].</FOREIGN>  Loke alswa &thorn;at &thorn;ou here na thing: &thorn;at mai stere to syn, as licherous wordes, bakbityng, fals domes, grete athis, threpyng, stryuing, &amp; o&thorn;er


<PB N="156">

slike vnthewes.  Alswa / at &thorn;i mete: ordeynli &thorn;ou &thorn;e bere, &amp; hald &thorn;e in mesure;
&amp; seke after na dayntees, bot of commune metis be paied. / Avise &thorn;e in
spekynge: to whaim, what, when, how, of whaim, &amp; whare; &amp; so ordeynli &thorn;ou &thorn;e
hafe: &thorn;at &thorn;ou be noght like til o&thorn;er werldis men, bot fulfil &thorn;e apostle worde:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nolite conformari huic seculo, quia vestra conuersacio in celis est.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;of oure bodi be in &thorn;is werld as a clote of erth: it nedis oure spirit &thorn;at is boght with &thorn;e dere-worthi blode of god almighti / be with mynde &amp; will in heuen, noght soil
him here with syn as swyne dose in &thorn;e dike.  And what-so &thorn;ou dose / &amp; whare-so &thorn;ou comes: do as &thorn;e apostle teches: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnibus prebe te exemplum bonorum operum;</FOREIGN> for thorugh gode ensample: god is worschipd &amp; loued, men are helpid
&amp; lerid / &amp; strynthid in &thorn;aire bileue.  Haue &yogh;ow so / &thorn;at men &thorn;at duellis with &yogh;ow: mai sai bi &yogh;ow / &thorn;at was said bi &thorn;e apostles Paule and Barnabe: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dii similes facti hominibus: descenderunt ad nos,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;goddis in liknes of men: are
comen downe til vs&raquo;. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> Deo gracias.</FOREIGN>
</P></DIV4>
</DIV3>

<DIV3 N="Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="310"><HEAD>Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="243" UNIT="folio">

<P>Thre thynges are nedefull till ilk a mane of what state he be, to mekill his
mede, thurgh goddes grace helpande, als abouene es sayde, &thorn;at hym sall lede.
The ffirste es &thorn;at mane be in honeste werke with-owttene lettynge of his tyme.
The secunde, &thorn;at he his werke do with a fredome of spyrite, in stede and in
tyme als till ilke werke falles.  The thirde, &thorn;at his vttire berynge, whare-so he
cummes, so honeste be &amp; faire, &thorn;at louynge be to god, and stirryng of gude till
all &thorn;at hyme seese; &thorn;at &thorn;e appostill byddynge &thorn;ay ful-fill in dede, &thorn;at sayse:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnia in vobis honeste &amp; secundum ordinem fiant,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es at saye: &laquo;all &thorn;at &yogh;e do, honestely be it done, [&] in ordire&raquo;.
</P>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<P>At the fyrste, sall euer-ylke gud cristene mane vmbyluke hyme &amp; euer be
warre &thorn;at he tyne noghte the schorte tyme, or wrange dispende it, or in ydilnes
late it ouer passe; &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at god hase lente hyme to serue hym with-all, to
gedir in gud werkes tresure of grace, to by hym with heuene.  The tyme of
werke es schorte, &amp; for-thi the faster it es to wirke, &thorn;at we ne tyne noghte &thorn;is
schorte tyme &amp; sa lose oure mede.  &amp; noghte anely this schorte tyme fra vs flees,
bot &thorn;are flees, als &thorn;e wyse mane sayse, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nostra etas volat,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es at say &laquo;oure elde flees&raquo;.  Slepe we, wake we, or whate sa we elles do, oure lyfe glyddes away; and als saynt Gregor sayse, &laquo;oure lyfe es lyke a mane in a schippe: sytte he or stande, slepe he or wake he, euer he es thedirwarde whedir &thorn;e schipe
dryues thurgh strenthe of &thorn;e wynde.  Righte sa we in this schorte whille, whate
sa we do, we dryue euer till oure ende&raquo;.  For-thi we spede vs in this schorte


<PB N="311">

tyme, als oure enemy folows vs euer at &thorn;e bake with a scharpe swerde to styke
vs thurghe.  And sothely oure enemy, thate es &thorn;e [dede], folows vs euer at the
bakke: ffor als Senec sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vita fugit, mors sequitur,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;the lyfe flees &amp; the dede freschely folows&raquo;; for oure lyfe es noghte elles bot passynge fra lyfe, and saynt Austyne sayse &thorn;at &laquo;lyf es bot a swyfte rynnynge to &thorn;e dede&raquo;. For-thi it es [noght] to tell by how lang a mane lyffes, bot how wele.  &yogh;it this schorte lyfe es vncertayne &amp; vnstabill, how lang it sall laste: &amp; for-thi Iob sayse:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nescio quam diu subsistam, &amp; si post modicum tollatt me factor meus,</FOREIGN> &laquo;I ne wate, sayse &thorn;e haly mane Iobe, how lange here I sall duelle, ne whene my makere will take me hythene&raquo;.  Here-of spekes saynt Gregor whare he &thorn;us sayse: &laquo;I ne wate noghte, sayse &thorn;is haly mane, the while I sall duelle here, ne whene &thorn;at I
hythene sall be tane and ledde to &thorn;e dome&raquo;.  Mannes lyfe es lykkynde to the
wynde, &thorn;at of all thynges es maste vnstabill.  For saynt Gregore sayse: &laquo;Schorte es
mannes lyfe, &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;at schortnes es euer vncertayne&raquo;.  For-[&thorn;i] saynt Ierome sayse: &laquo;na thynge sa mekill be-gyles mane als, mane ne knawes noghte &thorn;e tyme of his lyfe, &thorn;at to his witt vncertane es, &amp; &yogh;itt highte he hym-selfe lang to lyfe, als he myghte at his will dryue dede obake&raquo;.  Thus desceyued was &thorn;e riche mane of whame &thorn;e gospelle spekes, &thorn;at sa mekill gud hade raked to-gedir &thorn;at he ne
wyste whare it to do; na thyng hym greuede, so all thynge felle to his will, bot
&thorn;at he had no housesynge to do his gudes Ine; thus als vnwitty he spake to
hym-selfe: &laquo;My saule, now may [&thorn;ou] reste the &amp; lede thi lyfe with ese, for
reches &amp; gudes &thorn;ou hase ynoghe for many &yogh;eres to spende&raquo;: bot for he thoghte
all one his gudes &amp; noghte one the dede, a voyce come fra almyghtty god &amp; sterynly to hym sayde: &laquo;a, foule, this nyghte &thorn;e fendis of helle thy saule sall
fra the refe; and at &thorn;ou sa lange gadirde samene, wha sall it hafe?&raquo;  Happy had
&thorn;is riche mane bene and wyselyere had he wroghte, &amp; he wolde hafe done after
Salamone rede, &thorn;at all teches how &thorn;ay sall do if reches to &thorn;ame fall; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Diuicie si affluant, nolite apponere cor,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es at say: &laquo;if reches to &thorn;e falle, feste noghte one &thorn;ame thy herte&raquo;; for &thorn;ay are faylande &amp; noghte lastande ay, &amp; slepir als ane eele, &thorn;at whene mene wenys he hase hym faste, als fantome he fra hyme glyddys, &amp; tynys hym for ay.  And thus it es by erthely gudes ffor whame mene swynke so sare to gedir &thorn;ame to-gedir &thorn;at riste may &thorn;ay nane hafe ne of noghte elles thynkkes, &amp; whene &thorn;ay hafe &thorn;at &thorn;ay &yogh;erne, with righte or with wrange, or with pore mene malysouns that bytterly &thorn;ame bannes, &thorn;ane, whene &thorn;ay thynke &thorn;ame maste sekire, and alle to &thorn;ame falles ryghte als &thorn;ay walde, sodanly &thorn;ay fra &thorn;ame glyde als a sleper eele mene haldes by &thorn;e tayle: for owthir &thorn;aire gudes fra &thorn;ame partys whylls &thorn;ay are here, or ells &thorn;ay dy fra &thorn;air gudes whene &thorn;ay walde fayneste lyfe, &amp; noghte with &thorn;ame beris bot malysouns &amp; synnes &thorn;at sall wende with &thorn;ame to &thorn;e strayte dome &amp; chalange &thorn;ame by-fore god, for with wrange &amp; in ill vse &thorn;ay spende &thorn;ame &amp; ouer-mekill luffede &thorn;ame agaynes goddis will.  Vnhappy me thynke &thorn;ane &thorn;ay ere &thorn;at for &thorn;am ouer-mekill cares.  And &thorn;at mane sall noghte affy hym in reches, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">exemplum</FOREIGN>: Mighte reches, &thorn;at &thorn;e worlde &yogh;eldis to thase &thorn;at for &thorn;ame swynkes, bynde hym to make &thorn;am sekyre &thorn;at &thorn;ay sulde euer with &thorn;ame laste?  &yogh;it lo, &thorn;at &thorn;ane hade mene some coloure erthely gudes to &yogh;erne &amp; hertly for &thorn;ame to swynke als mene now dose.  Bot this may


<PB N="312">

noghte the werlde mow do one na wyse, ffor that thynge he ne hase of
hym-selfe &thorn;at may lett that na he sall passe, and &thorn;at he hase noghte, gyffe it to
o&thorn;er; ffor &thorn;e haly wrytt be &thorn;e werlde &amp; by all his thynges thus sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Mundus transsibit, &amp; concupiscencia eius,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es thus mekill for to say: &laquo;The werlde salle
passe, with all his thynges &thorn;at mene here after &yogh;ernes, whate so euer &thorn;ay be&raquo;;
and the law wretyne thus sayse: That mane may gyffe na mare ryghte in a
thynge to o&thorn;er thane hym-selfe hase.  Righte als &thorn;ou may see by a mane &thorn;at
es fallene in a watter &amp; thurgh strenghe it beris hym forthe &amp; reues hym &thorn;e
grounde; if he may wyne to a stake or to a rote &thorn;at gud festenynge hase,
he may lett &thorn;e water to bere hym furthe: bot if he festyne hym-selfe till a
thynge &thorn;at fletis als he duse, he may noghte &thorn;ane lett &thorn;e water to bere hyme
furthe or whedir it will.  Bot sothely, nyll we will we, in &thorn;is werlde als in
a water with &thorn;e gudes of this werlde euer are we passande, &amp; noghte es in
&thorn;is werlde to festyne vs by to lett vs &thorn;at we ne sall passe: ffor als &thorn;e haly
mane by vs sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnes moriemur &amp; sicut aqua dilabimur in terra,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say: &laquo;Alle sall we dy and als water wende in to &thorn;e erthe&raquo;. For-thi &thorn;e haly mane Iob sayse by hym-selfe &thorn;at here I knawe &thorn;e sothe: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ego ille opulentus quondam, repente contritus sum, et ecce leues amici mei transierunt,
et semitam per quam non reuertor ambulo:</FOREIGN> &laquo;loo, said &thorn;is haly mane, I &thorn;at some-tyme was so riche, to what meschefe I am now fallene!  loo my schortt frendis hase me lefte, &amp; by &thorn;at way now I wende bot &thorn;er-by I come neuer agayne&raquo;; and is als if he saide: &laquo;Riches &amp; frendis I ha[d]e ma &thorn;ane o&thorn;er of &thorn;e lande, &amp; all tha na myghte me lett &thorn;at ne me byhouede furthe wende, &amp; nyll I will I &thorn;at waye I wende with-owtene agayne-come&raquo;.  Bot whylke es &thorn;is pase mane sall wende by, &thorn;e prophett &thorn;er he schewes with thir wordis: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnis caro fenum, &amp; omnis gloria eius quasi flos agri,</FOREIGN> &laquo;Mane, he saise, es als hay, &amp; als flowres in the medowe &thorn;at growes, to mane &thorn;at es lufly &amp; faire&raquo;.  Mannes flesche es als haye, &amp; all his Ioy &amp; noblaye as &thorn;e flour in &thorn;e medowe, &thorn;at so faire growes. Haye firste waxes in grene grysse, &amp; sone after he brynges furthe faire floures; &amp; if he stande after a while &thorn;ane &thorn;e floures dryes &amp; falles, and after he es mawene downe with &thorn;e sythe &amp; d[r]ye[d], sythene es it lede to house &amp; &yogh;emyd to bestis fode.  Thus it fares by &thorn;e mane &thorn;at borne es in &thorn;is werlde: in his childhede he sprynges &amp; waxes as dose &thorn;e grysse &thorn;at lufly es one to luke, efter he waxes to mane &amp; so he floresche in fairenes &amp; strenghe &amp; wytt &amp; hauynge of erthely gudes &thorn;at to hym falles; &thorn;ane sone after als he drawes till elde, &thorn;e floures falles &amp; fayles, &thorn;at ere his vertus, fairehede, strenghe, wytte, syghte, felynge &amp; herynge, &amp; efter &thorn;at he es smetyne downe with the sythe of dede, sythene led to house to bestis fode, &thorn;at es to say, doluene he es in &thorn;e erthe to fede wormes with.  &amp; this wittnes &thorn;e holy mane &thorn;er he thus sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cum moritur homo habitabit inter serpentes et bestias,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es thus for to say: &laquo;When mane es dede, with tadis, neddirs &amp; foulle venymos bestis sall his duellyng be&raquo;.  Whatt thynge es so wlatesome to &thorn;e werlde or vnworthi, als es mane whene he es dede?  &thorn;at &thorn;e werlde so mekill lattis by whills mane by hym lyffes, so hethely &thorn;e werlde lattis by hym sone whene he es dede, &thorn;at he ne may thole hym be in his house thre dayes to-gedir, bot borne [he] es owte &thorn;at he harme noghte with stynke &thorn;at of


<PB N="313">

hym commes, &amp; es grauene depe vndir &thorn;e erthe to be wormes mete. / &amp; ffor-thi
it es now in &thorn;is tyme to wyrke, for in &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at es to come es na tyme to
swynke, bot to resceyue mede for are-done dede.  &amp; &thorn;is affermes &thorn;e angell with
athe &thorn;er he &thorn;us sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iurauit enim angelus quod non erit tempus amplius,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to saye: &laquo;&thorn;e angell sware by athe &thorn;at after manes dede na
tyme sall he hafe oghte for to wyne, bot &thorn;at that he hase by-fore wonne&raquo;.  Wete
he wele, ffor-thi it es to do als &thorn;e appostill sayse &amp; redis: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dum tempus habemus, operemur bonum ad omnes,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;Whills we hafe tyme do we gud till
all&raquo;.  And als &thorn;e appostill o&thorn;er mene redis, hym-selfe did in dede, for as &thorn;ir
clerkes by saynt Paule sayse, euer he was styrrande in sum gude werkes:
for fra &thorn;e fyrste houre of &thorn;e daye vn-to &thorn;e fyfte he trauelde with his hende to
wyne his fode, &amp; fra &thorn;e fyfte houre vn-to &thorn;e tende houre to &thorn;e folke he
prechede, and fro none till euene he seruede to &thorn;e pure [&] pilgrymes with slyke
[gude] als he hade, also by nyghte was he prayande: &amp; thus spendid he his tyme.
</P>
<P>In thre maners tynes mane his tyme, &thorn;at es: in ydilchipe; or in werke &thorn;at na
gude commes offe; or in gud werkes bot noghte ordayned als &thorn;ay sold be.  Firste
it es to fordo ydilchipe, for it mekill harmes; &amp; this witnesse Salamone &thorn;e wytty
&thorn;at thus sayse:<FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> Multam maliciam docuit ociositas,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to saye &laquo;&thorn;at mekill malece &amp; syne leris ydilnes&raquo;.  &amp; for-thi sayse haly wryte &thorn;erby: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui sectatur ocium stultissimus est,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekyll for to say: &laquo;he &thorn;at spendis his
tyme; in ydilchipe, ouer-mekill he es a fole&raquo;: for he for-beres noghte &thorn;e thyng
&thorn;at duse hym harme; &amp; &yogh;it mare fole es he for he wynnes hym na mede in &thorn;e
tyme; and al&thorn;er-maste fole he es for he wynnes hym payne.  &amp; ffor-&thorn;i god blames
&thorn;e ydill &thorn;are he to &thorn;ame sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quid hic statis tota die ociosi?</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;whi stand &yogh;e here al &thorn;e day ydill &amp; will noghte wyrke?&raquo; Ydilchipe wastes gudes &thorn;at are warely won&macr;ne, &amp; for-thi saynte Iohn&macr; sayse &thorn;at na thyng es werse &thorn;an ydilnes, &amp; noghte anely for he wynnes noghte, bot for he wastes &thorn;at are won&macr;ne. Ydillnes tilles &thorn;e fende till house, &amp; for-thi sayse saynt Iohn&macr;: &laquo;euer be wyrkande sum gud werke &thorn;at &thorn;e fende fynde the noghte ydill&raquo;; ffor als thurghe gude werke &thorn;e fende es lettid to enter in to manes herte, swa ydillnes makes waye to manes herte &amp; drawes &thorn;e fende in.  Idillnes lettis mane to lyfe mannes lyfe ordanely als to mane falles, als &thorn;e wyse Senec sayse: &laquo;he lyffes noghte till hym-selfe &thorn;at lyffes till hys wambe &amp; to ese of his foulle flesche in all &thorn;at he may&raquo;; for he lyffes noghte till his prophett ne to nane o&thorn;er, &amp; for-&thorn;i he lyffes noghte, ffor Iob sayse:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Homo enim ad laborem natus est,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es at saye: &laquo;Mane es borne to trauelle&raquo;: and
for-&thorn;i mane &thorn;at trauells noghte he lyffes noghte as mane.  To trauelle was mane
boundene efter he had synned, thurgh goddes bynddynge &thorn;at &thorn;us to hym sayde:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In sudore wltus tui vesceris pane tuo, donec reuertaris in terram de qua assumptus
es, quia terra es &amp; in terram ibis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to saye: &laquo;In swete of thi face &thorn;ou sall ete thi brede&raquo;, &thorn;at es, &thorn;ou sall trauelle stalworthely &amp; noghte fayntly, for he byddis &thorn;e trauelle &laquo;with swete of thi face&raquo; &mdash; he &thorn;at trauells &thorn;at swettes
hertly, he &thorn;at swynkkes; &amp; so &thorn;ou sold, &laquo;ay till &thorn;ou torne in to &thorn;e erthe, he
sayse, &thorn;ou erte of[fe] tane&raquo;, &thorn;at es, all thi lyfe &thorn;ou trauelle, &thorn;at &thorn;ou lose no
tyme. / This vice of ydilchipe mekill gude it lettis and [mase] mane vnworthi any


<PB N="314">

gud to do, and smyttis hym als it were with a parlesy &thorn;at all his lymes dryes,
&thorn;at he may na gud do als he sulde; for-thi spekes &thorn;e psalme-wrytter &thorn;are he
&thorn;us sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Manus habent et non palpabunt, pedes habent et non ambulabunt, os
habent et non loquentur, oculos habent et non videbunt, aures habent et non audient,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say: &laquo;Thay hafe handes, he sayse, bot &thorn;ay wyrke noghte,
ffeete &thorn;ay hafe bot &thorn;ay ga noghte, Mouthes &thorn;ay hafe bot &thorn;ay speke noghte, Eres
&thorn;ay hafe bot &thorn;ay here noghte&raquo;&mdash;ffor &thorn;aire lymmes are so boundene in syne &thorn;at
to all thynge &thorn;at euyll es are &thorn;ay lyghte, bot to do &thorn;e gud &thorn;ay are als dede.
&YOGH;itt ydilnes es a vyce &thorn;at wyrkes mekill euyll, for it nuresche to all &thorn;at euyll es,
Saynt Clement sayse, for it makes mane rekles &amp; for-getill for to do &thorn;at he [es]
haldene to do if he sauede sall be.  For whene &thorn;e fend fyndes a mane ydill,
&thorn;ane he drawes hym nere hyme to draw hym to his werkes: ffirste he puttis hym
fowle thoghttes in &thorn;e herte and taries hyme with foulle &yogh;ernynges of fleschely
fylthe or of o&thorn;er folyes &thorn;at brynges mane to syne; efter he prikkes hym to do
thiese &yogh;ernynges in dede; &amp; &thorn;us he makes hym to lose hym-selfe in syne, hys
tyme also, and lettis [hym] gud dedis to do &thorn;at myghte helpe hyme till heuene.  And
sa he dose agaynes &thorn;e appostell rede &thorn;at &thorn;us till all mene sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nolite dare locum diabulo, </FOREIGN>&thorn;at es to say: &laquo;Gyffe na stede to &thorn;e fende&raquo;.  Bot in &thorn;at mane &thorn;at
trauels in gud werkes, the fende may fynd na stede in hyme for to reste, ffor
what vessale sa it be &thorn;at es euyne full, if mene &yogh;ett mare &thorn;are-in, it castes it
agayne.  &amp; &thorn;at mane mase waye to &thorn;e fende &amp; tillis hym to reste with hyme, &amp; fulfill[is] in dede whate sa he hym byddes. / &amp; thus he mase hym-selfe vnworthi to
all o&thorn;er stedis in to dwelle bot anely to helle; ffor als helle es &thorn;e duellyng-stede
of &thorn;e fowle fende, righte sa it es howsynge to &thorn;e ydill mane &thorn;at here serues hym
in syne.  And at this thus be, by skyll it may be prouede.  Sothe it es &thorn;e ydill
mane may noghte duelle in heuene, ffor heuene es anely full mede to &thorn;ame &thorn;at
in &thorn;is lyfe spendis &thorn;aire tyme in &thorn;ase werkes &thorn;at &thorn;ay hope be Criste to paye.
In purgatorie nane slyke may duelle, [for] &thorn;are &thorn;e gude anely are purgede in &thorn;at
clensand fyre till &thorn;ay be als clene of syne als whene &thorn;ay crystenyd ware; &amp; here-to witnes &thorn;e psalme-wrytter &thorn;er he &thorn;us sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In labore hominum non sunt, &amp; cum hominibus non flagellabunttur,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us for to say: &laquo;The ydill trauels noghte
with mene, ffor-thi &thorn;ay sall noghte in purgatorye be pyned with thase mene &thorn;at
are in &thorn;e waye to heuene&raquo;.  Bot &thorn;ay sall be for euer pynede in helle with &thorn;e
fende, for &thorn;ay als his thralles serued hym in syne. / Grete schame it es cristyne
mane nowe ydill to be in &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at nowe es, &thorn;at callede es &thorn;e tyme of grace,
in &thorn;e whylke tyme Ensampill es schewed vs of gud werkes, &amp; we are hyrede for
to wyrke, &amp; if we wyrke als we awe grete mede vs habydes.  Firste, ensample
god sett hym-selfe &thorn;at we suld lufe to wyrke, als &thorn;e apostille by hyme sayse:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Exinaniuit semetipsum forman serui accipiens, in similitudinem hominum factus
&amp; habitu inventus vt homo; humiliauit semetipsum factus obediens vsque ad mortem,
mortem autem crucis: propter quod &amp; deus exaltauit illum &amp; donauit illi nomen
quod est super omne nomen, vt in nomine Ihesu omne genu flectatur, celestium,
terrestrium et infernorum, et omnis lingua confiteatur quia dominus Ihesus in gloria
est dei patris,</FOREIGN> this es &thorn;us mekill for to saye: &laquo;[He], this es goddes sone of heuene,
with trauelle hase wastede hym-selfe, he tuke &thorn;e body of thralles, made to lyknes


<PB N="315">

of mane, in clethyng fondene as mane; he mekid hym-selfe [&] boxome by-come to
&thorn;e dede, &thorn;are to dy on &thorn;e croyse: for-thi god hase heghede hyme &amp; gyffene hym
name &thorn;at es abowne al &thorn;at name beres, so &thorn;at in &thorn;e name of Ihesu all spyrites
sall knele of helle, of heuene &amp; erthe, &amp; all sall witnesse bere &thorn;at oure lorde
Ihesu Cryste dwelles with his fadir in Ioye&raquo;.  Ouer-prowde &thorn;ane es &thorn;e seruande
&amp; ouer-delycate &thorn;at in a batelle will ryste, and seese his lorde by-fore his eghne
of his enymyse be assayllede &amp; of &thorn;ame euyll wondyde. / The to&thorn;er skyll es why
we sulde wyrke now in &thorn;is tyme of grace: for we are goddes boghte thralles,
with &thorn;e pryce of his dere-worthy blode, noghte to sytt ydill, bot for to wyrke
in his vyne-&yogh;arde, and &yogh;itt he hyghttes vs mede if we do with gud wyll &thorn;at we
thurgh dett awe for to do. / The third skyll es: &thorn;at mare mede he hyghtes vs if
we do his will, &thorn;a[n] he highte to his preue frendis be-fore &thorn;e tyme of grace; to
&thorn;ame, if &thorn;ay wele dyde, he hyghte erthely gudes: to vs he highte to wonne
with hyme for euer in his blysse. / The ferthe es, if he to any of his preue frendes
highte &thorn;e blysse of heuene, lange tyme after it was or &thorn;ay myghte wyne &thorn;erto,
and &yogh;itt by-houed &thorn;ame wende by helle and &thorn;are make lang habyddynge, some
a thowsand wynter, sum twa thowsand and some thre thowsand wynters, or &thorn;ay
to heuene myghte come: bot now in a littill whyle mene may wyne heuene at
will, als, if any dye sone aftir he es crystennede, owther if he hafe done full
penance for his mysdedis &thorn;at may for-do payne of purgatorie &thorn;at he for &thorn;ame
sulde thole, or martyrs &thorn;at for goddes lufe scheddes &thorn;aire blode.  The blys es
now redy to mane if he it serue, and for-thi, als &thorn;e gospelle tellis of saynt Luke,
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Misit dominus seruum suum hora cene dicere invitatis vt venirent, quia iam parata
sunt omnia,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say: &laquo;God hase sent his seruant in &thorn;e
soper-tyme to say &thorn;ame &thorn;at bodene warre &thorn;at &thorn;ay sulde come &amp; na duellyng make, for alle es redy &thorn;at graythed es to the feste&raquo;.  This tyme of soper es tyme of
grace &thorn;at now es, in whylke all es redy with-owttene lettynge to brynge mane
with to blysse; &thorn;are es noghte ells to do bot wasche mene handes &amp; sett &thorn;ame
to the mete, &thorn;at es, &thorn;at &thorn;ay perfytely be clensyde of all &thorn;e synns &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe
donne sene &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ay were borne agaynes goddes will. // What losyng of
tyme es it to trauelle abowte &thorn;ase thynges &thorn;at na profet commes of!  Noghte
anely it es euylle for to waste &thorn;e tyme in ydillnes &amp; in vayne: bot il it es &amp; losyng of tyme to trauelle abowte &thorn;ase thynges &thorn;at na profete commes of, for
forto trauelle abowte swylke thynges [es] wastynge of lyfe.  His lyfe es lange &thorn;at
trauells in &thorn;at he may for hyme-selfe, &thorn;at es to &thorn;e wyrchipe of god &amp; his
saule-hele.  Thow sall noghte deme the mane &thorn;at he hase lang lyffede &thorn;of &thorn;ou se hym
white-harede &amp; ga stowpande with a staffe: for &thorn;at of mannes lyfe es noghte to
telle by &thorn;at es wasted in ydilnes &amp; in dedly syne.  For-thi ansuerde Baralame to
Iosaphate his disciple &thorn;at to hym sayde, &laquo;Mayster, how alde arte &thorn;ou?  I pray the,
&yogh;if it be thi will, &thorn;ou telle me &thorn;e sothe&raquo;; and he ansuerde &amp; sayd: &laquo;I am of fourty &yogh;eres &amp; fyve&raquo;.  &laquo;Maister, quod Iosaphate, me thynke &thorn;at &thorn;ou solde be of sexty &yogh;ere &amp; mare&raquo;.  And than ansuerde Baralame: &laquo;If &thorn;ou aske me of all &thorn;ase &yogh;eres &thorn;at I haffe lyffede sene I was borne, &thorn;ane haf I lyffed als many als &thorn;ou laste sayd.  Bot &thorn;ase &yogh;eres I spendid in ydillnes &amp; in syne or I tuke to &thorn;e lyf &thorn;at I now halde, &thorn;ase &yogh;eris I halde &yogh;eris of dede.  Bot all &thorn;ase &yogh;eris I telle &yogh;eris


<PB N="316">

of my lyfe &amp; na ma, &thorn;at I hafe serued Cryste my lorde in thurgh his dere-worthy
grace; for &yogh;eris of dede with &yogh;eris of lyfe are noghte for to telle&raquo;.  Wha so walde vmbythynke hyme whate tyme stelis fra hyme in lang etyng &amp; drynkynge in
owtrage, whate [in] vnmayte werkes, ydilchipe, ydill thoghtes and foule, vnmayte
wordes &amp; o&thorn;er vanytes &thorn;at mane delyttes hyme Ine, he suld sothely vndirstande
&amp; fynd &thorn;at &thorn;ofe he alde be of &yogh;eris, &thorn;at littill he hase lyffed, &amp; &thorn;at es for to say, one &thorn;e manere he sulde hafe lyffede and he hym wele vmbythynke; for he
lyffed noghte to his profet, ne wane hym no mede als he sold hafe done, bot
peranter wane hym payne, for lossyng of his tyme.  Wondir thyng it ware &thorn;at
the mane &thorn;at gyffes hyme to &thorn;e besynes of &thorn;is werlde mare &thorn;ane nedis, had na
[lettyng in] prayere, in reste of herte, in sothefastnes of worde, in perfeccione of
gud werkes, in lufe to god &amp; till all crystene mene.  I trow &thorn;at wha sa with a
clene hert will charge thire many lettynges, he may fynd &thorn;at ofte tyme will lett
hyme god to serue to paye.  And for-thi haly mene by-fore &thorn;is tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ire
lettynges knewe, &thorn;ay flede &thorn;e werlde with all his vanytes righte als it were
cursede, for &thorn;ame thoghte &thorn;ay myghte na ryghtwyse lyfe lede &thorn;erin; and
for-thi went &thorn;ay vntill wyldirnes, for ther they trowed &thorn;at &thorn;ay myghte better serue
&thorn;aire lorde to paye.  For Senec &thorn;e wyse sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Auarior redeo &amp; crudelior [&] inhumanior, quia inter homines fui:</FOREIGN> &laquo;Mare auerus I am, sayse Senec, &amp; mare couetus, &amp; mare kene &amp; lesse mane I ame, &thorn;at haue duelled amanges mene&raquo;.
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Off thre maners ocupacions.</HEAD>

<P>Thre maners of Ocupaciouns es owtwith, als in sere Ianglyng &amp; mekill, in
vtwith raykyng, &amp; in mekill traualynge abowte werldly thynges.  Firste may many
trauelle &thorn;ame-selfe in mekill Iangelynge, &amp; agaynes this Salomone sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui dimittit aquam, caput est Iurgii,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;he &thorn;at lattes owte &thorn;e water, he
es heued of the stryuyng&raquo;.  &laquo;Late &thorn;e water owt&raquo;, es late &thorn;e tunge flete owt in mekill Iangillynge, [&] als many vnmayte wordes &amp; ydill &thorn;at mane spekes, als so
many sythes he latis &thorn;e water owte.  [Bot] to knawyng [of] god ne of hym-selfe may
nane wyne &thorn;at latis his herte owte flete with mekill vnmayte speche: for he mase
waye to the fende, his faa, in hym-selfe; &amp; for-thi slyke lykyns Salamone to &thorn;e
cete &thorn;at es with-owttene walle, &thorn;are he &thorn;us sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sicut vrbs sine murorum ambitu, Ita vir qui non potest cohibere spiritum suum in loquendo,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say: &laquo;Wha sa noghte refrenes his tonge fra mekill speche, he es als a cete with-owttene walles, &thorn;are hostes may enter ouer-alle&raquo;.  The fend of helle with his hoste gase thurgh &thorn;at mouthe &thorn;at euer es opyne with euyll speche.  In <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vitis patrum</FOREIGN> it es tolde of a haly mane &thorn;at saide whene mene praysede a felawchipe of bre&thorn;er &thorn;at he had herde of mekill speche: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Boni vtique sunt, set habitacio eorum non habet Ianuam; quicunque wlt intrat &amp; asinum soluit,</FOREIGN> &laquo;Gude, quod he, &thorn;ay ere, bot &thorn;aire wonnyng hase no &yogh;ate; wha sa will may ga in and lede furthe the asse&raquo;, &thorn;at es, &thorn;aire vnwitty saules.  For-thi sayse sayne Iames: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Si quis putat se religiosum esse non refrenans linguam suam, sed seducens cor suum, huius vana est religio,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;If any wenys &thorn;at he es religious and brydills noghte
his tunge, his religio[n] es vayne, he be-gyles his herte&raquo;.  He sayse swythe wele
&laquo;he brydils noghte his mouthe&raquo;.  A brydill es noghte anely in the horse mouthe,


<PB N="317">

for sum es abowte &thorn;e eghne, &amp; sum abowte &thorn;e eres, for all thre es mekill nede
&thorn;at &thorn;ay brydild be.  In the mouthe lygges the heuy Iryne one &thorn;e lyghte tunge,
for &thorn;at es maste to halde.  Ofte we thynke when we by-gyne to speke, for to
spek lyttill &amp; sett wele oure wordes: bot &thorn;e tung es sleper, for it wades in
wate[r], &amp; glyddes lyghtly furthe fra faa wordes to many, fra gud to sume ille,
fra sothe to lese: and &thorn;ane, als Salomone sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In multiloqueo non deest peccatum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es thus for to say: &laquo;Mekill speche, by-gyne it neuer sa wele, may noghte
be with-owttene syne&raquo;; for fra sothe it strikes in to false, owt of gud in to euyll,
fra mesure to ouer-mekill, and as of a drope &amp; a drope, waxes a mekill flode &thorn;at
drownnes the saule, for with &thorn;e fletand worde fletis &thorn;e hert owt, &thorn;at lang
&thorn;erafter may it noghte gedir to-gedire.  &amp; &thorn;erfore sayse Gregor &thorn;us: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et os nostrum tanto est deo longinquum quanto mundo proximum; tanto [minus] exauditur in prece quanto magis inquinatur [stulta] locucione</FOREIGN>&mdash;thir are saynt Gregor wordis in his Dyalogs, &thorn;at ere &thorn;us for to say: &laquo;Als nere als oure mouthe es to &thorn;e werlde speche, als ferre es it fra god whene we to hym speke &amp; prayes hym of oghte; ffor-thi es whene we calle on hyme &amp; he with-drawes hym agayne fra oure steuene, for he will noghte it here: ffor we stynke to hym als of ydill speche and of ydill Iangelyng &thorn;at vs hase fyled&raquo;.  For-thi wha so will &thorn;at goddes ere be nere his mouthe when he to hym prayes, drawe his herte fra &thorn;e werlde, elles may he
lange cry or god hym here, als he thurgh &thorn;e prophet Ysaye sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cum extenderitis manus vestras auertam oculos meos a vobis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;When &yogh;e make many-falde prayere to me &yogh;e &thorn;at playes with the werlde, I ne here &yogh;ow noghte &thorn;at while, I will turne me away when &yogh;e &yogh;our handes lyftes to me&raquo;.  For sa mekill lettyng of &thorn;e gud philosophire sayse es in mekill spekyng, &thorn;at &thorn;ay bynd &thorn;aire dyscypylls with sylence &thorn;aire firste fyve &yogh;ere, als saynt Ambrose sayse.  And wretyne it es by a haly habot &thorn;at hyghte Agathone, &thorn;at thre &yogh;ere he bare a stane in his mouthe, to lere hym to halde hym stylle. / The to&thorn;er es of &thorn;ase &thorn;at kane hafe na ryste bot euer [er] raykand abowte fra stede to stede, &amp; for nane o&thorn;er enchesone bot for to fede &thorn;aire wyttis with vanytes &amp; lustes slyke als &thorn;e flesche &yogh;ernes.  &laquo;Flee &thorn;e werlde and his &yogh;ernynges, &amp; halde [&thorn;e] in ryste, and brydelle the tonge &thorn;at he noghte owte flete no&thorn;er in Iangelyng ne in ydill speche&raquo;, thire thre &thorn;e haly angelle lerede &thorn;e abbot Arsenius &thorn;at he &thorn;am solde &yogh;eme; ffor whare thir thre er haldene &thorn;at &thorn;e angelle leris, thare es way to god [&] with-drawyng fra ill.  It telles of an abbot &thorn;at fully twenty &yogh;ere satt in his selle, &thorn;at neuer lyftede vp his heued to see &thorn;e selle-rofe. / The third es of tha &thorn;at wastes &thorn;aire
tyme with trauelle in couatyse to gedir &thorn;ame werldly thynges ma &thorn;ane &thorn;am nedis;
&amp; of slyke spekes Salamon &thorn;e wyse &amp; telles what betis to &thorn;am for all &thorn;aire
grete swynke, here what for-&thorn;i: &thorn;us by &thorn;ame he sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vana est spes eorum et labor sine fructu:</FOREIGN> &laquo;ffalse es &thorn;air hope, he sayse, &amp; &thorn;air trauell with-owtene mede&raquo;;
&amp; &yogh;it he sayse be swylke mene: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nichil aufert secum de vniuerso labore suo,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say: &laquo;Na thynge with hym he beris when he hythene weyndis, of all &thorn;at he hase wonne with care &amp; swynke&raquo;.  This es ilk a day sene by &thorn;ase &thorn;at are dede, &thorn;at noghte with &thorn;am beris to &thorn;aire lang hame, of all &thorn;e gudes &thorn;ay hade were &thorn;ay neuer sa ryche, bot a lytill cloute of clathe to hille &thorn;aire
body with&mdash;na mare the werlde vouches-saufe one &thorn;ame, &thorn;at &thorn;ay so mekill luf-


<PB N="318">

fede.  Here-of sulde &thorn;e Riche thynke &thorn;at playes &thorn;ame with &thorn;e werlde, and thir
couatouse mene &thorn;at &thorn;e pure pylles, &thorn;at rakes hally to-gedir &thorn;at &thorn;ay may gete,
rekkes he neuer of whayme, be he pure or be he ryche he takes na kepe, bot
ane &thorn;at he hafe: and alle es bot fantom &amp; dreme &thorn;at &thorn;ay with dele.  Righte
by a ryche mane it es &thorn;at here his lykyng hase of golde &amp; of syluer &amp; of o&thorn;er
fleschely lykynge whare-with als an vnworthi wreche &thorn;e werld hym dyssayues,
als by a pure mane &thorn;at hungres swythe sare &amp; swa sare thrystes &thorn;at almaste he
dyes.  Efter hungere lange hase hyme pyned he falles one slepe, and he dremys
&thorn;at he es bodyne till a feste, &amp; heghe sett one &thorn;e desee, &amp; all deyntes &thorn;at his
herte may thynke sett by-fore hyme, wyne &amp; pyment in faire cowppes; he etis
&amp; drynkes at his will &amp; makes hym righte glade, &amp; all &thorn;at abowte hym standis
are fayne for to do his wylle.  Efter &thorn;at he hase etyne &thorn;at hym gud thynke,
&thorn;e clathe es drawene &amp; he with mekill noblaye to chambir es gane, and &thorn;are,
hym thynkes, he etis spyce &amp; drynkes &thorn;e wyne, &amp; sythene to bede he es broghte
als it ware a prynce, &amp; happed with ryche robes appone hyme ynewe, wele
furrede with vayre &amp; with gryse.  Bot whene this wreche wakyns, he felis his legges
all calde; he thynkes on &thorn;at noblaye hyme thoghte he was in, &amp; of all &thorn;at riche
noblaye hym thoghte &thorn;at was abowte his bed, he grapes abowte hyme if he
myghte oghte fynde of &thorn;ase riche clathes he wende ware one hyme&mdash;bot &thorn;an
feles he noghte elles bot taters &amp; ragges; &amp; mare hym hungers &amp; thrystes &thorn;an
he dyd by-fore.  &THORN;ane knawes he sothely it was bot a dreme; &thorn;at false fantome
made hym to trowe &thorn;at it was [a] fest.  &THORN;usegate false reches of &thorn;e werlde taries
&thorn;e Riche, &thorn;at mase &thorn;ame to wene &thorn;at all es sothe &thorn;at fantome &thorn;ame leris.  So
witles riches &thorn;ame makes &thorn;at &thorn;ay for-gete &thorn;am-selfe, and hethyng makis at o&thorn;er
&amp; lyghtly by &thorn;am settis &thorn;at sothely &thorn;ase reches wane.  &THORN;ay make feste of &thorn;ase
gudis &thorn;ay pylled fra &thorn;e pure, and ilke man for drede es fayne to do &thorn;aire will.
Bot whene dede &thorn;ame sall wakyne of &thorn;at balefull dreme, &thorn;ane fynd &thorn;ay bot
fantome all &thorn;at &thorn;ay wende had bene sothe. // The thirde maner of mene thare are
&thorn;at lykyng hase to do &thorn;e gude, bot for &thorn;ay do it noghte in &thorn;e maner &thorn;ay suld
do, &thorn;ay putt &thorn;e mede of &thorn;aire gud dede in a reuene sekke, for &thorn;ay losse &thorn;aire
mede &thorn;at &thorn;ay sulde wyne if &thorn;ay wroghte &thorn;ase gud dedis in gud entent; for &thorn;are
whare gud entent fayles in any gude dede, than mede &thorn;at to &thorn;e gude werke
sulde falle, fayles alswa.  And &thorn;at may fayle on foure maners.  The firste, for &thorn;e
wykkednes of &thorn;e wyrkande; als it telles in &thorn;e firste buke of &thorn;e lawe that Cayme,
Adam sone, offerde to godd of &thorn;e fruyte &thorn;at hym newede: to &thorn;is offerand of
Cayme god walde noghte luke, bot to &thorn;e offerand of Abelle, his brothir.  Of &thorn;ir
wordes saynte Gregor spekis &amp; sayse: &laquo;by [&thorn;e] herttis will of hym &thorn;at &thorn;e offerand mase es the gyfte of god resceyued or &thorn;er-with-all repreued: for by Abelle wretyne it es &thorn;at god firste luked to Abelle &amp; sythene to his gyfte, for to vndirstande &thorn;at noghte for &thorn;e offerande of Abelle god was payed, bot of &thorn;e offeryng for Abelle,
&thorn;at in all his werke was trew &amp; gud, &amp; after &thorn;at god luked.  Bot to Cayme &amp; his offerande god wold noghte luke, &thorn;at es for-thi &thorn;at he [&thorn;at] &thorn;e offerande made
gretly my[s]payed god&raquo;.  Whi oure offerand myspayes god or what so we do &thorn;at
gud es in kynde, &thorn;e haly prophete schewes by skyll, here &amp; lere who so will;
for &thorn;us he sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cum multiplicaueritis oraciones non exaudiam, quia manus vestre


<PB N="319">

plene sanguine sunt,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us for to say: &laquo;When &yogh;e many prayers to me makes
I will &thorn;ame noghte here, ffor &yogh;oure handes are full of blode&raquo;, that by-takyns
syne. / &yogh;itt whi trauelle falles with-owttene mede, &thorn;at es v[an]yte &thorn;at stirres many
gud to do, as it es whene mane dose any gud &thorn;at gud [es] in his kynde, for we
walde be praysede of men for oure gude.  For-&thorn;i sayse god till all mene &thorn;at ere
in slyke Entent to be loued of mene: &laquo;If &yogh;e so do, for sothe I say &yogh;e tyne &yogh;oure
mede&raquo;.  For vayne glorie es &thorn;at thynge &thorn;at of gud makes euyll; als it es by
almos-dede &thorn;at in his kynde es gude, bot do it for manes praysynge &amp; it wynnes
bot syne. / The thirde &thorn;at for gud werke refes mane his mede, than es roysyng
of &thorn;ame &thorn;at dose &thorn;e gud dede; &amp; for-thi god in &thorn;e gosepelle by &thorn;e phara&yogh;ene
sayse &thorn;at talde his gud dedis by-fore &thorn;e folke in goddes temple thare he in
prayede, for-&thorn;i god by hym sayde till all &thorn;at by-fore hym stode: &laquo;Sothely, &thorn;is
man hase loste his mede, trayste he none o&thorn;er, for all his gud dede&raquo;.  Of this
phara&yogh;ene sayse saynt Gregore: &laquo;Loo so many gud dedis are loste thurgh a syne.
This mane, als hym-selfe sayd, fasted twa dayes in a weke, &amp; payed wele his
tendis of all &thorn;at hym newede, &amp; ouer-passed many o&thorn;er with his gud dedis: bot
for he roysed hyme of his dedis, he losed all &thorn;at he dide&raquo;.  Nedefull forthi it es
to mane &thorn;at he do &thorn;e gud he may, and &thorn;at he warely vmbyluke hym &thorn;at he pryde
hym noghte &thorn;are-of in thoghte ne in worde.  &amp; for-thi by &thorn;is phara&yogh;ene saynt
Gregore sayse: &laquo;Als reproued of god he went to his house, for &thorn;e merit of his
gud dede he had gyfuene to hym-seluene &amp; mad hym with his worde bettir &thorn;ane
he was&raquo;.  For one foure maners mene loses mede of &thorn;air gud dede.  The first es
when mane wenys, &thorn;e gude he hase, &thorn;at he it haues of hym-selfe.  The to&thorn;er
whene he trowes &thorn;at god gyffes &thorn;ase gudes for he hase &thorn;ame serued.  The thirde
es whene he ruses hyme of his gud dedis.  The ferthe whene he o&thorn;er dispyses of
&thorn;aire gud dede for he wolde be haldene better &thorn;ane any o&thorn;er. / &YOGH;it dedis &thorn;at gud
are fayles of &thorn;aire mede whene mene dose [&thorn;am] in &thorn;at Entent to be haldene better
&thorn;ane any o&thorn;er, or for to lesse gud dede of othire, &amp; for to for-do it with all
&thorn;at he may.  And be slyke gud-doers saynt Gregor spekes &amp; tellys by a haly
bechope &thorn;at hyghte Fortunate, &thorn;at thurghe grace &thorn;at he had of god he chased
owte fendis of &thorn;ame &thorn;at &thorn;ay had duellede with.  And sa by-felle on a tym&macr;e
&thorn;at &thorn;is Fortunate chased the fende owte of a mane in an Euene-tyde: &thorn;e fende
sone whene he was chased owte he put hym in lyknes of a pilgrymme &amp; went
thurgh &thorn;e cete &thorn;ar the bechope was, wepand and &yogh;elland als a pure wreche, als
he &thorn;at was will of herbery &thorn;at nyghte, and &thorn;us by-gane he to crye &thorn;at all &thorn;e
cete myghte here: &laquo;Loo whate &yogh;oure bechope hase done to me, &thorn;at &yogh;e halde so
gude &amp; so haly!  &THORN;are I had tane my herberye &amp; wend to [haf] bene in reste, the
bechope come to &thorn;e house &amp; putt me owte with force: And now als a pure
wreche of my herberye I am will.  Ouer-all herbery I seke &amp; nane will one me
rewe&raquo;.  A mane of &thorn;at cete &thorn;at this herde &amp; herd hym &thorn;us speke, tuk hym in
to his house &amp; hym by &thorn;e fyre sett &amp; esede hym one this wyese.  Whene &thorn;e
mane had spokene with &thorn;e pilgryme as he wende he had bene, and he had spyrred
hym of ferre ty&yogh;nges as mene dose pilgrymes, &thorn;e fend styrte to &thorn;e childe in &thorn;e
credill and wrathe &thorn;e neke in-twa &amp; keste it in &thorn;e fyre, and vanyste awaye
sodanly: &amp; thus at his partynge he qwytt &thorn;e mane his gud dede.  Off [&thorn;is] spekes


<PB N="320">

saynt Gregor &amp; sayse: &laquo;Many semys gud dedis &thorn;at are noghte gud, for &thorn;ay are
noghte done with a gud will.  For &thorn;is mane &thorn;at &thorn;e pilgryme herberde &thorn;at was
&thorn;e fende, it was for na pete &thorn;at he of hym hade, bot anely for of his bechope
he spake &thorn;e ill; he called hym to house &thorn;at he suld be haldene better &amp; mare
of pete &thorn;ane his bechope was, als he &thorn;at herberde &thorn;e pure &thorn;at &thorn;e bechope
with strenghe putt owte of his house&raquo;.  Thus it es by mony &thorn;at dose &thorn;e gude
for to lessene &thorn;e gud dedis of o&thorn;er mene &amp; to for-do &thorn;ame with-all. / &YOGH;it gud
dedis are forowttene mede als willyng to wyne to grete honoures or any werldes
gude, for to hafe mede of mane; &thorn;ofe to mans dome it seme &thorn;at many duse &thorn;e
gud: &thorn;ay do it anely for god, noghte-for-&thorn;i many of thir &thorn;at are abouene neuennede
reues &thorn;ame &thorn;aire mede.  &YOGH;it thurgh syne fylande gude dede es loste; &amp; here-to
accordes &thorn;at haly wryte sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui in vno peccauit multa bona perdidit,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us for to say: &laquo;he &thorn;at a thyng synnes, many gud dedis he tynes&raquo;, &thorn;at es bot he amend hym with schryfte &amp; penance do &thorn;erfore.
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<P>The secu[n]de party &thorn;at teches mane to do &thorn;e gude: he es haldene to do it in
stede &amp; in tyme als to ilke gud dedis falles with a fredome of spirite, &amp; noghte
benedit &thorn;er-to, ne with angir, ne with a dede herte.  For god takes gretly to thanke
&thorn;at a mane dose with a glade herte, for-thi &thorn;e wyse mane sayse by god: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hillarem datorem diligit deus,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us for to say: &laquo;god lufes &thorn;ase &thorn;at hym gyffes oghte
with a glade herte&raquo;; and namly &thorn;ase werkes &thorn;at to goddes honour &amp; his louynge
falles &amp; to lykyng of manes saule, &amp; gastely werkis als prayers and haly thoghttes,
and clere mynde of god &amp; of his gude dedis.  Thir &amp; o&thorn;er slyke to &thorn;ame lyttill
reste will hafe if &thorn;ay wele sall bee, for als &thorn;e haly mane sayse, prayers with-owtene
deuocione es als claterynge of pyes.  For prayere es a sacrafyce &thorn;at mekill payes
gode if it [be] made one &thorn;e maner &thorn;at it awe to be; for-thi god askes it of vs als
dette &thorn;at we it to hym paye, &thorn;are he vs sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacrificium laudis honorificabit me,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es to say: &laquo;with sacrafyce of prayere &thorn;ou sall honoure me&raquo;.  And &thorn;at es gud skylle; for god mad mane for he wolde be loued of hyme, &amp; for-thi haly wryt
sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gentes creauit deus in laudem &amp; gloriam suam,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us to say: &laquo;God made mane to his honour and his wyrchip &amp; his louyng&raquo;.  For-&thorn;i &thorn;e appostill sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oportet semper orare &amp; nunquam deficere,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us for to say: &laquo;for-thi behoues mane euer pray and neuer fayle&raquo;.  He es euer prayand &thorn;at es [ai] gud wyrkande.  Ryghte es it by prayere als by draweyng of ande: ffor euer to &yogh;emyng of oure bodily lyfe vs nedis to drawe oure ande, &thorn;at es to drawe ayere, &amp; sa it es by prayere to &yogh;emyng of saule lyfe.  For-&thorn;i if we noghte drawe of god thurgh prayere, we are to wyte.  For-&thorn;i it es be tymes to drawe mene fra &thorn;e werlde and his besynes, &thorn;at &thorn;ay &thorn;e better may serue &thorn;aire lorde in prayere &amp; in lykyng of hyme, with &thorn;ase thynges &thorn;at may styre to hyme.  And of all be haldene to
wyrchipe god with prayere, mene of religione are namely haldene &thorn;at by almus
lyffes, and mene of haly kyrke &thorn;at lyfes by tendis: ffor alle &thorn;e werlde trauels to
bryng &thorn;ayme to hande all &thorn;at &thorn;ame nedis, so &thorn;at &thorn;ay may with mare reste better
god serue &amp; with haly dedis saughtelyng make bytwyx god &amp; mane; and also
maydyns &amp; wedows &thorn;at hase avowede chaste&mdash;all thir by-fore othir are maste
bowndene.  It es noghte by heuenly werke as by o&thorn;er werkes &thorn;at in &thorn;e werlde
fall whare-to mane es ofte constreynede to wyrke agayne his will, als an oxe &thorn;at


<PB N="321">

ledis &thorn;e &yogh;okke to drawe, thynke hym neuer sa ille: bot &thorn;is werke &thorn;at I of speke
wil be done with a fredome of spyrit, &amp; with lykyng in god, for &thorn;at softes alle
trauell be it neuer sa grete.  &amp; for-thi he &thorn;at will plese god with prayere, do &amp; thynk to demene hym to seke grace of god, &amp; hafe graythely his memorie als
he es taghte here, &amp; he sall noghte fayle for to comme to grace of gode &amp; aylastand hele; to &thorn;e wylke hele &amp;c.</P>
</DIV4></DIV3>
</DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="300"><HEAD>Prayer</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="MS">Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)<NOTE ID="n3">The beginning is missing, but appears in the Arundel 507 copy of <TITLE>Our Daily Work</TITLE> (p. 142 in Horstman's edition).</NOTE></HEAD><MILESTONE N="237" UNIT="folio">
<P>
...mercy habydes, &amp; sythene for all &thorn;at myster hase, qwykk &amp; dede; and
that souerayne mede w&ymacr;nnes &thorn;e prayand, als saynt Gregore sayse: &laquo;&thorn;e titter sall
he be herde and of his prayere spede, &thorn;at for all prayes&raquo;; &amp; saynt Ambrose thus:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Si pro omnibus roges, pro te rogabunt,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;if &thorn;ou pray for all, all sall praye for the&raquo;; &amp; saynt Ierome sayse: &laquo;Nede byndis mane to pray for hym-selfe, bot charite of brethirhede stirres to pray for all: for mare it stirres gode &amp; payes hym &thorn;at noghte nedfulnes, bot charite, &thorn;at ilkane byndis to o&thorn;er, makis to pray for all&raquo;.  Als god in &thorn;e <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN> vs teches, &thorn;are he byddis vs say, &laquo;oure fadir&raquo;, noghte &laquo;my fadir&raquo;, and teches vs &thorn;us to say in &thorn;e same prayere, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Da nobis hodie,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es &laquo;gyf vs to-day&raquo;; he sayse noghte &laquo;gyf to me&raquo;, bot &laquo;gyf to vs, oure ilke day brede&raquo;, to mak vs to vndirstande &thorn;at we sall pray for all, frendis &amp; fase, and &yogh;erne thurgh prayere &thorn;at all may be helpede.
</P>
<P>The ferth, what mene sall aske in prayere?  Now certis, grace in this lyfe,
&amp; endles Ioye in &thorn;e to&thorn;er.  This techis god vs to pray afterwarde, &thorn;are he sayse
thus: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Primum querite regnum dei &amp; iusticiam eius, &amp; hec omnia adicientur vobis,</FOREIGN>
&laquo;ffirst, he saise, layte&yogh; with prayere &thorn;e blis of heuene, &amp; rightwysnes&raquo;, &thorn;at &thorn;e waye makis &thorn;er-to, &laquo;and &thorn;an [al] at &thorn;e nedis sall &thorn;ou fynd&raquo;; for god es dettour to &thorn;ame &thorn;at rightwyse ere to fynd &thorn;ame at &thorn;am nedis of erthely gudis, for rightwysnes makis of mene goddes childir; for-thi erthely gudes are ordayned to &thorn;e sustenance of goddes childir &thorn;of &thorn;ay noghte after &thorn;ame pray, and &thorn;e ffadir thurgh kynd es haldene to sustene his childir.  Erthly gudes ere noghte for to &yogh;erne ne &yogh;itt for &thorn;ame to pray, for mane wate neuer certaynly if &thorn;ay be for hyme&mdash;for ofte we hafe


<PB N="301">

herde &thorn;at to many &thorn;ay harme; ffor-thi be erthely gudis Salamone sayse &thorn;at knewe
&thorn;e sothe: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vsquequo stulti ea que sibi sunt noxia cupiunt,</FOREIGN> &laquo;Whare-to, he sayse, foles &yogh;ernes &thorn;at &thorn;ame may harme?&raquo;  For-thi, if mane erthely gudis will aske of godd, with grete drede aske he &thorn;ame of godd, and praye hy[s] lorde if he see &thorn;at &thorn;ay may helpe to [hyme], send &thorn;ame if it be his will, &amp; if &thorn;ay will noghte helpe bot harme, with-drawe &thorn;ame at his will; ffor what may helpe, whate may harme, better wate &thorn;e leche &thorn;ane &thorn;e seke.  For-thi it es noghte [ay] beste in prayere to be herde to oure propire will, bot to oure profitt.  Better it es we be [noght] herde
whene we to god praye: for of ane of &thorn;ir twa sall we trayste in prayere to spede:
owthir of &thorn;at we for pray, or of &thorn;at at better es for vs, with-owttyne any drede.
It es noghte ay best in prayere to be herd to oure propir will: ffor agaynes &thorn;e
prayere of Paule god stode, &amp; graunted to &thorn;e fende &thorn;at at he fore prayede, &thorn;at
he myghte enter in till a draue of swyne.  Paule prayed to god &thorn;at he suld
fordo &thorn;ase fandynges &thorn;at hym pynede so sare: bot god herd hyme noghte, bot he
did with better &thorn;ane he prayede fore.  God grauntes vs noghte ay &thorn;at we for
pray, ffor he will gyfe vs better &thorn;ene we after &yogh;erne, as he duse to &yogh;onge childir
&thorn;at in &thorn;e scole leris; of &thorn;ay praye to god &thorn;at &thorn;ay be noghte downgene, god
heris &thorn;ame noghte, for if &thorn;ay were noghte doungene, &thorn;ay wolde noghte lere &amp;c.
</P>
<P>The fyfte es to wyet: what lettes prayere to be herde of god? and sex thynges
&thorn;er are, sothely to telle.  The fyrst es, syne of &thorn;e prayande; this thurgh god
the profett sayse thus: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cum multipl[i]caueritis oraciones non exaudiam, quia manus
vestre sanguine plene sunt,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es thus for [to] say: &laquo;Whene &yogh;e to me prayers makes, I will noghte here &yogh;owe, for &yogh;owre handis are full of blode&raquo;: &thorn;at es, thay
are full of synfull werkes, &thorn;at &thorn;e blode by-takyns.  For-thi Dauid sayse by
hym-selfe: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Iniquitatem si aspexi in corde meo, non exaudiet dominus,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es thus for to say: &laquo;if I se wykkednes in my hert, god will noghte me here&raquo;.  And &thorn;e p[ro]phete sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Peccata nostra absconderunt faciem suam a nobis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;oure synnes hydes godis face fra vs&raquo;.  And at oure synnes lettis oure prayere to be herde, &thorn;e gospelle of sayne Iohne it sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Scimus quoniam peccatores non exaudiet dominus,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es: &laquo;sothely we wate &thorn;at god heris noghte &thorn;e synfull, ne
whylles &thorn;ay lygge in syne&raquo;. //  The secund es, &thorn;e vnworthynes of &thorn;ame for whayme men prayes; ffor whayme god thurgh &thorn;e profett byddis &thorn;at mene sall noghte praye, &thorn;ar he &thorn;us sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nolite orare pro popullo isto neque assumas laudem &amp; oracionem, quia non exaudiam,</FOREIGN> &laquo;Ne pray &yogh;e noghte for &thorn;is folke, &thorn;e prophete sayse, for &yogh;if
&yogh;e do, I sall noghte here&raquo;.  For-thi nane affye &thorn;ame in o&thorn;er prayere bot if &thorn;ay
leue &thorn;aire syne. /  It telles in the lyfe of haly fadyrs of ane &thorn;at boundene was in
syne, &thorn;at com to &thorn;e haly habott saynt Antone &amp; sayd: &laquo;haly ffadir, hafe mercy
on me &amp; pray for mee!&raquo;; to whame &thorn;e haly habott sayde: &laquo;I will hafe no mercy on the bot &thorn;ou helpe thi-selfe &amp; leue thi syne&raquo;.  // The thirde es, foule thoghtes &amp; ydill &thorn;at lettis vs to thynke one oure prayere, &amp; sa merres vs of oure mede; als it falles whene &thorn;e mouthe prayes and &thorn;e hert fletis owt in foule thoghtes &amp; ydylle, &thorn;e body in &thorn;e kyrke, &thorn;e hert with-owttyne.  Of &thorn;ir fals prayande spekis
god thir wordes: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Populus iste labiis me honorat, cor autem eius longe est a me,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es &thorn;us for to say: &laquo;This folke honours me with &thorn;aire lyppes, bot &thorn;aire hertes are ferre fra mee&raquo;.  Es this noght gret vnworthynes of &thorn;ir wrechis, &thorn;at whene


<PB N="302">

we speke wyth prayere till almyghtty godd, &amp; we alls vnwitty herkyns noghte
what we saye?  Sothely, gret dispyte we do till hyme whene we till hym praye &thorn;at
he oure prayere here, and &thorn;e prayere &thorn;at we till hym make, oure-selfe will noghte
it here; we pray hyme &thorn;at he be Entendant to vs, and we to hyme ne to
oure-selfe will be Entendant, bot, &thorn;at werse es, in foulle thoghtes &amp; ydille wastes oure
tyme.  For-thi it es to do alls Abraham dyde.  Whene Abrahame made his
sacrafyse to god, ffoules lyghtted &thorn;er-appone &amp; walde hafe fylide it: bot what dyd
Abraham &thorn;at this sawe? he chasede &thorn;e fowles clene awaye, &thorn;at nane durste it
neghe, to alle &thorn;e tyme were passede &amp; &thorn;e sacrafyce made.  Do we &thorn;ane swa by
thir flyande thoghtes, &thorn;at &thorn;e sacrafyce of owre prayere so fouly fyles &thorn;at &thorn;ay
may noghte paye wele als &thorn;ay solde.  This sacrafyce full qweme es to god whene
it es clene &amp; cummes of a luffande herte; ffor-thi [this] sacrafice askes god of mane
as rent for it es to hym dere, and for-thi thrugh &thorn;e haly prophett he sayse thus:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sacrificium laudis honorificabit me, et illic iter quo ostendam illi salutare dei,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us for to say: &laquo;With sacrifyce of prayere &thorn;ou sall honour me, &amp; &thorn;are-thurgh way &thorn;ou makes to me, &thorn;at of my heuenly lykynge &amp; hele I may sende to the. Thane by-twix vs may be fulfillide &thorn;at one ynglysche es sayd: Gyff &thorn;ou me &amp; I
the, &amp; so may we frendis be.  Send to me prayere &amp; I sall sende to &thorn;e grace,
&amp; what-sa &thorn;ou me duse I for-gett it noght.&raquo;
</P>
<P>The ferthe &thorn;at lettis oure prayere to be herde of god, &thorn;an es hardnes of
herte agaynes the pure; &amp; hereby &thorn;e prophett sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui obturat aures suas ad clamorem pauperis, clamabit ipse &amp; non exaudietur,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say: &laquo;He &thorn;at stoppes his erys agaynes &thorn;e pure &thorn;at one hym cryes besekand hym of helpe, whene he cries to god &amp; of oghte hym bysekes god hym sall noghte here.&raquo; The to&thorn;er es hardnes of &thorn;ame &thorn;at noghte will forgyfe &thorn;ame &thorn;at agaynes &thorn;ame hase mysdone; and to slyke Salomone spekes: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Relynque proximo tuo nocenti te, &amp; tunc depricanti tibi peccata soluuntur,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say: &laquo;forgyf hym &thorn;at agaynes the hase mys-done, &amp; &thorn;ane god will forgyf the thi syne whene &thorn;ou to hym prayes&raquo;.  And in &thorn;e gospelle god sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cum stabitis ad orandum, dimittite si quid habetis adversus aliquem, vt pater vester qui in celis est dimittat vobis peccata vestra,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say: &laquo;whene &thorn;ou standis to pray,
forgyf thase &thorn;at hase mysdone agaynes the; &thorn;at thi fadir of heuene forgyf the
thi synnes&raquo;.
</P>
<P>The fyfte es, lyttill &yogh;ernynge efter &thorn;e [&thorn;ynge] mene prayes fore, and noghte
lastande in prayere; for-thi sayse saynt Austyne: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quod homo ex toto corde confitetur seruat tibi deus, quod [non]wlt cito tibi dare vt discas magna magne desiderare,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill for to say: &laquo;ffor &thorn;ou sall with all thyne hert gret thynges gretly
&yogh;erne, god &yogh;emys thase thynges to thi byhoue; &thorn;at he will [noght] als tyte gyfe
to the or &thorn;ou &thorn;erfore stalworthely swynke with all thi herte, &thorn;at &thorn;ou lere grete
thynges hertly to &yogh;erne&raquo;.  And sayn Greggor sayse thus: &laquo;if we with mouthe pray after &thorn;e blyse of heuene, &amp; noghte &yogh;erne it with hert, criand we halde vs styll&raquo;. And if we be lastande in prayere, god hyghttes vs to spede in his gospelle, &thorn;are he sayse thus: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui perseuerauerit pulsans: surget &amp; dabit sibi quot habet necessarios,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es to say: &laquo;If he lastande calle one god, god sall gyffe hym &thorn;at he after
prayes&raquo;.</P>
<P>
<PB N="303">The sexte &thorn;at lettis oure prayere, es foule speche &amp; ydill &thorn;at we fyle oure
lyppis wyth.  For if &thorn;ou gafe a gret lorde drynke in a slutty coppe &amp; foule: ware
&thorn;e drynke neuer sa gude, hym wolde wlate with-all &amp; byd do it awaye, thriste
hym neuer sa sare.  Sa dose god with the prayere &thorn;at comes of a foule mouthe:
he latys noghte &thorn;er-by &amp; turnes hym &thorn;er-fra; &amp; for-thi saynt Gregor sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Os nostrum a deo tantum minus exauditur in prece, quanto plus polluitur stulta
locucione,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us for to say: &laquo;Als mekill es oure prayere herde lesse of god, in
als mekill as oure mouthe es fyled with foule speche&raquo;.  (vi.) Mene &thorn;at ware by-for
this tyme, with prayere wane of god what-so &thorn;ay fore prayede, for &thorn;ay helde
&thorn;ame in sothefastnes &amp; noght ydyll spake.  And this was schewede till ane haly
heremyte &thorn;at highte Florencius, &thorn;at wonned in a wildirnes vnknawene fra mene.
Sa mekill vermyne was abowte this heremyte stede, &thorn;at nane durste thedir come,
be a ferre waye.  A dekene was in &thorn;at lande &thorn;at of &thorn;is herymyte had herde: he
went so lange in &thorn;at wildirnesse hym to seke, ay to he come to &thorn;e place whare
he duelland was.  Bot sa mekill vermyne he saw &thorn;are abowte, &thorn;at he durste come
no nerre, bot criede after helpe, as he &thorn;at was afferde.  &THORN;at haly mane come owte
to wiete whate &thorn;at was &thorn;at cryede: &amp; he sawe a mane stand with-owte, &amp; he
spirred hyme whate he walde.  &THORN;e dekyne was fayne &thorn;at he hym sawe, &amp; thus
to hyme sayde: &laquo;Haly fadir, I haue soghte the ferre, for thi blyssynge I walde
hafe; and now I hafe the foundene I hafe Ioye ynoghe, myghte I to &thorn;e wyne;
bot sa many venemos bestes abowte I se, &thorn;at I dare come no nerre the.&raquo;  &THORN;e
haly mane, whene he this herde, felle downe appone his knees &amp; hertly to god
he prayede he wold for-do &thorn;ase wormes, &thorn;at &thorn;e dekyne myghte come &amp; speke
with hyme.  &amp; vnnethes had this haly mane hys prayere to god made, whene a
grysely storme with thonore rase, was nane slyke herd ne sene by-fore, &amp; slewe
all &thorn;e wormes by-dene.  &THORN;ane sawe the heremyte &thorn;is syghte &amp; sayd till oure
lorde: &laquo;Now, lord, thir bestes lygges here slayne sa thikke one ylke a syde, &thorn;at
I to hym come ne may ne he to me, bot we of thir dede wormes be envenomede.
Lo, lord, &thorn;ay lygge here dede: bot wha sall lefte &thorn;ame awaye?&raquo;  Att this worde
of &thorn;is haly mane sa many fowles come in a littill whylle &thorn;at bare all &thorn;ir wormes
a-waye.  Here-of spekys saynt Gregore &amp; sayse: &laquo;For-thi &thorn;at goddes seruande&yogh;
with-drawes &thorn;ame fra the werlde and his werkes, ydill &amp; vayne kane &thorn;ay noghte
speke, sa to sylence &thorn;ay bynd &thorn;ame-selfe dare &thorn;ay no worde say bot it myghte
be outhir to lerenynge or to louynge of god: ffor-[&thorn;i] whene &thorn;ay oghte by-soghte
god, he graunted &thorn;ame als sone, als he dyd to &thorn;is haly mane of whame we spake.
Bot we wofull wrechys &thorn;at with &thorn;e werlde delis, &thorn;at all daye clatirs as pyes,
righte alls we wittles ware; now lyes, now wryes, now ill spekes, now flyttes,
now bakbyttis, now sweres grete athes: thir fyles oure prayere &amp; lettis it to be
spede; ffor als ferre es oure mouthe prayande fra god, als it es nere &thorn;e werlde
with ydill speche.  Mekill fletis ouer oure herte &amp; passys owt of warde, whils we
are taryed to speke with werldes mene; ffor-[&thorn;i] &thorn;e lesse we are herde of god if we
to hym pray, if oure mouthe be fyled be-fore with werldes speche.&raquo;  For so
myghtfull es prayere if he hafe his ryghte, &thorn;at he maysters &thorn;e fende &amp; lettis hym to
do his will.  For als it tellis by an Emperour &thorn;at hyghte Iulyane, &thorn;at had many
fendis &thorn;at did whate he &thorn;ame badde: this Iulyane comandid a fende to wend to


<PB N="304">

&thorn;e owttireste syde of &thorn;e werlde, to bryng hym hasty tydynges how it was &thorn;are.
And whene the fende had flowene by &thorn;e lyfte tene day Iourne thedirwarde, he come
flyand ouer a place whare an herymet duellyd &thorn;at hight Puplius, &thorn;at prayand was &thorn;at
tyme.  &THORN;e prayere of &thorn;at holy heremyt ouer-gat &thorn;e fende &thorn;ar he flowe, and &thorn;ar still
it helde hym faste as he ware boundene, ywhils tene dayes lastede&mdash;for all &thorn;at
tyme &thorn;e holy heremyte wasse in prayere.  &amp; whene he cessyde of his prayere, &thorn;e
fende tournede agayne; for prayere hym lettide &thorn;at he myghte na ferrere wende. //
</P>
<P>When &thorn;ou hase gedirde hame thi herte with his witt, &amp; hase for-done &thorn;ase
thynges &thorn;at &thorn;e prayand myght lett, and wone to &thorn;at deuocyone &thorn;at god to
&thorn;e sendis thurgh his dere-worthy grace: Qwykly ryse &thorn;ane of thi bede at
&thorn;e belle ryngynge, if &thorn;ou may it here; and if na kirke be &thorn;are &thorn;ou duellis, &thorn;e
Cokk be thi belle; if &thorn;er be nowthir cokk ne belle, goddes lufe &thorn;ane wakkene
the&mdash;and this I hald &thorn;e beste, for it payes maste to godd whene mane wakkyns
and mase hym to ryse to serue his lorde &amp; his creat[o]ure als to hym fallys.  And
ofte by goddes lufers it falles &thorn;at gelelousely es in lufe ruted, &thorn;at &thorn;ay wakkene
be-fore bathe Cokk &amp; belle, and hase weschene &thorn;aire face with swete lufe-teris,
and &thorn;aire saules with-in hase Ioye in gode with deuocyone &amp; lykynge &amp; murnynge
to hym, &amp; with o&thorn;er heuenly gladynges &thorn;at god to his lufers sendis.  Cely are
&thorn;ay by-fore o&thorn;er &thorn;at lufe wakkynns, for many gladynges &thorn;ay hafe whene o&thorn;er
faste slepis: for &thorn;ay fynd by-fore &thorn;ame &thorn;at gladdes all, ryse &thorn;ay neuer so sone;
ffor god hyghtis this till all his &thorn;are he &thorn;us sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui mane vigilauerit ad me, inveniet me,</FOREIGN> &laquo;he &thorn;at arely wakkyns to me, for sothe I say he sall fynd me, to
speke with me, to glade hyme with me, &amp; hafe me at his will.&raquo;  For-thi lere of
&thorn;e lufe-buke als goddes spouse &thorn;e techis, so he dyd &thorn;are he &thorn;us sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ego dormio &amp; cor meum vigilat,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es: &laquo;whils I slepe my body to ese, my hert es
ay wakire in gelousy to my lord.&raquo;  / Qwykly &thorn;ane &thorn;ou ryse when any o&thorn;er(!) &thorn;e
calles, &amp; thank hertly thi gud lord for &thorn;e rest &thorn;at &thorn;ou hadd, for &thorn;e mynd of
angels &thorn;at god to &thorn;e sent.  Ryse &thorn;ane qwykly at this calle as knyght &thorn;at es
called to speke with his lord &thorn;e kynge.  If a knyghte gret lykynge hafe to be
called to come speke with &thorn;e kynge, whene he knawes sothely &thorn;at it es for his
profet: with more skyll goddes knyghte, &thorn;at es ilke gud crystyne mane, at &thorn;e
callyng of his lord god aughte to be redy, sene so es he calles hym for his mekill
prowe, and for no thynge elles.  At &thorn;is calle arely to ryse ffalles ilke gude crystyne
mane, and namely thir thre degres of mene, &thorn;at es at say: Mene of relegione are
namely haldene &thorn;at by almus lyfes, and mene of haly kyrke &thorn;at lyfes by tendis&mdash;
for alle &thorn;e werld trauells to brynge thame to hande all &thorn;at &thorn;ame nedis, so &thorn;at
&thorn;ay may with more ryst better serue godde, &amp; with &thorn;aire haly dedis saughetelynge
make by-twyx god &amp; mane; and also maydens &amp; wedous &thorn;at hase a-vowede chaste.
All thir byfore o&thorn;er ere moste holdene to pray to god and loue hyme als till
ylkane falles, &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne rysesynge fynd &thorn;ame noghte in bedde, bot if &thorn;ay wery
be for trauelle or sekenes &thorn;at &thorn;ame lettis, or any nedfull enchesone &thorn;at &thorn;ay may
noghte with-stande.  Sobirly &thorn;ou ryse with a glade chere, and thynk &thorn;ou herys
god calle the with &thorn;ir wordes &thorn;at are wretyne in the lufe-buke, &thorn;are he &thorn;us spekes
to his leue spouse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Surge propria amica mea, formosa mea, et veni ostende michi faciem tuam, sonet vox tua in auribus meis:</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &thorn;us mekill to say: &laquo;Ryse, he


<PB N="305">

sayse, to me my lefe, my faire thynge, &amp; schewe thi face to me, [I] &yogh;erne &yogh;at
the voyce of thi prayere rynge in myne ere.&raquo;  The Cok wakyns to loue his lorde
by nyghte for &thorn;at he hym made, othir mede gettis he nane efter &thorn;at he es dede:
Thane aughte the, Crystyne mane, &thorn;at lyghtenyde es with skylle &amp; goddis lyknes
berys, &amp; traystys one hyme thurgh his grete grace heuenly mede to haue if &thorn;ou
hym trewly serue, for thus thi byleue &thorn;e sayse, schame &thorn;ane with thi-selfe if &thorn;ou
withstand his calle.  Thynke &thorn;e coke es goddes messangere and with hym he the
calles.  Whene &thorn;ou heris hyme, or whene &thorn;ou heris &thorn;e belle ryng, wakyne &thorn;ane at
this calle &amp; qwykly ryse, &amp; gedir thi herte all to-gedir, to loue thy lorde, &amp; thanke hym of alle his gud dedis &thorn;at he to &thorn;e hase done &thorn;are &thorn;ou lyttill seruede &amp;c.
</P>
</DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="112"><HEAD>Meditations on the Passion and of Three Arrows on Doomsday</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="Rawlinson C 285" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD>Ms. Rawlinson C 285</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="64" UNIT="folio">
<P>Now open &thorn;i hert wyde to thynke
on &thorn;ase paynes &thorn;at Cryst for &thorn;e
thoolede, and thynke &thorn;aim in &thorn;i hert rygth
als he &thorn;aim thoolede, How &thorn;ai his
lufly face all with spyttyng fyeled, How
&thorn;ai buffetted &thorn;e fayrest face of al
mankynde.  How &thorn;ai his swete hend with
coordis band so fast, &thorn;at of all &thorn;e
fyngers &thorn;e blod oute brast.  How &thorn;ai
bette hym with knotty skourges, &thorn;at
neeuer did amisse with worde ne with
deid.  How all sayd with a voyce and
on Pylate cryed, &thorn;at he suld dye als
schameful dede als eeuer any di[e]d.  &para;
Yhete thynke how he was streekede


<PB N="113">

opon &thorn;e croyce &thorn;at layd was on &thorn;e
erthe, and draghene out with rapis,
to mak fote and hande accoord to &thorn;e
boores &thorn;at mad war In &thorn;e tree.  So
fer he was draghen on &thorn;e croyce &thorn;at
he on lay, &thorn;at all his baanes men
mygth telle, als haly wrytte tellis.  And
to &thorn;e tree he on lay, &thorn;ai fest hym with
Irene nayles.  &para; Thynk after how his
body was lift vp with &thorn;e croyce and
smyten in &thorn;e erth, als men duse with
a staake of tree to make it fast in &thorn;e
erth to stande; with &thorn;at swete body &thorn;at
hanged was &thorn;are-on.  &para; At &thorn;is smytyng
in to &thorn;e erthe all his vaynes brast, &thorn;at
of all his lyms &thorn;e blod out stremede.
&THORN;is greued hym sorest [of] all his paynes,
outakyne our vnkyndenes, &thorn;at ylke a
day newys his payn.  &para; Thynke after
how a knygth bifoor hym kneelede and
sayd to hym on schorne: &laquo;Haylle be
&thorn;ou, kyng offe Iewys!  &THORN;at so many
helpis, now &thorn;e nedes to help &thorn;i-self.
Lat now se whate &thorn;ou may do!  Come
now doune fro &thorn;e croyce &thorn;at &thorn;ou ert
to naylled, and we sal trowe with-outen
moor &thorn;ou ert goddis son of heeuene&raquo;.
&para; Thynke on &thorn;at scharpe coroun of
thorne &thorn;ai [had] corouned hym with, &thorn;at
made his lufly face streeme all on blod.
And of &thorn;at bitter aysel menged with
galle, &thorn;ai gaf hym to drynke whene he
pleyned hym of threst, als he &thorn;at mykel
had blede.  Bot wite &thorn;ou wele, hym
thrested nogth after pyement ne wyne,
ne after othir likour &thorn;at men nootes for
threst, bot anely after &thorn;e luf of man,
&thorn;at he so dere bogth.  Thynke &thorn;an
when &thorn;ou ogth agaynes hym duse, &thorn;ou
bedis hym gall at drynk, als &thorn;e Iewys
dide.  &para; Thynke on his careful moder,
and of his Cosyne Iohn&macr;, &thorn;at stod by
hym nere and sagth all &thorn;at he thoolede.
Na speche of man may telle what sorrow
&thorn;ai had &thorn;at stound!  &para; Thynke on &thorn;ase
wordes he to his moder sayd whilles he


<PB N="114">

hanged on &thorn;e rode: &laquo;Woman, lo here
&thorn;i son!&raquo;; he sayd to hys Cosyn Iohn&macr;:
&laquo;lo here &thorn;i moder dere!  &THORN;ou serue hir
with all &thorn;i mygth!&raquo;  Whate thynges com
fra hir hert when scho herd &thorn;ir wordis,
whene mans son for goddis sone, &thorn;e
dysciple for &thorn;e mayster, &thorn;e seruaunt for
&thorn;e lord, was gifen hire to yheme!  &para;
Thynke how &thorn;at blyssed body nakede
and pale, hanged on &thorn;e rode so bette
with skourges &thorn;at noth left on hym hale.
And yhete so pouerly he was stedde
&thorn;at he had na place his heeued on for
to rest; and als naked als he hangede,
gude he nane had hym with for to
hide, bot his moder courchife knetted
obout his lyms.  &para; Thynke how ful he
was of mercy whils he hanged on &thorn;e
rod, &thorn;at forgaf &thorn;e thef his synnes &thorn;at
hanged by his syde, &thorn;at myssayd hym
a whyle befoore, als &thorn;e gospell tellis;
and higth hym &thorn;at he suld be &thorn;at day
In paradyse with hym.<MILESTONE N="65" UNIT="folio">  &para; Thynke &thorn;an on &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at Bernarde to Ihesu
sayd: &laquo;A, god, my loouerd, swete Ihesu,
whate hafs &thorn;ou don &thorn;at &thorn;ou so blodye
hanges on &thorn;e rode, &thorn;at neeuer dide
amysse bot eeuer dide &thorn;e gude?  Sackles
&thorn;ai do &thorn;e to &thorn;e dede, woo es me so: ffor
I am gylty of &thorn;i dede, for-[&thorn;i] &thorn;ai suld
me sla and late hym passe with-outen
harme, &thorn;at no cheesoun es of dede.
For-&thorn;i, yhe wrytches &thorn;at wrange has
done, takis me for hym and duse me
to dede: for I am &thorn;e synfull &thorn;at ille
hafs wrogth, thurgth &thorn;at I haf folwed
&thorn;[e] fendes rede; ffor-&thorn;i lat &thorn;is
Innocent passe &thorn;at neeuer man couth say
ille by, bot til all has done &thorn;e gude,
for-&thorn;i I pray &yogh;ow I may for hym dye&raquo;.
&para; And &yogh;ite thynk Inwardely on &thorn;e word
he sayd befoor he yhelded &thorn;e gaast,
&thorn;at es &thorn;at he to &thorn;e synfull man cryes
and says: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Consummatum est,</FOREIGN> &laquo;Al es
fulfilled&raquo;; &thorn;at es: &laquo;I am fulfilled of sorowe,


<PB N="115">

bath in body and in saul&raquo;.  In body,
&thorn;at all was pyned, for fra &thorn;e schuf of
&thorn;e hele was nogth left hale.  In saul
was he pyned, als &thorn;e prophete says:
thurgth our vnkyndnes &thorn;at kyd hym na
thanke for his gud dide, and duse &thorn;at
in vs es ilke a day to new his payne;
and &thorn;at ouer-passis all his payne &thorn;at
he bifoor thooled, ffor-&thorn;i he says at
his end &laquo;I am fulfilled of sorow&raquo;.  &para;
Thynke &thorn;an, after &thorn;ir wordes war sayde
he bogthed doun with his heeued and
sayd at all mygth here: &laquo;In to &thorn;i
handes, loouerde my fader, my gast I
yheld&raquo;.  &para; Thynk on &thorn;ase wonderes &thorn;at
fele &thorn;at tyme: how creatures &thorn;at na
witte had forthogth of his dede, and
mad sorow on &thorn;aire manere, and kid
at &thorn;ai felid his dede ful sare.  &THORN;e sone
withdrogh hym and wex myrke; &thorn;e
harde stane all to-raaf, &thorn;at all &thorn;e erth
qwoke; &thorn;e toumbes of dede men
altoraafe &thorn;at mad war of stane, and &thorn;e ded
&thorn;at in &thorn;aim war lokene, qwyckened to
lif, and witenest &thorn;at he was southfast
god &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewys did to &thorn;e dede.  &para;
And thynke yhete Inwardly on &thorn;ase
sorowes &thorn;at his moder had, &thorn;at folwed
hym in all &thorn;at tyme rigth vnto &thorn;e dede,
and als carefull moder eeuer bihelde al
&thorn;at &thorn;ay did hir child.  Was neeuer na
martire &thorn;at thooled so mykel payne als
scho dide!  for in &thorn;at party all martires
war pyned &thorn;at deedly er of kynde: bot
goddis moder was pyned in saul &thorn;at
neeuer mygth dye; for all &thorn;at hir son
thooled, stake thurgth hir hert.  His
paynes left hym at &thorn;e dede, &thorn;ay mygth
griefe hym no mare: bot in hir saul
all &thorn;ai left, for-&thorn;i hir paynes war maare;
for scho yherned for sorow to dye, bot
na sorow mygth hir sla.  &THORN;an was &thorn;e
worde fulfillede of Symeone, &thorn;at to hir
sayd: &laquo;&THORN;e swerd of sorow sal stycke
thurgth &thorn;i hert&raquo;.  &para; Thynke &thorn;an whate
he es &thorn;at alle has thoolede, and how
vnworthy &thorn;ai war to luf wham he dyed


<PB N="116">

foor.  If &thorn;ou &thorn;ir stirynges oft haf in
mynde what-so-eeuer &thorn;ou be, it agth
to meke &thorn;i hert in lufe and make &thorn;e
synnes to fle.  &para; Thynke after with whate
deuocyone he was taken doune of &thorn;e
rode.  How &thorn;e thre Maryes his body
digth, and layd hym in a tounbe new
made of stane.  &para; Thynke after of his

vp-rysynge: how brygth, how fayre &thorn;at
body raas &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewys made so
laythely in &thorn;at entent forto hafe for-done
hym for eeuer: and nowe he lifs
allmyghty god, kyng corouned in heeuene,
and sal deme &thorn;aim at his wile &thorn;at hym
demed to dede.  &para; Thynke what Ioy his
discyples had whene &thorn;ai sagh hym risen
and haf Maystery of &thorn;e dede; &thorn;an &thorn;ai
war so drunken<MILESTONE N="66" UNIT="folio"> In &thorn;e luf of hym
&thorn;at &thorn;ai war prest forto dye for hym, &thorn;at
befor forsoke hym and swore &thorn;ai knew
hym nogth.  To tell of &thorn;e Ioy &thorn;at his
moder had, es na tung &thorn;at may it telle!...
Thynke &thorn;an, if we kepe vs fra synne
our life, of we synfull haf bene of
neeuer so lange tyme, and we wille
sare forthynke and schrife of &thorn;at we
haf myse-done and neeuer turne agayne,
we may chalenge als rigth ayrers to
dwele with hym In blisse with-outene
ende.  &para; And thynke &thorn;an on &thorn;e
dredful day of dome: whene god allmyghty
sall come all cristene sauls forto deme
and gif til ylke ane after &thorn;ai haf seruede,
ille or gude.  And als gladfull als his
come sal be vnto his chosyn childer,
als g[r]ymly and als agthful sal it be til
&thorn;ase wryckched caytifs &thorn;at has led &thorn;aire


<PB N="117">

lif in lust and likynges of &thorn;aire flesshe
and in dedely synne, and walde nogth
amend &thorn;aim bot ended &thorn;are-Inne.  Til
&thorn;ase god sal say: &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Congregabo super
eos mala: Et sagittas meas complebo
in eis:</FOREIGN> &laquo;And I sal schote&raquo;, says god,
&laquo;thre scharpe arows at &thorn;aim, &thorn;at sal
smyte &thorn;aim &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal neeuer couere&raquo;.
&para; &THORN;e first arow es when he sal bide
&thorn;aim rise &amp; come til &thorn;e dome, when
he sal say: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Surgite mortui &amp; venite ad
iudicium.</FOREIGN>  Thurgth &thorn;e mygth of &thorn;is
word all &thorn;at deed eer sal qwycken to
life, and toumbes of marble and of
brasse sal al to-ryue, to lat out &thorn;e bodys
&thorn;at In &thorn;aim war lokyne.  &THORN;is es &thorn;e
arowe &thorn;at &thorn;e haly man eeuer ilike felid
smert hym ful sare, and sayd: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Siue commedam siue bibam siue aliquid aliud faciam,
semper michi videtur quod illa vox
terribilis intonat in auribus meis: Surgite
mortui &amp; venite ad iudicium</FOREIGN>&mdash;&thorn;is word com neuer fra his hert.  Sen &thorn;is haly
man had swilk dred of &thorn;ire wordis, me
thynk it war nedfull to &thorn;e synfull to
haf &thorn;aim in mynde, to make &thorn;aim
affered &thorn;at &thorn;ai fall in no syne.  For als
Salamon says: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sicut fremitus leonis, ita
ira dei.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;an &thorn;is [es] &thorn;e kynd of &thorn;e
lyoun &thorn;at he feris all beestes with his
romying and makes &thorn;aim so hertles for
drede &thorn;at &thorn;ai dar nowr flee; bot &thorn;ogh
his noyse be hidouse til all bestes, yhet
it comfortis his awene whelpis and
whyckenes &thorn;aim to life.  Rigth so sal
Ihesu Crist beer hym at &thorn;e day of dome
til all &thorn;at haf lifd in syne and wald
mak na endyng of &thorn;aire ille life; at
&thorn;is Callyng &thorn;ai sal be so feride and so
vnmyghty of &thorn;aire self &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal nogth
mow stire &thorn;aim on na syde, bot &thorn;are
bihoues &thorn;aim to take als &thorn;ai haf seruede,
ille or gud.  And als he sal be
wrothefull vnto &thorn;ase weryed wrycches: so to
his awen childer &thorn;at here has wrogth
his wille, lufely he sal be and wynly


<PB N="118">

on to loke; &thorn;ai sal waken with ioy at
his callyng and to his blisse wend, eeuer
to be [&thorn;ar] with-outen end.  Bot &thorn;e
synfull wricches sal seke hooles &thorn;aim
Inne forto hid, &thorn;at &thorn;ai se nogth his
dredful face &thorn;at feres &thorn;aim out of &thorn;aire
witte; als Isaye &thorn;e prophete says:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Introibunt in speluncis petrarum et in
voragines terre a facie formidinis domini,
cum surrexerit percutere terram.</FOREIGN>  Of &thorn;is Commyng spekis saynt Ancelyne and
says: &laquo;On &thorn;e ta half on &thorn;e day of dome
sal our laythly synnes be-call vs of &thorn;e
slaghter of our saul.  On &thorn;e to&thorn;er half
sal rigthwy[s]nese stand, &thorn;at no pyte es
with.  How sal &thorn;e synful fare &thorn;an?  for flee
may he nogth, ne hid hym may he
nogth, bot &thorn;are bihoues hym stand to
tak als he has serued.  &THORN;an sal &thorn;ai &thorn;at
now er so kene &thorn;at harmes all &thorn;at
oboute &thorn;aim dwellis, be als<MILESTONE N="67" UNIT="folio"> Cowardis and hertles bath in worde and in dede;
&thorn;ai sal be so stade &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal wille
crepe in a moushool or in a pitte
stynke it neeuer so ille&raquo;.  &para; &THORN;e tothir
arowe es &thorn;at sal smert &thorn;aim ful sare:
when god sal reyne &thorn;aim of al &thorn;at &thorn;ai
haf done sen &thorn;ai war borne, &thorn;at fell to
syne.  &THORN;an sal &thorn;e domes-man schew
his woundes til al man folke, &thorn;at &thorn;ai
may southely se what he vngilty for
&thorn;aire synnes tholede, and on &thorn;is manere
he sal &thorn;aim areyne: &laquo;Of &thorn;e erth I &thorn;e
toke and made &thorn;e with my hende, and
in paradise &thorn;at lufely stede I &thorn;e stalled
&thorn;ore to lende: with-outen care &thorn;ar to
haf bene and dwellid, had &thorn;ou bouxome
bene, and had nogth broken &thorn;e
forwarde &thorn;at was mad vs bi-twene.  Bot
sen &thorn;ou my biddyng withstod and
leeued me for my foo: for-&thorn;i my
rigthwysnes dampnes &thorn;e to hele &thorn;are to be
in sorow &amp; wo.  And when I sagth &thorn;at
&thorn;ou ille ferid so, pyte me stird to rew
on &thorn;e, &thorn;hof &thorn;ou nogth seruede; I ligth
doune in til &thorn;e erth and toke &thorn;e kynd


<PB N="119">

of &thorn;e, whare-In I mygth for &thorn;i gilt
sare pyned be.  In &thorn;at kynd I toke
many a dispyte, I tholed vilany in word
and dede, and for &thorn;e was bogth &amp; salde;
affter Iudas had sald me, &thorn;e Iewys
buffeted me and spittid in my face, and
with scharpe thornes &thorn;ay corouned me,
and with knotty skourges &thorn;ai bete me&mdash;
al &thorn;us for &thorn;e was I digth.  &THORN;is agth
haf mad &thorn;e rew on me, had &thorn;ou bene
kynd.  Ande in my threst &thorn;ai gaf me
aysell menged with bitter gall; and for
&thorn;e &thorn;us was I threlled bath fote &amp; hand
and naylled on &thorn;e tre, and opend my
syd with a spere to make my hert bledde
for &thorn;e.  I forgate my self for me list
luf &thorn;e: ffor on &thorn;e was all my thogth;
all &thorn;is haf I done for &thorn;e, and &thorn;ou als
ane vnkynd wryche hafs sette it at nogth.
Now vndirstand &thorn;ou vnkynd man, lift
vp &thorn;i heeued &amp; loke to me, bihald my
syd, fote &amp; hand, how I am digth for
&thorn;e.  &THORN;us am I digth nogth for my gylt
bot to heele &thorn;i wondis &thorn;at war so sare,
and &thorn;i gilt on me I toke &thorn;at &thorn;ou suld
luf me &thorn;e mare.  For suth I ne wate
qwate I mygth haf done mare &thorn;an I
haf done for &thorn;e: ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;e bihoues
now nedely schewe qwat &thorn;ou has
thooled or done for me.  For now
rigthwysnes wil &thorn;at ilke ane haf als &thorn;ai haf
seruede, outhire to dwel in payne or in
blysse, for eeuer and ay&raquo;.  How sal &thorn;an
&thorn;e wricched fare when he sal be &thorn;us
areynede of &thorn;e domes-man, and all his
synnes openly knawene and schewed to
all mens sigth?  For nogth may &thorn;are
be hid, bot &thorn;at at here es fordone with
scryft of mouth; for als &thorn;e haly man
Iob says: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Reuelabunt celi iniquitatem,
et terra consurget aduersus eum. </FOREIGN> And yhete &thorn;e apostel says: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Testimonium reddet illis consciencia illorum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es: &laquo;&THORN;aire awen Inwite sal bere wittenes
agaynes &thorn;aim&raquo;.  Who may better bere
wittenes agaynes man, &thorn;an he &thorn;at eeuer
dwellis with man, &thorn;at sese &amp; knawes
all his werkis?  &thorn;at es mans Inwite, &thorn;at


<PB N="120">

nogth may by hide fra.  And yhete his
ille werkes sal wend with hym to &thorn;e
dredful dome, &amp; stand by hym all on
rawe, to his schame and to all man folk,
and &thorn;us bitterly sal with hym flyte &thorn;at
al &thorn;e werlde may here: &laquo;We&raquo;, sal &thorn;ai
say, &laquo;er &thorn;ase werkis &thorn;at &thorn;ou with
wrange has wrogth, In dispyte of &thorn;i
gud loorde &thorn;at &thorn;ou for vs sette at nogth;
for &thorn;ou wrogth vs agaynes<MILESTONE N="68" UNIT="folio"> his wille &thorn;at schede his hert-blod for &thorn;e,
for-&thorn;i we er now gedired alle to-gider
als witenes agayne &thorn;e; for &thorn;ou wald
nogth amend &thorn;e qwils &thorn;ou mygth.  Now
&thorn;e forthynkes &thorn;at eeuer &thorn;ou synned:
bot, sory wriche, alto lat, for &thorn;ou had
no likyng bot in vs; and for-&thorn;i we now
sal be with &thorn;e in pyne with-outene
ende, to eke &thorn;i payne&raquo;.  &para; &THORN;e threde
arowe &thorn;at he sal schote, sal be when
he sal say &thorn;at saynt Mathew says in &thorn;e
gospell: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ite maledicti in ignem eternum.</FOREIGN>
&THORN;e haly man says: &laquo;Sare &amp; blody er
&thorn;ase eghen &thorn;at for smoke &amp; hete sal
grete ma teris &thorn;an dropes of water er in
&thorn;e se&raquo;.  &THORN;ou may &thorn;an aske: &laquo;Sen &thorn;ai
sal gret so mykel water, why sleckis
it nogth &thorn;e fyre &thorn;at &thorn;aim so hat
brynnes&raquo;?  &THORN;ane answers saynt Austyne and
says &thorn;at &laquo;so wodly it brynnes eeuer Ilike
&amp; so stalwarde it es in &thorn;e kynd &thorn;at if
all &thorn;e water of all &thorn;is werlde
ouer-flwed it, it myght nogth slecke it, ne
yhet litelle kele it; bot teres makes it
mare wodly to brynne als oyll casten
in &thorn;e fyre&raquo;.  Mynde of &thorn;is wordis had
&thorn;e haly fader &thorn;at to his disciples sayd
after &thorn;ai had lange on hym cryed to
say &thorn;aim sum gud word; &thorn;an sayd he:
&laquo;My dere childer, leer we to wepe for
our synnes, &thorn;at we wepe nogth for
eeuer&raquo;.  What sorow, qwat dred hopes
&thorn;ou &thorn;e weryed wrycches sal hafe whene
god sal say: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ite maledicti in ignem
eternum.</FOREIGN>  When &thorn;e weryed wryches heres


<PB N="121">

and knawes &thorn;at &thorn;ai er dampned and
&thorn;at &thorn;are es na gayne-calle mercy to
craue, &thorn;an sal &thorn;ai say &thorn;e wordis of Iob:
&laquo;&THORN;e day mot perysshe &thorn;at I in borne
was, and &thorn;e nygth in &thorn;e whilke I
consayued was!  Allas &thorn;at sorye while &thorn;at
I borne was, &thorn;at I ne had bene dede
in my moder wambe!  Whare-to noryst
my modir me and sette me on hire
knese and fed me of hir brest?  Allas
&thorn;at while! so mykele trayuelle scho
lost, and noryst of me a brand to
smore in hell-fyere&raquo;.  When &thorn;is of goddis
mouth es sayd, &thorn;an sal &thorn;e gude be
twynnede fra ylle, &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal
neeuer-mare mete.  &THORN;an sal &thorn;e foule deeuells
dryfe &thorn;ase wrytches in til hell als wod
lyouns, with-outen end &thorn;are forto dwele.
&THORN;an sal &thorn;ay wery &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai
eeuer ylle wrogth; ffor all &thorn;at &thorn;aim may
pyne sal &thorn;ai redy fynd.  For &thorn;e fendes
&thorn;at &thorn;aim sall pyne sal neeuer wery be,
bot eeuer Ilyke freke to wirke &thorn;aim all
waa: and yhet na payne sa[l] mow &thorn;aim
sla.  Nedderes, snakis, tadis and other
venemous beestis, ma &thorn;an I can neeuene,
sal lif in &thorn;at fyre als fysshes duse in
&thorn;e flode, to pyne &thorn;ase wrytches.  And
yhet, for threst at &thorn;ai sal haue, &thorn;ai
sal seke &thorn;e neddir, ffor threst &thorn;e
venymm out to souke, for &thorn;e hate fyre
at &thorn;ai er In.  &THORN;are sal na thyng be herd
bot yhellyng and Crying and grettyng.
And ligth es &thorn;are nane, for smoke it
for-duse.  &THORN;an wald &thorn;ai be fayne, and
pyne wald &thorn;aim slaa.  Bot goddis childir,
&thorn;at here haf done his wille, with aungells
sal be lede tile heeuene, In Ioy and
blysse to dwelle eeuer withoutene ende.
To &thorn;e whilk Ioy he bryng vs &thorn;at
bogth vs.  Amen.  Amen.  Amen.
</P>
</DIV3>

<DIV3 N="Arundel 507" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="112"><HEAD>Ms. Arundel 507</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="48" UNIT="folio"><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Meditacio de passione Ihesu Christi.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Oppyn &thorn;i hert with sighings sare til
&thorn;ink on &thorn;e pynes &thorn;at Ihesus Crist suffred,
&amp; sette &thorn;aim in &thorn;i saule: bi ordere /
as he &thorn;aim tholid: How &thorn;ai his hali
face with spittynge filid, How &thorn;ai
buffettid &thorn;e fairest face of al mankynde; How
&thorn;ai with cordis bande his faire handes,
so &thorn;at oute of alle his fyngres &thorn;e blode
oute brast; How &thorn;ai betid him with
knottid scourgis; How alle with a voice
cried &laquo;do him on croice, / &thorn;at he die
als schameful dead: as eauer any deied&raquo;,
How he was strekid on &thorn;e croice &thorn;at


<PB N="113">

was laid on &thorn;e erth, / &amp; drawyn oute
with rapis: til make handes &amp; fete
acorde til &thorn;e holes / &thorn;at ware made
in &thorn;e tree.  So straite he was dra(w)en
oute on &thorn;e croice: &thorn;at men might telle
alle his banes; &amp; to &thorn;at croice was he
festenid with irnen nailes.  Thinke after
how is bodi was liftid vp with &thorn;e croice /
&amp; smyten oft in &thorn;e erth: als men dose
a stake of tree til make it fast til stand:
with &thorn;at swete bodi lifand &thorn;at hinged
&thorn;eron.  At &thorn;is smytynge in &thorn;e erth:
alle his vaynes brast, &thorn;at oute of alle
his swete lymes: &thorn;e blode oute stremid.
&THORN;is greuid him sarest of alle o&thorn;er paynes:
oute-take oure vnkyndenesse, &thorn;at ilk
daie newes his pyne.  Thynk after
how knightis to him knelid: &amp; said to
him in scorne: &laquo;Haile, kynge of Iues!
&THORN;ou &thorn;at mani helpis: &thorn;ou nedes now
helpe &thorn;e selfe; come downe fra &thorn;e
croice / &thorn;ou art nailid to: &amp; we sal
trow &thorn;at &thorn;ou art goddis sone of heuen&raquo;.
Think on &thorn;e scharpe corone of thornis,
&thorn;at made his loueli face: til streme al
on blode; &amp; of &thorn;e bitter aysill myngid
with galle, &thorn;ai gafe him to drink / when
he pleynid him of thrist / als he &thorn;at
mikil had bledde.  Bot witte &thorn;ou wele,
him thristis noght after pyment ne wyne /
ne after o&thorn;er liquore: bot aneli after
&thorn;e lufe of man / &thorn;at he so dere boght.
think &thorn;en / when &thorn;ou dose ani thinge
agayn his wille: &thorn;ou dose as &thorn;e Iues
did / birles him galle to drinke, as a
vnkinde wreche.  Thinke on his careful
moder, &amp; on sayn Iohan his dere cosyn,
&thorn;at stode bi him &amp; sagh al &thorn;at he
tholid; na tonge mai telle: how sari
&thorn;ai ware &thorn;at tyme.  Thinke on &thorn;e wordes
he spake til his moder hangand on &thorn;e


<PB N="114">

rode: &laquo;woman: lo here &thorn;i sone&raquo;; til
sayn Iohan his cosyn: &laquo;lo here &thorn;i moder
dere: &thorn;ou serue hire with al &thorn;i might&raquo;.  /
What sighinges come til hire hert / when
sche herd &thorn;is wordes: when mannes
sone for goddis sone / &thorn;e disciple for
&thorn;e maister / &thorn;e seruant for &thorn;e lorde:
was gifen hire to &yogh;eme.  Thinke on &thorn;at
blissid bodi nakid &amp; pale hinged on &thorn;e
rode / so ryuen with scourges: &thorn;at
noght left hale.  And &yogh;itte so pouerli
was he stad in &thorn;at stoure: &thorn;at he had
noght to rest his heuid on; &amp; als nakid
as he was borne&mdash;bot his moder
couerchiefe was knit aboute his lymes.  Thinke
how ful he was of merc(i) &yogh;it whil he
hinged on rode / &thorn;at forgafe &thorn;e theefe
his synnes &thorn;at hinged biside him: &thorn;at
missaid him a while bifore; &amp; hight him
he suld &thorn;at daie be with him in
paradise.  When &thorn;ou art vmbithought of
alle<MILESTONE N="47" UNIT="folio"> (&thorn;e) pynes &thorn;at Ihesus suffred
for &thorn;e: thinke in &thorn;i saule / &thorn;at &thorn;ou
standis bi (him) in &thorn;at place &amp; sees
what &thorn;ai him do; speke &thorn;en to &thorn;i lorde
&thorn;e wor(des) of sayn Bernarde: &laquo;God mi
lorde, swete Ihesu, / what haues &thorn;ou
(do)ne: &thorn;at &thorn;ou so blodi hinges on rode /
&thorn;at neauer did iuel: bot eauer did gode? /
Sakles &thorn;ai do &thorn;e til deade, wa is me
&thorn;erfore / for i am gilti of &thorn;i deade;
&amp; agayn lawe &amp; reson it is: til sla him
&thorn;at neauer did misse, &amp; lat him passe
free: &thorn;at did &thorn;e harme.  For-&thorn;i, &yogh;e
wreches(!) Iues, (ta)kes me, for i am &thorn;e
synful &thorn;at yuel has done &amp; folowid &thorn;e
fendis rede.  I prai &yogh;ow / latis &thorn;is
Innocent passe: &amp; dose me til deade,
for i haue trespassid&raquo;.  Thinke alswa
inwardli / how he said on &thorn;e rode
bifore he &yogh;elde &thorn;e gaste&mdash;for it mai
stere &thorn;e til haue sorugh of &thorn;i synnes
&amp; rue on his deade &thorn;at was so pynid
for &thorn;e, &amp; swa wreke his deade on &thorn;e
selfe; / &thorn;at &thorn;us on &thorn;e rode cried:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Consummatum est:</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;al is fulfillid&raquo;,


<PB N="115">

as if he said: &laquo;I am fulfillid of sorugh:
bathe in bodi &amp; saule&raquo;.  In bodi: for
al was pynid / fra &thorn;e croune of &thorn;e
heuid til &thorn;e sole of &thorn;e fote.  In saule:
thorugh oure vnkyndnesse, &thorn;at kithis
him na thanke for his gode dede: bot
dose &thorn;at in vs is: euer til (n)ew his
payne; &amp; &thorn;at ouerpassis alle his paynes
&thorn;at he bifore tholid, for-&thorn;i he said at
his ende: &laquo;I am fulfillid of sorugh&raquo;.  &amp; at &thorn;is worde: he loutid downe his heuid / &amp; said til his fader: &laquo;In til &thorn;i handes:
mi saule i &yogh;elde&raquo;.  Think &thorn;en on &thorn;e
wondres &thorn;at &thorn;en felle: how creatures
&thorn;at na witte had: rued on his deade.
&THORN;e sone withdrow his brightnesse &amp; bicome al mirke, &amp; schewid so: &thorn;at it
rued Cristes deade; &thorn;e harde roche rafe;
&thorn;e erth qwoqe; &thorn;e grafes openid / &amp; &thorn;e deade men &thorn;at ware in &thorn;aim / rase
to life, &amp; wittenesid &thorn;at he was
sothefast god: &thorn;at &thorn;e Iues did til deade, /
with sighings &amp; teres.  Als i rede &thorn;ou
&thorn;ink on &thorn;e stingand sorughs of his
moder, &thorn;at was with him ai til &thorn;e
deade / &amp; bihild al &thorn;at &thorn;ai did with
hire child.  Neauer tholid martir so
mikil / as sche tholid!  for martirs ware
pynid in bodi, &amp; goddis modir: in saule,
&thorn;at mai noght deie; for alle &thorn;e pynes
&thorn;at hire sonne tholid: thorugh-stikid
hire saule, &amp; sche &yogh;ernid for sorugh til
deie: &amp; na sorugh might hire sla.  &THORN;en
was fulfillid &thorn;e worde of Simeon: Tuam
ipsius animam pertransibit gladius, &thorn;at
is: &laquo;&THORN;e swerd of sorugh sal
thorugh-stike &thorn;i saule&raquo;.  Think als inwardli
what he is &thorn;at &thorn;us tholid, &amp; how
vnworthi &thorn;ai ware to lufe / for whaim he


<PB N="116">

deied; ffor if &thorn;ou haue oft in mynde
&thorn;is steryngs: &thorn;ai hald &thorn;i hert in lufe &amp; makis &thorn;e to flee synne.  Thinke after
with what deuocion he was taken downe
of &thorn;e rode; how &thorn;e .III. Maries dight
him with oignementis &amp; faldid his bodi
in white clathe &amp; laid him in toumbe
of stane.  Thinke after of his wendynge
til helle; / what comforte &thorn;ai had: &thorn;at
abade so lange his (co)mynge &thorn;are in
so mirke stede; what sorugh &amp; drede /
sighing &amp; gn(as)tinge &thorn;e wode fendes of
helle had &thorn;at tyme; how he bande
Sathan so &thorn;at he might neauer harme
ne fande &thorn;e folke after / as bifore.  After
of (his) vprisyng: / how bright / how
faire he rase in bodi: &thorn;at &thorn;e Iues so
laitheli di(ght) in &thorn;at entente / for
til haue fordone &thorn;e mynde of him for
eauer; &amp; now he lifes al-mighti god
&amp; kyng coronid in heuen, &amp; sal deme
&thorn;aim at (his) wille.  Thinke what ioie
alle his disciples had: when &thorn;ai saw
him risyn / &amp; haue &thorn;e maistri of deade;
bifore: &thorn;ai deniid him &amp; sa(id) &thorn;ai
knew him noght; bot &thorn;en &thorn;aim
for-thought &thorn;at &thorn;ai had missaide, &amp; luffied
him as &thorn;aire lorde; &amp; ware so fulfillid
of his lufe: &thorn;at &thorn;ai ware redi til die for
him / &amp; qwite him deade for deade.
Til telle what ioie his (mo)der had / when
sche sagh him risen til life: na man mai
telle.  Thinke af(ter) how he steie til
heuen with oure manhede, &amp; sette it on
&thorn;e right hand of al-mighti god his
fader; &amp; swa festenid oure kynd in him:
&thorn;at &thorn;ai sal neu(er) twyn; &amp; thorugh &thorn;is
alliaunce / if we kepe vs fra synne / or
forth(inke) &amp; schryue vs of &thorn;at we haue
misdone / &amp; turne na mare agayn: we
m(ay) chalange as haires / til dwelle in
his blisse.  Thinke &thorn;at he sal come &amp; deme al mankynde / &amp; gife ilk man
after he has wroght; &amp; als gl(ad)ful as
is come is to &thorn;e gode: als auful &amp;


<PB N="117">

grisly sal it be to &thorn;e ille.  For god thretis
&thorn;e yuel with .III. arowes / &amp; sais:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Congregabo super eos mala &amp; sag.III. com.
in eis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;I sal hepe on &thorn;aim
alkyns yuel &amp; wa, &amp; mi .III. sharpe
arowes sal i in &thorn;aim feste: &thorn;at sal
wounde &thorn;e s(in)ful / &thorn;at he sal neuer
couer&raquo;.  &THORN;e first arow is: when he sal
bidde &thorn;(aim) rise &amp; come til &thorn;aire
dome / with &thorn;is wordes: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Surgite mortui:
venite ad iudicium,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;rise &yogh;e &thorn;at
are deade, &amp; comes til &yogh;oure dome&raquo;.
Thorugh might of &thorn;ir wordes: alle &thorn;at
ware deade sal quikyn.  &THORN;is is &thorn;(e) arowe
&thorn;at sayn Ierome said by: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Siue comedam
siue bibam, semper vi(detur) michi quod
illa vox terribilis insonet auribus meis
&laquo;Surgite mortui, venite ad iudicium&raquo;,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at is: &laquo;Whe&thorn;er i ete or drynke / or
what ellis i do: euer me thinke &thorn;is
dredeful wordes rynges in mine eres:
Rise &yogh;e &thorn;at are deade, &amp; comes til &yogh;oure
dome&raquo;.  Sen &thorn;is hali man dredid &thorn;is
wordes: nede is a synful man til drede
&thorn;aim, so &thorn;at he falle in na synne.  For
Salomon sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sicut fremitus leonis: ita
ira eius;</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;&thorn;e wreke of &thorn;e
domesman at his comynge: is as romiinge of
a lion&raquo;. / &THORN;e liones kynd is til f(ere)
alle bestes with his romiinge, &amp; &yogh;itte
dar &thorn;ai noght flee; &amp; &thorn;ofe &thorn;is noice
be dredeful til alle bestes: &yogh;itte
comfortis it his awen whelpis &amp; quykins
&thorn;aim til life.  Swa sal Ihesu Crist at &thorn;e
straite dome do til alle bestli men &thorn;at
has liuid in synne &amp; wold<MILESTONE N="44" UNIT="folio"> make na endynge of &thorn;aire ille; at &thorn;is callinge
&thorn;ai sal be so f(erid) &amp; so vnmighti,
&thorn;at on na halfe sal &thorn;ai flee, bot &thorn;ai sal
dwelle (&) take as &thorn;ai haue seruid.  &amp; as
he sal be wrathful to &thorn;e wreches, so
sal he be loueli til his aune childre &thorn;at
has wroght his wille here: for &thorn;ai sal


<PB N="118">

wakyn with ioie at his callinge / &amp; wend
with him til dwelle in blisse.  Bot &thorn;e
synful wreches sal seke til hide &thorn;aim
&thorn;at &thorn;ai see noght his dredeful face /
&thorn;at flais &thorn;aim oute of &thorn;aire wi(tte); as
Ysaie sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Introibunt in cauernas
petrarum &amp; voragines terre / a facie (for)
midinis domini: cum surrexerit percutere
terram,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;&THORN;e weried synful sal
crepe in to &thorn;e creuys of &thorn;e stane: &amp; in holis in &thorn;e erth, for to hide &thorn;aim
fra &thorn;e wrekeful face of god / when he
risis til smyte &thorn;e erth&raquo;, &thorn;at is, when
he sal come to deme erthli men.  Of
&thorn;is comynge spekis sa(yn) Anselme &amp; sais: &laquo;On a halfe sal oure synnes bitterli
bicalle vs of &thorn;e slaghter of oure saule.
On an o&thorn;er halfe sal stand rightwisenesse,
&thorn;at na pitee is with.  Abouen vs / &thorn;e
wrekeful domesman / &thorn;at als soft as he
is here: als wrathful he is &thorn;are; mild
here: storne &thorn;are; &amp; he is bathe
domesman, &amp; wittenesse, &thorn;at wate alle oure
giltis&raquo;. // &THORN;at o&thorn;er aro(w) is: when god
sal &thorn;aim areyn of al &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue
misdone, sethen &thorn;ai ware borne; &amp; &thorn;e
domesman sal schew his woundis til alle
men / &thorn;at &thorn;ai mai see sotheli &thorn;at he
vngiltli tholid for &thorn;aire synnes, &amp; with
&thorn;is word(es) he sal &thorn;aim areyne: &laquo;Of &thorn;e
erth i &thorn;e toke / &amp; with mi handes &thorn;e
made, In paradise &thorn;at loueli stede
withoute kare til haue duellid / if &thorn;ou had
bien buxom to me &amp; kepid mi
comandmente; bot sone &thorn;ou brake it, &amp; left
me: for mine enemy; for-&thorn;i
rightwisenesse dampnid &thorn;e til helle, &thorn;are to be
n sorugh &amp; waa.  When i sagh after
&thorn;ine iuel fare: i had pite on &thorn;e / &thorn;of
&thorn;ou nane deseruid; I lightid til erth &amp; toke &thorn;e kyn of &thorn;e; whare i was sare


<PB N="119">

pinid &amp; despisid, &amp; toke for &thorn;e mikil
vil(a)nie in dede &amp; worde.  And after
Iudas had salde me: &thorn;e Iues toke me,
&amp; buffet me &amp; spittid in mi face; with
scharpe thornis &thorn;ai coronid me, with
knottid scourgis &thorn;ai dang me; so laitheli
&thorn;ai dight me: &thorn;at i was like a mesell
til loke on.  Al &thorn;is aght haue gart &thorn;e
haue pite on me / if &thorn;ou had bien
kynde.  In mi thrist &thorn;ai gaf me to
drinke aysill myngid with bitter galle;
&thorn;ai thirlid mi fete &amp; handes: &amp; nailid
me to &thorn;e rode, &amp; hopenid mi side with
a spere: &amp; made mi hert til blede.  I
forgate me selfe: for on &thorn;e was al mi
thoght; &amp; &yogh;itte &thorn;ou as an vnkind: settis
al at noght.  Now &thorn;ou vnkyndman
vnderstand &amp; loke to me, &amp; bihald mi
side / fete &amp; handes / how waful i
am made for &thorn;e, &amp; to hele &thorn;i wondes;
&amp; for-&thorn;i &thorn;ou suld haue louid me &thorn;e
mare; (for i) ne wate what i might
haue done for &thorn;e: mare &thorn;en i haue
do(ne).  For-&thorn;i nedli bihoues &thorn;e til
schew: what &thorn;ou haues done or tho(li)d
for me; ffor now mi rightwisnes wil:
&thorn;at i schape til ilk man his mede /
to dwelle in pyne or in ioie for eauer /
after he has seruid&raquo;.  How sal &thorn;en &thorn;e
waried synful fare / when he is &thorn;us
reyned of &thorn;e wrathful domesman / &amp; alle his synnes schewid til alle men?
for noght mai &thorn;are be hid: bot &thorn;at was
fordone here with schrifte; for hali Iob
sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Reuelabunt celi iniquitatem eius, &amp; terra consurget aduersus eum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;heuen sal schew &thorn;e wikednesse of &thorn;e
synful, &amp; erth sal rise &amp; stand agayn
him &amp; bere witnes of his werkis&raquo;.  And
&yogh;itte &thorn;e apostle sais: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Testimonium
reddet illis: consciencia eorum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;&thorn;aire inwitte sal bere witnes agayn
&thorn;e synful&raquo;, fra &thorn;e whilke man mai noght


<PB N="120">

hide.  And &yogh;itte his iuel werkes sal
stand bi him at &thorn;e dredful dome, &amp; bitterli flite with him &amp; sai: &laquo;We are
&thorn;e werkis &thorn;at &thorn;ou wreche has wroght
in despite of &thorn;i gode lorde; for &thorn;ou
wroght vs agayn his wille: &thorn;at schad
his hert-blode for &thorn;e.  Now forthinkis
&thorn;e &thorn;at eauer &thorn;ou synnid: bot, sari
wreche, / al to late; &amp; &thorn;erfore sal we
dwel with &thorn;e with-outen ende: for til
eke &thorn;i pyne&raquo;. // &THORN;e .III. arow sal he
schote: when he sais &thorn;is wordes: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ite maledicti in ignem eternum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;ga &yogh;e waried, in til endeles fire&raquo;.  &THORN;e hali
man sais: &laquo;&THORN;e inee of &thorn;a &thorn;at are in
&thorn;at fire &amp; smoke: sal grete ma teres /
&thorn;en water is in &thorn;e brade see&raquo;.  &THORN;is fire,
as saynt Austin sais, brennis so wodeli
&amp; eauer ilike / &amp; so stalword is in his
kynd: &thorn;at &thorn;of alle &thorn;is werldis waters it
al ouerflowid: it might noght &thorn;is fire
slokyn nor kele it a litil.  &THORN;is fire makis
ai smoke, &thorn;at makis &thorn;e wreches til
wepe; &amp; &thorn;aire teres strynthis &thorn;e fire
&thorn;are: as oil wold if it ware castin in
&thorn;is fire here.  &THORN;e hali man had mynd
of &thorn;is teres, &thorn;at said til his disciples /
when &thorn;ai had lange cried on him til
sai &thorn;aim some gode worde: &laquo;Mi dere
childre, he saide, wepe we here: so &thorn;at
oure teres seche vs noght in helle&raquo;.
When &thorn;e waried heris &amp; wate &thorn;at &thorn;ai
are dampnid, &amp; wate &thorn;er is na
gaynchare ne merci to fynd: &thorn;en he sais &thorn;e
wordes of Iob: &laquo;&THORN;e dai mote peris &thorn;at
i was borne inne / &amp; &thorn;e night &thorn;at i
was conceyuid inne!  When had i
bien dead in mi moders wambe?  allas
&thorn;at sari while &thorn;at eauer i was borne!
Wharto sette mi moder me on hire kne,
&amp; wesch me, &amp; rokkid me, &amp; fed me on
hire breste?  allas &thorn;e while, so mikil
trauail sche lost / &thorn;at norist me a brande
til smore in helle-fire&raquo;.  When &thorn;is waful
worde <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ite maledicti &amp;c.</FOREIGN>  is said, &thorn;e


<PB N="121">

latheli deuels sal geder &thorn;e iuel fra &thorn;e
gode, &amp; as wode lions: draw &thorn;aim til
helle / eauer &thorn;are to be in al &thorn;e pynes
&thorn;at mai be on thoght.  For &thorn;e fendes
&thorn;at sal &thorn;aim pyne: sal neauer be weri,
bot eauer ilik fresche, til wirke &thorn;aim waa;
&amp; &thorn;ir sari wreches / na pyne mai sla
&thorn;aim.  Neddres / snakis &amp; tades &amp; o&thorn;er
venemouse bestes sal life in &thorn;at hate
fire / as fish in water: til pyne &thorn;a
wreches; &amp; for (f. 45) thrist &thorn;at &thorn;ai
haue: &thorn;[ai] sal souke &thorn;e venym oute of
&thorn;e neddres heuid(es.  &THORN;are) sal noght be
herd / bot &yogh;ellinge &amp; gretyng &amp; gnaistinge
of tethe.  (Light) is &thorn;are nane for smoke,
bot so mikel merknesse: &thorn;at men mai
it g(rape). / Bot goddis awen childre &thorn;at
haues done here his wille: sal be ledde
w(ith) angels til &thorn;e blisse of heuen /
&thorn;are til be in ioie / eauer with-outen
ende.  S(o) grete is &thorn;at ioie, as &thorn;e
apostle tellis: &thorn;at na hert mai it thinke /
ne iee it (se).  If man might be in &thorn;at
ioie / halfe an houre &amp; felid &thorn;at heuenli
likynge / &amp; ware broght agayn til &thorn;is
middel erth: so strange payne it ware
t(il) him til life here-inne, / &thorn;at, of al
&thorn;e welth of &thorn;is werld ware at his wille,
he wold his bodi ware dalte in a
thousand pecis / til wynne &thorn;at ioie a(gayn)
&thorn;at he come fra. // Thinke, &thorn;ou was with
Ihesu Crist in alle his paynes, &amp; &thorn;at
&thorn;ou stode so nere him in al his
passion-tyme &amp; al &thorn;e hardnes &thorn;at was done til
him: &amp; be awondird &thorn;at so grete a lord
wold thole swilke hardnesse: &amp; falle
&thorn;(ou) doune to &thorn;e erth, as gilti of his
deade, &amp; thank him of &thorn;e woundes &thorn;at
he for &thorn;e tholid / &amp; haue him eauer in
mynde.  Thinke noght of alle &thorn;is
togeder at ane tyme / as &thorn;ai stand in
ordre, for kolynge of deuocion: bot
n(ow) on ane / now on ane o&thorn;er / as
&thorn;ou felis &thorn;at god &thorn;e steris / thorugh
his dere g(race). // &THORN;us mani woundes
suffird god for man kynde: ffyue
thousa(nd) &amp; foure hundreth &amp; sexti &amp; fiftene.
And if &thorn;ou sai ilk dai of &thorn;e (&yogh;)ere
fiftene: &thorn;ou sal sai als many pater nostres
in &thorn;e hale &yogh;ere.
</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="293"><HEAD>An Epistle on Salvation by Love of the Name of Jesus</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="MS">Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD>
<P>Wit thou wele dere ffrende, &thorn;at &thorn;of &thorn;ou had neuer done syne with thi bodi,
dedly ne venyall, bot anely this &thorn;at es called Orygynall for it es &thorn;e firste syne,
and &thorn;at es &thorn;e lossyng of thy ryghtwysnes whilke &thorn;ou was mad in: suld thou neuer
hafe bene safe if oure lord Ihesu Criste by his passione hade noghte delyuerde the
and restorede &thorn;e agayne.  And &thorn;ou sall wit &thorn;at &thorn;ou, be &thorn;ou neuer so mekill a
wreche, hafe &thorn;ou donne neuer so mekill syne: forsake thi-selfe and all thi werkes
gude &amp; ill, cry mercy and aske anely saluacyone by &thorn;e vertu of his precyouse
passyone mekly and tristely, and with-owttene dowte &thorn;ou sall haf it and fra this
orygynall syne and all o&thorn;er &thorn;ou sall be safe.  &YOGH;a and &thorn;ou sall be safe as ane
ankir incluse, and noghte anely &thorn;ou bot all cristene mene &amp; wymene &thorn;at trowes
appone his passione and mekes &thorn;am-selfe, knawande &thorn;aire wrechidnes, askand
mercy and forgyfnes and &thorn;e fruyte of his precyouse passione, anely lawand
selfe to &thorn;e Sacramentes of haly kyrke, &thorn;of it be swa &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe bene cumbyrde
in syne &amp; with syne all &thorn;aire lyfe-tyme, and neuer had felyng of gastely sauour
or swetnes or gastely knawynge of godde, &thorn;ay sall in this faith and in &thorn;air gud
will be safe by &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e precyouse passione of oure lorde Ihesu Criste,
and com to &thorn;e blysse of heuene. / See here &thorn;e Endles mercy of owre lorde, how
lawe he fallis to &thorn;e &amp; to me and to all synfull caytyfs.  Aske mercy and hafe
it; thus said &thorn;e prophete in &thorn;e persone of oure lorde: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnis enym quicunque inuocauerit nomen domini saluus erit:</FOREIGN> &laquo;Ilk mane, what &thorn;at he be, &thorn;at in-calles &thorn;e name of godde&raquo;, &thorn;at es to say askes saluacione by Ihesu and by his passione, &laquo;he sall be safe&raquo;.  Bot &thorn;is curtasye of oure lorde sum mene takes and erre safede &thorn;erby, and sum in traiste of his mercy and his curtasye lyffes still in &thorn;air synnes &amp; wenys for to hafe it when &thorn;am lyst, and &thorn;an may &thorn;ay noghte, ffor &thorn;ay ere takyne or &thorn;ay wit, and swa &thorn;ay dampne &thorn;ame-selfe. / Bot now sayse &thorn;ou if &thorn;is be sothe, &thorn;ou wondirs gretly &laquo;for &thorn;at I fynde wretyne in sum haly mens saghes. Sum sayse, as I vndirstande, &thorn;at he &thorn;at cane noghte lufe &thorn;is blyssed name Ihesu ne fynd ne fele in it gastely Ioye and delitabilite with wondirfull swetnes in &thorn;is lyfe here, ffra &thorn;e souerayne Ioy and gastely swetnes in &thorn;e blysse of heuene he sall be aliene and neuer sall he come &thorn;ar-to.  Sothely &thorn;ise wordes when I here thayme or redis &thorn;ame stonyes me and makis me gretly ferde: ffor I hope, as &thorn;ou sayse, &thorn;at many by &thorn;e mercy of godde sall be safe be kepyng of his commandemente&yogh;
and by verray repentance of &thorn;aire euyll lyfe be-fore done, &thorn;e wylke felid neuer
gastely swetnes ne inly sauour in &thorn;e name of Ihesu or in &thorn;e lufe of Ihesu.  And
for-thi I meruell me &thorn;e more &thorn;at &thorn;ay say the contrarye here-to as it semys&raquo;.  Als
vn-to &thorn;is, I may say as me thynke, that theire saynge if it be wele vndirstandene
es sothe, ne it es noghte contrarye to &thorn;at that I hafe said.  For &thorn;is name Ihesu
es noghte ells for to say one ynglische bot &laquo;heler&raquo; or &laquo;hele&raquo;.  Nowe euer-ilk mane &thorn;at lyffis in &thorn;is wrechid lyfe es gastely seke, ffor &thorn;are es na mane &thorn;at lyffis with-owttene syne whilke es gastely seknes, as sayn Ihon&macr; sayse of hym-selfe and
o&thorn;er perfite mene thus: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Si dixerimus quia peccatum non habemus ipsi nos seducimus &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> &laquo;If we say &thorn;at we hafe na syne, we begile oure-selfe and sothefastnes es
noghte in vs&raquo;; and for-&thorn;i he may neuer fele ne come to &thorn;e Ioyes of heuene,


<PB N="294">

vn-to he first be made hale of &thorn;is gostely seknes.  Bot &thorn;is gastely [hele] may na
mane haf &thorn;at hase vse of resone, bot if he desire it, and lufe it, and hafe delite &thorn;ar-in
in als mekill als he hopis for to get it.  Now &thorn;e name of Ihesu es noghte elles
bot &thorn;is gastely hele.  Whare-fore it es sothe &thorn;at &thorn;ay say, &thorn;at &thorn;ar may na mane
be safe bot if he lufe &amp; lyke in &thorn;e name of Ihesu, ffor &thorn;ar may na mane be
gastely hale bot if he lufe and desire gastely hele.  For ryght als, [if] a mane ware
bodily seke &thorn;er ware nane erthely thyng sa dere ne so nedfull to hyme ne so
mekill suld be desyrid of hyme, als bodily hele&mdash;ffor &thorn;ofe &thorn;ou wald gyff hyme
all &thorn;e reches and &thorn;e wirchips of &thorn;is werlde and noghte make hym hale if &thorn;at
&thorn;ou myghte, &thorn;ou plesid hym noghte&mdash;righte so it es to a mane &thorn;at es seke
gastely and felis &thorn;e payne of gastely seknes; nathyng es so dere, so nedfull, ne
so mekill desired of hyme als his gastely hele, and &thorn;at es Ihesu, withowttene whilke
all &thorn;e Ioyes of heuene may noghte lyke hyme.  And this es &thorn;e skill, as I hope,
whi oure lorde whene he tuke mankynde for oure saluacyone, he walde noghte be
called by na name betakenande his endles beyng, or his myghte, or his wysdome,
or his ryghtwysnes, bot anely by &thorn;at that was cause of his commyng, and &thorn;at
was saluacyone of mans saule whilke saluacione was maste dere and maste
nedfull to mane, and &thorn;is saluacyone betakens &thorn;is name Ihesu.  &THORN;an bi this it semes
&thorn;at &thorn;er may na mane be safe bot if he lufe Ihesu, ffor &thorn;er may na mane be safe
bot if he lufe saluacyone, whilke lufe he may hafe &thorn;at lyfes and dyes in &thorn;e
laweste degre of charite.  Also I may say one a no&thorn;er wyse &thorn;at he &thorn;at cane
noghte lufe &thorn;is blessede name Ihesu with gastely myrthe, ne enjoye in it with
heuenly melodye here, he sall neuer hafe ne fele in &thorn;e blisse of heuene &thorn;at
fulhede of souerayne Ioye, &thorn;e whilke he &thorn;at myghte in &thorn;is lyfe by habondance
of perfite charite enioye in Ihesu sall hafe &amp; fele, and so may &thorn;aire saynge be
vndirstandene.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les he sall be safe and hafe full mede in &thorn;e syghte of
godd, all-if he be in &thorn;is lyfe in the laweste degre of charite by kepyng of goddes
commandementes.  For Criste sase in the gospelle: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In domo patris mei mansiones multe sunt:</FOREIGN> &laquo;In my fadir house erre many sere dwellynges&raquo;.  Sum are for perfite
saules &thorn;e whilke in this lyfe ware fulfillede of grace of &thorn;e haly gaste and sang
louyn&macr;gs to godd in contemplacione of hym with wondirfull swetnes and heuen&macr;ly
savour: &THORN;ise saules, for &thorn;ay hade maste charite, sall haue hegheste mede in &thorn;e
blysse of heuene, ffor &thorn;ise ere callid goddes derlyngs.  Othir saules &thorn;at ere in
&thorn;is lyfe inperfite and erre noghte disposed to contemplacyone of godde, ne had
noghte &thorn;e fulhede of charite as apostells or martirs had in &thorn;e begynnyng of
haly kirke: &thorn;ay sall hafe &thorn;e lawere mede in &thorn;e blyse of heuene, ffor &thorn;ise er
callede goddis frendis.  &THORN;us callis oure lorde chosene saules in haly writt, sayand
thus: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Comedite amici, et inebriamini crissimi:</FOREIGN> &laquo;Mi frendes etc &yogh;e, and my derlynges be &yogh;e drunkyne&raquo;.  As if oure lorde said one &thorn;is wyse: &laquo;&YOGH;e &thorn;at er my frendis for &yogh;e keped my commandmente&yogh; and sett my lufe be-fore &thorn;e lufe of &thorn;e werlde, and lufed me more &thorn;an any o&thorn;er erthely thynge, &yogh;e sall be feedd with gastely fude of &thorn;e brede of lyfe.  Bot &yogh;e &thorn;at er my derlynges and noghte anely kepid my commandementis bot also of &yogh;oure awene fre will fulfillede my consailles, and ouer &thorn;at &yogh;e luffed me anely enterely with all &thorn;e myghtes of &yogh;oure saule, and brynnede in my lufe with gastely delyte as did pryncypally &thorn;e apostills &amp; martirs and all o&thorn;er &thorn;at myghte come by grace to &thorn;e gyfte of perfeccione, &yogh;e sall be


<PB N="295">

made drunkene with &thorn;e freeste wyne in my celer, &thorn;at es &thorn;e souereyne Ioye of
lufe in &thorn;e blysse of heuene&raquo;.&mdash;To the whilke blise he brynge vs &thorn;at boghte vs
with his precyouse passione, Ihesu Criste, goddes sone of heuene.  Amen.
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text"><HEAD>On Prayer</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="MS">Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD><NOTE>Note that this item is independent of the portion of <TITLE>&THORN;e Holy Boke Gratia Dei</TITLE> known as "Prayer," which appears above.</NOTE><MILESTONE UNIT="folio 233">
<P>Prayng es a gracyous gyfte of owre lorde godd tyll ylk mane diuysed as he
vouches-safe, till sum mare delyttabyll, till sum lesse, as all o&thorn;er gudnes &amp; gyftes
ere gyffene till sere mene apone sere wyse as &thorn;e haly gaste will, and principally
aftire &thorn;at ilk a mane besyes hyme to gett goddes grace.  The vertu and &thorn;e
swetnes of &thorn;e Pater noster, and of the psalmes of &thorn;e sautyr, and of all o&thorn;er
prayers &thorn;at er inwardly prayede with lufe and mekenes and clennes of herte,
may na tung tell, hert thynke ne eghe see.  Thorowe &thorn;e souerayne wysdome
and &thorn;e grete grace of &thorn;e gloryouse gyfte of oure lorde Ihesu Criste goddis sone
of heuene, if &thorn;ay be sadly soungene or saide in a clene herte with lufe and
mekenes and lufely drede in &thorn;e louynge of godd, thay bryng in till vs bryghte
brynnande by-haldynge mengede with myrthe, and selcouthe schynynge fra &thorn;e
heghenes of heuene with gleteryng and glemyng, with myrthe and melodye, that
herte vnclosande &thorn;at lufes Ihesu Criste goddes sonne of heuene with-owttene
forgetyng, whare &thorn;e haly gaste dwelles balefull bandes brystande with &thorn;e
brynnynge of lufe &;are &thorn;e heghe name of Ihesu duelles euer in mynde. / Prayere es
a precyous prikkynge in a clene hert makand men myghtty firste fra &thorn;e erthe to
&thorn;e ayere to be-halde with a meke herte heghand one heghte, clymbande to &thorn;e
clouddes all planetes perchande what so it hittes, ffor&thorn;er-mare foundande ferly
to fele and meruelle to beholde; euer &thorn;e lufe of godd mekely desyrande, preuely
puttande his grace &thorn;are hym lykes and namely to &thorn;ame &thorn;at abills &thorn;ame &thorn;are-to
with &thorn;e helpe of godd in all &thorn;at &thorn;ay may, one &thorn;e same wyse for &thorn;ay sulde
preuely with the desire of theire hertes lufe hyme agayne.  Many meke hertes
perchance trewely lufande godd in all &thorn;at &thorn;ay canne here and speke of &thorn;is lufe,
walde fayne hafe sum sauour or swettnes of it: &thorn;e whilke for &thorn;aire gud wyll
and &thorn;aire grete desyre hase it and wate noghte, and mekill thanke of godd fo[r]
&thorn;air gud will; and peraunter and &thorn;ay wyste &thorn;at &thorn;ay hadd it, &thorn;ay suld noghte
bere it so dredefully as if &thorn;ay wyste noghte.  And &thorn;arfore he &thorn;at knawes oure
wyllis and oure hertes, hydes it fra vs for we suld lyffe in drede, and halde vs
wele payedde of what so he sente vs. and faste folowe hyme.  And ay &thorn;e faster
&thorn;at mene folowes, the mare sall mene fele of &thorn;e lufe of godd.  Bot by lange
tyme and grete traueile trewe lufe behuse be getyne, and namely of thayme &thorn;at
gretly hase trispaste and one lange tyme, &thorn;at felis &thorn;aire concyence vnclere for
are-done dedis, lesse or mare whe&thorn;er so &thorn;ay bee.  And sene it may noghte
clerely be getyne with-owttene lange traueile, ne goghte be felide with-owttene
clennes of herte, whi sulde we &thorn;an &thorn;at ere synfull and vnclene in herte, and
littill hase traueilde, wrangwisely grefe vs or gruche with godd or with oure
awene selfe, ffor we hafe it noghte?  Wate we noghte wele &thorn;at godd es
sothefaste and trewe?  How dare we &thorn;ane be wrathe for we hafe noghte &thorn;at we ere
noghte &yogh;it worthi to hafe by &thorn;e sothefastenes of godd and by oure awene defautes?


<PB N="296">

What sall we &thorn;ane do?  Sall we &thorn;ar-fore cesse and waxe slawe, and turne vs to
syne, and latte oure hertes dye fra all gude werkes?  Nay, godd forbede, ffor
&thorn;ane are we dampnabill; bot with &thorn;e grace of godd gyffe we vs styffely to gude
werkes: and we sall wounderfully fynde &thorn;at we couthe noghte seke, and
grayceousely se &thorn;at we neuer herde say ne neuer knewe.  For vs by-hufes nedelynges
besyly traueile if we desyre for to fynd lufe; and thayme nedis maste for to traueile
that maste hase trispaste.  Bot comonly thay that leste hase trispaste, erre leueste
to trauelle, and &thorn;ay &thorn;at maste hase trispaste thay are vmwhile latheste to traueille;
and godd gyffe thayme &thorn;at liste noghte to traueile, or may noghte traueille, or hase
littill will for to traueille, couthe trowe &thorn;ame als gude &thorn;at lufes for to traueille,
als &thorn;ay &thorn;at lufes for to trauelle haldes &thorn;ame and trowes &thorn;at will noghte trauelle
or may noghte traueille!  For thay &thorn;at lufes to trauelle haldes and trowes &thorn;ame
&thorn;at will noghte or may noghte, gude and mekill better &thorn;ane &thorn;aym-selfe, ffor &thorn;aire
awene selfe inwith thayre herte seett &thorn;ay att noghte, and at lesse, if &thorn;ay myghte.
For all-if lufe make &thorn;ame to trauelle and &thorn;ai[n]e ilke daye trispas, &yogh;itt thynke &thorn;ay
&thorn;at all o&thorn;er lufes mare and trauels mare and trespas lesse &thorn;an &thorn;ay, and &thorn;at
makes &thorn;ame to thynke &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe nede to hye faste aftyre, &thorn;at &thorn;ay myghte at
the laste, if godd vouche-safe, hafe happe and grace to come with &thorn;e hyndireste.
And thus are thay worthy to ga with &thorn;e forthirmaste.  Bot vmwhile thorowe
grace of oure lorde godde it es geuene sonere to thayme &thorn;at hase trespaste apone
schorte tyme, &thorn;ane it es sone gyuene to &thorn;ame &thorn;at ere clene with-owttene dedly
syne and with-owttene preue byttynge of conscience, &thorn;at ay ere besy to doo
goddes will after &thorn;aire myghte, that euer hase bene sumdele thynkande one godd
with prayere and penance and sekynge of lufe.  Bot it es gyuene soneste to &thorn;ase
namely &thorn;at hase noghte loste &thorn;at thynge &thorn;at es maste lykynge to godde by &thorn;e
way of lyffynge, &thorn;at es &thorn;e floure of &thorn;aire &yogh;outhe, if it be festened in all o&thorn;er
vertus in-with &thorn;e saule, and pryncypally groundid in schamefullness and mekenes.
Thay hafe ay hadde &thorn;e luf of godd encressande inwith &thorn;e herte sene &thorn;ay ware
borne, &thorn;at neuer felid &thorn;aire hertes ne &thorn;aire willis fully assenttande to losse &thorn;e
clennes of &thorn;aire &yogh;outhe whene &thorn;ay ware tempede; and &thorn;ay littill knewe how &thorn;ay
sulde lufe godd what for &thorn;e lufe and whafe for &thorn;e drede of godd and for &thorn;e
drede of payne &thorn;at es ordaynede for syne, and what for &thorn;e lufe of godd and
for &thorn;e lufe of &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at es ordaynede in heuene for all &thorn;ase &thorn;at liffes clene.
Bot sothely &thorn;at hert &thorn;at walde fayne fele preuete of lufe, it nedid ay to be
clensede with many salte teres, ffastynge and wakynge, praynge and thynkynge,
sorowynge and syghynge, and with o&thorn;er smale poyntes &thorn;at pertenys to penance,
&thorn;at nankynne manere of ill be lefte in oure hertes, owte-tane ilke-day fallynge
as oure freelte askes&mdash;ffor if any saye &thorn;at &thorn;ay fall noghte, &thorn;ay dyssayue
thaymeselfe.  For &thorn;ay &thorn;at hase any tendirnes or drede in &thorn;e lufe of godde, &thorn;ay fall
for a worde &thorn;at es vaynely spokene owte of &thorn;e louynge of godd, bot if &thorn;ay be
mare warre in &thorn;aire spekyng, for hurtynge of &thorn;aire hertes and of &thorn;er conscience;
all-if it seme littill ill, it duse grete dere.  It heuyes a clene herte ay till it be
brente oute and with trewe contricione waschene awaye, and with the kyndillynge


<PB N="297">

of lufe clensede and hyghtenede.  Bot &thorn;ay &thorn;at walde fayne lufe godd one this
wyse, thayme by-houede hertly beseke and besely pray with-owttene any besynes
in werldes wele bot at nede askes, and at &thorn;ay make noghte nede ouer-large;
and seett thaire mynde fully in godd with-owttene cessynge, whare-so &thorn;ay walke
or dwelle or speke, slomerande and slepande, in all &thorn;at &thorn;ay may with &thorn;e mekenes
and &thorn;e clennes of &thorn;aire hertes by-fore godd cryande, and vmwhill, if godd will,
of the lufe of godd dremande, and euer-mare of &thorn;e Ioye of heuene thynkande;
wakande and wynkande, knelande and standande, sittande and gangande, lyggand
and ryssande, ettande and drynkande and all o&thorn;er werkes wyrkande, nyghte and
day, euyne and morne, midill-tyme and all tyme in trewe lufe lastande, houre
ne halfe wastande, bot euer-mare freely in lufe doune fallande to &thorn;e ffadir of
heuene preuely prayande, to &thorn;e pereles prynce Ihesu goddis sone, ant till &thorn;e haly
gaste hertly besekande; and before &thorn;e haly trinyte tremble and qwake for Ioy
and myrthe and lufely drede one godd to be-halde.  Owte of whilke thre gloryous
persouns and a godd commes all grace fra heuene vn-till erthe thorowe a meke
herte besyly prayande, all worldly thynges for &thorn;e lufe of godd vtterly forsakande,
and all werldly solace and werldly delyte vtterly forgetande, and &thorn;aire awene
selfe vndir &thorn;aire awene futt styffely tredande.  And thus may all liffe as es before
saide &thorn;at hase hade gude wille for to lufe godd and for to hate syne fra &thorn;aire
begynnynge, and whate tyme so &thorn;ay cume &thorn;ay mekely will amende thayme.  Allas
for schame, whate may we say if we &thorn;at ere synfull and foule halde oure-selfe
gude, whene &thorn;ay &thorn;at ere maste clene and maste lufes godde haldes &thorn;ame-selfe
maste synfull and maste vile and maste vne-worthi?  Bot wha-sa hase na will
for to liffe thus and myghte come &thorn;artill, thay hafe full grete matire for to make
sorowe, to purchase &thorn;ame &thorn;is will.  For &thorn;e werlde es wyde enoghe and gude
enoghe to wyne heuene in, gete at gete maye; and it es riche enoghe and lykande
enoghe and synfull enoghe for to wyne helle with, flee at flee maye. / Prayere
frely floresches oure saules with flores of swetnes, with &thorn;e fairenes &amp; &thorn;e swetenes
of &thorn;e fruyte in to meke hertes fallande, &thorn;at es in all meke vertus freely to
behalde &thorn;e faire face of godd, with &thorn;e bemys of his bryghtnes all clene conscience
and meke hertes lightenande.  Bot noghte perchaunce as sum thynkes inwith
&thorn;aire hertes whene &thorn;ay hafe lefte grete synn&macr;s and a party begynnes to turne
&thorn;ame to vetus and punesche&yogh; &thorn;aire bodyes with many-faulde penance apone sere
wyse, &thorn;at &thorn;ay cane hafe contemplacione of Ioy in-with schorte tyme.  The
whilke if it so be, wele mot &thorn;ay brouke it.  Bot for &thorn;e drede of godde and
hele of &thorn;aire saules it ware gret nede trewly to hafe in-with &thorn;aire hertes how
&thorn;ay hafe commene &thorn;are-to, in whate tyme, in whate trauelle and in whate lyfe:
and if &thorn;e begynnynge be gude thurghe &thorn;e grace of godd, halde one hertly and
godd will make it better; and if [it] be amys, it es gude to amende it or elles
it will be harde for to gyffe accounte of all preuee defautes &thorn;are &thorn;e sothe mone
noghte be laynede, one &thorn;e dredfull daye of dome.  And wha-sa felis &thorn;am-selfe
&thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe gretly trespaste, and thynkes &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe in-with schorte tyme
comforthe and lyghtnes with-owttene lang trauelle, it may be lykynge &amp; myrthe
&thorn;at makes &thorn;aire hertes merie for &thorn;ay hafe lefte syne and thynkes &thorn;ame Ioyefull
and lyghte for &thorn;ai ere clene, bot if &thorn;e sorowe of thaire hertes be &thorn;e mare tendir,


<PB N="298">

so &thorn;at it hafe clensede &thorn;aym of all alde synn&macr;s.  &THORN;e whilke lyghtnes es gude so
&thorn;ay passe noghte to ferre, and a gret be-gynnynge of gudnes mekill grace for to
purchase if &thorn;ay laste furthe in &thorn;aire gud trauaile: bot noghte &yogh;it contemplacyone
of Ioy ne noghte &yogh;it clere syghte of saule and of conscience if &thorn;ay so wene, as
&thorn;ay sall eftir verraylye knawe inwith &thorn;aire hertis if &thorn;ay be-seke godd of grace
and besy &thorn;ayme to laste furthe in goddes lufe; or elles erre &thorn;ay fra godd &amp; fra all
gudnes, sa &thorn;at if &thorn;ay turne agayne to vanyte of &thorn;e werlde, .... as it may sothely
be herde by &thorn;e herte whene &thorn;e tunge spekes of &thorn;ayme &thorn;at lufes syne, and hates
goddes worde.  Bot take &thorn;is worde as it es saide, ffor he es werre &thorn;an wode &thorn;at
demes any manes herte &thorn;e whilke [he] one na wyse knawe[s].  For na manes witt
may trewly knawe, ne awe noghte to knawe as by demynge, a no&thorn;er mans herte;
and he &thorn;at es in his witt, and with his witt passis his witt goddis preuete to
knawe and the hedills of manes herte &thorn;e whilke es noghte leuefull bot dredfull
to knawe, it es bot wodenes and owte of all gudnes&mdash;ffor it falles vnto godde
and noghte vn-to mane for to deme mans herte, bot ilke mane his awene.  For
trewe riste in saule may na mane fynde till &thorn;ay kane lyffe and deme neuer
na mane, and till &thorn;ay cane trewly in-with &thorn;aire hertis thurghe goddes grace halde
all o&thorn;er better &thorn;ane &thorn;ame-selfe, and namely all &thorn;ase &thorn;at gyffes &thorn;ame to gude.
And if &thorn;ay halde thayme-selfe maste vnworthi of all, and &thorn;erwith falles noghte
in to ouer-mekill drede ne in till dispaire, &thorn;ay hafe bot the mare grace.  Bot
&thorn;us may nane meke &thorn;ame with-owttene gret grace, thynkande all o&thorn;er better
&thorn;ane &thorn;aym-selfe.  Ilke mane for &thorn;ame-selfe luke &thorn;aire awene conscience how
&thorn;at &thorn;ay erre, and deme &thorn;ayre awene selfe: ffor sothely &thorn;ay dare deme neuer na
mane &thorn;at are trewe demers of &thorn;aire awene selfe.  Bot if [it] be saide of any, it
es saide of &thorn;ase &thorn;at bakbyttes haly writte and turnes it bakwarde, or ells &thorn;ay
degrade it makand [it] mare tendire &thorn;an it es, accordande to thayme; whas hertes
erre so harde, and so ferre &thorn;are-fra, &thorn;aire conscience witnesande, &thorn;at &thorn;ay may
vnnethes habyde to here it be spokene.  Bot ane es, by mekenes a mane selfe
trewly to thynke hym ferre fra it, and a no&thorn;er es, styll or lowde to thynke &thorn;at
it may noghte be so, or ells to agayne-say it, and &thorn;at es maste dredfull.  Bot
whare &thorn;ay sulde lawly knawe &thorn;aire trespas and mekely amende &thorn;ame, thay caste
wafull wordes agaynes goddes wordes for to defende &thorn;ame and to mayntene styfly
&thorn;at es noghte gude, and sayse wrange opynly and ruydely with-owttene drede.
Thay agayne-say godde and sayse &thorn;at<MILESTONE N="236" UNIT="folio"> &laquo;godd saide neuer soo, godd walde neuer say so; It may noghte be so: wha sulde be safe if it ware so?&raquo;  See how &thorn;e fende pykes owte &thorn;e trouthe of cristyne menes hertes; ffor ou&thorn;er he makes &thorn;ame to trowe &thorn;at haly writt es noghte trewe, or elles &thorn;at na mane sall be safe: and &thorn;ese ere no&thorn;er trewe.  If thay thoghte it preuely, it ware na heuenes ne na charge bot anely for &thorn;ame-selfe: Bot whene &thorn;ay say it appertely, &thorn;ane charge &thorn;ay o&thorn;er mene gretely, and namely tendir hertes to make sorowe for thayme.
And &thorn;us walde &thorn;ay make godd, &amp; &thorn;ay moghte, to hald with syne, and agayne
godd &thorn;aire ill to excuse&mdash;ffor &thorn;ai ere noghte of will for to leue it.  For, dredeles,
and &thorn;ay ware of will for to leue &amp; ceesse of &thorn;aire synnes, thay walde noghte
say &thorn;us; and if &thorn;ay hade neuer so lyttill of &thorn;e drede of godd, thay durste noghte
speke thus.  &laquo;Bot wha sa duse &thorn;us?&raquo;  Peraunter fone dus &thorn;us or spekes &thorn;us.  Bot


<PB N="299">

wha so dus &thorn;us&mdash;&thorn;ame nedis no no&thorn;er wittnes bot thaire awene selfe&mdash;amend
&thorn;ame whaa so will, or &thorn;at day comme &thorn;at heuene and erthe and helle mone
dampne vs for oure ill dedis, and all gud mene sall be gloryfyede for &thorn;aire gud
dedis. / Thurghe &thorn;e vertu of prayere beande hate in oure hertes with &thorn;e brynnynge
of lufe, Ihesu Criste sendis haly angels of heuene in helpynge of vs in all
meschefes, myrthe for to make and &thorn;e mare glade for to be whene mescheues
fallis, and mekely to thole dispysynge and skorne, hatredene, ill will, angere and
noy, whilke mekely to thole makes &thorn;e herte lyghte of &thorn;ame &thorn;at lufes godde.
/ Prayere purifie&yogh; &thorn;ase &thorn;at hase vsede syne and &thorn;e vanite of &thorn;e werlde.  It slaaes
&thorn;aire alde synns, and fulfillis &thorn;ame of grace &thorn;at hadd loste &thorn;e lufe of godd
thurghe &thorn;aire alde trispase, and makes &thorn;ame Ioyfull and lyghte for to serue godd
&thorn;at with &thorn;aire ill dedis gretly hadd hym greuede.  All &thorn;at euer may &thorn;ay doo for
&thorn;e lufe of godd, &thorn;aym thynke it ouer-lyttill and countes it at noghte, so full es
&thorn;aire will sette for to plese godd: &thorn;are &thorn;e lufers of &thorn;e werlde, if &thorn;ay oughte
doo for &thorn;e lufe of godd and hele of thaire saules, thaym thynke &thorn;ame mare
worthi to hafe thanke of godd for a gud dede, than the trewe lufers of godd
thynke &thorn;ame worthi for all &thorn;e gud dedis and &thorn;e trewe seruyce of all &thorn;aire
lyfe-tyme.  Bot &thorn;e lufers of &thorn;e werlde &amp; of &thorn;aire awene luste gettis neuer &thorn;e mare bot &thorn;e lesse for swilke vayne styrrynge, ne &thorn;e lufers of godd gettis neuer &thorn;e lesse
bot &thorn;e mare for &thorn;aire meke thynkynge. / Prayere es euer-mare plesande to godd
with lowe bryghtyly brennande in a meke herte, with-owttene smokynge smelland
full swetly, in all meke myndis haldand &thorn;e lufe of oure lorde godd hate in oure
hertes. / Prayere puttes at &thorn;e fende and haldes hyme obake and makes hyme to
faile and flee as a fonne standande oferre, noghte darrand come nere, hafande
grete ferly how &thorn;at it faris &thorn;at his myghte es noghte bot turnede to myste; ffor
schame of hym-selfe he wynnes hym awaye als a cowerde clene ouer-comene.
Bot powere in herte es nane agaynes &thorn;e fende with-owttene goddes grace. / Prayere
slakes and slaas and stiffly brynges vndir &thorn;e luste and &thorn;e lykynge of &thorn;e freele
flesche, and makes &thorn;e herte Ioyefull and bryghte with brynnynge of lufe in &thorn;e
loueuyng of godd heuene at by-halde. / Prayere mekis oure saules and makes oure
hertis lyghte, in &thorn;e lufe of godd lykand to lyffe, with gastely wyrkynge for to
plese godde, and gladly to dye bathe with lufe &amp; with drede whene godd
vouchessafe; mekill myrthe and solace in clene hertis festenande, with gastely fyre of
brynnande lufe makand freele flesche downe for to falle, fra alkyn lustes
wondirfully losand his myghte&mdash;ffor flesche es noghte myghtty &thorn;is lufe to abyde; and
whils &thorn;e herte lufes &thorn;e luste and &thorn;e lykynge of &thorn;e flesche, it may neuer wit what
&thorn;is lufe menes.  For as &thorn;e herte &thorn;at es lufely festenede in &thorn;e lufe of godd
forgettis all &thorn;e luste and lykynge of &thorn;e flesche, righte swa &thorn;at herte &thorn;at es festenede
in luste and lykynge of &thorn;e flesche ffor-getes all lufe and lykynge &thorn;at it sulde
hafe in godd. / Prayere opyns oure wittis and &thorn;e eghe of oure hertes one heghte
to be-halde with &thorn;e leue &amp; &thorn;e grace and &thorn;e gyfte of godde, all-if we be vnkynde,
to &thorn;e kyngdome of heuene. / Prayere wesches of vs all wykkid werkes and all
sare synns; apone all wyse it dystruyes syne and puttes it vndire, and brynnes
insundir &thorn;e bannde of all bale with a ferly fyre festened in lufe snythand oure
hertes if we will hate syne, with a ferly fyre flyande fra heuene as fyre owtt of
flyntte, ferly to be-halde, with bryghte schynynge lyghtenande &thorn;ase hertes &thorn;at


<PB N="300">

stiffely standis in &thorn;e lufe and in &thorn;e louynge of godde; whilke es a brennande
lufe lyghtenede with myrthe in a meke herte.  Wha so lykes to lufe godd
with-owttene desire of werldly vanyte and with-owttene mengynge of worldely myrthe
&amp; werldly solace, and wha so hade grace for to lufe godd soo, &thorn;ay myghte sytt
nerehande it and hafe of it na dere; bot noghte in it, ne noghte melle &thorn;ame
with it, with-owttene gret sorowe. /  Prayere prynttede and closede in a laghe
herte with &thorn;e lufely drede of godd and with mylde mekenes, euer-mare dredande
for to greue godd and euer-mare desyrande for to lufe godd, reues fra &thorn;e &yogh;onge
lufers of godd lykynge and luste &thorn;at &thorn;e alde lufers of godd before hase loste,
and fulfilles &thorn;ame of Ioye and makes &thorn;ame to lyffe angells lyfe, &thorn;at es to lufe
godd with-owttene forgetynge, and euer-mare to sette thaym saddly in his syghte,
with ay-lastande lufe and clennes of herte one hyme to behalde. /  Prayere gyfes
endelesse comforthe &amp; Ioye till &thorn;ame &thorn;at hase trispaste and gretly greuede godd,
&thorn;at ere ofte-sythis sygheand and sorowande &thorn;aire synn&macr;s; &thorn;at ere of trewe will
to trespase no more, bot besily to thynke one ay-lastande lyfe in &thorn;e louynge of
godd.  All-if &thorn;ay hafe will and grace for to serue godd, &yogh;itt may &thorn;ay make bot
lyttill owtwarde myrthe
</P>
