<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">(O)leum effusum nomen tuum:</FOREIGN> &THORN;at es on Inglyssch: &laquo;Oyle oute-&yogh;ettyd es
&thorn;i name&raquo;.  &THORN;e name of Ihesu comes in
to &thorn;o worlde &amp; als sone it smelles
oyle out-&yogh;ettyd.  Oyle, &thorn;at es taken for
ay-lastande saluacion is hopyd.  Sothle
Ihesu es als mykel to be-mene os
sauyour or hel[e]ful.  &THORN;arfor qwat menys
it &laquo;Oyle out-&yogh;ettyd es &thorn;i name&raquo; bot
&laquo;Ihesu es &thorn;i name?&raquo; &thorn;is name es oyle
out-&yogh;ettyd, for Ihesu &thorn;e worde of god
has takun mans kynde.  Ihesu, &thorn;ou
fulfylles in warke &thorn;at at &thorn;ou art cald in
name: sothly man sauys &thorn;ou qwam we
call saueour: &THORN;erfor Ihesu es &thorn;i name.
/ A, &thorn;at wondurful name, A, &thorn;at
delytabul name!  &THORN;is is &thorn;o name &thorn;at es
aboue al names, name al&thorn;er-heghest,
with-outen qwilk na man hopes hele.
&THORN;is name es swete &amp; Ioyful, gyfand
sothfast comforth vnto mans hert.  Sothle
&thorn;o name of Ihesu es in my mynde
Ioyus sang, in my nere heuenly sounde,
in my mouth hunyful swetnes.
Qwarfor na wondur If I luf &thorn;at name &thorn;e
qwilk gyfs comforth to me in al angwys.
I can noght pray, I can noght haue
mynde, bot sownand &thorn;o name of Ihesu;
I sauour noght Ioy &thorn;at with Ihesu es
noght mengyd.  Qwar-so I be qwar-so
I sit, qwat-so I do, &thorn;o mynd of &thorn;o name
of Ihesu departes noght fra my mynde.
I haue set it as a takenyng opon my


<PB N="187">

hert, als takenyng apon myn arme: ffor
&laquo;luf es strange as dede&raquo;.  Als dede slos
alle, so luf ouercomes alle.  Ay-lastand
luf has ouercomen me, noght for to sla
me, bot for to qwyken me: bot it
has wonded me for it suld leche me,
It has thurgh-fitched my herte &thorn;at
merghlyer it be heled, &amp; now
ouer-commen I fayle.  Vnethes I lyfe for Ioy,
nerehande I dye, for I suffice noght in
&thorn;is febul flesch for to bere so flowand
swetnes of so mykel a mageste.  &THORN;er
skrythes in to my mynde delyciost
swetnes, &amp; ay to it be drounkynd it
falles; &thorn;e flesch may noght of his
vertue noght defayle, ay-qwyles &thorn;o
saule in swylk Ioyes is rauyssched for
to Ioy. / Bot qwen vnto me swilk Ioy
bot for Ihesu &thorn;o name of Ihesu has
taght me for to syng, &amp; has lyghtynd
my mynde with &thorn;o hete of vnmade
light.  &THORN;erfor I sygh &amp; crye: &laquo;Wa sal
schew vnto &thorn;e lufed Ihesu &thorn;at I
languyssch for luf?&raquo;  My flesch has
fayled &amp; My herte has meltyd in luf,
&yogh;ernand Ihesu.  Alle &thorn;o hert festynde in
&thorn;o &yogh;ernyng of Ihesu is turnyd in to
fyre of luf, &amp; with &thorn;o swetnes of &thorn;o
godhede fullyly it is fylde.  &THORN;erfor, a
gode Ihesu, haue mercy of &thorn;is wretch,
schew &thorn;e to &thorn;o languysshande, be leche
vnto &thorn;is wonded.  If &thorn;ou come I ame
hale: I fele me noght seke bot
languysshande for &thorn;i luf.  Late my saule
tak and, sekand Ihesu qwam it lufs, with
qwas luf it es takun, qwam anele it
coueytis.  Sothle &thorn;e mynd touched
with &thorn;e souerayn swetnes, andes for
to wax hate in &thorn;e luf of &thorn;o maker,
I-qwiles it enforces for to halde bysile
in it &thorn;e swettest name of Ihesu.  Sothly
fra thethyn ryses a grete luf, &amp; qwat
thyng &thorn;at it trewle touches, it rauysches
it ottyrle to it.  It inflawmes &thorn;e affection,
&amp; byndes &thorn;o thoght, &yogh;a, &amp; alle &thorn;e


<PB N="188">

man it drawes to &thorn;e seruys of it. / Sothly,
Ihesu, desiderabul es &thorn;i name, luf-abul
&amp; confortabul.  [Nane so swete sange
may be herd, nane so swete Ioye
may be conceyued], nane so delitabul
solace may be had in mynde.  &THORN;erfor,
qwat so euer &thorn;ou be &thorn;at redys &thorn;e to &thorn;o
luf of god: [if] &thorn;ou wil no&thorn;er be
dissayued ne dyssayue, yf &thorn;ou wil be wyse
&amp; noght vnwyse, yf &thorn;ou wil stand &amp; noght falle, haue in mynde bysele for
to halde &thorn;e name of Ihesu in &thorn;i mynde.
&THORN;in enmy sal falle &amp; &thorn;ou sal stande;
&THORN;in enmy sal be made wayke &amp; &thorn;ou
sal be made strange.  &amp; if &thorn;ou wil do
lele &thorn;is, far fra [drede] &thorn;ou sal be [a]
gloriouse &amp; a lowabul ouercomer. / Seke
&thorn;erfor &thorn;o name of Ihesu, hald it, &amp; forgete it noght.  Sothle na thyng slokuns
sa felle flawmes, destroyes alle ille
thoghtes, puttys out venemus affections,
dose away curious &amp; vayn occupacions
fra vs.  Also &thorn;is name Ihesu lele halden
in mynde, draghes vpe be &thorn;o rotes vices,
settes vertues, insawes charite, [in]-&yogh;ettis
sauour of heuenly thyng, wastes
discorde, reformes pees, gyfs in-lastand
ryst, dose away vtturle greuousnesse of
fleschly desyres, turnys alle erthle thyng
to noy, fylles &thorn;o lufand of gastle Ioy;
so &thorn;at wele it may be sayde: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et gloriabuntur omnes qui diligunt nomen tuum,
quoniam tu benedices iusto,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;Alle sal Ioy &thorn;at lufs &thorn;i name, for
&thorn;ou sal blys &thorn;o ryghtwyse.&raquo;  &THORN;erfor &thorn;e
ryghtwyse has deseruid to be blyssud,
yf &thorn;o name of Ihesu trewle he haue
lufed.  &amp; &thorn;erfor es he called ryghtwyse
for he enforced hym trewle to luf Ihesu. /
&THORN;erfor qwat may defayle vn-to hym &thorn;at
couetys vncessandly for to luf &thorn;e name
of Ihesu?  Sothle he lufs &amp; he &yogh;ernis


<PB N="189">

for to luf, ffor we haue knawen &thorn;at
&thorn;o luf of god standys in swilk maner
&thorn;at in als mykel &thorn;at we mare luf, &thorn;o
mare vs langys for to luf; for qwy it
es sayde: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui me edunt adhuc esuriunt,
&amp; qui me bibunt adhuc siciunt,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;&THORN;ei &thorn;at etys me, &yogh;it hungurs &thorn;am, &amp; &thorn;ei &thorn;at drinkes me &yogh;it thrist &thorn;ei.&raquo;
&THORN;erfor be it-selfe delitabul &amp; couetabul
es &thorn;o name of Ihesu &amp; &thorn;o luf of it.
/ &THORN;erfor Ioy sal not want vnto hym &thorn;at
coueytes bysile for to luf hym &laquo;in qwam
angels &yogh;ernys to behalde&raquo;.  Angels euer
sese &amp; euer &yogh;ern for to se, and so are
&thorn;ei fylled [&thorn;at] &thorn;er fyllyng do noght
away &thorn;er desire, [&amp; so &thorn;ai desire] &thorn;at
&thorn;eir desire do noght away &thorn;eir fyllyng.
&THORN;is es full Ioy, &thorn;is is endyng Ioy,
&thorn;is es glorious Ioy, &thorn;e qwilk [we] fyld
[vses] lastandly with-outen noy, &amp; if we
vise it we sal be fyld euer with-outen
lessyng. / &THORN;erfor, Ihesu, &laquo;all sal Ioy &thorn;at
lufs &thorn;i name&raquo;.  Sothle &thorn;ei sal Ioy now
be in&yogh;ettyng of grace, &amp; in tyme to
cum be syght of Ioy; &amp; &thorn;erfor &thorn;ei sal
Ioy for &thorn;ei luf &thorn;i name.  Sothly warne
&thorn;ei lufd, &thorn;ei myght not Ioy; &amp; &thorn;ei &thorn;at
lufs mare, sal Ioy [mare]: for-qwi Ioy
cummes of luf. / &THORN;erfor he &thorn;at lufs
noght, he sal euermare be with-outen
Ioy.  &THORN;erfor many wretches of &thorn;o world
trowand &thorn;am to Ioy with Cryst, sal
sorow with-outen ende, &amp; &thorn;at for &thorn;ei
lufed noght &thorn;o name of Ihesu.  [&laquo;What so
&yogh;e do, if &yogh;e gif al &thorn;at &yogh;e haf vnto &thorn;e
nedy, bot &yogh;e lufe &thorn;e name of Ihesu],
&yogh;e trauel in vayn&raquo;.  Allanely &thorn;ei may Ioy
en Ihesu &thorn;at lufs hym in &thorn;is lyfe; &amp; &thorn;ei &thorn;at fylles &thorn;am with vices &amp; venomes delites, na drede &thorn;at [ne] &thorn;ei are put out
of Ioy. / Also witte alle &thorn;at &thorn;e name
of Ihesu is heleful, frutful, &amp; glorious.
&THORN;erfor qwo sal haue hele &thorn;at lufs it
noght?  qwa sal bere &thorn;e fruit before
Crist &thorn;at has not &thorn;o floure?  and Ioy


<PB N="190">

sal he noght see &thorn;at Ioyande lufd noght
&thorn;o name of Ihesu.  &laquo;&THORN;o wykkyd sal be
done away, &thorn;at he see noght &thorn;o Ioy
of god&raquo;. / Sothly &thorn;e ryghtwyse sekus &thorn;e
Ioy &amp; &thorn;o lyfe &amp; [&thorn;ei] fynde it in
Ihesu, qwam &thorn;ei lufde.  I &yogh;ede about
[be] couaytys of Ryches &amp; I fand noght
Ihesu.  I ran be &thorn;o wantones of flesch
&amp; I fande noght Ihesu.  I sat in
companyes of wordly myrth &amp; I fand not
Ihesu.  In alle &thorn;ere I soght Ihesu bot
I fand hym noght, ffor he let me
wete be hys grace &thorn;at he ne is
foundone in &thorn;o lande of softly lyfand. /
&THORN;erfor I turned be ano&thorn;er way, &amp; I
ran about be pouert: &amp; I fande Ihesu
pore-borne in &thorn;o worlde, layde in a
cryb, lapped in cla&thorn;es.  I &yogh;ede be
suffryng of scharpenesse: &amp; I fand Ihesu
wery in &thorn;o way, tourment with hungur,
thryst &amp; calde, fyld with reproues &amp; blames.  I sat be myn ane fleande &thorn;e
vanite of &thorn;e worlde &amp; I fande Ihesu
in desert fastand, in &thorn;o mount anele
prayande.  I ran be payne &amp; penance:
&amp; I fande Ihesu bounden, scourged,
gyfen gall to drynke, nayled to &thorn;o
crosse [hyngand in &thorn;e crosse], &amp; dyand in &thorn;o crosse.  &THORN;erfor Ihesu es
noght funden in ryches bot in pouert,
noght in delitesbot in penance, noght in
wantone Ioyng bot [in bitter] gretyng, not
among many bot in alon[n]es. / Sothly
an ill man fyndes noght Ihesu, for &thorn;er
he es he sekes hym noght.  He
enforces hym to seke Ihesu in &thorn;o Ioy
of &thorn;o worlde, qware neuer he sal be
funden. / Sothle &thorn;erfor &thorn;o name of Ihesu
es helpful, &amp; nedus behoues be lufed of
alle couetand saluacion.  He couetys


<PB N="191">

wele hys saluacion &thorn;at kepis bysele in
hym &thorn;e name of Ihesu.  Sothly I haue
no wondur if he temptyd falle &thorn;at
puttis not &thorn;o name of Ihesu in lastand
mynde.  Sykerle may he chese to lyf
anele &thorn;at has chosin &thorn;o name of Ihesu
to hys special; for &thorn;er may ne wykkyd
spirit noy &thorn;er Ihesu es mykel in mynde,
or neuend in mouth.  &THORN;erfor it is to
hald in mynde bysele &thorn;o name of
Ihesu.&mdash; Qwen I had taken my syngulere
purpose &amp; left &thorn;o seculere habit, &amp; I
be-gan mare to serf god &thorn;en man:
it fell on a nyght os I lay in my rest,
in &thorn;o begynnyng of my conuersione,
&thorn;ar appered to me a ful fayre &yogh;ong
woman &thorn;e qwilk I had [sene] before, &amp; sche lufd me noght a litel in gode luf.
&amp; qwen I had behalden hir, &amp; I wondred
qwy scho come so on nyght in &thorn;o
wyldernesse: sodenle with-outen mare
speche scho layde hir be-syde me.  &amp; qwen &thorn;at I felde hir &thorn;are, I dred &thorn;at
scho suld draw me to euel, &amp; sayde I
walde ryse vpe &amp; blysse vs in &thorn;o name
of &thorn;o haly trinite.  &amp; sche streyned
me so stalworthle &thorn;at I had na mouth
to speke, ne na hand to styrre.  &amp; qwen I saw &thorn;at, I perseyued wele &thorn;at
&thorn;er was no woman [bot &thorn;e deuel in
schappe of a woman].  &THORN;erfor I turned
me to god &amp; with my mynde I sayde:
&laquo;A, Ihesu, how precious is &thorn;i blode&raquo;,
makande &thorn;o crosse with my fyngur in
my brest: &amp; als fast scho wex wayke,
&amp; sodenle al was away; [&] I thankyd
god &thorn;at delyuerde me.  &amp; sothle fro
&thorn;at tyme forth I forced me to luf Ihesu:
&amp; ay &thorn;o more I profet in &thorn;o luf of
Ihesu, [&thorn;e] swetter I fand it; &amp; fra &thorn;at
day it went neuer fra my mynde.
&THORN;erfor blyssud be &thorn;o name of Ihesu in
&thorn;o worlde of worldes.  Amen.
</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="186"><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD>

<NOTE>Thornton MS renders <TITLE>"Oleum Effusum"</TITLE> as two separate, consecutive texts, given below at the div4 level.</NOTE>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Of the vertu&yogh; of the haly name of Ihesu.
</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">  Ricardus herimita super versiculo Oleum effusum nomen tuum, in Cantic. I. 3.</FOREIGN></HEAD><MILESTONE N="192" UNIT="folio">
<P>That es on Inglysce: &laquo;Oyle
owt-&yogh;ettede es thi name.&raquo;  The name of
Ihesu commys in to the worlde and als
sone it smellys Oyle out-&yogh;etted.  Oyle
it es takyne, for ay-lastande saluacyone
es hopede.  Sothely Ihesu es als mekyll
to be-mene als &laquo;saueoure&raquo; or &laquo;helefull&raquo;.
Thare-fore what menys it &laquo;Oyle
owt-&yogh;ettide es thy nam&raquo; Bot &laquo;Ihesu es thy
name&raquo;?  This name es Oyle owte-&yogh;ettyd,
ffor Ihesu the worde of god has tane
manes kynde.  Ihesu, thow fulfillis in
warke that thow es called in name:
Sothely sauys man, &thorn;at wham we calle
saueoure, Thare-fore Ihesu es thy name.
A, A, that wondyrfull name, A, that
delittabyll name!  This es the name
&thorn;at es abowne all names name
althirhegeste, with-owttene whilke na man
hopes hele.  This name es...in myne
ere heuenly sowne, in my mouthe
honyfull swetnes.  Whare-fore na wondire
&thorn;ofe I luf &thorn;at name, the whylke gyffes
comforthe to me in all angwys.  I can
noghte pray, I cane noghte hafe mynde,
Bot sownnande the nam of Ihesu; I
sauyre noghte Ioye that with Ihesu es
noghte mengede.  Whare-so I be,
Whare-so I sytt, What-so I doo, the
mynd of the sauoyre of the name Ihesu
departis noghte fra my mynde.  I haf
sett my mynde, I haf sett it als
takynnynge...appone myne arme: for luf es


<PB N="187">

strange als dede.  Als ded slaas all,
Swa lufe ouer-comes all.  Ay-lastande
lufe has ouer-comemyne me, noghte for
to sla me, but for to qwykkyn me: Bot
it has wondyde me ffor it sulde leche
me, It has thurghe-fychede my herte,
&thorn;at merghlyere it be helyde.  And now
ouer-comene I fayle.  Vnnethes I lyfe
for Ioye, nerehand I dye, ffor I suffyce
noghte . . . in delycyouseste swettnes, And
ay to be dronkenede it falles(!); the
flesche may noghte of his vertu noghte
defaile, ay-whils &thorn;e saule in swylk
Ioyes is rauyste for to Ioye.  Bot
whene vn-to me swylke Ioye bot for
Ihesu?  the name of Ihesu has taughte
me for to synge, and has lyghtenede
my mynde with the hete of vn-made
lyghte.  thare-fore I syghe and crye:
&laquo;Wha sall schewe to &thorn;e lufede Ihesu
&thorn;at I langwys for lufe?&raquo;  My flesche has
faylede and my herte meltes in lufe,
&yogh;arenande Ihesu.  All &thorn;e herte festenede
in &thorn;e &yogh;ernynge of Ihesu es turned in
to &thorn;e fyre of lufe, &amp; with &thorn;e swettnes
of &thorn;e godhede fullyly es it fillide.
Thare-fore, a gude Ihesu, hafe mercy
of &thorn;is wreche, schewe &thorn;e to &thorn;is
languessande, be &thorn;ou leche vn-to &thorn;is
woundyde!  If &thorn;ou come I am hale: I fele
me noghte seke bot langwyssande for &thorn;i
lufe.  Late my saule tak ande, sekande
&thorn;e, Ihesu, whaym it lufes, with whas
lufe it es takyne, whaym anely it
couaytes.  Sothely &thorn;e mynd towchede
with &thorn;e soueraynge swettnes andes for
to waxe hate in the lufe of &thorn;e makare,
I-whyls it enforthis for to halde besyly
in it the swetteste name of Ihesu.
Sothely fra thythene Inryses a gret lufe,
and what thynge &thorn;at it trewely towches
it rauesche it vtterly to it.  It inflawmes
&thorn;e affeccyone, it byndis &thorn;e thoghte,
&yogh;a &amp; all &thorn;e [mane] it drawes to &thorn;e serues


<PB N="188">

of it.  Sothely, Ihesu, desederabill es
thi name, lufabyll and comfortabyll.
Nane swa swete Ioye may be
consayeuede, Nane swa swete sange may
be herde, Nane swa swete &amp; delytabyll
solace may be hade in mynde.
Thare-fore what-so-euer &thorn;ou bee &thorn;at redies
the for to lufe gode: if &thorn;ou will
now-thire be dyssayuede ne dyssayue, if
&thorn;ou will be wysse and noghte vnwysse,
if &thorn;ou will stande &amp; noghte fall, haue
in mynde besely for to halde &thorn;e name
of Ihesu in &thorn;i mynde, and &thorn;ane thyne
Enemy sall fall and &thorn;ou sall stande;
Thyne Enemye sall be made wayke, &thorn;ou
sall be made strange.  And if &thorn;ou will
lelely doo this, ferre fra drede &thorn;ou
sall be gloryus and lowuabyll
ouer-commere.  Seke &thorn;erfore the name of
Ihesu, and halde it, and for-gette it
noghte.  Sothely na thynge slok&ymacr;ns sa
fell flawmes, Dystroyes ill thoghtes, Puttes
owte venemous affeccyons, Dos a-waye
coryous &amp; vayne Ocupacyons fra vs.
This name Ihesu, lelely haldyne in
mynde, drawes by &thorn;e rote vyces,
Settys vertus, In-[s]awes charytee, In-&yogh;ettis
sauoire of heuenely thynges, Wastys
discorde, reformes pese, Gyffes In-lastande
ryste, Dose awaye greuosnes of fleschely
desyris, Turnes all Erthely thynge to
noye, Fyllys &thorn;e luffande of gastely Ioye.
So &thorn;at wele it may be saide: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et gloriabuntur omnes qui deligunt nomen tuum,
quoniam tu benedices Iusto,</FOREIGN> That es: &laquo;All sall Ioye &thorn;at lufes &thorn;i name, for
&thorn;ou sall blysse &thorn;e ryghtwyse.&raquo;
Thare-fore &thorn;e ryghtewyse has dysseruede to
be blyssede, if &thorn;e name of Ihesu trewly
he hafe luffede.  And &thorn;are-fore es [he]
cald ryghtwyse, ffor he Enforssede hym
trewly to lufe Ihesu.  Whare-fore what
may defaile vn-to hym &thorn;at couaytes
vn-cessandly for to lufe &thorn;e name of
Ihesu?  Sothely he lufes and he &yogh;arnes


<PB N="189">

for to lufe, ffor we haue knawene &thorn;at
&thorn;e lufe of gode standis in swylke
manere &thorn;at In als mekyll als we [mare]
lufe, &thorn;e mare vs langes for to lufe, ffor
why it es saide: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">&laquo;Qui edunt me adhuc esurient, &amp; qui bibunt me adhuc
sciciunt,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to saye: &laquo;that ettys me
&yogh;itt hungres thaym, and &thorn;ay &thorn;at drynkes
me &yogh;it thristis thaym&raquo;.  Thare-fore be
it-selfe delitabill &amp; couaytabill es &thorn;e
name of Ihesu and &thorn;e lufe of it.
Thare-fore Ioy sall noghte faile vn-to hym &thorn;at
couaytes besyly for to lufe hym In whaym
angells &yogh;ernys for to be-halde.  Angells
euer sese &amp; euer &thorn;ay &yogh;erne for to see,
and swa are &thorn;ay fild &thorn;at &thorn;aire fillynge
duse noghte awaye &thorn;aire desyre, and so
[&thorn;ai desyre &thorn;at] &thorn;ayre desyre duse noghte
awaye &thorn;aire fillynge.  This es full Ioye,
This es Endles Ioye, This es glorious
Ioye, &thorn;e whylke &thorn;e fylde vses lastandly
with-owttene noye, &amp; if we vse it we sall
be fyllyde euer withowttyne lessynge.
Thare-fore, Ihesu, all sall Ioye &thorn;at lufes
thi name.  Sothely &thorn;ay sall Ioy nowe
be in-&yogh;ettynge of grace, and in tym to
come be syghte of Ioye; and
thare-fore &thorn;ay sall Ioye...ffor why Ioy comes
of lufe.  Thare-fore he &thorn;at luffes noghte
he sall euer-mare be with-owttyne Ioye.
Thare-fore many wreches of &thorn;e worlde
trowande &thorn;ame to Ioye with Criste, sall
sorowe with-owttyne ende, and why?
ffor thay lufede noghte &thorn;e name of
Ihesu.  &laquo;What so &yogh;e doo, if &yogh;e gyfe all
&thorn;at &yogh;e hafe vn-to &thorn;e nedy, bot &yogh;e lufe &thorn;e
name of Ihesu &yogh;e trauelle in vayne&raquo;.
All-anely &thorn;ay may Ioye in Ihesu &thorn;at lufes
hym in &thorn;is lyfe; and thay &thorn;at files &thorn;ame
with vices &amp; venemous delittes, Na drede
&thorn;at ne &thorn;ay ere putt owte of Ioye.  Also
wit all &thorn;at &thorn;e name of Ihesu es
helefull, fruytfull, &amp; glorious.  &THORN;are-fore wha
sall haue hele &thorn;at lufes it noghte?  or wha
sall bere &thorn;e frwyte be-fore Criste &thorn;at


<PB N="190">

has noghte the floure?  and Ioye sall he
noghte see That Ioyeande luffede noghte
&thorn;e name of Ihesu.  &laquo;The wykkyde sall
be done awaye, &thorn;at he see noghte &thorn;e
Ioye of god&raquo;.  Sothely &thorn;e ryghtwyse
sekys &thorn;e Ioye and &thorn;e life and &thorn;ay
fynd it in Ihesu whayme &thorn;ay luffede.
I &yogh;ede abowte be couaytyse of reches and
I fande noghte Ihesu.  I rane [be] the
wantonnes of flesche and I fand noghte
Ihesu.  I satt in companyes of worldly
myrthe and I fand noghte Ihesu.  In
all thire I soghte Ihesu, bot I fand hym
noghte, ffor he lett me wyete by his
grace &thorn;at he ne es fundene in &thorn;e lande
of softly lyfande.  Thare-fore I turnede
by anothire waye, and I rane abowte
be pouerte: and I fande Ihesu pure-borne
in &thorn;e worlde, laid in a crybe and
lappid in clathis.  I &yogh;ode by sufferynge
of werynes, and I fand Ihesu wery in
&thorn;e way, turment with hu[n]gyre, thriste &amp; calde, fild with repreues &amp; blames.  I
satt by myne ane ffleande &thorn;e vanytes of
&thorn;e worlde, and I fande Ihesu in deserte
fastande, in &thorn;e monte anely prayande.
I rane by &thorn;e payne of penaunce, and
I fand Ihesu bowndene, scourgede,
Gyffene galle to drynke, naylyde to &thorn;e
crosse, hyngande in &thorn;e crosse and
dyeand in &thorn;e crosse.  Thare-fore Ihesu
es noghte fundene in reches bot in
pouerte, noghte in delytes bot in
penance, noghte in wantone Ioyeynge
bot in bytter gretynge, noghte emange
many bot in anelynes.  Sothely ane
euyll mane fyndis noghte Ihesu, for
&thorn;are he es he sekes hym noghte.  He
enforces hyme to seke Ihesu in &thorn;e Ioy
of &thorn;e worlde whare neuer he sall be
fundene.  Sothely thare-fore &thorn;e nam
of Ihesu es helefull &amp; nedys by-houys
be lufed of all couaytande saluacyone.


<PB N="191">

He couaytes wele hys saluacyone &thorn;at
kepis besyly in hym &thorn;e name of Ihesu.
Sothely I haue na wondyr if &thorn;e temptid
fall &thorn;at puttes noghte &thorn;e name of Ihesu
in lastande mynde.  Sekerly may he or
scho chese to lyfe anely &thorn;at has chosene
&thorn;e name of Ihesu to thaire specyalle;
ffor thare may na wykked spyritte noye
&thorn;are Ihesu es mekyll in mynde or es
neuennyd in mouthe &amp;c.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit.</FOREIGN>
</P>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Narracio:</FOREIGN> A tale &thorn;at Rycherde hermet [made].</HEAD>

<P>When I hade takene my syngulere purpos &amp; lefte &thorn;e seculere habyte, and I
be-gane mare to serue god &thorn;an mane, it felle one a nyghte als I lay in my ryste,
in &thorn;e begynnynge of my conuersyone, &thorn;are appered to me a full faire &yogh;onge
womane &thorn;e whilke I had sene be-fore &amp; &thorn;e whylke luffed me noght lytill in gude
lufe.  And whene I had be-haldyne hyre and I was wondyrde why scho com swa
on nyghte in &thorn;e wyldyrnes: sodanly, with-owttyne any mare speche, scho laid
hire be-syde me.  And whene &thorn;at I felyd hir thare, I dred &thorn;at scho sulde drawe
me to Iuell, and said &thorn;at I wald ryse &amp; blyse vs in &thorn;e name of &thorn;e haly trynytee.
And scho strenyde me so stallworthely &thorn;at I had no mouthe to speke, ne no
hande to styrre.  And whene I sawe &thorn;at, I perceyuede wele &thorn;are was na womane
bot &thorn;e deuell in schappe of womane.  Thare-fore I turnede me to gode and with
my mynde I said: &laquo;A, Ihesu, how precyous es thi blude!&raquo;, makand &thorn;e crosse with
my fyngere in my breste: and alls faste scho wexe wayke &amp; sodanly all was
awaye; and I thankked gode &thorn;at delyuerd me.  &amp; sothely fra &thorn;at tyme furthe I
forced me for to luf Ihesu, and ay &thorn;e mare I profette in &thorn;e luf of Ihesu, &thorn;e
swetter I fand it, &amp; to &thorn;is daye it went noghte fra my mynde.  Thare-fore,
blysside be &thorn;e name of Ihesu in the worlde of worldes!  Amen.  Amen.  Amen &amp;c.
</P><L>Ihesu &thorn;e sone of &thorn;e glorious virgyne,</L><L>Now, lorde, haue mercy one all thyne.  </L><TRAILER>Amen.  Amen pur charite Amen.</TRAILER>
</DIV4></DIV3>
