<DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="192"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">De Im-perfecta Contricione</FOREIGN></HEAD>
 <HEAD>Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD><MILESTONE N="194" UNIT="folio">
<P>Rycharde hermyte reherces a dredfull tale of vn-perfitte contrecyone &thorn;at a haly
mane Cesarius tellys in Ensample.  He says &thorn;at a &yogh;onge mane, a chanone at Parys,
vn-chastely and delycyousely lyfande and full of many synnys, laye seke to &thorn;e dede.
He schrafe hym of his gret synnys, he hyghte to amende hym, he rescheyuede &thorn;e
sacrament of &thorn;e autire and anoynte hyme, and swa he dyede.  Till hys grauynge
it semyde als &thorn;e ayere gafe seruese.  Eftyr a faa dayes he apperyde till ane &thorn;at
was famyliare till hym in hys lyfe, and sayde &thorn;at he was dampnede, for &thorn;is
Enchesone: &laquo;&THORN;ofe I ware, quod he, schreuen &amp; hyghte to doo penance, me
wanntede verray contrycyone, wythowttene &thorn;e whylke all othere thynges avayles


<PB N="193">

noghte.  For-thy if I hyghte to lefe my foly, my concyens sayde &thorn;at if I lefede
tham, &yogh;et walde I hafe delyte in myne alde lyfe, and till &thorn;at my herte heldede
mare and bowghede thane to restreyne me fra all thoghtes &thorn;at I knewe agaynes
goddes will.  And for-thy I had na stabyll purpos in gude, na perfite contrycyone,
Wharefore sentence of dampnacyone ffelle one me &amp; wente agaynes mee.&raquo;
</P>
<P>All-swa he reherces anothyre tale of verraye contrecyone &thorn;at &thorn;e same clerke
Cesarius says.  He tellys &thorn;at a scolere at Pares had done many full synnys, &thorn;e
whylke he hade schame to schryfe hym of.  At &thorn;e laste gret sorowe of herte
ouercome his schame, and whene he was redy to schryfe hym till &thorn;e priore of
&thorn;e Abbay of Saynte Victor, swa mekill contricyone was in his herte, syghynge in
his breste, sobbynge in his throtte, &thorn;at he moghte noghte brynge a worde furthe.
Thane the priore said till hym: &laquo;Gaa and wrytte thy synnes.&laquo;  He dyd swa, and
come a-gayne to &thorn;e pryoure and gafe hym &thorn;at he hadde wretyne, ffor &yogh;itt he
myghte noghte schryfe hym with mouthe.  The prioure saghe the synnys swa
grette &thorn;at thurghe leue of &thorn;e scolere he schewede theyme to &thorn;e abbotte to hafe
conceyle.  The abbotte tuke &thorn;at byll &thorn;at &thorn;ay warre wrettyne Ine, and lukede
thare-one: He fande na thynge wretyne, and sayd to &thorn;e prioure: &laquo;What may
here be redde &thorn;are noghte es wretyne?&raquo;  That saghe &thorn;e pryour &amp; wondyrde gretly, &amp; saide: &laquo;Wyet &yogh;e &thorn;at his synns here warre wretyne, &amp; I redde thayme, bot now I see &thorn;at god has sene hys contrycione &amp; forgyfes hym all his synnes.&raquo; &THORN;is &thorn;e abbot &amp; &thorn;e prioure tolde &thorn;e scolere, and he with gret Ioye thanked god.
</P>
